{"title_page": "Maggi", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Undue weight|date=March 2020|to=The \"Maggi noodles safety concerns in India\" part which constitutes about half of this article's length; seems undue weight and recentism for the (global) history of a brand founded in 1884}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Maggi\n| logo = Maggi logo.png\n| caption = \n| type = Food\n| traded_as = \n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{Start date|1884}}\n| founder = [[Julius Maggi]]\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = \n| location_country = [[Switzerland]]\n| location = \n| locations = \n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = \n| industry = \n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Nestl\u00e9]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.nestle.com/brands/allbrands/maggi_culinary}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n'''Maggi''' ({{IPA-all|\u02c8ma\u0261i}} or similar in many countries, {{IPA-it|\u02c8madd\u0292i|IPA}} in Malaysia and others) is an international brand of seasonings, instant soups, and noodles that originated in Switzerland in late 19th century. The Maggi company was acquired by [[Nestl\u00e9]] in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|title = Maggi|url = http://www.nestle.com/brands/allbrands/maggi_culinary|website = www.nestle.com|access-date = 2016-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Fabrik von Maggis Nahrungsmitteln 1908.jpg|thumb|Share of the Fabrik von Maggis Nahrungsmitteln, issued 1. July 1908]]\nKhushi loves maggi. and its never her day in ludo. The company originated in Switzerland in 1884, when [[Julius Maggi]] took over his father's mill. He quickly became a [[wikt:Pioneer|pioneer]] of industrial food production, aiming to improve the nutritional intake of worker families. Maggi was the first to bring protein-rich [[legume]] meals to the market, and followed up with a ready-made soup based on legume meals in 1886. After that Julius Maggi introduced bouillon concentrates, first in capsules, then in cubes. In 1897, Julius Maggi founded the company Maggi GmbH in [[Singen]], [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|title =History of Maggi|url = https://www.maggime.com/en/about-us|website = www.nestle.com|access-date = 2017-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, following several changes in ownership and corporate structure, Maggi's holding company merged with the Nestl\u00e9 company to form [[Nestl\u00e9 S.A.|Nestl\u00e9-Alimentana S.A.]], currently known in its [[francophone]] home base as Nestl\u00e9 S.A.<ref>{{cite web|title = FOOD HISTORY: History of Maggi brand of Nestl\u00e9|url = http://www.world-foodhistory.com/2014/03/history-of-maggi-brand-of-nestle.html|website = www.world-foodhistory.com|access-date = 2016-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"220\">\nImage:Maggiw\u00fcrze-alt.jpg|Maggi Seasoning sauce (replica of a historic bottle)\nImage:Maggiw\u00fcrze-neu.jpg|A bottle of Maggi sauce in 2006\nImage:Br\u00fchw\u00fcrfel-1.jpg|Bouillon cubes\n</gallery>\n\n===Cube===\nThe [[bouillon cube]] or ''Maggi cube'' is a meat substitute product that was introduced in 1908.\n\nIn [[Germany]], [[Cameroon]], [[C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]], [[B\u00e9nin]], [[Gambia]], [[Senegal|S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]], [[Guinea]], [[Nigeria]], [[Ghana]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Togo]], [[Sierra Leone]], [[Liberia]], [[Mali]], [[Niger]], and [[Mauritania]] and parts of the [[Middle East]], Maggi cubes are an integral part of the local cuisine. In [[Haiti]] and throughout [[Latin America]], Maggi products, especially bouillon cubes, are widely sold with some repackaging to reflect local terminology.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Albala|first1=Ken|title=Food Cultures of the World Encyclopedia|date=2011|publisher=Greenwood|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=9780313376276|page=166|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zG1H75z0EYYC&pg=RA1-PA166&lpg=RA1-PA166&dq=maggi+bouillon+cubes+haiti#v=onepage&q=maggi%20bouillon%20cubes%20haiti&f=false|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> In the German, Dutch, and Danish languages, [[lovage]] has come to be known as ''Maggi herb'' (Ger. ''Maggikraut'', Du. ''maggikruid'' or ''maggiplant'', Da. ''maggiurt''), because it tastes similar to Maggi sauce, although lovage is not present in the sauce.\n\n[[File:MaggiSenegal2.jpg|thumb|250px|Maggi advertisement in [[Senegal]]]]\n\n===Seasoning sauce===\nIn [[Romanian cuisine|Romania]], [[Mexican cuisine|Mexico]], [[German-speaking countries]], the [[Dutch cuisine|Netherlands]], the [[Czech cuisine|Czech Republic]], [[Slovenian cuisine|Slovenia]], [[Polish cuisine|Poland]] and [[French cuisine|France]], \"Maggi\" is still synonymous with Maggi-W\u00fcrze (Maggi seasoning sauce), a dark, [[soy sauce]]-type [[Acid-hydrolyzed vegetable protein|hydrolysed vegetable protein]]-based condiment sauce. In [[Spanish cuisine|Spain]] and Mexico, it is sold under the name ''Jugo Maggi.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmejornido.com/en/maggi/products/seasoning-sauce |title=Seasoning Sauce &#124; Maggi\u00ae &#124; Brands & Offers &#124; Nestl\u00e9 Recipes |publisher=ElMejorNido.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226234432/https://www.elmejornido.com/en/maggi/products/seasoning-sauce |archive-date=26 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  There are a total of nine different formulations, which differ between nations and/or regions.\n\n===Noodles===\nMaggi instant noodles are popular in [[Bangladesh]], [[Pakistan]], [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], and [[India]]. Nestle has 39% market share in Malaysia, where \"Maggi\" is synonymous with instant noodles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromonitor.com/Noodles-in-Malaysia/report |title=Noodles in Malaysia |publisher=Euromonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> and had 90% market share in India prior to [[Maggi#Maggi_noodles_safety_concerns_in_India|a nationwide ban]] by the [[Food Safety and Standards Authority of India]]. Following the ban, the market share was reduced to 53% in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromonitor.com/noodles-in-india/report |title=Noodles in India |publisher=Euromonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-17}}</ref> In Malaysia, fried noodles made from Maggi noodles are called [[Maggi goreng]]. Maggi Instant noodles are branded as \"Maggi [[Instant noodle#Australia|2 Minute Noodles]]\" in Australia, New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maggi.com.au/products/maggi-noodles/core|title=MAGGI 2 Minute Noodles Chicken - 2 Minute Noodles - MAGGI Australia|website=www.maggi.com.au|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> and India <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maggi.in/our-range\n|title=MAGGI 2 Minute Noodles|website=www.maggi.in|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn India, Maggi Masala noodles carry a green dot, meaning they are specifically formulated to serve vegetarians. However, Maggi chicken noodles carry a red dot, indicating that they are not vegetarian. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/columns/maggi-controversy-it-s-a-wake-up-call-for-indian-consumers/story-cvYfmeOk3tK9xBE2v9FkiP.html |title=Maggi controversy: It's a wake-up call for Indian consumers &#124; columns |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 6 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> This special formulation is not available in other countries, unless imported from [[India]].\n\n===Recipe mixes===\nRecipe mixes or so called Fixes were introduced in Germany in 1974. The product offers to the consumers an idea and a recipe to cook with two or three fresh ingredients and a Maggi mix. A complete step-be-step recipe is given on the back of pack. Following the recipe guarantees the result. These products were originally launched in Germany, where they became very popular, and some Western European countries. In the 1990s, recipe mixes were introduced in Eastern Europe, particularly in Russia and Poland (under the Winiary brand), where they became a big success. Nowadays, the portfolio of recipe mixes offer consumers more than 100 recipe ideas across different European countries.\n\n==Maggi noodles safety concerns in India==\nIn May 2015, food safety regulators from [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]], a district of [[Uttar Pradesh]], India reported that samples of Maggi 2 Minute Noodles had unexpectedly high levels of [[monosodium glutamate]] (MSG), as well as up to 17 times the permissible limit of lead. This finding led to multiple market withdrawals and investigations in India and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rajasthanpatrika.patrika.com/story/business/maggi-controversy-nestle-india-may-be-in-loss-again-1276240.html|title=Maggi controversy: Nestle India may be in loss again|accessdate=16 August 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://merofact.blogspot.in/2015/05/doubts-over-msg-and-lead-content-in.html |title=Doubts over MSG and Lead Content in Maggi Instant Noodles &#124; Merofact Awareness Blog |publisher=Merofact.blogspot.in |date=2015-05-19 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Beware! Eating 2 -Minute Maggi Noodles can ruin your Nervous System|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2015/05/beware-eating-2-minute-maggi-noodles-can-ruin-your-nervous-system/|accessdate=18 May 2015|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|date=18 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.ndtv.com/india-news/maggi-noodles-packets-recalled-across-uttar-pradesh-say-food-inspectors-764729|work=[[NDTV]]|title=Maggi Noodles Packets Recalled Across Uttar Pradesh, Say Food Inspectors: Report|date= 20 May 2015|access-date= 20 May 2015|location=[[New Delhi]], India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sushmi Dey|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Maggi-under-regulatory-scanner-for-lead-MSG-beyond-permissible-limit/articleshow/47304615.cms |work=[[The Times of India]]|title='Maggi' under regulatory scanner for lead, MSG beyond permissible limit |date= 16 May 2015|access-date= 20 May 2015|location=[[New Delhi]], India}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n* June 3, 2015 \u2013 The [[New Delhi]] Government banned the sale of Maggi in New Delhi stores for 15 days due to these findings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Delhi-govt-bans-sales-of-Maggi-from-its-stores/articleshow/47525207.cms|work=[[Times of India]]|title=Delhi govt bans sales of Maggi from its stores: Report|date= 3 June 2015|access-date= 3 June 2015|location=[[New Delhi]], India}}</ref> [[First Information Report]]s (FIRs) against [[Bollywood]] Maggi Brand Ambassadors [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Madhuri Dixit]], and [[Preity Zinta]] were lodged by Sudhir Kumar Ojha, a lawyer, at Muzaffarpur district court, asking the authorities to arrest them if required. He complained that he fell sick after eating Maggi which he had purchased from a shop at Lenin Chowk on 30 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/maggi-case-bollywood-actors-face-fir/article7276001.ece |title=Maggi case: Bollywood actors face FIR |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2015-06-03 |accessdate=2016-01-16|last1=Tewary |first1=Amarnath }}</ref>\n* June 4, 2015 \u2013 The [[Gujarat]] FDA banned the noodles for 30 days after 27 out of 39 samples were detected with objectionable levels of metallic lead, among other things,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Gujarat-bans-Maggi-noodles-for-30-days/articleshow/47541846.cms|title=Gujarat bans Maggi noodles for 30 days|author=IANS|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=([[The Times Group]])|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=4 June 2015}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[Assam]] banned sale, distribution, and storage of Maggi's \"extra delicious chicken noodles\" variety for 30 days after tests carried out at the state public health laboratory concluded that the particular variety contained added an excessively high amount of lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Assam-bans-Maggi-variety-for-30-days/articleshow/47546109.cms|title=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com is temporarily unavailable|work=indiatimes.com}}</ref> On June 4, 2015 the government of [[Tamil Nadu]] banned Maggi foods due to an unacceptable amount of lead and other components.<ref>{{cite web|author=The author has posted comments on this article |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Centre-may-ban-Maggi-as-other-brands-fail-test-in-TN/articleshow/47547551.cms |title=Centre may ban Maggi as other brands fail test in TN \u2013 The Times of India |publisher=M.timesofindia.com |date=2015-06-05 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* June 5, 2015 \u2013 The [[Andhra Pradesh]] Government also banned Maggi foods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150606/nation-current-affairs/article/andhra-pradesh-bans-maggi-telangana-awaits-report |title=Andhra Pradesh bans maggi, Telangana awaits report |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= 6 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* Also on June 5, 2015, the [[Food Safety and Standards Authority of India]] (FSSAI)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/did-not-order-maggi-ban-fssai-tells-sc/article7978147.ece|title=Did not order Maggi ban, FSSAI tells SC|last=Rajagopal|first=Krishnadas|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-02-26|language=en}}</ref> ordered a recall of all nine approved variants of Maggi instant noodles and oats masala noodles, suggesting that they were unsafe and hazardous for human consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fssai.gov.in/Portals/0/Pdf/Order_Nestle.pdf|title=FSSAI Order to Nestle India|date=5 June 2015|publisher=FSSAI, India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616090435/http://www.fssai.gov.in/Portals/0/Pdf/Order_Nestle.pdf|archivedate=16 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Food Standards Agency]] of the [[United Kingdom]] launched an investigation into the level of lead in Maggi noodles.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/uk-launches-maggi-tests-for-lead-content/articleshow/47556524.cms |title=UK launches Maggi tests for lead content \u2013 The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2015-06-05 |accessdate=2016-01-16|newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref>\n* June 6, 2015 \u2013 The Central Government of India banned nationwide sales of Maggi noodles for an indefinite period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/miscellenous-india/supreme-court-denies-to-give-clean-chit-to-maggie-orders-to-re-test-1159819/|title=Supreme Court denies to give clean chit to Maggie, orders to re-test|work=www.patrika.com}}</ref>\n* June 26, 2015 \u2013 During a press meeting, the Minister for Health and Family Welfare of [[Karnataka]], [[U. T. Khader]], stated that Maggi foods would not be banned.<ref>{{cite web|author=News Karnataka |url=http://newskarnataka.com/bangalore/maggie-will-not-be-banned-in-karnataka#sthash.wxFsBtki.dpuf |title=Maggi will not be banned in Karnataka |publisher=Newskarnataka.com |date=2015-06-27 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* July, 2015 \u2013 The Bombay High Court allowed the export of Maggi while the ban in India remained.<ref>{{cite news|author=Maulik Vyas, ET Bureau 1 July 2015, 03.59AM IST |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/food/hc-allows-nestle-to-export-maggi-though-ban-continues-in-india/articleshow/47878617.cms |title=Bombay HC allows Nestle to export Maggi though ban continues in India \u2013 timesofindia-economictimes |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= July 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16|newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref>\n* August 2015 \u2013 Tests performed by the US health regulator FDA showed no dangerous lead levels in the products.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/> On 13 August 2015, the nationwide ban was struck down by the Bombay high court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ban-on-maggi-lifted-bombay-hc-orders-fresh-test-of-noodle-samples/|title=Ban on Maggi: High Court lifts ban, orders fresh tests within 6 weeks|last=|first=|date=14 August 2015|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> The court stated that proper procedure was not followed in issuing the ban and called into question the test results, as the samples were not tested at authorized laboratories accredited to the [[National Accreditation Board for Testing and Calibration Laboratories]] (NABL).<ref>{{cite web|author=Shibu Thomas |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Relief-for-Nestle-Bombay-HC-sets-aside-food-regulators-ban-on-Maggi/articleshow/48463583.cms |title=Relief for Nestle, Bombay HC sets aside food regulator's ban on Maggi \u2013 Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n* January 2019 - Maggi instant noodles were again under the scanner for lead content in the noodles.<ref>\n[https://www-timesnownews-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.timesnownews.com/amp/mirror-now/in-focus/article/nestle-admits-to-presence-of-lead-in-maggi-supreme-court-makes-scathing-observations/341058?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQECAFYAQ%3D%3D#referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.timesnownews.com%2Fmirror-now%2Fin-focus%2Farticle%2Fnestle-admits-to-presence-of-lead-in-maggi-supreme-court-makes-scathing-observations%2F341058 Popular noodles brand has lead in it! Presence of toxin admitted during SC hearing]</ref>\n\n===Additional market bans===\nSome of India's biggest retailers (including [[Future Group]]'s [[Big Bazaar]], [[Easyday]], and Nilgiris) imposed a nationwide ban on Maggi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/business/future-group-bans-maggi-too-the-two-minute-death-of-a-indias-favourite-noodle-brand-2277008.html|publisher=FirstPost|title=Future Group bans Maggi too: The two-minute death of a India's favourite noodle brand|date= 3 June 2015|access-date= 3 June 2015}}</ref> In addition, multiple state authorities in India found an unacceptable amount of lead, leading to bans in more than 5 other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/maggi-s-twisted-tale-gujarat-jharkhand-decision-on-ban-today/article1-1354696.aspx |title=North to south: 5 states ban two-minute Maggi noodles in a day &#124; india |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 4 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/maggi-noodles-fail-lucknow-lab-test/1/559802.html|title=Maggi noodles fail Lucknow lab test|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nNepal indefinitely banned Maggi over concerns about the lead levels in the product.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/nepal-bans-import--sale-of-nestle-maggi-noodles/article1-1354986.aspx |title=Nepal bans import, sale of Maggi noodles &#124; world |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 4 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> Maggi noodles were subsequently withdrawn from the market of five African nations: Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Zimbabwe and South Sudan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33053683 |title=Maggi noodles withdrawn in East African supermarket - BBC News |date= 8 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16|work=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n===Testing controversies===\n* [[Monosodium glutamate]] (MSG): Testing found some MSG in Maggi noodles. The packet stated \"No added MSG\"; however, MSG naturally occurs in hydrolyzed peanut protein, onion powder and wheat flour. Maggi offered to remove the words \"No added MSG\" from the package to overcome the objection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/we-will-remove-no-msg-from-the-maggi-noodle-label-nestles-global-ceo-768951 |title=We Will Remove No MSG from the Maggi Noodles Label: Nestles Global CEO - NDTV Food |publisher=Food.ndtv.com |date=2015-06-06 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* [[Lead]]: Maggi noodles include flavouring packets named \"Tastemaker\" which is intended to dissolve in water during cooking. Maggi insisted that testing should be done on the product as it is eaten; however, the FSSAI insisted that the powder itself should be tested. On June 5, the FSSAI said that the prescribed standards of 2.5 parts per million would have to apply to all components of the product. Out of the 13 samples tested by Delhi authorities, 10 of them had lead content exceeding this limit. The packets that initiated the investigation from Uttar Pradesh had 17.2 ppm of lead.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rohan Venkataramakrishnan |url=http://scroll.in/article/732356/nestles-defence-its-only-real-lead-free-maggi-when-the-noodles-and-masala-are-boiled-in-water |title=Nestl\u00e9's defence: It is only real (lead-free) Maggi when the noodles and masala are boiled in water |publisher=Scroll.in |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> Nestl\u00e9 also questioned the reliability of the labs used. Results from testing outside of India ([[Singapore]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Singapore-resumes-sale-of-India-made-Maggi-noodles/articleshow/47597535.cms |title=Singapore resumes sale of India-made Maggi noodles - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-06-09 |accessdate=2016-01-16 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref> US<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/US-health-regulator-says-lead-in-Maggi-within-acceptable-levels/articleshow/48460940.cms |title=US health regulator says lead in Maggi within acceptable levels - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-08-13 |accessdate=2016-01-16 |agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref>) reported that Maggi noodles were safe.  In the later Bombay High Court judgment, the court agreed that the test results by earlier labs were unreliable. The court mandated testing to be done at three specific laboratories (Punjab, Hyderabad and Jaipur) where Maggi was found safe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/maggi-clears-bombay-hc-mandated-lab-tests-nestle-india/ |title=Maggi clears Bombay HC mandated lab tests: [Nestle] India |publisher=The Indian Express |date=2015-10-17 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> The lead may have been naturally occurring in plants and soil<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Lead in soils and plants: A literature review|journal=C R C Critical Reviews in Environmental Control|volume=3|issue = 1\u20134|page=213|doi=10.1080/10643387309381602|year=2010|last1=Zimdahl|first1=Robert L.|last2=Arvik|first2=Jon H.|last3=Hammond|first3=Paul B.}}</ref> or from Indian spices, although within acceptable limits.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Park |first=Alice |url=http://content.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1971906,00.html |title=Study: Indian Spices, Powders Linked with Lead Poisoning - TIME |journal=Time |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===Company response===\nMaggi always insisted that their noodle product is safe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nestle.in/aboutus/ask-nestle/answers/maggi-noodles-india-test-results |title=What testing methodology does Nestl\u00e9 use? &#124; MAGGI Noodles - Nestl\u00e9 India &#124; Nestl\u00e9 India |publisher=Nestle.in |date=2016-01-01 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> Maggi recalled stock worth nearly Rs. 320 [[crore]] (Rs. 3.2 Billion) from the shelves and paid Rs. 20 crores (Rs. 200 million) to a cement factory to burn the product. In addition, the Corporate Affairs Ministry of India imposed a Rs. 640 crore (Rs. 6.4 Billion) fine on Nestle India for the presence of MSG and lead beyond the permissible limit.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ruchika Shah |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-how-much-did-maggi-ban-cost-nestle-india-2140196 |title=How much did Maggi ban cost Nestle India? &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=2015-10-30 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===Return to market===\nIn India, Maggi products were returned to the shelves in November 2015,<ref>Bhusan, Ratna and Malviya, Sagar (17 October 2015) http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/food/maggi-clears-all-tests-nestle-india-to-restart-production-within-2-3-weeks/articleshow/49423524.cms</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/business/maggi-noodles-return-to-india-after-crisis/story-fnkgdftz-1227602617859 |title=Maggi noodles India ban: Celebrations as Nestle returns to shelves |publisher=News.com.au |date=2015-11-10 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> accompanied by a [[Nestl\u00e9]] advertising campaign to win back the trust of members of the Indian community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketing-interactive.com/look-maggis-latest-ploy-winning-back-consumer-trust-safety-concerns/|title=LOOK Maggi India's latest ploy to win back customers|author=marketing-interactive.com|date=|website=|publisher=www.marketing-interactive.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref> At this time, the \"Maggi anthem\" by [[Vir Das]] and Alien Chutney became popular.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goswami|first1=Shreya|title=Try getting this Maggi song by Vir Das and Alien Chutney out of your head|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/vir-das-alien-chutney-new-maggi-anthem-youtube-video-msg-lead-masala-is-my-king/1/649138.html|accessdate=5 August 2016|work=[[India Today]]|date=22 April 2016}}</ref> Nestl\u00e9 resumed production of Maggi at all five plants in India on 30 November 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/nestle-brings-back-maggi-to-shelves-in-india/article7860831.ece|title=Maggi noodles is back|last=Bhargava|first=Yuthika|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-02-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thehindu.com/business/Industry/nestle-resumes-maggi-noodles-production-at-all-plants-in-india/article7932803.ece |title=Nestle resumes Maggi noodles production at all plants in India : The Hindu - Mobile edition |publisher=M.thehindu.com |date=2015-11-30 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nNestl\u00e9 has faced criticism of its advertising not adhering to marketing regulations in developed countries, and for making misleading claims in developing countries. In October 2008, Nestl\u00e9 aired a commercial meant for Bangladeshi television on British TV. The advert made false claims that the noodles would \"help to build strong muscles, bone, and hair\". The [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|British Advertising Standards Authority]] stated that the advertisement did not abide by the new [[European Union|EU]] consumer protection legislation, by which advertisers have to provide proof of health claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/nestle-criticised-for-child-health-claims-968404.html |title=Nestle criticised for child health claims - Business News, Business - The Independent |accessdate=2016-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612025352/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/nestle-criticised-for-child-health-claims-968404.html |archivedate=12 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of instant noodle brands]]\n* [[List of Nestl\u00e9 brands]]\n* {{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=pronunciation}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Maggi}}\n* {{cite news|title=How Maggi noodles became an iconic Indian snack|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-33002261|work=BBC News|date=4 June 2015}}\n* [http://www.nestle.com/brands/allbrands/maggi_culinary Nestle Global Website]\n{{Nestl\u00e9}}\n{{Noodle}}\n\n[[Category:Cham, Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Culinary Heritage of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Instant noodle brands]]\n[[Category:Haitian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nestl\u00e9 brands]]\n[[Category:Swiss brands]]\n[[Category:Umami enhancers]]\n[[Category:1947 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Undue weight|date=March 2020|to=The \"Maggi noodles safety concerns in India\" part which constitutes about half of this article's length; seems undue weight and recentism for the (global) history of a brand founded in 1884}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Maggi\n| logo = Maggi logo.png\n| caption = \n| type = Food\n| traded_as = \n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{Start date|1884}}\n| founder = [[Julius Maggi]]\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = \n| location_country = [[Switzerland]]\n| location = \n| locations = \n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = \n| industry = \n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Nestl\u00e9]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.nestle.com/brands/allbrands/maggi_culinary}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n'''Maggi''' ({{IPA-all|\u02c8ma\u0261i}} or similar in many countries, {{IPA-it|\u02c8madd\u0292i|IPA}} in Malaysia and others) is an international brand of seasonings, instant soups, and noodles that originated in Switzerland in late 19th century. The Maggi company was acquired by [[Nestl\u00e9]] in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|title = Maggi|url = http://www.nestle.com/brands/allbrands/maggi_culinary|website = www.nestle.com|access-date = 2016-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Fabrik von Maggis Nahrungsmitteln 1908.jpg|thumb|Share of the Fabrik von Maggis Nahrungsmitteln, issued 1. July 1908]]\nThe company originated in Switzerland in 1884, when [[Julius Maggi]] took over his father's mill. He quickly became a [[wikt:Pioneer|pioneer]] of industrial food production, aiming to improve the nutritional intake of worker families. Maggi was the first to bring protein-rich [[legume]] meals to the market, and followed up with a ready-made soup based on legume meals in 1886. After that Julius Maggi introduced bouillon concentrates, first in capsules, then in cubes. In 1897, Julius Maggi founded the company Maggi GmbH in [[Singen]], [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|title =History of Maggi|url = https://www.maggime.com/en/about-us|website = www.nestle.com|access-date = 2017-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, following several changes in ownership and corporate structure, Maggi's holding company merged with the Nestl\u00e9 company to form [[Nestl\u00e9 S.A.|Nestl\u00e9-Alimentana S.A.]], currently known in its [[francophone]] home base as Nestl\u00e9 S.A.<ref>{{cite web|title = FOOD HISTORY: History of Maggi brand of Nestl\u00e9|url = http://www.world-foodhistory.com/2014/03/history-of-maggi-brand-of-nestle.html|website = www.world-foodhistory.com|access-date = 2016-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"220\">\nImage:Maggiw\u00fcrze-alt.jpg|Maggi Seasoning sauce (replica of a historic bottle)\nImage:Maggiw\u00fcrze-neu.jpg|A bottle of Maggi sauce in 2006\nImage:Br\u00fchw\u00fcrfel-1.jpg|Bouillon cubes\n</gallery>\n\n===Cube===\nThe [[bouillon cube]] or ''Maggi cube'' is a meat substitute product that was introduced in 1908.\n\nIn [[Germany]], [[Cameroon]], [[C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]], [[B\u00e9nin]], [[Gambia]], [[Senegal|S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]], [[Guinea]], [[Nigeria]], [[Ghana]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Togo]], [[Sierra Leone]], [[Liberia]], [[Mali]], [[Niger]], and [[Mauritania]] and parts of the [[Middle East]], Maggi cubes are an integral part of the local cuisine. In [[Haiti]] and throughout [[Latin America]], Maggi products, especially bouillon cubes, are widely sold with some repackaging to reflect local terminology.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Albala|first1=Ken|title=Food Cultures of the World Encyclopedia|date=2011|publisher=Greenwood|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=9780313376276|page=166|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zG1H75z0EYYC&pg=RA1-PA166&lpg=RA1-PA166&dq=maggi+bouillon+cubes+haiti#v=onepage&q=maggi%20bouillon%20cubes%20haiti&f=false|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> In the German, Dutch, and Danish languages, [[lovage]] has come to be known as ''Maggi herb'' (Ger. ''Maggikraut'', Du. ''maggikruid'' or ''maggiplant'', Da. ''maggiurt''), because it tastes similar to Maggi sauce, although lovage is not present in the sauce.\n\n[[File:MaggiSenegal2.jpg|thumb|250px|Maggi advertisement in [[Senegal]]]]\n\n===Seasoning sauce===\nIn [[Romanian cuisine|Romania]], [[Mexican cuisine|Mexico]], [[German-speaking countries]], the [[Dutch cuisine|Netherlands]], the [[Czech cuisine|Czech Republic]], [[Slovenian cuisine|Slovenia]], [[Polish cuisine|Poland]] and [[French cuisine|France]], \"Maggi\" is still synonymous with Maggi-W\u00fcrze (Maggi seasoning sauce), a dark, [[soy sauce]]-type [[Acid-hydrolyzed vegetable protein|hydrolysed vegetable protein]]-based condiment sauce. In [[Spanish cuisine|Spain]] and Mexico, it is sold under the name ''Jugo Maggi.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmejornido.com/en/maggi/products/seasoning-sauce |title=Seasoning Sauce &#124; Maggi\u00ae &#124; Brands & Offers &#124; Nestl\u00e9 Recipes |publisher=ElMejorNido.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226234432/https://www.elmejornido.com/en/maggi/products/seasoning-sauce |archive-date=26 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  There are a total of nine different formulations, which differ between nations and/or regions.\n\n===Noodles===\nMaggi instant noodles are popular in [[Bangladesh]], [[Pakistan]], [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], and [[India]]. Nestle has 39% market share in Malaysia, where \"Maggi\" is synonymous with instant noodles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromonitor.com/Noodles-in-Malaysia/report |title=Noodles in Malaysia |publisher=Euromonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> and had 90% market share in India prior to [[Maggi#Maggi_noodles_safety_concerns_in_India|a nationwide ban]] by the [[Food Safety and Standards Authority of India]]. Following the ban, the market share was reduced to 53% in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromonitor.com/noodles-in-india/report |title=Noodles in India |publisher=Euromonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-17}}</ref> In Malaysia, fried noodles made from Maggi noodles are called [[Maggi goreng]]. Maggi Instant noodles are branded as \"Maggi [[Instant noodle#Australia|2 Minute Noodles]]\" in Australia, New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maggi.com.au/products/maggi-noodles/core|title=MAGGI 2 Minute Noodles Chicken - 2 Minute Noodles - MAGGI Australia|website=www.maggi.com.au|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> and India <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maggi.in/our-range\n|title=MAGGI 2 Minute Noodles|website=www.maggi.in|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn India, Maggi Masala noodles carry a green dot, meaning they are specifically formulated to serve vegetarians. However, Maggi chicken noodles carry a red dot, indicating that they are not vegetarian. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/columns/maggi-controversy-it-s-a-wake-up-call-for-indian-consumers/story-cvYfmeOk3tK9xBE2v9FkiP.html |title=Maggi controversy: It's a wake-up call for Indian consumers &#124; columns |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 6 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> This special formulation is not available in other countries, unless imported from [[India]].\n\n===Recipe mixes===\nRecipe mixes or so called Fixes were introduced in Germany in 1974. The product offers to the consumers an idea and a recipe to cook with two or three fresh ingredients and a Maggi mix. A complete step-be-step recipe is given on the back of pack. Following the recipe guarantees the result. These products were originally launched in Germany, where they became very popular, and some Western European countries. In the 1990s, recipe mixes were introduced in Eastern Europe, particularly in Russia and Poland (under the Winiary brand), where they became a big success. Nowadays, the portfolio of recipe mixes offer consumers more than 100 recipe ideas across different European countries.\n\n==Maggi noodles safety concerns in India==\nIn May 2015, food safety regulators from [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]], a district of [[Uttar Pradesh]], India reported that samples of Maggi 2 Minute Noodles had unexpectedly high levels of [[monosodium glutamate]] (MSG), as well as up to 17 times the permissible limit of lead. This finding led to multiple market withdrawals and investigations in India and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rajasthanpatrika.patrika.com/story/business/maggi-controversy-nestle-india-may-be-in-loss-again-1276240.html|title=Maggi controversy: Nestle India may be in loss again|accessdate=16 August 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://merofact.blogspot.in/2015/05/doubts-over-msg-and-lead-content-in.html |title=Doubts over MSG and Lead Content in Maggi Instant Noodles &#124; Merofact Awareness Blog |publisher=Merofact.blogspot.in |date=2015-05-19 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Beware! Eating 2 -Minute Maggi Noodles can ruin your Nervous System|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2015/05/beware-eating-2-minute-maggi-noodles-can-ruin-your-nervous-system/|accessdate=18 May 2015|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|date=18 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.ndtv.com/india-news/maggi-noodles-packets-recalled-across-uttar-pradesh-say-food-inspectors-764729|work=[[NDTV]]|title=Maggi Noodles Packets Recalled Across Uttar Pradesh, Say Food Inspectors: Report|date= 20 May 2015|access-date= 20 May 2015|location=[[New Delhi]], India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sushmi Dey|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Maggi-under-regulatory-scanner-for-lead-MSG-beyond-permissible-limit/articleshow/47304615.cms |work=[[The Times of India]]|title='Maggi' under regulatory scanner for lead, MSG beyond permissible limit |date= 16 May 2015|access-date= 20 May 2015|location=[[New Delhi]], India}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n* June 3, 2015 \u2013 The [[New Delhi]] Government banned the sale of Maggi in New Delhi stores for 15 days due to these findings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Delhi-govt-bans-sales-of-Maggi-from-its-stores/articleshow/47525207.cms|work=[[Times of India]]|title=Delhi govt bans sales of Maggi from its stores: Report|date= 3 June 2015|access-date= 3 June 2015|location=[[New Delhi]], India}}</ref> [[First Information Report]]s (FIRs) against [[Bollywood]] Maggi Brand Ambassadors [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Madhuri Dixit]], and [[Preity Zinta]] were lodged by Sudhir Kumar Ojha, a lawyer, at Muzaffarpur district court, asking the authorities to arrest them if required. He complained that he fell sick after eating Maggi which he had purchased from a shop at Lenin Chowk on 30 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/maggi-case-bollywood-actors-face-fir/article7276001.ece |title=Maggi case: Bollywood actors face FIR |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2015-06-03 |accessdate=2016-01-16|last1=Tewary |first1=Amarnath }}</ref>\n* June 4, 2015 \u2013 The [[Gujarat]] FDA banned the noodles for 30 days after 27 out of 39 samples were detected with objectionable levels of metallic lead, among other things,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Gujarat-bans-Maggi-noodles-for-30-days/articleshow/47541846.cms|title=Gujarat bans Maggi noodles for 30 days|author=IANS|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=([[The Times Group]])|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=4 June 2015}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[Assam]] banned sale, distribution, and storage of Maggi's \"extra delicious chicken noodles\" variety for 30 days after tests carried out at the state public health laboratory concluded that the particular variety contained added an excessively high amount of lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Assam-bans-Maggi-variety-for-30-days/articleshow/47546109.cms|title=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com is temporarily unavailable|work=indiatimes.com}}</ref> On June 4, 2015 the government of [[Tamil Nadu]] banned Maggi foods due to an unacceptable amount of lead and other components.<ref>{{cite web|author=The author has posted comments on this article |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Centre-may-ban-Maggi-as-other-brands-fail-test-in-TN/articleshow/47547551.cms |title=Centre may ban Maggi as other brands fail test in TN \u2013 The Times of India |publisher=M.timesofindia.com |date=2015-06-05 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* June 5, 2015 \u2013 The [[Andhra Pradesh]] Government also banned Maggi foods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150606/nation-current-affairs/article/andhra-pradesh-bans-maggi-telangana-awaits-report |title=Andhra Pradesh bans maggi, Telangana awaits report |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= 6 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* Also on June 5, 2015, the [[Food Safety and Standards Authority of India]] (FSSAI)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/did-not-order-maggi-ban-fssai-tells-sc/article7978147.ece|title=Did not order Maggi ban, FSSAI tells SC|last=Rajagopal|first=Krishnadas|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-02-26|language=en}}</ref> ordered a recall of all nine approved variants of Maggi instant noodles and oats masala noodles, suggesting that they were unsafe and hazardous for human consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fssai.gov.in/Portals/0/Pdf/Order_Nestle.pdf|title=FSSAI Order to Nestle India|date=5 June 2015|publisher=FSSAI, India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616090435/http://www.fssai.gov.in/Portals/0/Pdf/Order_Nestle.pdf|archivedate=16 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Food Standards Agency]] of the [[United Kingdom]] launched an investigation into the level of lead in Maggi noodles.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/uk-launches-maggi-tests-for-lead-content/articleshow/47556524.cms |title=UK launches Maggi tests for lead content \u2013 The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2015-06-05 |accessdate=2016-01-16|newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref>\n* June 6, 2015 \u2013 The Central Government of India banned nationwide sales of Maggi noodles for an indefinite period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/miscellenous-india/supreme-court-denies-to-give-clean-chit-to-maggie-orders-to-re-test-1159819/|title=Supreme Court denies to give clean chit to Maggie, orders to re-test|work=www.patrika.com}}</ref>\n* June 26, 2015 \u2013 During a press meeting, the Minister for Health and Family Welfare of [[Karnataka]], [[U. T. Khader]], stated that Maggi foods would not be banned.<ref>{{cite web|author=News Karnataka |url=http://newskarnataka.com/bangalore/maggie-will-not-be-banned-in-karnataka#sthash.wxFsBtki.dpuf |title=Maggi will not be banned in Karnataka |publisher=Newskarnataka.com |date=2015-06-27 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* July, 2015 \u2013 The Bombay High Court allowed the export of Maggi while the ban in India remained.<ref>{{cite news|author=Maulik Vyas, ET Bureau 1 July 2015, 03.59AM IST |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/food/hc-allows-nestle-to-export-maggi-though-ban-continues-in-india/articleshow/47878617.cms |title=Bombay HC allows Nestle to export Maggi though ban continues in India \u2013 timesofindia-economictimes |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= July 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16|newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref>\n* August 2015 \u2013 Tests performed by the US health regulator FDA showed no dangerous lead levels in the products.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/> On 13 August 2015, the nationwide ban was struck down by the Bombay high court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ban-on-maggi-lifted-bombay-hc-orders-fresh-test-of-noodle-samples/|title=Ban on Maggi: High Court lifts ban, orders fresh tests within 6 weeks|last=|first=|date=14 August 2015|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> The court stated that proper procedure was not followed in issuing the ban and called into question the test results, as the samples were not tested at authorized laboratories accredited to the [[National Accreditation Board for Testing and Calibration Laboratories]] (NABL).<ref>{{cite web|author=Shibu Thomas |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Relief-for-Nestle-Bombay-HC-sets-aside-food-regulators-ban-on-Maggi/articleshow/48463583.cms |title=Relief for Nestle, Bombay HC sets aside food regulator's ban on Maggi \u2013 Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n* January 2019 - Maggi instant noodles were again under the scanner for lead content in the noodles.<ref>\n[https://www-timesnownews-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.timesnownews.com/amp/mirror-now/in-focus/article/nestle-admits-to-presence-of-lead-in-maggi-supreme-court-makes-scathing-observations/341058?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQECAFYAQ%3D%3D#referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.timesnownews.com%2Fmirror-now%2Fin-focus%2Farticle%2Fnestle-admits-to-presence-of-lead-in-maggi-supreme-court-makes-scathing-observations%2F341058 Popular noodles brand has lead in it! Presence of toxin admitted during SC hearing]</ref>\n\n===Additional market bans===\nSome of India's biggest retailers (including [[Future Group]]'s [[Big Bazaar]], [[Easyday]], and Nilgiris) imposed a nationwide ban on Maggi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/business/future-group-bans-maggi-too-the-two-minute-death-of-a-indias-favourite-noodle-brand-2277008.html|publisher=FirstPost|title=Future Group bans Maggi too: The two-minute death of a India's favourite noodle brand|date= 3 June 2015|access-date= 3 June 2015}}</ref> In addition, multiple state authorities in India found an unacceptable amount of lead, leading to bans in more than 5 other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/maggi-s-twisted-tale-gujarat-jharkhand-decision-on-ban-today/article1-1354696.aspx |title=North to south: 5 states ban two-minute Maggi noodles in a day &#124; india |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 4 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/maggi-noodles-fail-lucknow-lab-test/1/559802.html|title=Maggi noodles fail Lucknow lab test|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nNepal indefinitely banned Maggi over concerns about the lead levels in the product.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/nepal-bans-import--sale-of-nestle-maggi-noodles/article1-1354986.aspx |title=Nepal bans import, sale of Maggi noodles &#124; world |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 4 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> Maggi noodles were subsequently withdrawn from the market of five African nations: Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Zimbabwe and South Sudan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33053683 |title=Maggi noodles withdrawn in East African supermarket - BBC News |date= 8 June 2015|accessdate=2016-01-16|work=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n===Testing controversies===\n* [[Monosodium glutamate]] (MSG): Testing found some MSG in Maggi noodles. The packet stated \"No added MSG\"; however, MSG naturally occurs in hydrolyzed peanut protein, onion powder and wheat flour. Maggi offered to remove the words \"No added MSG\" from the package to overcome the objection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/we-will-remove-no-msg-from-the-maggi-noodle-label-nestles-global-ceo-768951 |title=We Will Remove No MSG from the Maggi Noodles Label: Nestles Global CEO - NDTV Food |publisher=Food.ndtv.com |date=2015-06-06 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* [[Lead]]: Maggi noodles include flavouring packets named \"Tastemaker\" which is intended to dissolve in water during cooking. Maggi insisted that testing should be done on the product as it is eaten; however, the FSSAI insisted that the powder itself should be tested. On June 5, the FSSAI said that the prescribed standards of 2.5 parts per million would have to apply to all components of the product. Out of the 13 samples tested by Delhi authorities, 10 of them had lead content exceeding this limit. The packets that initiated the investigation from Uttar Pradesh had 17.2 ppm of lead.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rohan Venkataramakrishnan |url=http://scroll.in/article/732356/nestles-defence-its-only-real-lead-free-maggi-when-the-noodles-and-masala-are-boiled-in-water |title=Nestl\u00e9's defence: It is only real (lead-free) Maggi when the noodles and masala are boiled in water |publisher=Scroll.in |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> Nestl\u00e9 also questioned the reliability of the labs used. Results from testing outside of India ([[Singapore]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Singapore-resumes-sale-of-India-made-Maggi-noodles/articleshow/47597535.cms |title=Singapore resumes sale of India-made Maggi noodles - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-06-09 |accessdate=2016-01-16 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref> US<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/US-health-regulator-says-lead-in-Maggi-within-acceptable-levels/articleshow/48460940.cms |title=US health regulator says lead in Maggi within acceptable levels - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-08-13 |accessdate=2016-01-16 |agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref>) reported that Maggi noodles were safe.  In the later Bombay High Court judgment, the court agreed that the test results by earlier labs were unreliable. The court mandated testing to be done at three specific laboratories (Punjab, Hyderabad and Jaipur) where Maggi was found safe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/maggi-clears-bombay-hc-mandated-lab-tests-nestle-india/ |title=Maggi clears Bombay HC mandated lab tests: [Nestle] India |publisher=The Indian Express |date=2015-10-17 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> The lead may have been naturally occurring in plants and soil<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Lead in soils and plants: A literature review|journal=C R C Critical Reviews in Environmental Control|volume=3|issue = 1\u20134|page=213|doi=10.1080/10643387309381602|year=2010|last1=Zimdahl|first1=Robert L.|last2=Arvik|first2=Jon H.|last3=Hammond|first3=Paul B.}}</ref> or from Indian spices, although within acceptable limits.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Park |first=Alice |url=http://content.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1971906,00.html |title=Study: Indian Spices, Powders Linked with Lead Poisoning - TIME |journal=Time |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===Company response===\nMaggi always insisted that their noodle product is safe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nestle.in/aboutus/ask-nestle/answers/maggi-noodles-india-test-results |title=What testing methodology does Nestl\u00e9 use? &#124; MAGGI Noodles - Nestl\u00e9 India &#124; Nestl\u00e9 India |publisher=Nestle.in |date=2016-01-01 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> Maggi recalled stock worth nearly Rs. 320 [[crore]] (Rs. 3.2 Billion) from the shelves and paid Rs. 20 crores (Rs. 200 million) to a cement factory to burn the product. In addition, the Corporate Affairs Ministry of India imposed a Rs. 640 crore (Rs. 6.4 Billion) fine on Nestle India for the presence of MSG and lead beyond the permissible limit.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ruchika Shah |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-how-much-did-maggi-ban-cost-nestle-india-2140196 |title=How much did Maggi ban cost Nestle India? &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=2015-10-30 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===Return to market===\nIn India, Maggi products were returned to the shelves in November 2015,<ref>Bhusan, Ratna and Malviya, Sagar (17 October 2015) http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/food/maggi-clears-all-tests-nestle-india-to-restart-production-within-2-3-weeks/articleshow/49423524.cms</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/business/maggi-noodles-return-to-india-after-crisis/story-fnkgdftz-1227602617859 |title=Maggi noodles India ban: Celebrations as Nestle returns to shelves |publisher=News.com.au |date=2015-11-10 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> accompanied by a [[Nestl\u00e9]] advertising campaign to win back the trust of members of the Indian community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketing-interactive.com/look-maggis-latest-ploy-winning-back-consumer-trust-safety-concerns/|title=LOOK Maggi India's latest ploy to win back customers|author=marketing-interactive.com|date=|website=|publisher=www.marketing-interactive.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref> At this time, the \"Maggi anthem\" by [[Vir Das]] and Alien Chutney became popular.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goswami|first1=Shreya|title=Try getting this Maggi song by Vir Das and Alien Chutney out of your head|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/vir-das-alien-chutney-new-maggi-anthem-youtube-video-msg-lead-masala-is-my-king/1/649138.html|accessdate=5 August 2016|work=[[India Today]]|date=22 April 2016}}</ref> Nestl\u00e9 resumed production of Maggi at all five plants in India on 30 November 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/nestle-brings-back-maggi-to-shelves-in-india/article7860831.ece|title=Maggi noodles is back|last=Bhargava|first=Yuthika|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-02-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thehindu.com/business/Industry/nestle-resumes-maggi-noodles-production-at-all-plants-in-india/article7932803.ece |title=Nestle resumes Maggi noodles production at all plants in India : The Hindu - Mobile edition |publisher=M.thehindu.com |date=2015-11-30 |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nNestl\u00e9 has faced criticism of its advertising not adhering to marketing regulations in developed countries, and for making misleading claims in developing countries. In October 2008, Nestl\u00e9 aired a commercial meant for Bangladeshi television on British TV. The advert made false claims that the noodles would \"help to build strong muscles, bone, and hair\". The [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|British Advertising Standards Authority]] stated that the advertisement did not abide by the new [[European Union|EU]] consumer protection legislation, by which advertisers have to provide proof of health claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/nestle-criticised-for-child-health-claims-968404.html |title=Nestle criticised for child health claims - Business News, Business - The Independent |accessdate=2016-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612025352/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/nestle-criticised-for-child-health-claims-968404.html |archivedate=12 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of instant noodle brands]]\n* [[List of Nestl\u00e9 brands]]\n* {{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=pronunciation}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Maggi}}\n* {{cite news|title=How Maggi noodles became an iconic Indian snack|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-33002261|work=BBC News|date=4 June 2015}}\n* [http://www.nestle.com/brands/allbrands/maggi_culinary Nestle Global Website]\n{{Nestl\u00e9}}\n{{Noodle}}\n\n[[Category:Cham, Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Culinary Heritage of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Instant noodle brands]]\n[[Category:Haitian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nestl\u00e9 brands]]\n[[Category:Swiss brands]]\n[[Category:Umami enhancers]]\n[[Category:1947 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "5.194.139.222", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maggi"}
{"title_page": "James Stewart Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American motorcycle racer}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Peacock|date=December 2009}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2008}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Ben Dover \n| image          = Stewart Anahiem04.jpg\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Ben Dover Stewart \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = American\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|12|21}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bartow, Florida|Bartow]], [[Florida]]\n| height         = {{convert|5|ft|7|in|m}}<ref name=\"musa\">http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/493/1094/Motorcycle-Article/James-Stewart-Bio.aspx</ref>\n| weight         = {{convert|161|lb|kg}}<ref name=\"musa\"/>\n| sport          = [[Motocross]]\n| event          = [[sx]]\n\n<!-- achievements-->\n| worlds         = 2006 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion<br />\n2007 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion<br />\n2006 Motocross of Nations Champion<br />\n2008 Motocross of Nations Champion\n2009 FIM World Supercross Champion\n| nationals      = 2002 AMA 125 Motocross national champion\n<br />\n2004 AMA 125 Motocross National Champion<br />\n2007 AMA Supercross Champion<br />\n2008 AMA Motocross National Champion<br />\n2009 AMA Supercross Champion\n| regionals      = 2003 AMA 125 West Supercross Champion<br />\n2004 AMA 125 East Supercross Champion\n| updated     = 30 July 2009\n}}\n\n'''James Stewart Jr.''' (born December 21, 1985), also known as '''Bubba Stewart''', is an [[Americans|American]] former professional [[motocross]] racer who competed in the [[AMA Motocross Championship|AMA Motocross]] and the [[AMA Supercross Championship]]s. Through his years of racing, he earned the nickname \u201cThe Fastest Man on The Planet\u201d, due to his extraordinary talent, speed, athleticism and innovation.  \n\nIn 2008 James won every race and every moto of the AMA Motocross season. The only other person to do this is Ricky Carmichael, who had perfect seasons in 2002 and 2004. James is second in all time 450 Supercross wins (50), and second all time in AMA outdoor national wins (48). He is also known for innovating the \"Bubba Scrub\" or just \"scrub\", which revolutionized the sport and became a fundamental skill needed to compete in Professional Motocross. He was the first to host his own television show \"Bubba's World\" which brought even more attention to the sport. He is arguably the most financially lucrative racer, bringing in endorsement deals paying him over $10M a year throughout his career. Known for his vibrant personality and big smile, James has been featured in news outlets like Rolling Stone, The New York Times, Maxim, ESPN The Magazine, GQ and many more. Additionally, Teen People named him one of \u201c20 Teens Who Will Change the World\u201d. He has the record for best rookie season, having won 10/12 Motocross races in 2002. \n\nJames has 5 FIM World Champion titles from Motocross of Nations, and World Supercross.  4 AMA Supercross Champion titles, and 3 AMA Motocross Champion titles. He won the Redbull Straight Rhythm in both 2014 and 2015. He's a Motocross legend who battled the greats of multiple era's.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Amateur and Lites Class===\nStewart was born in [[Bartow, Florida]]<ref name=\"musa\"/> and currently resides in [[Haine City Lake Hamilton, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amasupercross.com/riders/Bio.aspx?id=553278 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707125048/http://www.amasupercross.com/riders/bio.aspx?id=553278 |archivedate=2011-07-07 }}</ref> His father, James Sr., was a [[motocross]] enthusiast and introduced his son to the sport at the age of three. Stewart entered his first motocross race when he was four years old.<ref name=\"js7.com\">{{cite web |url=http://js7.com/bio/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731215303/http://js7.com/bio/ |archivedate=2009-07-31 }}</ref>\n\nHaving 84 amateur wins and 7 [[Loretta Lynn's Amateur Championship]]s all before the age of 16, he debuted as pro in 2002. While crashes and rookie mistakes kept him from winning the 2002 125 West Supercross title, he finished 2nd overall. He went on to dominate the 2002 Motocross Championship, and was named the 2002 AMA [[Rookie]] of the Year.<ref name=\"js7.com\"/>   He was also named one of \"20 Teens Who Will Change the World\" in the April 2003 issue of ''Teen People'' magazine.\n\nStewart went on to win the 2003 125 West Supercross Championship and the 125 East/West Shootout in Las Vegas, Nevada.\n\nIn 2004 he won both the 125 East Supercross title and the 125 Outdoor national title, only losing one moto to Mike Brown in the latter due to a broken clutch cover.\n\n1 of 2 riders in history to win every moto/race in season\nRanked #2 all time SX wins (50).  Ranked #3 all time pro AMA wins (98).  X games medal for best whip.  2002 AMA 125 Motocross national champion.  2003 AMA 125 West Supercross Champion.       2004 AMA 125 East Supercross Champion.  2004 AMA 125 Motocross National Champion.              2006 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion.  2006 Motocross of Nations Champion.             2007 AMA Supercross Champion.  2007 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion.  2008 AMA Motocross National Champion.  2008 Motocross of Nations Champion.  2009 AMA Supercross Champion.         2009 FIM World Supercross Champion.  2014 Redbull Straight Rhythm Champion.  2015 Redbull Straight Rhythm Champion\n\n===Supercross===\n\nOn April 2, 2005, at [[Texas Stadium]] (in only his 3rd  Supercross race), Stewart captured his very first Supercross victory.  He would go on to record many more victories throughout 2005 and 2006, and he eventually won the 2007 Supercross Championship.  He was unable to finish the 2007 National series due to a knee injury.\n[[File:JamesStewartMotorcycleRacerMay2007.jpg|thumb|Stewart in 2007]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! Rnd<br />1\n! Rnd<br />2\n! Rnd<br />3\n! Rnd<br />4\n! Rnd<br />5\n! Rnd<br />6\n! Rnd<br />7\n! Rnd<br />8\n! Rnd<br />9\n! Rnd<br />10\n! Rnd<br />11\n! Rnd<br />12\n! Rnd<br />13\n! Rnd<br />14\n! Rnd<br />15\n! Rnd<br />16\n!valign=\"middle\"| Average<br />Finish\n!valign=\"middle\"| Podium<br />Percent\n!valign=\"middle\"| Place\n|-\n! 2006 SX\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 8\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 17\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 6\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n! 3.25\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|75%\n! 2nd\n|-\n! 2007 SX\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 5\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n! 1.38\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|94%\n! 1st\n|}\n\n====2008====\nStewart missed the last 15 races of the 2008 Supercross season due to a knee injury caused by a crash into Dale White #7.<ref name=\"js7.com\"/>\n\n====2009====\nStewart signed with L&M Yamaha racing for the 2009 season, replacing Chad Reed for the supercross season. In the latter season Stewart and [[Chad Reed]] were involved in the tightest (and sometimes heated) points race of Stewart's career.  Stewart won 11 of the 17 events.  On May 2, 2009, at [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] in Las Vegas, Stewart won the 2009 Supercross Championship by a margin of 4 points over Reed (377-373).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! Rnd<br />1\n! Rnd<br />2\n! Rnd<br />3\n! Rnd<br />4\n! Rnd<br />5\n! Rnd<br />6\n! Rnd<br />7\n! Rnd<br />8\n! Rnd<br />9\n! Rnd<br />10\n! Rnd<br />11\n! Rnd<br />12\n! Rnd<br />13\n! Rnd<br />14\n! Rnd<br />15\n! Rnd<br />16\n! Rnd<br />17\n!valign=\"middle\"| Average<br />Finish\n!valign=\"middle\"| Podium<br />Percent\n!valign=\"middle\"| Place\n|-\n! 2009 SX\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 19\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 7\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n! 4.53\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|88%\n! 1st\n|}\n\n====2010====\nAfter a strong charge by Supercross class rookie [[Ryan Dungey]] at the opening round at Anaheim, Stewart captured the lead on lap 18, going on to take the win . In round 2, Stewart was involved in a crash during his heat, but came back to win the Last Chance Qualifier. In the final, a collision with [[Chad Reed]] caused both riders to fall. Reed's left hand was pinned under Stewart and Reed pushed Stewart's head off his arm, in what some deemed to be a physically aggressive manner. Controversy followed in the pits when Stewart pushed Reed's bike off its stand, resulting in an official warning from the AMA.<ref name=\"motoonline.com.au\">http://www.motoonline.com.au/2010/01/17/ama-sx-dungey-wins-in-phoenix-reed-and-stewart-clash/</ref> Still struggling with injury Stewart finished 3rd behind [[Ryan Dungey]] and Josh Hill in round 3. Stewart retired from the season after having surgery from Dr. [[Arthur Ting]] for a broken right [[scaphoid]].<ref name=\"Hilderbrand\">{{cite news|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/727/5666/Motorcycle-Article/James-Stewart-Out-for-San-Francisco-SX.aspx|title=James Stewart Out for San Francisco SX|last=Hilderbrand|first=JC|date=2010-01-30|work=motorcycle-usa.com|accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref>\n\nStewart's wrist injury took longer than expected to heal, leaving him out of the 2010 Motocross series, although he did return for one round at Unadilla where he placed third in the first moto and retired early from the second moto,<ref name=\"motorcycle-usa.com\">http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/751/7724/Motorcycle-Article/2010-AMA-Motocross-Unadilla-Results.aspx</ref> citing bike setup issues and exhaustion.<ref name=\"vitalmx.com\">http://www.vitalmx.com/news/press-release/Team-San-Manuel-Yamahas-James-Stewart-Withdraws-from-the-Motocross-Outdoor-National-Series-Race-Series,7922</ref>\n\n====2011====\nOn January 8, 2011 Stewart made his return to Supercross placing 3rd in the Anaheim season opener. The next week at Phoenix on January 15, he won his first main event in over a year, leading all 20 laps over [[Ryan Villopoto]], who trailed close behind for most of the race. Throughout the season Stewart suffered several crashes with his last big crash in the season finale at Las Vegas where he had the lead but then crashed in the whoops. He took out [[Kevin Windham]] along with him, allowing Villopoto and Reed to pass  <ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.vitalmx.com/videos/features/Interview-James-Stewart,1451/GuyB,64]</ref>\n\n====2012====\nOn March 10, 2012 Stewart claimed his 44th Supercross win by taking 1st place at Daytona International Speedway.<ref name=\"Stewart Storms To Daytona Win\">{{cite web|url=http://moto-racing.speedtv.com/article/sx-stewart-storms-to-daytona-win/|title=Stewart Storms To Daytona Win|date=March 10, 2012|work=SPEED Channel|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=2012-03-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312085854/http://moto-racing.speedtv.com/article/sx-stewart-storms-to-daytona-win/|archivedate=March 12, 2012}}</ref> At the end of the season, Stewart left Joe Gibbs Motocross Racing.<ref name=\"Leistikow\">{{cite news|last=Leistikow|first=Chad|title=Supercross star James Stewart splits with Joe Gibbs Racing|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/story/2012-05-06/James-Stewart-out-at-Joe-Gibbs-Racing/54787158/1|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=May 7, 2012|date=May 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\nOn January 5, 2013, after an unsuccessful finish of the 2012 AMA Motocross Series, Stewart made his return to Supercross with his new Yoshimura Suzuki bike. Although having a sore right knee and in pain, he  finishes 8th in the Main Event at the Anaheim season opener. He got back up in Atlanta winning the main event, leading all 20 laps. Throughout the season, Stewart had several crashes, including at the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome|Metrodome]], in Minneapolis, where he had the lead in the Heat Race, but crashed in the rhythm section near the Mechanics Area. He did come back with a win in the LCQ. In the Main Event, Stewart was injured again, this time tweaking his wrist and retired on Lap 7. Consequently, Stewart was  out for the remainder of the three rounds of the 2013 AMA Supercross Series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Poelman|first1=Ryan|title=JAMES STEWART OUT FOR REMAINDER OF 2013 SUPERCROSS SEASON|url=http://supercross.com/james-stewart-out-for-remainder-of-2013-supercross-season-3/|website=supercross.com|publisher=Supercross.com, LLC|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 19, 2013 Stewart raced the [[Monster Energy Cup (Supercross)|Monster Energy Cup]] for the first time at Sam Boyd Stadium in Las Vegas. Having a bad start in the first heat, he fought up to 8th. In the second heat he took the holeshot and was battling hard with Villopoto, beating Villopoto due to a hard crash on the Last Lap after missing the Joker Lane. In the third heat, James fought hard past Ken Roczen and took the 3rd moto win. On the Final Lap, Stewart took the Joker Lane twice on second and third Motos, before crossing the finish line. He won the overall and the $100,000 payout. come back to racing james stewart\n\n====2014====\nComing off an  overall win in the Monster Energy Cup, Stewart was now a  title threat for the 2014 Supercross Championship. On January 4, 2014 at Angel Stadium at A1 Stewart starts mid pack and works his way up to the leader Ken Roczen. With only 5 laps to go, he has a big crash in the whoops. He would finish seventeenth. At San Diego on February 8, he won his first main event for 2014 and went on to win 5 more main events, including a win in Toronto to pass [[Ricky Carmichael]] for second in all-time wins in Supercross. Stewart made the podium 8 times and finished the season in 3rd place.\n\n====2015====\nStewart was suspended for 16 months for failing an anti-doping test.  Stewart, who is medically prescribed Adderall, failed to submit the proper paperwork for a [[Therapeutic Use Exemption]] (TUE).<ref>http://www.vitalmx.com/features/Breaking-News-James-Stewart-Suspended,3666</ref> Stewart missed the entire 2015 Supercross season and the 2015 Lucas Oil Pro Motocross Championship series.\n\nFollowing his suspension, Stewart returned to race the single-day Monster Energy Cup in Las Vegas, NV. After a crash in the first of three rounds however, Stewart did not start the following motos.\n\n====2016====\nStewart returned for Anaheim 1 at the start of the 2016 Supercross season. However, in the main event a first lap mishap by Ryan Dungey caused Stewart to crash. Stewart was knocked unconscious and suffered a concussion. Although no official retirement has been announced, Stewart has not returned to racing since this injury.\n\n====2019====\n\nMay 17 2019 James Stewart announced his retirement saying \u201cWhere I\u2019m at in my life, I think it\u2019s time to say I\u2019m retiring. I\u2019ve retired,\u201d he said in part. \u201cIt\u2019s hard for sure, because I love racing and I love the fans, I love the opening ceremonies, I love the autograph lines, but I don\u2019t miss the sweat and tears and training and having to feel like you have to win every race and having to be James Stewart. I don\u2019t love doing that anymore.\u201d\n\n===Motocross class===\n\n====2005====\nAMA 250 class 10th overall <ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/2005/mx/points</ref>\n\n====2006====\nAMA 4th overall <ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/2006/mx/points</ref>\n\n====2007====\nAMA 7th overall <ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/2007/mx/points</ref>\n\n====2008====\nHaving missed the entire Supercross season, he returned to racing at the first round of the outdoor nationals and went on to win all 24 motos and thus the championship.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! Rnd<br />1\n! Rnd<br />2\n! Rnd<br />3\n! Rnd<br />4\n! Rnd<br />5\n! Rnd<br />6\n! Rnd<br />7\n! Rnd<br />8\n! Rnd<br />9\n! Rnd<br />10\n! Rnd<br />11\n! Rnd<br />12\n!valign=\"middle\"| Average<br />Finish\n!valign=\"middle\"| Podium<br />Percent\n!valign=\"middle\"| Place\n|-\n! 2008 MX\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n| 1.00\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|100%\n! 1st\n|}\n\n====2009====\nStewart did not compete in the 2009 Motocross series.<ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/rider/james-stewart/races</ref>\n\n====2010====\nA wrist injury sustained in the Supercross season prevented Stewart from competing in the 2010 Motocross series although he did return for one round at Unadilla where he placed second in the first moto and retired early from the second moto,<ref name=\"motorcycle-usa.com\"/> citing bike setup issues and exhaustion.<ref name=\"vitalmx.com\"/>\n\n====2011====\nStewart chose not to race the 2011 National season citing lack of preparation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://js7.com/2011/05/news-about-the-motocross-season/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110731063835/http://js7.com/2011/05/news-about-the-motocross-season/ |archivedate=2011-07-31 }}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nOne day after announcing his split from JGRMX and [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]], Stewart signed to ride with Yoshimura [[Suzuki]] aboard their RMZ-450. Stewart won the first four motos of the season. However, during Round 3 of Thunder Valley in Colorado, Stewart was leading when a person ran across the track in front of him, causing him to crash. The result of the crash was a serious injury is his right hand breaking his wrist. Consequently, he was unable to finish the rest of the Motocross series due to the extent of the injury. Though he did come back at some point in Red Bud, but due to multiple injuries, Stewart will not race for the rest of the 2012 AMA Motocross Series until he gets 100% healthy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Waheed|first=Adam|title=James Stewart Signs with Yoshimura Suzuki|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/834/13035/Motorcycle-Article/James-Stewart-Signs-with-Yoshimura-Suzuki.aspx|publisher=Motorcycle USA|accessdate=May 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\nThe 2013 Season was a three-way battle with Stewart, [[Ryan Villopoto]] and [[Ryan Dungey]]. [[Chad Reed]] was thought to be the main show for the title, even though he struggled to ride hard and pass for the lead. Throughout the season, Stewart had several crashes including Motocross 338 in Southwick, Massachusetts, where he had the lead halfway through, but crashed in the sand section in Moto 1 ending up finishing in 34th place. He did come back to finish 4th in Moto 2 making him 5th place overall. Stewart struggles to ride hard, riding though a neck injury.\n               -\n\n==Total career AMA wins==\n*28 wins in 125/250 AMA Motocross 10-2002 7-2003 11-2004\n*50 wins in 450 AMA Supercross 3-2005 8-2006 13-2007 1-2008 11-2009 1-2010 5-2011 2-2012 1-2013 5-2014\n*20 wins in 250/450 AMA Motocross 3-2006 1-2007 12-2008 2-2012 1-2013 1-2014\n*98 total AMA wins 10-2002 7-2003 11-2004 3-2005 11-2006 14-2007 13-2008 11-2009 1-2010 5-2011 4-2012 2-2013 5-2014\n\n===X Games===\nStewart made his X Games debut on July 30, 2009 at [[X Games XV]], and placed second in the best whip competition with 21% of the votes winning his first X Games medal.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/action/news/story?id=4367862]</ref>\n\nHe suffered a deep bruise to his bone and muscle in his left shoulder during seeding trials for SuperMoto on July 31, forcing him to drop out of the games.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/outposts/2009/07/james-stewart-suffers-shoulder-injury-and-is-out-of-x-games.html | work=The Los Angeles Times | title=Outposts | date=July 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Reality TV show===\n\nOn March 28, 2010 Stewart's reality show \u201cBubba\u2019s World\u201d debuted and ran 10 episodes. The show got mixed reviews, due in part to Stewart\u2019s somewhat self-centered actions throughout the show.   The second season started in December, offered 13 episodes and concluded Feb. 24. There has been no announcement about a third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_tv_tvblog/2011/03/bubbas-world-whats-its-status.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401182203/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_tv_tvblog/2011/03/bubbas-world-whats-its-status.html |archivedate=2011-04-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Gibbs and NASCAR==\n\nIn October 2011, Stewart signed to race for [[Joe Gibbs Racing]], with a multiyear contract to run for [[JGRMX]] in motocross as well as plans to run [[NASCAR]] [[stock car]] races in the [[K&N Pro Series East]] and [[Nationwide Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/story/2011-10-24/Motocross-James-Stewart-joins-Joe-Gibbs-Racing-with-eye-on-NASCAR/50895284/1|title=Motocross' James Stewart joins Gibbs team with eye on NASCAR|last=Ryan|first=Nate|date=October 24, 2011|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Co.|accessdate=2011-10-26|location=McLean, VA}}</ref> At the end of the [[2012 Supercross Season]], Stewart left Joe Gibbs Racing and JGRMX. Stewart said that he would be open to racing with Gibbs in the future, but stated that he wanted to get back to being competitive in motorcycle racing, and that a change was necessary.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leistikow|first=Chad|title=Supercross star James Stewart splits with Joe Gibbs Racing|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/story/2012-05-06/James-Stewart-out-at-Joe-Gibbs-Racing/54787158/1|publisher=USA Today|date=May 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.js7.com}}\n* [[Dirt Rider]] Magazine: [https://web.archive.org/web/20081007105905/http://www.dirtrider.com/features/141_0810_james_stewart_kyle_chisolm/index.html \"James Stewart and Kyle Chisolm racing Team San Manuel L&M Racing Yamahas\"]\n*[https://archive.is/20130418222014/http://www.fuel.tv/bubbasworld/2010/2/bubbas-world-premiers-march-28-on-fuel-tv/ FUEL TV Series]\n{{Commons category|James Stewart Jr.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, James Jr.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bartow, Florida]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Florida]]\n[[Category:American motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:Motocross riders]]\n[[Category:AMA Motocross Championship National Champions]]\n[[Category:NASCAR drivers]]\n[[Category:African-American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in motorcycle racing]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople in doping cases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American motorcycle racer}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Peacock|date=December 2009}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2008}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = James Stewart Jr\n| image          = Stewart Anahiem04.jpg\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = James Bubba Stewart\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = American\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|12|21}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bartow, Florida|Bartow]], [[Florida]]\n| height         = {{convert|5|ft|7|in|m}}<ref name=\"musa\">http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/493/1094/Motorcycle-Article/James-Stewart-Bio.aspx</ref>\n| weight         = {{convert|161|lb|kg}}<ref name=\"musa\"/>\n| sport          = [[Motocross]]\n| event          = [[Supercross]]\n\n<!-- achievements-->\n| worlds         = 2006 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion<br />\n2007 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion<br />\n2006 Motocross of Nations Champion<br />\n2008 Motocross of Nations Champion\n2009 FIM World Supercross Champion\n| nationals      = 2002 AMA 125 Motocross national champion\n<br />\n2004 AMA 125 Motocross National Champion<br />\n2007 AMA Supercross Champion<br />\n2008 AMA Motocross National Champion<br />\n2009 AMA Supercross Champion\n| regionals      = 2003 AMA 125 West Supercross Champion<br />\n2004 AMA 125 East Supercross Champion\n| updated     = 30 July 2009\n}}\n\n'''James Stewart Jr.''' (born December 21, 1985), also known as '''Bubba Stewart''', is an [[Americans|American]] former professional [[motocross]] racer who competed in the [[AMA Motocross Championship|AMA Motocross]] and the [[AMA Supercross Championship]]s. Through his years of racing, he earned the nickname \u201cThe Fastest Man on The Planet\u201d, due to his extraordinary talent, speed, athleticism and innovation.  \n\nIn 2008 James won every race and every moto of the AMA Motocross season. The only other person to do this is Ricky Carmichael, who had perfect seasons in 2002 and 2004. James is second in all time 450 Supercross wins (50), and second all time in AMA outdoor national wins (48). He is also known for innovating the \"Bubba Scrub\" or just \"scrub\", which revolutionized the sport and became a fundamental skill needed to compete in Professional Motocross. He was the first to host his own television show \"Bubba's World\" which brought even more attention to the sport. He is arguably the most financially lucrative racer, bringing in endorsement deals paying him over $10M a year throughout his career. Known for his vibrant personality and big smile, James has been featured in news outlets like Rolling Stone, The New York Times, Maxim, ESPN The Magazine, GQ and many more. Additionally, Teen People named him one of \u201c20 Teens Who Will Change the World\u201d. He has the record for best rookie season, having won 10/12 Motocross races in 2002. \n\nJames has 5 FIM World Champion titles from Motocross of Nations, and World Supercross.  4 AMA Supercross Champion titles, and 3 AMA Motocross Champion titles. He won the Redbull Straight Rhythm in both 2014 and 2015. He's a Motocross legend who battled the greats of multiple era's.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Amateur and Lites Class===\nStewart was born in [[Bartow, Florida]]<ref name=\"musa\"/> and currently resides in [[Haine City Lake Hamilton, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amasupercross.com/riders/Bio.aspx?id=553278 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707125048/http://www.amasupercross.com/riders/bio.aspx?id=553278 |archivedate=2011-07-07 }}</ref> His father, James Sr., was a [[motocross]] enthusiast and introduced his son to the sport at the age of three. Stewart entered his first motocross race when he was four years old.<ref name=\"js7.com\">{{cite web |url=http://js7.com/bio/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731215303/http://js7.com/bio/ |archivedate=2009-07-31 }}</ref>\n\nHaving 84 amateur wins and 7 [[Loretta Lynn's Amateur Championship]]s all before the age of 16, he debuted as pro in 2002. While crashes and rookie mistakes kept him from winning the 2002 125 West Supercross title, he finished 2nd overall. He went on to dominate the 2002 Motocross Championship, and was named the 2002 AMA [[Rookie]] of the Year.<ref name=\"js7.com\"/>   He was also named one of \"20 Teens Who Will Change the World\" in the April 2003 issue of ''Teen People'' magazine.\n\nStewart went on to win the 2003 125 West Supercross Championship and the 125 East/West Shootout in Las Vegas, Nevada.\n\nIn 2004 he won both the 125 East Supercross title and the 125 Outdoor national title, only losing one moto to Mike Brown in the latter due to a broken clutch cover.\n\n1 of 2 riders in history to win every moto/race in season\nRanked #2 all time SX wins (50).  Ranked #3 all time pro AMA wins (98).  X games medal for best whip.  2002 AMA 125 Motocross national champion.  2003 AMA 125 West Supercross Champion.       2004 AMA 125 East Supercross Champion.  2004 AMA 125 Motocross National Champion.              2006 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion.  2006 Motocross of Nations Champion.             2007 AMA Supercross Champion.  2007 FIM World Supercross Grand Prix Champion.  2008 AMA Motocross National Champion.  2008 Motocross of Nations Champion.  2009 AMA Supercross Champion.         2009 FIM World Supercross Champion.  2014 Redbull Straight Rhythm Champion.  2015 Redbull Straight Rhythm Champion\n\n===Supercross===\n\nOn April 2, 2005, at [[Texas Stadium]] (in only his 3rd  Supercross race), Stewart captured his very first Supercross victory.  He would go on to record many more victories throughout 2005 and 2006, and he eventually won the 2007 Supercross Championship.  He was unable to finish the 2007 National series due to a knee injury.\n[[File:JamesStewartMotorcycleRacerMay2007.jpg|thumb|Stewart in 2007]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! Rnd<br />1\n! Rnd<br />2\n! Rnd<br />3\n! Rnd<br />4\n! Rnd<br />5\n! Rnd<br />6\n! Rnd<br />7\n! Rnd<br />8\n! Rnd<br />9\n! Rnd<br />10\n! Rnd<br />11\n! Rnd<br />12\n! Rnd<br />13\n! Rnd<br />14\n! Rnd<br />15\n! Rnd<br />16\n!valign=\"middle\"| Average<br />Finish\n!valign=\"middle\"| Podium<br />Percent\n!valign=\"middle\"| Place\n|-\n! 2006 SX\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 8\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 17\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 6\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n! 3.25\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|75%\n! 2nd\n|-\n! 2007 SX\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 5\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n! 1.38\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|94%\n! 1st\n|}\n\n====2008====\nStewart missed the last 15 races of the 2008 Supercross season due to a knee injury caused by a crash into Dale White #7.<ref name=\"js7.com\"/>\n\n====2009====\nStewart signed with L&M Yamaha racing for the 2009 season, replacing Chad Reed for the supercross season. In the latter season Stewart and [[Chad Reed]] were involved in the tightest (and sometimes heated) points race of Stewart's career.  Stewart won 11 of the 17 events.  On May 2, 2009, at [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] in Las Vegas, Stewart won the 2009 Supercross Championship by a margin of 4 points over Reed (377-373).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! Rnd<br />1\n! Rnd<br />2\n! Rnd<br />3\n! Rnd<br />4\n! Rnd<br />5\n! Rnd<br />6\n! Rnd<br />7\n! Rnd<br />8\n! Rnd<br />9\n! Rnd<br />10\n! Rnd<br />11\n! Rnd<br />12\n! Rnd<br />13\n! Rnd<br />14\n! Rnd<br />15\n! Rnd<br />16\n! Rnd<br />17\n!valign=\"middle\"| Average<br />Finish\n!valign=\"middle\"| Podium<br />Percent\n!valign=\"middle\"| Place\n|-\n! 2009 SX\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 19\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 7\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 2\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 3\n! 4.53\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|88%\n! 1st\n|}\n\n====2010====\nAfter a strong charge by Supercross class rookie [[Ryan Dungey]] at the opening round at Anaheim, Stewart captured the lead on lap 18, going on to take the win . In round 2, Stewart was involved in a crash during his heat, but came back to win the Last Chance Qualifier. In the final, a collision with [[Chad Reed]] caused both riders to fall. Reed's left hand was pinned under Stewart and Reed pushed Stewart's head off his arm, in what some deemed to be a physically aggressive manner. Controversy followed in the pits when Stewart pushed Reed's bike off its stand, resulting in an official warning from the AMA.<ref name=\"motoonline.com.au\">http://www.motoonline.com.au/2010/01/17/ama-sx-dungey-wins-in-phoenix-reed-and-stewart-clash/</ref> Still struggling with injury Stewart finished 3rd behind [[Ryan Dungey]] and Josh Hill in round 3. Stewart retired from the season after having surgery from Dr. [[Arthur Ting]] for a broken right [[scaphoid]].<ref name=\"Hilderbrand\">{{cite news|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/727/5666/Motorcycle-Article/James-Stewart-Out-for-San-Francisco-SX.aspx|title=James Stewart Out for San Francisco SX|last=Hilderbrand|first=JC|date=2010-01-30|work=motorcycle-usa.com|accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref>\n\nStewart's wrist injury took longer than expected to heal, leaving him out of the 2010 Motocross series, although he did return for one round at Unadilla where he placed third in the first moto and retired early from the second moto,<ref name=\"motorcycle-usa.com\">http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/751/7724/Motorcycle-Article/2010-AMA-Motocross-Unadilla-Results.aspx</ref> citing bike setup issues and exhaustion.<ref name=\"vitalmx.com\">http://www.vitalmx.com/news/press-release/Team-San-Manuel-Yamahas-James-Stewart-Withdraws-from-the-Motocross-Outdoor-National-Series-Race-Series,7922</ref>\n\n====2011====\nOn January 8, 2011 Stewart made his return to Supercross placing 3rd in the Anaheim season opener. The next week at Phoenix on January 15, he won his first main event in over a year, leading all 20 laps over [[Ryan Villopoto]], who trailed close behind for most of the race. Throughout the season Stewart suffered several crashes with his last big crash in the season finale at Las Vegas where he had the lead but then crashed in the whoops. He took out [[Kevin Windham]] along with him, allowing Villopoto and Reed to pass  <ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.vitalmx.com/videos/features/Interview-James-Stewart,1451/GuyB,64]</ref>\n\n====2012====\nOn March 10, 2012 Stewart claimed his 44th Supercross win by taking 1st place at Daytona International Speedway.<ref name=\"Stewart Storms To Daytona Win\">{{cite web|url=http://moto-racing.speedtv.com/article/sx-stewart-storms-to-daytona-win/|title=Stewart Storms To Daytona Win|date=March 10, 2012|work=SPEED Channel|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=2012-03-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312085854/http://moto-racing.speedtv.com/article/sx-stewart-storms-to-daytona-win/|archivedate=March 12, 2012}}</ref> At the end of the season, Stewart left Joe Gibbs Motocross Racing.<ref name=\"Leistikow\">{{cite news|last=Leistikow|first=Chad|title=Supercross star James Stewart splits with Joe Gibbs Racing|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/story/2012-05-06/James-Stewart-out-at-Joe-Gibbs-Racing/54787158/1|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=May 7, 2012|date=May 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\nOn January 5, 2013, after an unsuccessful finish of the 2012 AMA Motocross Series, Stewart made his return to Supercross with his new Yoshimura Suzuki bike. Although having a sore right knee and in pain, he  finishes 8th in the Main Event at the Anaheim season opener. He got back up in Atlanta winning the main event, leading all 20 laps. Throughout the season, Stewart had several crashes, including at the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome|Metrodome]], in Minneapolis, where he had the lead in the Heat Race, but crashed in the rhythm section near the Mechanics Area. He did come back with a win in the LCQ. In the Main Event, Stewart was injured again, this time tweaking his wrist and retired on Lap 7. Consequently, Stewart was  out for the remainder of the three rounds of the 2013 AMA Supercross Series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Poelman|first1=Ryan|title=JAMES STEWART OUT FOR REMAINDER OF 2013 SUPERCROSS SEASON|url=http://supercross.com/james-stewart-out-for-remainder-of-2013-supercross-season-3/|website=supercross.com|publisher=Supercross.com, LLC|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 19, 2013 Stewart raced the [[Monster Energy Cup (Supercross)|Monster Energy Cup]] for the first time at Sam Boyd Stadium in Las Vegas. Having a bad start in the first heat, he fought up to 8th. In the second heat he took the holeshot and was battling hard with Villopoto, beating Villopoto due to a hard crash on the Last Lap after missing the Joker Lane. In the third heat, James fought hard past Ken Roczen and took the 3rd moto win. On the Final Lap, Stewart took the Joker Lane twice on second and third Motos, before crossing the finish line. He won the overall and the $100,000 payout. come back to racing james stewart\n\n====2014====\nComing off an  overall win in the Monster Energy Cup, Stewart was now a  title threat for the 2014 Supercross Championship. On January 4, 2014 at Angel Stadium at A1 Stewart starts mid pack and works his way up to the leader Ken Roczen. With only 5 laps to go, he has a big crash in the whoops. He would finish seventeenth. At San Diego on February 8, he won his first main event for 2014 and went on to win 5 more main events, including a win in Toronto to pass [[Ricky Carmichael]] for second in all-time wins in Supercross. Stewart made the podium 8 times and finished the season in 3rd place.\n\n====2015====\nStewart was suspended for 16 months for failing an anti-doping test.  Stewart, who is medically prescribed Adderall, failed to submit the proper paperwork for a [[Therapeutic Use Exemption]] (TUE).<ref>http://www.vitalmx.com/features/Breaking-News-James-Stewart-Suspended,3666</ref> Stewart missed the entire 2015 Supercross season and the 2015 Lucas Oil Pro Motocross Championship series.\n\nFollowing his suspension, Stewart returned to race the single-day Monster Energy Cup in Las Vegas, NV. After a crash in the first of three rounds however, Stewart did not start the following motos.\n\n====2016====\nStewart returned for Anaheim 1 at the start of the 2016 Supercross season. However, in the main event a first lap mishap by Ryan Dungey caused Stewart to crash. Stewart was knocked unconscious and suffered a concussion. Although no official retirement has been announced, Stewart has not returned to racing since this injury.\n\n====2019====\n\nMay 17 2019 James Stewart announced his retirement saying \u201cWhere I\u2019m at in my life, I think it\u2019s time to say I\u2019m retiring. I\u2019ve retired,\u201d he said in part. \u201cIt\u2019s hard for sure, because I love racing and I love the fans, I love the opening ceremonies, I love the autograph lines, but I don\u2019t miss the sweat and tears and training and having to feel like you have to win every race and having to be James Stewart. I don\u2019t love doing that anymore.\u201d\n\n===Motocross class===\n\n====2005====\nAMA 250 class 10th overall <ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/2005/mx/points</ref>\n\n====2006====\nAMA 4th overall <ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/2006/mx/points</ref>\n\n====2007====\nAMA 7th overall <ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/2007/mx/points</ref>\n\n====2008====\nHaving missed the entire Supercross season, he returned to racing at the first round of the outdoor nationals and went on to win all 24 motos and thus the championship.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! Rnd<br />1\n! Rnd<br />2\n! Rnd<br />3\n! Rnd<br />4\n! Rnd<br />5\n! Rnd<br />6\n! Rnd<br />7\n! Rnd<br />8\n! Rnd<br />9\n! Rnd<br />10\n! Rnd<br />11\n! Rnd<br />12\n!valign=\"middle\"| Average<br />Finish\n!valign=\"middle\"| Podium<br />Percent\n!valign=\"middle\"| Place\n|-\n! 2008 MX\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 1\n| 1.00\n! style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"|100%\n! 1st\n|}\n\n====2009====\nStewart did not compete in the 2009 Motocross series.<ref>http://vault.racerxonline.com/rider/james-stewart/races</ref>\n\n====2010====\nA wrist injury sustained in the Supercross season prevented Stewart from competing in the 2010 Motocross series although he did return for one round at Unadilla where he placed second in the first moto and retired early from the second moto,<ref name=\"motorcycle-usa.com\"/> citing bike setup issues and exhaustion.<ref name=\"vitalmx.com\"/>\n\n====2011====\nStewart chose not to race the 2011 National season citing lack of preparation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://js7.com/2011/05/news-about-the-motocross-season/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110731063835/http://js7.com/2011/05/news-about-the-motocross-season/ |archivedate=2011-07-31 }}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nOne day after announcing his split from JGRMX and [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]], Stewart signed to ride with Yoshimura [[Suzuki]] aboard their RMZ-450. Stewart won the first four motos of the season. However, during Round 3 of Thunder Valley in Colorado, Stewart was leading when a person ran across the track in front of him, causing him to crash. The result of the crash was a serious injury is his right hand breaking his wrist. Consequently, he was unable to finish the rest of the Motocross series due to the extent of the injury. Though he did come back at some point in Red Bud, but due to multiple injuries, Stewart will not race for the rest of the 2012 AMA Motocross Series until he gets 100% healthy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Waheed|first=Adam|title=James Stewart Signs with Yoshimura Suzuki|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/834/13035/Motorcycle-Article/James-Stewart-Signs-with-Yoshimura-Suzuki.aspx|publisher=Motorcycle USA|accessdate=May 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\nThe 2013 Season was a three-way battle with Stewart, [[Ryan Villopoto]] and [[Ryan Dungey]]. [[Chad Reed]] was thought to be the main show for the title, even though he struggled to ride hard and pass for the lead. Throughout the season, Stewart had several crashes including Motocross 338 in Southwick, Massachusetts, where he had the lead halfway through, but crashed in the sand section in Moto 1 ending up finishing in 34th place. He did come back to finish 4th in Moto 2 making him 5th place overall. Stewart struggles to ride hard, riding though a neck injury.\n               -\n\n==Total career AMA wins==\n*28 wins in 125/250 AMA Motocross 10-2002 7-2003 11-2004\n*50 wins in 450 AMA Supercross 3-2005 8-2006 13-2007 1-2008 11-2009 1-2010 5-2011 2-2012 1-2013 5-2014\n*20 wins in 250/450 AMA Motocross 3-2006 1-2007 12-2008 2-2012 1-2013 1-2014\n*98 total AMA wins 10-2002 7-2003 11-2004 3-2005 11-2006 14-2007 13-2008 11-2009 1-2010 5-2011 4-2012 2-2013 5-2014\n\n===X Games===\nStewart made his X Games debut on July 30, 2009 at [[X Games XV]], and placed second in the best whip competition with 21% of the votes winning his first X Games medal.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/action/news/story?id=4367862]</ref>\n\nHe suffered a deep bruise to his bone and muscle in his left shoulder during seeding trials for SuperMoto on July 31, forcing him to drop out of the games.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/outposts/2009/07/james-stewart-suffers-shoulder-injury-and-is-out-of-x-games.html | work=The Los Angeles Times | title=Outposts | date=July 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Reality TV show===\n\nOn March 28, 2010 Stewart's reality show \u201cBubba\u2019s World\u201d debuted and ran 10 episodes. The show got mixed reviews, due in part to Stewart\u2019s somewhat self-centered actions throughout the show.   The second season started in December, offered 13 episodes and concluded Feb. 24. There has been no announcement about a third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_tv_tvblog/2011/03/bubbas-world-whats-its-status.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401182203/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_tv_tvblog/2011/03/bubbas-world-whats-its-status.html |archivedate=2011-04-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Gibbs and NASCAR==\n\nIn October 2011, Stewart signed to race for [[Joe Gibbs Racing]], with a multiyear contract to run for [[JGRMX]] in motocross as well as plans to run [[NASCAR]] [[stock car]] races in the [[K&N Pro Series East]] and [[Nationwide Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/story/2011-10-24/Motocross-James-Stewart-joins-Joe-Gibbs-Racing-with-eye-on-NASCAR/50895284/1|title=Motocross' James Stewart joins Gibbs team with eye on NASCAR|last=Ryan|first=Nate|date=October 24, 2011|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Co.|accessdate=2011-10-26|location=McLean, VA}}</ref> At the end of the [[2012 Supercross Season]], Stewart left Joe Gibbs Racing and JGRMX. Stewart said that he would be open to racing with Gibbs in the future, but stated that he wanted to get back to being competitive in motorcycle racing, and that a change was necessary.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leistikow|first=Chad|title=Supercross star James Stewart splits with Joe Gibbs Racing|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/story/2012-05-06/James-Stewart-out-at-Joe-Gibbs-Racing/54787158/1|publisher=USA Today|date=May 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.js7.com}}\n* [[Dirt Rider]] Magazine: [https://web.archive.org/web/20081007105905/http://www.dirtrider.com/features/141_0810_james_stewart_kyle_chisolm/index.html \"James Stewart and Kyle Chisolm racing Team San Manuel L&M Racing Yamahas\"]\n*[https://archive.is/20130418222014/http://www.fuel.tv/bubbasworld/2010/2/bubbas-world-premiers-march-28-on-fuel-tv/ FUEL TV Series]\n{{Commons category|James Stewart Jr.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, James Jr.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bartow, Florida]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Florida]]\n[[Category:American motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:Motocross riders]]\n[[Category:AMA Motocross Championship National Champions]]\n[[Category:NASCAR drivers]]\n[[Category:African-American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in motorcycle racing]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople in doping cases]]\n", "name_user": "207.213.183.236", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Stewart_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge", "text_new": "{{Redirect2|Verrazzano Narrows|Verrazzano Bridge|the strait over which this bridge crosses|The Narrows|other bridges|Verrazano Bridge (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Suspension bridge crossing the Narrows between Brooklyn and Staten Island, New York}}\n{{good article}}<!-- Sources' titles and image names that already contain \"Verrazano\" should not be changed to \"Verrazzano\", as these would be incorrect. -->\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name= Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n|image= StatenIsland-13 (36416067785).jpg\n|image_upright = 1.1\n|alt=View of one of the bridge's towers\n|image_caption = \n|also_known_as=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge<br />Verrazzano Bridge<br />Narrows Bridge\n|designer= [[Othmar Ammann]]\n|carries= 13 lanes of {{jct|state=NY|I|278}}<br />(7 lanes on upper level: 6 fixed-direction, 1 reversible [[High-occupancy vehicle lane|HOV lane]];<br />6 lanes on lower level)\n|crosses= [[The Narrows]]\n|locale= [[New York City]] ([[Staten Island]]\u2013[[Brooklyn]]), New York\n|maint= [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]]\n|id=\n|mainspan= {{cvt|4260|ft|m|0}}\n|length= {{cvt|13700|ft|m|0}}\n|height= {{cvt|693|ft|m|0}}\n|width= {{cvt|103|ft|m|0}}\n|clearance= {{cvt|15|ft|m|2}} (upper level)<br />{{cvt|14.4|ft|m|2}} (lower level)\n|below= {{cvt|228|ft|m|1}} at mean high water\n|traffic=202,523 (2016)<ref name=\"nycdot16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/nyc-bridge-traffic-report-2016.pdf|title=New York City Bridge Traffic Volumes|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|publisher=New York City Department of Transportation|page=11|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|begin= {{start date and age|1959|8|13}}\n|open={{start date and age|1964|11|21}} (upper level)<br />{{start date and age|1969|06|28}} (lower level)\n|closed=\n|toll= {{As of|2019|3|31|df=US}}:<ref>{{cite web | title=Car Toll Rates | publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (MTA) | url=https://new.mta.info/fares-and-tolls/bridges-and-tunnels/tolls-by-vehicle/cars | access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n{{unbulleted list|$12.24 (New York [[E-ZPass]] users outside Staten Island)|$5.50 (Staten Island residents E-ZPass)|$19.00 (Tolls By Mail and non-New York E-ZPass)|\n$3.40 (Staten Island resident carpool HOV E-ZPass)}}\n|coordinates = {{coord|40|36|23|N|74|02|44|W|region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| map_relief = no \n| map_cue =\n| map_image = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=300|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.60633|-74.04545}}}} \n| map_text =\n| map_width =\n| map_caption = Location within New York City\n}}\nThe '''Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge''' ({{IPAc-en|v|\u0259r|\u0259|\u02c8|z|\u0251\u02d0|n|o\u028a}} {{respell|v\u0259r|\u0259|ZAH|noh}}) (also referred to as the '''Verrazzano Bridge''', locally as the '''Verrazzano''', and formerly as the '''Verrazano-Narrows Bridge''' or '''Narrows Bridge''') is the longest [[suspension bridge]] in the Western Hemisphere, connecting the [[Boroughs of New York City|New York City boroughs]] of [[Staten Island]] and [[Brooklyn]]. It spans [[the Narrows]], a body of water linking the relatively enclosed [[Upper New York Bay]] with [[Lower New York Bay]] and the Atlantic Ocean, and is the only fixed crossing of the Narrows. The [[double-deck bridge]] carries 13 lanes of [[Interstate 278]], with seven lanes on the upper level and six on the lower level. The span is named for [[Giovanni da Verrazzano]], the first documented European explorer to enter [[New York Harbor]] and the [[Hudson River]] in 1524.\n\nEngineer [[David B. Steinman]] proposed a bridge across the Narrows in the late 1920s, and subsequent proposals were deferred over the next 20 years. A 1920s attempt to build a [[Staten Island Tunnel|rail tunnel under the Narrows]] was aborted, as was another 1930s plan for vehicular tubes underneath the Narrows. Discussion of a tunnel resurfaced in the mid-1930s and early 1940s, but the plans were again denied. In the late 1940s, urban planner [[Robert Moses]] championed a bridge across the Narrows as a way to connect Staten Island with the rest of the city. Various issues delayed the start of construction until 1959. The bridge opened on November 21, 1964, and a lower deck was opened in June 1969 to alleviate high levels of traffic. The New York City government began a $1.5{{nbsp}}billion reconstruction of the bridge's two decks in 2014.\n\nThe Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge has a central span of {{convert|4260|ft|km mi|2}}. It was the [[List of longest suspension bridge spans|longest suspension bridge]] in the world until it was surpassed by the [[Humber Bridge]] in the United Kingdom in 1981. The bridge has the 14th-longest main span in the world, as well as the longest in America. When the bridge was officially named in 1960, it was misspelled \"Verrazano-Narrows Bridge\" due to an error in the construction contract, despite the explorer's name having two \"z\"s.<ref name=\"sim\" /> The name was officially corrected to \"Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\" in October 2018.<ref name=\"Campanile 2018\"/>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early plans ===\n\n==== Liberty Bridge ====\n[[File:The Narrows - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|alt=View of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge looking south from Upper New York Bay. The neighborhood of Coney Island in Brooklyn can be seen in the distance.|View of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge from [[Upper New York Bay]], with [[Coney Island]] in the distance]]\nA bridge across the Narrows had been proposed as early as 1926 or 1927, when structural engineer [[David B. Steinman]] brought up the possibility of such a crossing.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|135}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/06/07/archives/asks-suburban-aid-in-regional-plan-committee-urges-cooperation-in.html|title=Asks Suburban Aid In Regional Plan; Committee Urges Cooperation In Furthering Important Public Improvements|date=June 7, 1927|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> At the time, [[Staten Island]] was isolated from the rest of New York City, and its only direct connection to the other four boroughs was by the [[Staten Island Ferry]] to [[South Ferry (Manhattan)|South Ferry]] in [[Manhattan]], or 39th and 69th Streets in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/57555256/|title=The Future Staten Island|last=|first=|date=September 28, 1924|work=[[Brooklyn Eagle|The Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|access-date=September 19, 2017|page=65|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> In 1928, when the chambers of commerce in Brooklyn, [[Queens]], [[Long Island]], and Staten Island announced that the Interboro Bridge Company had proposed the future construction of the \"Liberty Bridge\" to [[United States Department of War]]. The bridge's towers would be {{Convert|800|ft|m}} high and it would cost $60{{nbsp}}million in 1928 dollars.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|136}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/05/02/archives/offer-to-span-narrows-four-ccmmerce-chambers-would-later-give.html|title=Offer To Span Narrows; Four Commerce Chambers Would Later Give Bridge To City.|date=May 2, 1928|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>  In November 1929, engineers released plans for the {{Convert|4500|ft|m|adj=on}} Liberty Bridge spanning the Narrows,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/11/17/archives/span-of-4500-feet-in-narrows-bridge-proposed-60000000-bridge-over.html|title=Span of 4,500 Feet in Narrows Bridge; Proposed $60,000,000 Bridge Over Narrows.|date=November 17, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> with 800-foot-tall towers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/11/14/archives/towers-of-bridge-to-rise-800-feet-db-steinman-engineer-tells-steel.html|title=Towers Of Bridge To Rise 800 Feet; D.B. Steinman, Engineer, Tells Steel Institute Of Huge Harbor Span Planned Here|date=November 14, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>  It was hoped that the new construction would spur development on Staten Island, along with the [[Outerbridge Crossing]] and the [[Bayonne Bridge]], which were under construction at the time.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/01/01/archives/says-bridges-boom-realty-in-richmond-many-industrial-firms-are.html|title=Says Bridges Boom Realty In Richmond|last=|first=|date=January 1, 1928|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberty Bridge would carry vehicles from Bay Ridge to an as-yet-undetermined location on Staten Island.<ref name=\":0\" /> On the Brooklyn side, the city planned to connect the Liberty Bridge to a \"Crosstown Highway\", spanning Brooklyn and Queens and connecting to the proposed [[Triborough Bridge]] in northwestern Queens. The city also envisioned a possible connection to the preexisting [[Manhattan Bridge]], connecting [[Downtown Brooklyn]] to [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59896875|title=Crosstown Highway Brooklyn Hope to Avert Great Industrial Crisis; Key to Traffic Congestion Relief|date=January 20, 1929|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=51|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> However, a vote on the planned Liberty Bridge was never taken, as it was blocked by then-Congressman [[Fiorello H. La Guardia]], who believed that a public necessity should not be provided by private interests.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|136}}\n\n==== 1920s tunnel plan ====\nA prior attempt to link Brooklyn and Staten Island, using the [[Staten Island Tunnel]], had commenced in 1923 but was canceled two years later.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A51VbeqTwogC&pg=PT177|title=Six Bridges: The Legacy of Othmar H. Ammann|last=Rastorfer|first=Darl|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2000|isbn=978-0-300-08047-6|series=Six Bridges: The Legacy of Othmar H. Ammann|chapter=Chapter 7: The Verrazano-Narrows Bridge|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>{{rp|135}}<ref name=\"SIRTImages\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eOSsCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA7&dq=staten+island+rapid+transit|title=Staten Island Rapid Transit Images of Rail|last=Pitanza|first=Marc|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4671-2338-9}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTImes-SITunnel-May1925\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/10/archives/staten-island-waits-for-narrows-tunnel-mayor-hylans-plan-to-build-a.html |title=Staten Island Waits for Narrows Tunnel; Mayor Hylan's Plan to Build a Tube That Can Be Adapted to Freight Traffic Raises Anew the Issue of New York Port Development|last1=Young|first1=James C.|date=May 10, 1925|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>  That tunnel would have extended [[New York City Subway|subway]] service from Brooklyn to Staten Island.<ref name=\"Raskin-RoutesNotTaken-2013\">{{cite Routes Not Taken}}</ref> This proposal was also revived with the announcement of the Liberty Bridge.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/57301690|title=Tube Projects to be Scanned by Chamber of Commerce Body|last=|first=|date=November 27, 1931|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=41|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> One of the alternative proposals had the subway tunnel going from [[St. George, Staten Island]], to [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]], before continuing to [[Governors Island]] and then Lower Manhattan.<ref name=\":1\" /> Simultaneously, engineers proposed a set of vehicular tunnels from [[Fort Wadsworth]], Staten Island, to 97th Street, Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/06/11/archives/narrows-tube-cost-put-at-78000000-engineers-favor-vehicle-tunnel.html|title=Narrows Tube Cost Put At $78,000,000; Engineers Favor Vehicle Tunnel From 97th St., Brooklyn, To Fort Wadsworth|date=June 11, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The tubes were being planned in conjunction with the [[Queens\u2013Midtown Tunnel|Triborough Tunnel]] (the modern-day Queens Midtown Tunnel), which would connect Manhattan, Brooklyn, and Queens.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/07/27/archives/work-is-started-on-plans-for-tubes-board-of-transportation-takes.html|title=Work Is Started On Plans For Tubes; Board Of Transportation Takes Charge And City Will Seek Law To Give It Authority. Bill To Go To Legislature Plant And Structures Bureau Has Jurisdiction, But Already Is Burdened, Walker Believes. Board Experienced With Tunnels. Work Assigned To Engineers.|date=July 27, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The city appropriated $5{{nbsp}}million for the tunnels in July 1929,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/07/26/archives/city-votes-5000000-assuring-midtown-and-narrows-tubes-estimate.html|title=City Votes $5,000,000 Assuring Midtown And Narrows Tubes; Estimate Board Appropriates Funds To Begin Preliminary Work At Once|date=July 26, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] also pledged funding for the vehicular tunnels.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/08/01/archives/bo-will-aid-city-on-narrows-tunnel-willard-offers-cooperation-of.html|title=B.&O. Will Aid City On Narrows Tunnel; Willard Offers Cooperation Of Railroad At Meeting With Delaney|date=August 1, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Planning for the vehicular tubes started that month.<ref name=\"The New York Times\" />\n\nThe Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce simultaneously considered all three projects\u2014the bridge, the vehicular tunnels, and the subway tunnel. Community groups on both sides of the Narrows disagreed on which projects should be built first, if at all.<ref name=\":1\" /> Residents of Bay Ridge opposed any plans involving a bridge because its construction would almost definitely require the demolition of part of the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/58211924|title=Civic Center Fights Span at Narrows|date=June 22, 1932|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=33|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Boring work for the vehicular tunnels started in November 1930. The {{Convert|11,000|ft|m|adj=on}} twin tunnels, projected to be completed by 1937, were to connect [[Hylan Boulevard]] on Staten Island with 86th Street in Brooklyn once they were completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/11/23/archives/the-narrows-tunnel-is-a-vast-project-engineers-are-making-borings.html|title=The Narrows Tunnel Is A Vast Project; Engineers Are Making Borings For The Tube To Join Staten Island And Brooklyn.|date=November 23, 1930|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> In January 1932, construction of these tunnels was put on hold indefinitely due to a lack of money.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/57286903|title=Economy Plan Hits Bay Ridge Improvements|date=January 22, 1932|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=37|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The construction work did not go beyond an examination of shoreline on the Brooklyn side.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59867305/|title=Private Group Studying Plans for Vehicular and Transit Narrows Tunnel|date=May 11, 1934|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=41|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Cancellation of bridge ====\nIn February 1933, the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] approved a bill authorizing the construction of a suspension bridge across the Narrows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/02/14/archives/approves-bill-for-narrows-span.html|title=Approves Bill for Narrows Span.|date=February 14, 1933|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> With this approval, the Interboro Bridge Company hoped to start constructing the bridge by the end of the year, thereby creating jobs for 80,000 workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/02/15/archives/expect-work-soon-on-narrows-span-backers-of-brooklynstaten-island.html|title=Expect Work Soon On Narrows Span; Backers Of Brooklyn-Staten Island Bridge Encouraged By Congressional Action|date=February 15, 1933|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Structural engineer [[Othmar Ammann|Othmar H. Ammann]], who was building the Triborough Bridge, Midtown Tunnel, and [[Golden Gate Bridge]] at the time, showed interest in designing the proposed Narrows bridge, which would be the world's longest bridge if it were built.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59982748|title=Master Bridge Builder Runs 3 Jobs at Once|last=Keating|first=Isabelle|date=June 10, 1934|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=6|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The city approved the construction of a rapid transit tunnel under the Narrows in December 1933. This tunnel was approved in conjunction with the proposed [[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]] connecting Red Hook with Lower Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/12/27/archives/92669000-works-approved-by-city-board-sanctions-narrows-and.html|title=$92,669,000 Works Approved By City; Board Sanctions Narrows And Manhattan-Brooklyn Tubes And Water Tunnel|date=December 27, 1933|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1934, the War Department announced its opposition to the Narrows Bridge's construction. The War Department's opposition to the bridge plan was based on the fact that a bridge could create a blockage during wartime, a rationale it gave for opposing a [[Brooklyn-Battery Bridge]] connecting [[Red Hook, Brooklyn]], with Lower Manhattan.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/07/20/archives/plans-for-tunnel-at-battery-rushed-agencies-move-to-ask-funds-as.html|title=Plans For Tunnel At Battery Rushed; Agencies Move To Ask Funds As Soon As Federal Lending Facilities Are Ready|date=July 20, 1939|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] did not have a public position regarding the Narrows Bridge plan, other than a request that it be allowed to operate the future bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59866160/|title=War Department Opposed to Bridge over Narrows; Port Authority Neutral|date=May 9, 1934|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=33|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref>  Following the War Department's announcement that they would oppose the Narrows bridge, private interests began studying the feasibility of a tunnel under the Narrows.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== 1930s tunnel plan ====\n[[File:VerrazanoBridge.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|View of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge from the Staten Island entrance plaza]]\n\nIn 1936, the plan for a Narrows crossing was brought up again when now-New York City Mayor La Guardia gained authorization to petition the [[U.S. Congress]] for a bridge across the Narrows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/04/18/archives/mayor-will-urge-narrows-bridge-estimate-board-authorizes-reopening.html|title=Mayor Will Urge Narrows Bridge; Estimate Board Authorizes Reopening Of The Project With War Department.|date=April 18, 1936|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Under the new plan, the proposed bridge would charge tolls for motorists, and its $50{{nbsp}}million cost would be paid off using federal bonds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52697541/|title=Mayor Launches Fresh Drive for Toll Bridge Across Narrows|date=January 28, 1936|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=41|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> LaGuardia preferred a tunnel instead, and so the next year he requested the  [[Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority|New York City Tunnel Authority]] to review the feasibility of such a crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/02/09/archives/mayor-urges-tube-to-staten-island-asks-tunnel-authority-to-study.html|title=Mayor Urges Tube To Staten Island; Asks Tunnel Authority To Study Such A Link To City's Arterial Road System|date=February 9, 1937|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The New York City Planning Commission was amenable to constructing either a bridge or a tunnel across the Narrows, and in 1939, put forth a plan to expand New York City's highway system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/06/20/archives/highway-network-for-city-is-mapped-master-plan-to-supplement-and.html|title=Highway Network For City Is Mapped|date=June 20, 1939|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> In March of the same year, as a bill for the Battery Bridge was being passed, Staten Island state legislators added a last-minute amendment to the bill, providing for a Narrows bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52753796/|title=Battery Span Bill Moves to Vote in Albany|date=March 3, 1939|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=8|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The Narrows crossing was not included in the final version of the Planning Commission's plan, which was approved in 1941.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1941/01/23/archives/master-road-plan-for-city-modified-planning-board-approves-its.html|title=Master Road Plan For City Modified|date=January 23, 1941|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943, the [[New York City Board of Estimate]] allocated $50,000 toward a feasibility study of the tunnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/04/16/archives/50000-plans-approved-fund-for-narrows-tunnel-study-is-authorized-by.html|title=$50,000 Plans Approved; Fund For Narrows Tunnel Study Is Authorized By Board|date=April 16, 1943|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> By this time, Bay Ridge residents now opposed the tunnel plan as well, because they feared that the tunnel's construction would lower the quality of life in that neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52819064/|title=Bay Ridge Aroused by Narrows Tube O.K.|date=March 22, 1943|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 2|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> After the war ended in 1945, the Planning Commission estimated that construction of the Narrows Tunnel would cost $73.5{{nbsp}}million. However, by then, La Guardia had turned against the tunnel, saying that \"it is not my time\" to construct the tunnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/08/01/archives/narrows-tunnel-opposed-by-mayor-he-agrees-it-is-coming-but-not-in.html|title=Narrows Tunnel Opposed By Mayor|date=August 1, 1945|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 1940s and 1950s bridge plan ===\n\n==== Initial proposal ====\nThe cancellation of plans for the Narrows tunnel brought a resurgence of proposals for a bridge across the Narrows. In September 1947, [[Robert Moses]], the chairman of the Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority (TBTA), announced that the city was going to ask the War Department for permission to build a bridge across the Narrows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1947/09/24/archives/city-plans-to-build-span-at-narrows-moses-says-he-expects-early.html|title=City Plans To Build Span At Narrows|last=Pierce|first=Bert|date=September 24, 1947|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses had previously created a feasibility study for a Narrows tunnel, finding that it would be much cheaper to build a bridge.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{rp|137}} Moses and Mayor [[William O'Dwyer]] both supported the Narrows Bridge plan, which was still being referred to as \"Liberty Bridge\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52916051/|title=Mayor, Moses Plead for S.I. Bridge|date=October 26, 1948|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The city submitted its request to the War Department in July 1948,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/07/19/archives/tunnel-authority-asks-army-for-narrows-bridge-permit-proposed.html|title=Tunnel Authority Asks Army For Narrows Bridge Permit|last=Crowell|first=Paul|date=July 19, 1948|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> and a commission composed of three [[United States Armed Forces]] branches was convened to solicit the public's opinions on the proposed span.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/12/08/archives/approval-sought-for-narrows-span-armynavy-air-force-board-to-get.html|title=Approval Sought For Narrows Span; Army-Navy Air Force Board To Get Petition Jan. 12 For Staten Island Bridge|date=December 8, 1948|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Verrazano Bridge 2012-12-23.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=View northwest at the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn during sunset|The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn during sunset]]\n\nU.S. Representative [[Donald Lawrence O'Toole]], whose constituency included Bay Ridge, opposed the proposal for the bridge because he believed it would damage the character of Bay Ridge, and because the bridge might block the Narrows in case of a war.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/01/13/archives/realty-fraud-seen-in-narrows-bridge-otoole-says-proposed-span-would.html|title=Realty Fraud Seen In Narrows Bridge; O'toole Says Proposed Span Would Lead To City's 'Greatest Swindle In History'|date=1949|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52895480/|title=O'Toole Urges U.S. Ban Bridge over Narrows|date=July 19, 1948|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 3|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He cited a poll showing that for every Bay Ridge resident who supported the bridge's construction, 33 more were opposed.<ref name=\":4\" /> The  U.S. military approved the proposal in May 1949, over the vociferous opposition of Bay Ridge residents, on the condition that construction start within five years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/05/25/archives/army-approves-narrows-bridge-worlds-longest-suspension-span-army.html|title=Army Approves Narrows Bridge, World's Longest Suspension Span; Army Backs Span Over The Narrows|agency=Associated Press|date=May 25, 1949|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59526452/|title=Bay Ridgeites Battle Army Okay on Span|date=May 25, 1949|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 2|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> By that time, plans for the {{Convert|6540|ft|m|adj=on}} span had been finalized, and the project only needed $78{{nbsp}}million in financing in order to proceed. This financing was not set to be awarded until 1950, when the Battery Tunnel was completed. Preliminary plans showed the bridge as being {{Convert|237|ft|m|abbr=on}} above the mean high water level, enough for the {{Convert|215|ft|m|adj=on}} [[RMS Queen Mary|RMS ''Queen Mary'']] to pass under it.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|137}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/05/26/archives/narrows-crossing-seen-4-years-away-financing-of-bridge-to-wait.html|title=Narrows Crossing Seen 4 Years Away|date=May 26, 1949|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMoses and acting Port Authority Chairman Bayard F. Pope were agreeable to letting either of their respective agencies construct and operate the proposed Narrows Bridge, as long as that agency could do so efficiently. In 1954, the two agencies started conducting a joint study on the logistics of building and constructing the bridge. Because of restrictions by the TBTA's bondholders, construction could not begin until at least 1957.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53591292/|title=Narrows Bridge Cited in Traffic Plans|date=February 15, 1954|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 3|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Frederick H. Zurmuhlen, the Commissioner of Public Works, estimated that the Narrows Bridge would cost $200{{nbsp}}million total.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/11/19/archives/for-narrows-bridge-zurmuhlen-sees-construction-within-next-8-years.html|title=For Narrows Bridge; Zurmuhlen Sees Construction Within Next 8 Years|date=November 19, 1954|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> He encouraged the TBTA to start construction on the bridge as soon as possible in order to reduce congestion on [[East River]] crossings to the north.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53590122/|title=Call for Work on Narrows Bridge|last=Noonan|first=Dan|date=February 11, 1954|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=4|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Staten Islanders viewed the project cautiously, since the Narrows Bridge would provide a connection to the rest of the city, but could also cause traffic congestion through the borough.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/01/18/archives/rural-staten-island-views-span-to-brooklyn-as-a-mixed-blessing.html|title=Rural Staten Island Views Span To Brooklyn as a Mixed Blessing|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses had only a positive view of the bridge's proposed effects on Staten Islanders, saying that it was vital for the borough's future.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/04/14/archives/narrows-bridge-held-a-vital-link-moses-warns-staten-island-its.html|title=Narrows Bridge Held A Vital Link; Moses Warns Staten Island Its Future Depends Greatly On Span To Brooklyn|last=Schumach|first=Murray|date=April 14, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1954, the Army's permit for starting construction on the Narrows Bridge lapsed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/05/01/archives/narrows-bridge-up-to-army-again-triborough-boards-request-for.html|title=Narrows Bridge Up To Army Again; Triborough Board's Request For Two-Year Extension Of Permit May Revive Dispute|date=May 1, 1954|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The Army granted a two-year extension for the start of construction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/07/08/archives/i-bridge-permit-extended-army-sets-may-1956-for-start-of-the.html|title=Bridge Permit Extended; Army Sets May, 1956, For Start Of The Narrows Span|date=July 8, 1954|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In a measure passed in March 1955, the city gained control over the approval process for several tasks related to the Narrows bridge's construction, including land acquisition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/03/30/archives/city-wins-control-of-plan-for-bridge-over-narrows-city-wins-dispute.html|title=City Wins Control Of Plan For Bridge Over Narrows |last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=March 30, 1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> A little more than a month later, New York Governor [[W. Averell Harriman]] signed a $600{{nbsp}}million spending bill authorizing the construction of the Narrows Bridge; the construction of the [[Throgs Neck Bridge]] between Queens and [[the Bronx]]; and the addition of a second level to the [[George Washington Bridge]] between Manhattan and [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/05/01/archives/city-artery-bills-signed-in-albany-package-would-allow-start-of.html|title=City Artery Bills Signed In Albany; 'Package' Would Allow Start Of Work On $600,000,000 Construction Program|date=May 1, 1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Later that year, it was announced that the Narrows Bridge would be part of an expansion to the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/09/29/archives/u-s-bureau-lists-interstate-roads-routes-for-highway-system-in-and.html|title=U. S. Bureau Lists Interstate Roads; Routes For Highway System In And Around 102 Urban Areas Are Approved|date=September 29, 1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Although a study on the viability of adding transit service to the Narrows Bridge was commissioned in early 1956,<ref name=\":12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/03/14/archives/engineers-obtained-for-transit-study.html|title=Engineers Obtained for Transit Study|date=March 14, 1956|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses rejected the idea of adding subway tracks onto the new bridge, saying that it would be too costly.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/09/archives/moses-bars-train-on-narrows-span-mocks-idea-of-transit-link-from.html|title=Moses Bars Train On Narrows Span; Mocks Idea Of Transit Link From Kings To Staten Island As Absurdly Expensive |last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=April 9, 1956|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In April of that year, New Jersey Governor [[Robert B. Meyner]] signed a bill that allowed the Port Authority to build the Narrows Bridge and lease it to the TBTA, who would operate the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/04/archives/meyner-signs-bill-on-narrows-bridge.html|title=Meyner Signs Bill on Narrows Bridge|date=April 4, 1956|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The TBTA would buy the bridge from the Port Authority in 1967 as part of the agreement.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/14/archives/bridge-is-started-across-narrows-ground-is-broken-on-staten-island.html|title=Bridge Is Started Across Narrows|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=August 14, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Finalization of plans ====\nOn the Brooklyn side, the Narrows Bridge was originally supposed to connect to the [[Belt Parkway|Circumferential (Belt) Parkway]], but in early 1957, Harriman vetoed a bill that stipulated that the main approach connect to the Belt Parkway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/05/18/archives/delay-is-sought-on-narrows-plan-bay-ridge-residents-call-for.html|title=Delay Is Sought On Narrows Plan; Bay Ridge Residents Call For Putting Off Approval Till All Links Are Proposed|last=Crowell|first=Paul|date=May 18, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> By May 1957, an updated location for the Brooklyn anchorage had been agreed on. The anchorage was now to be located at [[Fort Lafayette]], an island coastal fortification built next to [[Fort Hamilton]] at the southern tip of Bay Ridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/05/01/archives/moses-and-army-agree-on-narrows-span-site.html|title=Moses and Army Agree On Narrows Span Site|date=May 1, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses also proposed expanding Brooklyn's [[Gowanus Expressway]] and extending it to the Narrows Bridge by way of Seventh Avenue, which would require cutting through the middle of Bay Ridge. This proposal drew opposition from the community, who wanted the approach to follow the Belt Parkway along the Brooklyn shore.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/06/20/archives/span-approaches-approved-by-city-narrows-and-throgs-neck-routes-are.html|title=Span Approaches Approved By City; Narrows And Throgs Neck Routes Are Advanced By Planning Commission; Moses' Plan Rebuffed; Fourth Ave. Curve Is Deleted In Brooklyn--Alternate Ideas To Be Studied|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=June 20, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> These opponents said that the Seventh Avenue alignment would displace over 1,500 families.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/10/21/archives/city-bars-change-in-narrows-plan-rejects-liberty-bridge-or-tunnel.html|title=City Bars Change In Narrows Plan; Rejects Liberty Bridge Or Tunnel As Substitutes -No Action On Approach|date=October 21, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>  In February 1958, the New York State Legislature approved a bill to change the Brooklyn approaches back to Belt Parkway, which was almost identical to the bill Harriman had vetoed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/02/19/archives/assembly-votes-narrows-change-route-shift-bill-is-same-as-one.html|title=Assembly Votes Narrows Change; Route Shift Bill Is Same As One Vetoed In '57 -- G.O.P. Expects It To Aid Party|last=Egan|first=Leo|date=February 19, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> However, the city approved the Seventh Avenue bridge approach in August 1958.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/08/14/archives/approach-is-fixed-to-narrows-span-plan-board-rejects-urgent-bay.html|title=Approach Is Fixed To Narrows Span; Plan Board Rejects Urgent Bay Ridge Objections To The 7th Ave. Brooklyn Route|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=August 14, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The next month, Mayor [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]] said that the city was committed to building a bridge across the Narrows, but was not committed to the construction of the Seventh Avenue approach. In response, Moses wrote to Wagner that any continuing delays would cause the bridge to be canceled. The bridge's cost had now risen to $320{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/09/23/archives/narrows-bridge-backed-by-mayor-he-supports-moses-on-city-commitment.html|title=Narrows Bridge Backed By Mayor; He Supports Moses On City Commitment -- Suit Seeks To Bar Hearing Friday|date=September 23, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter holding a hearing for concerned Bay Ridge residents, the Board of Estimate affirmed the Narrows Bridge plan in October 1958,<ref name=\":6\" /> without any objections.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\" />{{rp|752}} At the same time, it rejected plans for a tunnel under the Narrows, as well as a bridge or tunnel from Brooklyn directly to [[Jersey City, New Jersey]].<ref name=\":6\" /> The Board was set to vote on the Seventh Avenue approach in mid-December, but the federal government stated that it would only agree to the bridge's construction if the Seventh Avenue approach had 12 lanes, with six on each level.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/12/23/archives/u-s-asks-12-lanes-on-bridge-access-estimate-board-defers-vote-in.html|title=U. S. Asks 12 Lanes On Bridge Access; Estimate Board Defers Vote in Impasse on Brooklyn End of Narrows Span|date=December 23, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The federal government was already paying for two highway improvements on both sides of the proposed bridge: the Clove Lakes Expressway on Staten Island, and the Gowanus Expressway in Brooklyn.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{Rp|137}}<ref name=\":6\" /> On December 31 of that year, the Board of Estimate voted to approve plans for the Seventh Avenue approach, having delayed that vote several times.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/12/31/archives/narrows-bridge-approved-by-city-job-to-be-speeded-estimate-board.html|title=Narrows Bridge Approved by City; Job to be Speeded|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=December 31, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe approval of the Seventh Avenue approach angered Bay Ridge residents since the construction of the approach would displace 7,500 people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/01/01/archives/bay-ridge-seethes-over-bridge-plan-housewife-and-dentist-chafe-over.html|title=Bay Ridge Seethes Over Bridge Plan; Housewife and Dentist Chafe Over Approval by City of Staten Island Span|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=January 1, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> This amount of opposition was not matched in Staten Island, even though more than twice as many people were being displaced there, because the Staten Island Ferry was the only way to get between the island and the rest of the city. On the contrary, the bridge's announcement was welcomed because it sparked a rise in real-estate prices on the island.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|18&ndash;20}} As the controversy progressed, Steinman brought up a competing proposal to build a bridge between Brooklyn and New Jersey directly.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{Rp|138}}<ref>{{cite news | title=Cross-Bay Bridge Urged by Builder | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 4, 1958 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/11/04/archives/crossbay-bridge-urged-by-builder.html | access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Nelson Rockefeller]], the Republican candidate for governor of New York, initially supported Steinman's proposal to build a bridge to New Jersey, but Moses later persuaded Rockefeller to endorse the bridge to Staten Island.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{Rp|138}}\n\nThe State Legislature drafted a bill in an effort to change the Brooklyn approach's location to Belt Parkway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/03/19/archives/bay-ridge-route-for-bridge-upset-narrows-span-approach-on-7th-ave.html|title=Bay Ridge Route for Bridge Upset; Narrows Span Approach on 7th Ave. Is Switched to Parkway by Legislature|date=March 19, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> However, now-Governor Rockefeller vetoed the Belt Parkway bill,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/04/11/archives/governor-backs-7th-avenue-route-to-narrows-span-he-vetoes-shore.html|title=Governor Backs 7th Avenue Route to Narrows Span; He Vetoes Shore Parkway Approach to Bridge as Costly and Long|last=Weaver, Jr.|first=Warren|date=April 11, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> and in March 1959, the Board of Estimate officially condemned land along Seventh Avenue to make way for the Gowanus Expressway extension to the Narrows Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/03/26/archives/7th-ave-affirmed-as-narrows-link-over-angry-protests-of-bay-ridge.html|title=7th Ave. Affirmed As Narrows Link; Over Angry Protests of Bay Ridge Dwellers, City Board Votes to Condemn Land|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=March 26, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The only tasks remaining before the start of construction were to finalize the design of the Narrows Bridge, and to speed up the construction schedule to meet a 1964 deadline.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/04/11/archives/design-is-speeded-on-narrows-span-bridge-to-be-completed-1964.html|title=Design is Speeded on Narrows Plan; Bridge, to Be Completed 1964, Expected to Spur Staten Island Growth|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=April 11, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In April 1959, the bridge was officially renamed after the Italian navigator [[Giovanni da Verrazzano]].<ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/04/18/archives/governor-backs-verrazano-span-favors-naming-of-narrows-bridge-for.html|title=Governor Backs 'Verrazano' Span; Favors Naming of Narrows Bridge for the Explorer -- Italian Honored Here|date=April 18, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> This sparked [[#Naming|a controversy]] because the proposed bridge's name only had one \"z\" while the explorer's name had two \"z\"s.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/14/archives/zs-spell-trouble-for-bridge-name-officials-go-to-staten-island-on.html|title=Z'S Spell Trouble for Bridge Name; Officials Go to Staten Island on Verrazzano Boat for a One-Z Affair|date=August 14, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\n==== Preparation ====\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge circa 1960.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=Construction progress: the towers and cables have been laid, but not the deck.|Tower and cables during construction without risers or roadbed]]\n\nSurveying work for the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge began in January 1959.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|29}} The official construction on the bridge began on August 14, 1959, with a groundbreaking ceremony on the Staten Island anchorage. Those in attendance included New Jersey Governor Meyner, New York City Mayor Wagner, and TBTA Chairman Moses. Although New York Governor Rockefeller had been invited to the event, neither he nor Assembly Speaker [[Joseph F. Carlino]] showed up.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|30}} In December 1959, the TBTA was put in charge of funding and building the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/12/archives/moses-takes-over-narrows-bridge-triborough-agency-regains-financing.html|title=Moses Takes Over Narrows Bridge; Triborough Agency Regains Financing Control From the Port Authority|date=December 12, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>  To raise money for construction, Rockefeller signed a bill that would remove the 4% [[Floor and ceiling functions|ceiling]] on the interest rates for the [[Security (finance)|securities]] that the TBTA was selling to pay for the bridge. This ceiling would be lifted until June 1965. In essence, this meant that the TBTA could sell securities at much higher interest rates to raise the $320{{nbsp}}million that was needed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/04/16/archives/governor-signs-bridge-bond-bill-measure-lifts-4-limit-on-securities.html|title=Governor Signs Bridge Bond Bill; Measure Lifts 4% Limit on Securities Sold to Speed Work on Narrows Span|date=April 16, 1960|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Swiss-born engineer [[Othmar Ammann]] was named as the senior partner for the project.<ref name=\":5\" /> Other notable figures involved chief engineer Milton Brumer;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/10/nyregion/milton-brumer-97-engineer-for-famed-new-york-bridges.html|title=Milton Brumer, 97, Engineer For Famed New York Bridges|last=Ravo|first=Nick|date=August 10, 1999|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Adams1996\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/hudsonriverguide0000adam|url-access=registration|title=The Hudson River Guidebook|last=Adams|first=Arthur G.|date=1996|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-82321-679-6|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hudsonriverguide0000adam/page/45 45]}}</ref> project engineers Herb Rothman and Frank L. Stahl;<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal|last=Kinney|first=John W.|last2=Rothman|first2=Herbert|last3=Stahl|first3=Frank|date=1966|title=Verrazano-Narrow {{sic|nolink=y|expected=Verrazano-Narrows}} Bridge: Fabrication and Construction|url=http://cedb.asce.org/CEDBsearch/record.jsp?dockey=0014164|journal=Journal of the Construction Division|volume=92|issue=2|pages=|via=}}</ref> design engineer [[Leopold Just]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/07/nyregion/leopold-h-just-95-is-dead-designer-of-new-york-bridges.html|title=Leopold H. Just, 95, Is Dead; Designer of New York Bridges|last=Thomas, Jr.|first=Robert McG.|author-link=Robert McG. Thomas Jr.|date=March 7, 1999|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Safety Engineer Alonzo Dickinson,<ref>{{cite book | title=Popular Science | publisher=Bonnier Corporation | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lyADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA74 |date=November 1963 | access-date=March 16, 2018 | page=74}}</ref> and engineer of construction John West Kinney.<ref name=\":10\" /> Meanwhile, John \"Hard Nose\" Murphy supervised the span's and cables' construction.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|52}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/08/25/tough-bridge-builder-nears-end-of-a-tough-job.html|title=Tough Bridge Builder Nears End of a Tough Job|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=August 25, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore starting actual work on the bridge, the TBTA destroyed the structures at the future locations of the anchorages.<ref name=\":5\" /> The agency acquired {{Convert|36|acre|ha}} of the {{Convert|138|acre|ha|abbr=on}} within Fort Hamilton, in return for paying for a $12{{nbsp}}million renovation of the Army installation and giving up {{Convert|10.8|acre|ha|abbr=on}} of land in [[Dyker Beach Park and Golf Course|Dyker Beach Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201963%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201963%2520-%25200579.pdf|title=Fort Hamilton Facelift Is Free To Taxpayer, As TBTA Pays Bill|last=Chatfield|first=James|date=April 1, 1960|work=New York World-Telegram|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=1|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> A 1,000-ton World War I monument on the Brooklyn side, within the path of the future Seventh Avenue approach, was placed atop rolling logs and shifted {{Convert|370|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/01/19/archives/1000ton-obelisk-to-be-moved-370-feet-on-rollers-in-brooklyn.html|title=1,000-Ton Obelisk to Be Moved 370 Feet on Rollers in Brooklyn|last=Maiorana|first=Ronald|date=1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The [[Right of way|right-of-way]] for the Seventh Avenue approach was also being cleared, and despite initial opposition to the clearing work, all of the residents within the approach's path eventually acquiesced to moving elsewhere.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|24}} To prevent contractors from delaying work on the expressways on either side of the bridge, Moses warned them of steep fines if the expressways were not completed by the time the bridge was finished.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/11/10/archives/road-builders-to-face-penalties-for-delays-at-narrows-bridge.html|title=Road Builders to Face Penalties For Delays at Narrows Bridge|date=November 10, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Progress ====\nAn anchorage was built on each side of the Narrows, with each anchorage measuring {{Convert|229|ft|m|abbr=on}} long by {{Convert|129|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide, and containing a combined {{convert|780,000|ST|LT}} of steel and concrete. Each anchorage contained sixty-six large holes for the cables.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{rp|147}}<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/03/16/archives/footing-is-sunk-for-bay-bridge-concrete-foundation-put-in-off-si.html|title=Footing is Sunk for Bay Bridge; Concrete Foundation Put In Off S.I. for One Tower -- Brooklyn Work Pushed|date=March 16, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The bases of each anchorage are built on glacial sands, reaching {{convert|52|ft|m}} below ground level on the Brooklyn side, and {{convert|76|ft|m}} below ground level on the Staten Island side.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{rp|147}} Foundation work for the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge was well underway by 1960, as visitors were able to see the anchorages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/08/06/archives/work-in-narrows-now-a-city-sight-waterborne-travelers-can-inspect.html|title=Work in Narrows Now a City Sight; Waterborne Travelers Can Inspect Foundation Work for Mammoth Bridge|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=August 6, 1960|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> A concrete workers' strike in mid-1961 threatened the timely completion of the Staten Island anchorage, which had only been partially filled with concrete.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/08/18/archives/washout-feared-at-site-of-bridge-lack-of-concrete-threatens-narrows.html|title=Washout Feared At Site Of Bridge; Lack Of Concrete Threatens Narrows Construction|date=August 18, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> This strike lasted several months and affected many projects under the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/07/11/archives/pact-cuts-tieup-in-construction-800-drivers-end-walkout-1200.html|title=Pact Cuts Tie-Up In Construction; 800 Drivers End Walkout -- 1,200 Continue Strike|last=Katz|first=Ralph|date=July 11, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs construction on the anchorages proceeded, two watertight [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] were sunk into the channel close to either shoreline, so that the bridge's suspension towers could be built atop each caisson. The bases of each caisson consisted of sixty-six circular openings each {{convert|17|ft|m}} in diameter, arranged in a six-by-eleven grid. Shafts of reinforced concrete would be built along the inner rim of each opening, and once each section of shaft reached {{convert|40|ft|m}} above water level, cranes with [[clamshell bucket]]s would dig the sand and mud inside each shaft before sinking the shafts deeper into the water.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|144}} The Staten Island side's caisson was sunk {{Convert|105|ft|m|abbr=on}} into the water, and necessitated the dredging of {{Convert|81000|yd3|m3}} of sand and assorted muck.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|144}} This caisson required {{Convert|47000|yd3|m3|abbr=on}} of concrete, and in March 1961, it became the first of the two caissons to be sunk.<ref name=\":11\" /> The Brooklyn side's caisson required even more work, since it was {{Convert|170|ft|m|abbr=on}} deep, displaced {{Convert|145000|yd3|m3|abbr=on}} of muck, and used {{Convert|83000|yd3|m3|abbr=on}} of concrete.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|144}} Once the caissons were sunk completely, the shafts inside each caisson were filled with water, and the bases of the caissons were covered by a sheet of reinforced concrete.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|146}} The process of constructing the anchorages and caissons took just over two years, and it was complete by the end of 1961.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}\n\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge- The Beginning (15694094466).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Construction of the suspension towers, seen in 1962]]\n\nAfterward, two separate companies constructed the modules that would make up the {{Convert|693|ft|m|-tall|adj=mid|abbr=on}} suspension towers. The Staten Island tower was built  by [[Bethlehem Steel]], and the Brooklyn tower was built by the [[Harris Structural Company]].<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|55}} The first piece of the towers, a 300-foot piece of the tower on the Staten Island side, was lifted into place in October 1961,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/10/11/archives/first-major-steel-section-placed-for-verrazano-narrows-bridge-moses.html|title=First Major Steel Section Placed For Verrazano -- Narrows Bridge; Moses Gives Signal to Put 47-Ton Piece on Pedestal Off Staten Island Shore|date=October 11, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and this tower was topped out by September 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/09/18/archives/tower-topped-out-on-narrows-bridge.html|title=Tower Topped Out on Narrows Bridge|date=September 18, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The Brooklyn tower started construction in April 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/04/10/archives/tower-in-brooklyn-for-bridge-is-begun.html|title=Tower in Brooklyn for Bridge Is Begun|date=April 10, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> When the towers were fully erected, workers began the process of spinning the bridge's cables. The [[American Bridge Company]] was selected to construct the cables and deck.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|53}} The cable-spinning process began in March 1963, and took six months, since {{Convert|142,520|mi|km|abbr=on}} of bridge cables had to be strung 104,432 times around the bridge.<ref name=\"Cables-Spinning-1963\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/03/08/archives/spinning-of-cables-begins-on-nys-narrows-span.html|title=Spinning of Cables Begins on N.Y.'s Narrows Span|date=March 8, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Moses Says Bridge Ahead Of Marks; Start of 6-Month Cable Spinning Operation|date=March 15, 1963|last=Griffin|first=J. Frank|work=Brooklyn Home-Reporter|pages=[http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201962%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201962%2520Dec-Jan%25201963%252000307_1.pdf 6], [http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2024/Brooklyn%20NY%20Home%20Reporter%20&%20Sunset%20News/Brooklyn%20NY%20Home%20Reporter%20&%20Sunset%20News%201962/Brooklyn%20NY%20Home%20Reporter%20&%20Sunset%20News%201962%20Dec-Jan%201963%2000307_2.pdf 7]|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> The main cables were hung on both sides of the span, and then suspender cables were hung from the bridge's main cables.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|58}} The main cables were fully spun by August.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/08/29/archives/cable-spinning-completed-for-the-verrazano-bridge.html|title=Cable Spinning Completed For the Verrazano Bridge|date=August 29, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1963, builders started receiving the rectangular pieces that would make up the roadway deck. The components for the sixty 40-ton slabs were first created in an assembly line in Jersey City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/09/20/archives/bridge-is-shaped-on-assembly-line-400ton-verrazano-units-fashioned.html|title=Bridge is Shaped on Assembly Line; 400-Ton Verrazano Units Fashioned in Jersey Yard 145 Men in Assembly Line|last=Stengren|first=Bernard|date=September 20, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Then, these components were combined in a Bayonne steelworks {{Convert|5|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} from the bridge site, and after the pieces of each slab were assembled, they were floated to the Narrows via barge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/23/bridge-delights-seaside-supers.html|title=Bridge Delights 'seaside Supers'|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=January 23, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Each piece measured {{Convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} high by approximately {{Convert|115|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide and long. These pieces of the deck were then hung from the suspender cables[[Harris Structural Company|.]]<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|94&ndash;95}} The first piece of the deck was lifted onto the bridge in October 1963.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/10/26/archives/first-overwater-steel-segment-is-hoisted-to-narrows-bridge.html|title=First Overwater Steel Segment Is Hoisted to Narrows Bridge|last=Stengren|first=Bernard|date=October 26, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> By early 1964, the span was nearly finished, and all that remained was to secure the various parts of the bridge.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|133}} By this point, plans for new development on Staten Island were well underway,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/11/20/archives/si-planning-now-for-great-influx-maniscalco-tells-of-efforts-to.html|title=S.I. Planning Now for Great Influx; Maniscalco Tells of Efforts to Keep City From Giving 'Too Much Too Late'|last=Knowles|first=Clayton|author-link=Clayton Knowles|date=November 20, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and tourists had come to observe the construction of the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/04/06/archives/verrazano-bridge-the-citys-newest-landmark-graces-harbor-with-a.html|title=Verrazano Bridge, the City's Newest Landmark|last=Stengren|first=Bernard|date=April 6, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The bridge had been scheduled to open in 1965, but as a result of the faster-than-anticipated rate of progress, the TBTA decided to open the bridge in November 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/03/28/narrows-bridge-is-due-to-open-a-head-of-schedule-in-november.html|title=Narrows Bridge Is Due to Open Ahead of Schedule in November|first=Bernard |last=Stengren|date=March 28, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> In preparation for the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge's opening, the TBTA fully repainted the structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/10/24/verrazano-bridge-getting-coat-of-gray-for-opening.html|title=Verrazano Bridge Getting Coat of Gray for Opening|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=October 24, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The construction process of the bridge had employed an average of 1,200 workers a day for five years, excluding those who had worked on the approaches; around 10,000 individuals had worked on the bridge throughout that five-year period.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\">{{cite Power Broker}}</ref>{{rp|736}}\n\nThree men died during the construction of the bridge.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{rp|91}} The first fatality was 58-year-old Paul Bassett, who fell off the deck and struck a tower in August 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/08/25/archives/man-killed-at-narrows-span.html|title=Man Killed at Narrows Span|date=August 25, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Irving Rubin, also 58 years old, died in July 1963, when he fell off of the bridge approach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2520May-Nov%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2520May-Nov%252000188_2.pdf|title=Bridge Claims 2nd Victim, Worker Dies In 80-Ft.Fall|date=July 19, 1963|work=Brooklyn Home-Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{rp|91}} The third worker who died was 19-year-old Gerard McKee, who fell into the water in October 1963, after slipping off the catwalk.<ref name=\"Talese Book\">{{cite book|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|title=The Bridge: The Building of the Verrazano\u2013Narrows Bridge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cK-pBAAAQBAJ|isbn=9781620409114|location=New York City|publisher=[[Harper & Row]]|year=1964|lccn=64-7832}}</ref>{{rp|91}}<ref name=\"Rasenberger\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XDSxwPx-yJ4C&pg=PA270|last=Rasenberger|first=Jim|title=High Steel: the Daring Men Who Built the World's Greatest Skyline|page=270|year=2004|location=New York, NY|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=0-06-000434-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/10/10/archives/bridge-worker-falls-to-death.html|title=Bridge Worker Falls to Death|date=October 10, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> After McKee's death, workers participated in a five-day strike in December 1963. The strike resulted in temporary safety nets being installed underneath the deck.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|98}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/12/07/archives/bridge-men-to-get-nets-on-narrows-300-will-return-to-job-on-monday.html|title=Bridge Men To Get Nets On Narrows|last=Arnold|first=Martin|date=December 7, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /> These nets had not been provided during the four years prior to the strike.<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" />\n\n{{Anchor|The Bridge: The Building of the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge|The Bridge}}The construction of the bridge was chronicled by the writer [[Gay Talese]] in his 1964 book ''The Bridge: The Building of the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge''. He also wrote several articles about the bridge's construction for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/02/nyregion/gay-talese-reminisces-about-verrazano-narrows-bridge-construction.html|title=Gay Talese Reminisces About Verrazano Construction|last=Berger|first=Joseph|date=July 1, 2014|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The book also contains several drawings by [[Lili R\u00e9thi]] and photographs by [[Bruce Davidson (photographer)|Bruce Davidson.]]<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|Cover Page}}\n\n=== Opening and early years ===\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge 5c 1964 issue U.S. stamp.jpg|thumb|alt=Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge commemorative stamp, first sold on November 21, 1964, in conjunction with the bridge's opening|{{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge commemorative stamp, first sold on November 21, 1964, in conjunction with the bridge's opening]]\nThe Staten Island approach to the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge was the first part of the new project to be completed, and it opened in January 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/27/verrazano-link-will-open-on-si.html|title=Verrazano Link Will Open on S.I.|last=Ingraham |first=Joseph C.|date=January 27, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The upper deck was opened on November 21, 1964, at a cost of $320&nbsp;million in 1964<!-- equivalent to ${{inflation|US|0.320|1964|fmt=c|r=3}}&nbsp;billion in present dollars -->.<ref name=\":14\"/> Politicians at all levels of the government, from Brooklyn Borough President [[Abe Stark]] to U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], wrote speeches paying tribute to the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201964%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201964%2520b%2520-%25203313.pdf|title=Notables Salute the New Queen|date=November 21, 1964|work=New York World-Telegram|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=2|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> The opening ceremony was attended by over 5,000 people, including 1,500 official guests. Several dignitaries, involving the mayor, the governor, and the borough presidents of Brooklyn and Staten Island, cut the gold ribbon. They then joined a motorcade to mark the official opening of the bridge.<ref name=\"wnyc\">{{cite news |title=Verrazano Bridge Turns 40 |first=Beth |last=Fertig |url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2004/nov/21/verrazano-bridge-turns-40/ |publisher=[[WNYC]] |date=November 21, 2004 |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607022340/http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2004/nov/21/verrazano-bridge-turns-40/ |archivedate=June 7, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/22/verrazano-bridge-opened-to-traffic.html|title=Verrazano Bridge Opened to Traffic|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=November 22, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> A 50-cent toll was charged to all motorists crossing the bridge.<ref name=\"NYTimes-NewBridge_Roads-1964\"/> The {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge's opening was celebrated across Staten Island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/22/opening-is-hailed-at-many-parties.html|title=Opening Is Hailed at Many Parties|first=Philip |last=Benjamin|date=November 22, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Moses did not invite any of the 12,000 workers to the opening,<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /> so they boycotted the event and instead attended a mass in memory of the three workers who died during construction.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nThe opening was accompanied by the release of a commemorative postage stamp, which depicted a ship sailing underneath the new span.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/10/23/new-verrazano-bridge-stamp-unveiled-at-a-democratic-rally.html|title=New Verrazano Bridge Stamp Unveiled at a Democratic Rally|date=October 23, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (MTA) created a bus route across the bridge to connect [[Victory Boulevard (Staten Island)|Victory Boulevard]] in Staten Island with the [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]] subway station in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/08/bus-service-set-for-new-bridge.html|title=Bus Service Set for New Bridge|date=November 8, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> This bus service initially saw low patronage, with only 6,000 daily passengers using the route.<ref>{{cite news | title=Transit Authority Cuts Bus Service On Narrows Span | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 7, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/01/07/archives/transit-authority-cuts-bus-service-on-narrows-span.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Five days after the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge opened, the ferry from Staten Island to Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, stopped running, as it was now redundant to the new bridge.<ref>{{cite news | last=Dougherty | first=Philip H. | title=Brooklyn Ferry Enters Oblivion | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 26, 1964 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/26/brooklyn-ferry-enters-oblivion.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWithin the first two months of the bridge's opening, 1.86{{nbsp}}million vehicles had used the new crossing, 10% more than originally projected, and this netted the TBTA almost $1{{nbsp}}million in toll revenue. The [[Goethals Bridge]], which connected New Jersey to the Staten Island Expressway and the {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge, saw its daily average use increase by 75%, or approximately 300,000 trips total, compared to before the Narrows Bridge opened. The [[Holland Tunnel]] from New Jersey to Manhattan, and the Staten Island Ferry from Staten Island to Manhattan, both saw decreased vehicle counts after the bridge opened.<ref>{{cite news | last=Ingraham | first=Joseph C. | title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge Traffic Runs 10% Above Forecasts; 1,860,000 Vehicles Have Paid Nearly $1 Million Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 8, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/01/08/archives/verrazanonarrows-bridge-traffic-runs-10-above-forecasts-1860000.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> In summer 1965, Staten Island saw increased patronage at its beaches, facilitated by the opening of the new bridge.<ref>{{cite news | last=Schanberg | first=Sydney H. | title=Over the Bridge They Go to Staten Island's Beaches | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=July 29, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/07/29/archives/over-the-bridge-they-go-to-staten-islands-beaches.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> By the time of the bridge's first anniversary, 17{{nbsp}}million motorists had crossed the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge, paying $9{{nbsp}}million in tolls.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201965%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201965%2520a%2520-%25202251.pdf|title=Verrazano Bridge Collects $9 Million in First Year|last=Gerard|first=Patterson|date=November 20, 1965|work=New York World-Telegram|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> The bridge had seen 34% more trips than planners had projected.<ref>{{cite news | last=Ingraham | first=Joseph C. | title=Narrows Bridge a Year Old Today; Traffic Is 34% Higher Than Builders Had Predicted | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 21, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/11/21/archives/narrows-bridge-a-year-old-today-traffic-is-34-higher-than-builders.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Conversely, 5.5{{nbsp}}million fewer passengers and 700,000 fewer vehicles rode the Staten Island Ferry to Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/28/archives/verrazano-bridge-cuts-into-si-ferry-revenue.html|title=Verrazano Bridge Cuts Into S.I. Ferry Revenue|date=April 28, 1966|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge was the last project designed by Ammann, who had designed many of the other major crossings into and within New York City. He died in 1965, the year after the bridge opened.<ref>{{cite news | title=Othmar Ammann, Engineer, Is Dead; Designed Verrazano Bridge and Triborough Span | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=September 24, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/09/24/archives/othmar-ammann-engineer-is-dead-designed-verrazano-bridge-and.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge was also the last great [[public works]] project in New York City overseen by Moses.<ref>{{cite news | last=Barron | first=Ann Marie | title=Robert Moses: Master planner saw Verrazano-Narrows Bridge as crucial link for commerce | website=Staten Island Advance | date=November 13, 2014 | url=http://www.silive.com/news/2014/11/moses_fingerprints_will_foreve.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The urban planner envisioned that the {{not a typo|Verrazano}} and Throgs Neck Bridges would be the final major bridges in New York City for the time being, since they would complete the city's expressway system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/06/24/archives/moses-sees-close-of-bigbridge-era-narrows-and-throgs-neck-to-be.html|title=Moses Sees Close Of Big-Bridge Era; Narrows And Throgs Neck To Be Last Here, He Says Moses Sees Close Of Big-Bridge Era|date=June 24, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Additional deck and later years===\nAlthough the bridge was constructed with only one 6-lane roadway, Ammann had provided extra trusses to support a potential second roadway underneath the main deck.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252010%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201963%2520%2520Grayscale%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201963%2520%2520Grayscale%2520-%25201091.pdf|title=Work Rushed On Bridge to Staten Island|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 5, 1963|work=Yonkers Herald Statesman|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> These trusses, which were used to strengthen the bridge, were a design alteration that was added to many bridges in the aftermath of the [[Tacoma Narrows Bridge (1940)|Tacoma Narrows Bridge]] collapse in 1940.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|45}} The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge became so popular among motorists that in March 1969, the TBTA decided to erect the lower deck<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/03/31/archives/narrows-bridge-to-get-2d-deck-in-midjune.html|title=Narrows Bridge to Get 2d Deck in Mid-June|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=March 31, 1969|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> at a cost of $22{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\"/>{{rp|1130}} The Verrazzano Bridge had not been expected to carry enough traffic to necessitate a second deck until 1978, but traffic patterns over the previous five years had demonstrated the need for extra capacity. By contrast, a lower deck on the [[George Washington Bridge]], connecting New Jersey and Upper Manhattan, had not been built until thirty-one years after the bridge's 1931 opening.<ref name=\"NYT19690629\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/06/29/archives/2d-level-of-verrazano-bridge-opens-11-years-ahead-of-plan.html|title=2d Level of Verrazano Bridge Opens 11 Years Ahead of Plan|last=Schumach|first=Murray|date=June 29, 1969|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The new six-lane deck opened on June 28, 1969.<ref name=\"NYT19690629\" /> Originally, the Verrazzano Bridge's Brooklyn end was also supposed to connect to the planned [[Cross-Brooklyn Expressway]], [[New York State Route 878]], and [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|JFK Airport]], but the Cross-Brooklyn Expressway project was canceled in 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/07/17/archives/mayor-drops-plans-for-express-roads-across-2-boroughs-mayor.html|title=Mayor Drops Plans For Express Roads Across 2 Boroughs; Mayor Abandons Plans for Expressways Across Brooklyn and Lower Manhattan|last=Carroll|first=Maurice|date=July 17, 1969|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 1976, to celebrate the United States' 200th anniversary, workers placed a very large U.S. flag on the side of the Verrazzano Bridge.<ref name=\"NYTimes-BigFlag-1976\"/> The flag, which measured {{convert|193|by|366|ft|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Perez 1980\"/> was described in ''The New York Times'' as being the size of \"a football field and a half\"<ref name=\"NYTimes-BigFlag-1976\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/26/archives/bigflag-story-unfurls-on-verrazano-bridge.html|title=Big\u2010Flag Story Unfurls On Verrazano Bridge|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|date=June 26, 1976|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> and billed as the world's largest flag.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/29/archives/bridge-flag-falls-victim-to-the-wind.html|title=Bridge Flag Falls Victim To the Wind|date=June 29, 1976|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> At the time, it was the largest U.S. flag ever made.<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /> The flag was supposed to withstand wind speeds of {{Convert|30|mph|kph}}, but it ripped apart three days later, when there was a wind speed of {{Convert|16|mph|kph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":15\" /> The flag had been stuck against the bridge's suspender cables, so any slight wind would have caused the cables to make tears in the flag.<ref name=\"Perez 1980\"/> A second flag was created in 1980 for the July 4 celebration that year. This flag was even larger at {{convert|411|by|210|ft|abbr=on}} (an area of {{convert|71,000|ft2|m2|abbr=on}}). The new flag was placed along a steel grid so that the suspender cables would not rip it apart.<ref name=\"Perez 1980\">{{cite news |first=Miguel |last=Perez | work=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | via=Newspapers.com | date=February 3, 1980 |page=334 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24382799/this_time_old_glory_wont_be_seeing/ |title=This time, Old Glory won't be seeing stars | access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Architectural critic [[Ada Louise Huxtable]] derided the new flag as a \"simple-minded, vainglorious proposal\" and asked, \"Does anyone really want to spend $850,000 to upstage the Statue of Liberty?\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Flag flap turns critics red |work=The Star-Gazette |location=Elmira, NY |page=13 | via=Newspapers.com | date=March 18, 1980 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24383069/flag_flap_turns_critics_red/ | access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Huxtable | first=A.L. | title=On Architecture: Collected Reflections on a Century of Change | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8027-7760-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t2nDO99m5-cC&pg=PA423 | access-date=October 9, 2018 | page=423}}</ref>\n\nThe TBTA's successor, [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]], stopped collecting tolls for Brooklyn-bound drivers on the Verrazzano Bridge in 1986, and doubled the toll for Staten Island-bound drivers.<ref name=\"NYTimes-OneWayTolls-1986\"/> This was a result of a bill introduced by [[Guy V. Molinari]], the U.S. Representative for Staten Island, as part of an initiative to reduce traffic that accumulated at the toll booth on Staten Island.<ref name=\"NYTimes-VerrazanoTolls-1985\"/> The one-way toll was initially intended to be part of a six-month pilot program,<ref name=\"NYTimes-TollExpEndsToday-1986\"/> but resulted in permanent changes to traffic flows on the Verrazzano Bridge. The crossing saw more Brooklyn-bound traffic and less Staten Island-bound traffic as a result.<ref name=\"Gold 1990\"/> This unidirectional collection remained in effect through the 21st century<!-- {{as of|March 2017|lc=y}}, the last time the MTA raised tolls on the bridge -->.<ref name=\"bt-tolls-2017\"/>\n\nBeginning in 2008, all 262 of the [[Mercury-vapor lamp|mercury vapor]] fixtures in the bridge's necklace lighting were replaced with energy-efficient [[light-emitting diode]]s. This retrofit was completed in 2009, years before LED street lights were installed in the rest of the city.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=[[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]] |date=October 29, 2009 |title=Verrazano\u2013Narrows Bridge LED Necklace Lights Add \"Green\" Sparkle to New York Harbor Entrance |url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/verrazano-narrows-bridge-led-necklace-lights-add-green-sparkle-new |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe [[#Naming|Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge's name]] was originally spelled with one \"z\". The \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name dates to 1960 when Governor Rockefeller had signed the bill authorizing the bridge's name as such.<ref name=NYTimes-VerrazanoItIs-1960/> A bill to formally change the bridge's name to the variant with two \"z\"s was introduced by college student Robert Nash in 2016,<ref name=CNY-NashPetition-2016/> but stalled the next year,<ref name=\"NYPost-SpellingFix-2018\"/> as did another bill in early 2018.<ref name=AP-AnotherZ-2018/> The New York State Senate voted to change the name of the bridge in June 2018,<ref name=\"AP-AnotherZ-2018\"/> and the name change was officially signed into law that October.<ref name=\"Campanile 2018\"/><ref name=\"AMNewYork-LongLostZ-2018\"/>\n\n===Renovation===\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge Repairs (17509134860).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=Workers rebuilding the bridge's upper deck|Rebuilding the upper deck]]\nIn 2014, the city began a $1.5{{nbsp}}billion reconstruction project on the bridge. At the time, it was expected to take up to 25 years.<ref name=\"Barone 2015\">{{cite news | last=Barone | first=Vincent | title=Decades of construction being planned for Verrazano-Narrows Bridge | website=Staten Island Advance | date=October 15, 2015 | url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2015/10/decades_of_necessary_construct.html | accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> The first phase, which cost $235{{nbsp}}million and lasted until 2017, included replacing the existing upper deck sections with new [[orthotropic deck]] sections, removing the divider on the upper deck, and adding a seventh lane on the upper deck, which was to be used as a [[high-occupancy vehicle lane|high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lane]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Katinas | first=Paula | title=Verrazano Bridge repair work brings lane closure until 2017 | website=Brooklyn Eagle | date=March 26, 2016 | url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2015/3/10/verrazano-bridge-repair-work-brings-lane-closure-until-2017 | accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> The ramps within the [[Belt Parkway]] interchange were also rearranged to allow for a ramp to be constructed for the new HOV lane on the upper deck. The parts for this deck were ordered from [[China]] because the parts that the MTA required were no longer manufactured in the United States.<ref>{{cite news | title=MTA outsources $235M Verrazano revamp |last=Adams Otis |first=Ginger | website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | date=July 1, 2013 | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-outsources-235m-verrazano-revamp-article-1.1387639 | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the upper deck was replaced, parts of the lower deck are to be replaced, but this necessitates the closure of the lower deck during construction. Hence, the MTA opted to replace the upper deck first to add more capacity. The upper level's new HOV lane opened in June 22, 2017.<ref>{{cite news | last=Rizzi | first=Nicholas | title=Cuomo Plan to Speed Up Verrazano Traffic Makes Traffic Worse, Oddo Says | website=DNAinfo New York | date=June 22, 2017 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170622/fort-wadsworth/verrazano-narrows-bridge-traffic-hov-lane | access-date=March 16, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317102232/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170622/fort-wadsworth/verrazano-narrows-bridge-traffic-hov-lane | archive-date=March 17, 2018 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Simultaneously, the MTA dismantled the Staten Island-bound toll booths to speed up westbound traffic.<ref name=NY1-Cashless-2017/> This work was done in advance of the reconstruction of tracks around [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]], which severely limited rail service into that station and created more vehicular traffic at crossings to Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news | last=Goldman | first=Henry | title=New York Speeds Up Road Projects Ahead of Penn Station Work | publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=June 12, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-12/new-york-accelerates-road-projects-ahead-of-penn-station-repairs | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Long-term plans also call for the installation of a bicycle and pedestrian path on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge.<ref name=\"Rivoli 2015\" />\n\n==Description==\nThe Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge is owned by [[Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority]] bondholders who paid for the bridge at its construction.<ref>{{cite book | title=Journal: Proceedings of the American Society of Civil Engineers | publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers | issue=v. 92\u201395 | year=1966 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N8xVAAAAMAAJ | access-date=March 18, 2018 | page=4}}</ref> It is operated by the TBTA's successor, [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]], which is an affiliate agency of the MTA.<ref>{{cite web | title=MTA Bridges and Tunnels Introduction | publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] | date=December 31, 2016 | url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/btintro.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> The bridge carries [[Interstate&nbsp;278]], which continues onto the [[Staten Island Expressway]] to the west and the [[Gowanus Expressway]] to the northeast. The Verrazzano, in combination with the [[Goethals Bridge]] and the Staten Island Expressway, created a new way for commuters and travelers to reach Brooklyn, Long Island, and Manhattan by car from [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/15/new-york-bypass.html|title=New York Bypass; Narrows Bridge Adds More New Ways To Avoid City's Traffic Jams|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=November 15, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2011-10-23-queen-mary-2-mast-under-verrazano-narrows-bridge.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=The Queen Mary 2 radar mast passing under the Verrazzano Bridge|''[[Queen Mary&nbsp;2]]'' radar mast passing under the Verrazzano Bridge, showing that there is sufficient clearance for the ship beneath the span]]\n\nEach of the two suspension towers, located offshore, contains around 1&nbsp;million bolts and 3&nbsp;million rivets.<ref name=\"sim\"/> The towers contain a combined {{convert|1,265,000|ST|LT}} of metal, more than three times the {{convert|365,000|ST|LT}} of metal used in the [[Empire State Building]].<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|141}} Because of the height of the towers ({{convert|693|ft|m|0|abbr=on|disp=or}}) and their distance from each other ({{convert|4260|ft|m|0|abbr=on|disp=or}}), the [[Figure of the Earth|curvature of the Earth's surface]] had to be taken into account when designing the bridge. The towers are not [[Parallel (geometry)|parallel]] to each other, but are {{convert|1+5/8|in|mm|3|abbr=on}} farther apart at their tops than at their bases.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}}<ref name=\"Caro 1974\"/>{{rp|752}}<ref name=\"sim\"/><ref name=\"MTA\">{{cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/veraz.html |title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> When built, the bridge's suspension towers were the tallest structures in New York City outside of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.amny.com/secrets-of-new-york/secrets-of-the-verrazano-narrows-bridge-its-construction-to-annie-hall-1.11027995|title=Secrets of the Verrazano Bridge|last=Caplan|first=David|date=October 29, 2015|website=[[AM New York]]|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The diameters of each of the four main suspension cables is {{convert|36|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}. Each main cable is composed of 26,108 wires amounting to a total of {{convert|142,520|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name=\"sim\"/><ref name=\"Cables-Spinning-1963\"/> The upper and lower levels are supported by trusses underneath each roadway, which stiffen the bridge against vertical, torsional, and lateral pressure.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|141}} The anchorage on the Staten Island side contains a facility for heating cinders that are used to de-ice the bridge deck during winter.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|148}}\n\nAt the time of opening, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was the [[List of longest suspension bridge spans|longest suspension bridge in the world]]; its 4,260-foot center span, between the two suspension towers, was {{convert|60|ft|m}} longer than the [[Golden Gate Bridge]]'s center span.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|5}}<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}} Despite being only slightly longer than the Golden Gate Bridge, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge could carry a 75% greater load than the former could.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}} In 1981, the Verrazzano Bridge was surpassed by the [[Humber Bridge]] in England, which has a center span of {{Convert|4626|ft|m|abbr=on}}, as the world's longest suspension bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/26/nyregion/follow-up-on-the-news-bridge-to-nowhere.html|title=Follow-Up on the News; Bridge to Nowhere|last=Haitch|first=Richard|date=December 26, 1982|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBecause of thermal expansion of the steel cables, the height of the upper roadway is {{convert|12|ft|m|2}} lower in summer than in winter.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}}<ref name=\"sim\"/><ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Guide to Civil Engineering Projects In and Around New York City |edition=2nd |publisher=Metropolitan Section, American Society of Civil Engineers |year=2009 |pages=36\u201337}}</ref> The Narrows is the only entry point for large cruise ships and container ships that dock in New York City. As a result, they must be built to accommodate the clearance under the bridge. At mean high water, that clearance is {{convert|228|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Adams1996\"/> The [[RMS Queen Mary 2|RMS ''Queen Mary&nbsp;2'']], one such vessel built to Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge specifications, was designed with a flatter funnel to pass under the bridge, and has {{convert|13|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} of clearance under the bridge during high tide.<ref name=\"sim\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/history-verrazano-narrows-bridge-50-years-after-its-construction-180953032/ | title=The History of the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, 50 Years After Its Construction | magazine=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] | date=November 2014 | accessdate=November 21, 2014 | last=Adler |first=Jerry}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Barron | first=James | title=This Ship Is So Big, The Verrazano Cringes | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 18, 2004 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/18/nyregion/this-ship-is-so-big-the-verrazano-cringes.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNumerous birds nest or roost on the bridge, most notably breeding [[peregrine falcon]]s.<ref>{{cite press release |title=10 Peregrine Falcons Are Banded and Doing Well in Their Nesting Boxes|url=http://www.mta.info/news-bridges-tunnels-bridge-and-tunnel-peregrine-falcons-falcons/2016/06/02/10-peregrine-falcons-are|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> The falcons nest at the top of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge's towers, as well as on the Throgs Neck and [[Marine Parkway\u2013Gil Hodges Memorial Bridge|Marine Parkway]] Bridges. As the falcons are endangered, the city places bands on each bird and examines the birds' nesting sites each year. The falcons were discovered on the top of the Verrazzano Bridge in 1983, though they had started breeding there several years prior.<ref>{{cite news | title=Verrazano bridge is home to adorable baby falcons | website=[[New York Post]] | date=May 1, 2016 | url=https://nypost.com/2016/06/01/verrazano-bridge-is-home-to-adorable-baby-falcons/ | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Grynbaum | first=Michael M. | title=City Room; 2 New Tenants Move In Atop The Verrazano Bridge | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=June 8, 2010 | url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9806E1DB1639F93BA35755C0A9669D8B63.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Naming ==\n\n=== Tentative names ===\n[[File:Verrazano Narrows Bridge Triboro monument SI jeh.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=Monument at the Staten Island side of the bridge|The {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge Memorial on [[Lily Pond Avenue]], near the bridge's Staten Island entrance]]\nDuring the planning stages, the bridge was originally named simply the \"Narrows Bridge\".<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/07/archives/hyphen-is-added-as-compromise-in-name-of-span-to-staten-island.html|title=Hyphen Is Added as Compromise In Name of Span to Staten Island|date=August 7, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The co-naming of the bridge for Verrazzano (with two \"z\"s)<!-- PLEASE DON'T CHANGE&nbsp;\u2014 SEE Giovanni da Verrazzano TALK PAGE FOR CONVENTIONAL NAMING --> was controversial. It was first proposed in 1951 by the [[Italian Historical Society of America]], when the bridge was in the planning stage. After Robert Moses turned down the initial proposal, the society undertook a public relations campaign to re-establish Verrazzano's largely forgotten reputation and to promote the idea of naming the bridge for him. The society's director, John N. LaCorte, successfully lobbied several governors of states along the U.S.'s East Coast to proclaim April 17, the anniversary of Verrazzano's arrival in the harbor, as Verrazzano Day. LaCorte then approached the TBTA again, but was turned down a second time. The manager of the authority, backed by Moses, said the name was too long and that he had never heard of Verrazzano.<ref name=\"italian\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italianhistorical.org/page50b.html|title=Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge|work=Italian Historical Society of America|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref> The explorer's name had previously been suggested for the [[George Washington Bridge]], located several miles north, in 1931.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/02/09/archives/would-name-new-span-verrazano-bridge-newark-man-says-navigator-was.html|title=Would Name New Span Verrazano Bridge; Newark Man Says Navigator Was First Man to Cross Bay of New York but Historians Doubt.|date=February 9, 1931|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Italian Historical Society later successfully lobbied to get a bill introduced in the [[New York State Assembly]] to name the bridge for the explorer. After the introduction of the bill, the Staten Island Chamber of Commerce joined the society in promoting the name. In April 1958, Governor W. Averell Harriman announced that he would propose naming the Narrows Bridge after Verrazzano in honor of the explorer's voyage to the New York Harbor in 1524.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/04/17/archives/verrazzano-gets-his-day-and-his-z-harriman-concedes-italian.html|title=Verrazzano Gets His Day And His 'Z'; Harriman Concedes Italian Spelling in Ceremonies Honoring-Explorer|date=April 17, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> His successor, Nelson Rockefeller, put his support behind the one-\"z\" \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name in April 1959, saying that it was the Americans' standard way of spelling the explorer's name.<ref name=\":7\" /> According to Gay Talese, the one-\"z\" name was bolstered by the fact that it appeared on the bridge's first construction contracts in 1959; this incorrect spelling persisted in all subsequent references to the bridge.<ref name=\"NYPost-SpellingFix-2018\" />\n\nAlthough the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name was not finalized yet, ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted that the Staten Island Ferry boat carrying dignitaries to the bridge's August 1959, groundbreaking ceremony was named the \"Verrazzano\". The ''Times'' further stated that former Governor Harriman and Mayor Wagner had respectively proposed a \"Verrazzano Bridge\" and proclaimed a \"Verrazzano Day\".<ref name=\":8\" /> The Staten Island Chamber of Commerce opposed the Verrazzano name altogether, saying that the proper name of the bridge should be \"Staten Island Bridge\" because there was also a \"[[Brooklyn Bridge]]\", a \"[[Manhattan Bridge]]\", a \"[[Queensboro Bridge|Queens Bridge]]\", and a \"[[Bronx\u2013Whitestone Bridge|Bronx Bridge]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/03/archives/name-protested-on-narrows-span-chamber-tells-governor-it-should-not.html|title=Name Protested on Narrows Span; Chamber Tells Governor It Should Not Be Verrazano but Staten Island Bridge|date=August 3, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The Italian Historical Society was reportedly perplexed about the opposition to the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/09/27/archives/name-of-verrazano-pushed-for-bridge.html|title=Name of Verrazano Pushed for Bridge|date=September 27, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In response to the Staten Island Chamber of Commerce's opposition, the TBTA offered to add a hyphen between \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" and \"Narrows\".<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Official name with one \"z\" ===\nRockefeller signed the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name into law in March 1960, which officially changed the name of the Narrows Bridge to \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge\".<ref name=\"NYTimes-VerrazanoItIs-1960\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/03/10/archives/verrazano-it-is-in-bridges-name-governor-signs-disputed-designation.html|title=Verrazano It Is, in Bridge's Name; Governor Signs Disputed Designation Into Law|date=March 10, 1960|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=February 25, 2010}}</ref> The naming issue did not encounter any more controversy until 1963, after the assassination of President [[John F. Kennedy]]. This prompted a series of suggestions to rename structures, monuments, and agencies across the United States after the late president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/11/28/archives/drives-under-way-for-kennedy-memorials-proposals-are-made-to-rename.html|title=Drives Under Way for Kennedy Memorials; Proposals Are Made to Rename Many Public Works Funds Also Set Up to Help the Widow of Policeman Urges Special Commission School to Honor Memory|last=Benjamin|first=Philip|date=November 28, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> A petition to rename the {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge for Kennedy received thousands of signatures.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2520Dec-May%25201964%252000040_2.pdf|title=Petitions Keep Coming In|date=December 13, 1963|last=Otey|first=Charles F.|work=Brooklyn Home-Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> In response, LaCorte contacted the president's brother, [[United States Attorney General]] [[Robert Kennedy]], who told LaCorte that he would assure that the bridge would keep the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name.<ref name=\"italian\" /> Ultimately, the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge kept its name, while [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|Idlewild Airport]] in Queens was renamed after Kennedy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/12/05/archives/mayor-for-naming-idlewild-kennedy-kennedy-airport-backed-by-mayor-a.html|title=Mayor for Naming Idlewild 'Kennedy'|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=December 5, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn part due to discrimination against Italian-Americans, the bridge's official name was widely ignored by local news outlets at the time of the dedication. Some radio announcers and newspapers omitted any reference to Verrazzano, referring to the bridge as the Narrows Bridge, or the Brooklyn\u2013Staten Island Bridge. The society continued its lobbying efforts to promote the name in the following years until the name became firmly established. Another ethnic slur for the bridge was its nickname as the \"Guinea Gangplank\", referring to the Italian-Americans who subsequently moved from Brooklyn to Staten Island.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{rp|33}} The Italian Historical Society's published references to the bridge's name all contained two \"z\"s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2016/24/br-spell-verrazano-bridge-right-2016-06-10-bk.html|title=To the letter! Petition to add second Z to Verrazano bridge|last=Lynch|first=Dennis|date=June 10, 2016|work=Brooklyn Daily|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Bills to change bridge's name ===\n[[File:VerraZZano Bridge sign vc.jpg|thumb|Installation of new road signs saying Verrazzano with two \"z\"s in February 2020]]\nIn June 2016, [[St. Francis College]] student Robert Nash started a petition to correctly spell Giovanni da Verrazzano's name on the bridge with two \"z\"s.<ref name=\"CNY-NashPetition-2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20160608/TRANSPORTATION/160609864/robert-nash-a-21-year-old-brooklyn-college-student-has-started-an-online-petition-to-correct-the-spelling-of-the-verrazzano-narrows-bridge-by-adding-the-other-z-to-the-north-americas-longest-suspension-bridge|title=Robert Nash, a 21-year-old Brooklyn college student, has started an online petition to add the other Z to North America's longest suspension bridge|agency=Associated Press|date=June 2016|publisher=[[Crain Communications]]|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pix11.com/2016/06/30/new-yorkers-want-spelling-of-verrazano-narrows-bridge-fixed/|title=New Yorkers want spelling of Verrazano-Narrows Bridge fixed|first=Andrea |last=Cavallier |date=June 2016|publisher=[[WPIX]]|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/New-Petition-Aims-to-Fix-Misspelling-of-New-York-Citys-Verrazano-Bridge-382262961.html|title=New Petition Aims to Fix Misspelling of NYC's Verrazano Bridge|first=Verena |last=Dobnik |date=June 2016|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/06/mama_mia_brooklyn_man_seeks_to.html|title=Mamma mia! Brooklyn man seeks to add second \"Z\" to Verrazano Bridge|first=Diane |last=Lore |date=June 2016|work=[[Staten Island Advance]]|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref> The petition gained support from politicians including New York State Senators [[Martin Golden]] and [[Andrew Lanza]]. The petition was also supported by actors and celebrities of Italian heritage, including [[Robert DeNiro]] and [[Tony Gemignani]].<ref name=\"Shapiro, Rachel\">{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/12/lanza_to_mta_correctly_spell_v.html|title=Lanza to MTA: Correctly spell Verrazzano on future signs|last=Shapiro|first=Rachel|date=December 2016|work=Staten Island Advance|publisher=[[Staten Island Advance]]|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> In December 2016, Senators Golden and Lanza sent letters to the Metropolitan Transportation Authority CEO [[Thomas F. Prendergast (railroad executive)|Thomas F. Prendergast]], in which they recommended that the bridge's name be spelled correctly. An MTA spokesperson said the agency was reviewing the letter.<ref name=\"Shapiro, Rachel\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/39/51/all-mta-fixes-verrazano-bridge-spelling-2016-12-16-bk.html|title=Zed-letter day! Pols back Verrazano-Narrows name fix|first=Max |last=Jaeger |date=December 2016|work=[[The Brooklyn Paper]]|accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA bill to formally change the bridge's name stalled in 2017,<ref name=\"NYPost-SpellingFix-2018\">{{cite news | title=Verrazano Bridge spelling fix could cost taxpayers millions | website=New York Post | date=June 7, 2018 | url=https://nypost.com/2018/06/07/verrazano-bridge-spelling-fix-could-cost-taxpayers-millions/ | access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref> as did another bill in early 2018.<ref name=AP-AnotherZ-2018/> In mid-2018, Golden sponsored a [[New York State Senate]] bill to change the bridge's spelling to \"Verrazzano\" with two \"z\"s. On June 6 of that year, the Senate unanimously passed a bill to change the spelling of the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge, sending the measure to the [[New York State Assembly]] and the office of New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] for approval. If the bill was passed, the MTA would modify nearly a hundred road signs at a cost of $350,000.<ref>{{cite news | title=How Do You Solve a Problem Like the Verrazano? With an Extra Z | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | first=Vivian | last=Wang | date=June 7, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/07/nyregion/bill-would-spell-verrazano-bridge-with-an-extra-z.html | access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AP-AnotherZ-2018\">{{cite news | agency=[[Associated Press]] | title=Bill Would Add Another 'Z' to NYC's Verrazano Bridge | website=[[WNBC]] | date=June 7, 2018 | url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Verrazano-Narrows-Bridge-Spelling-Bill-484815681.html | access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref> The Assembly passed the bill on June 21, sending the measure to Governor Cuomo with a minor modification. As a cost-saving measure, existing signs would retain the one-\"z\" spelling, and only new signs would contain the double-\"z\" spelling.<ref>{{cite news | last=Bascome | first=Erik | title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge spelling fix poised to become law | website=[[Staten Island Advance]] | date=June 21, 2018 | url=https://www.silive.com/news/2018/06/assembly_passes_bill_to_fix_sp.html | access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AMNewYork-LongLostZ-2018\"/> On October 1, 2018, Governor Cuomo signed the bill into law, effectively changing the legal spelling of the bridge to the \"Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\".<ref name=\"Campanile 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Campanile |first1=Carl |title=Cuomo Finally Fixes a 50-Year-Old Typo |url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/01/cuomo-finally-fixes-a-50-year-old-typo/ |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Rivoli | first=Dan | title=Verrazzano Bridge finally gets name corrected, decades later | website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | date=October 1, 2018 | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-metro-verrazano-bridge-name-change-20181001-story.html | access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AMNewYork-LongLostZ-2018\">{{cite news | title=Verrazzano Bridge finally gets its long lost 'z' | website=AM New York | date=September 1, 2018 | url=https://www.amny.com/transit/verrazzano-verrazano-bridge-cuomo-1.21345852 | access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Tolls==\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge @ Night from Brooklyn.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn at night|Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn at night]]\n{{As of|2019|03|31|df=us}}, drivers traveling westbound into Staten Island pay $19.00 per car or $8.00 per motorcycle for Tolls by Mail, while eastbound drivers do not pay tolls. E-ZPass users with transponders issued by the New York E-ZPass Customer Service Center pay $12.24 per car or $5.32 per motorcycle; a five-axle truck pays $102.82, or $60.38 with NY E-ZPass.<ref name=\"bt-tolls-2019\"/>\n\nThe Staten Island Resident Rebate Program provides a discounted rate of $5.50 to registered residents of Staten Island who use E-ZPass. Staten Island residents can request a special Carpool HOV E-ZPass, which can be used when three or more people are in a passenger vehicle. The Carpool HOV rate is $3.40.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/sicarpol.html|title=Staten Island Carpool HOV E-ZPass| publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> Non-residents do not get the rebated or discounted rates. All E-ZPass users with transponders not issued by the New York E-ZPass Customer Service Center are charged the Toll-by-mail rates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://new.mta.info/fares-and-tolls/bridges-and-tunnels/tolls-by-vehicle/cars |title=Car Toll Rates |at=Footnote 3 | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> A bill that passed in the New York State Senate in May 2019 would give the discounted rate to Brooklyn residents with E-ZPass who cross at least 10 times per month. The discount, not yet approved by the State Assembly, would only apply to non-commercial vehicles.<ref>[https://hamodia.com/2019/06/03/senate-passes-verrazzano-toll-discount-brooklynites/ Senate Passes Verrazzano Toll Discount for Brooklynites]. ''[[Hamodia]]''.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/06/verrazzano-discount-for-brooklynites-passes-state-senate-report-says.html|title=Verrazzano discount for Brooklynites passes state Senate, report says|date=2019-06-02|website=Staten Island Advance|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/42/23/bn-verrazzano-toll-bill-passes-senate-2019-06-07-bk.html|title=Easy rider: Bill to lower Verrazzano Bridge toll for some Brooklyn drivers sails through state Senate|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\nThe undiscounted tolls for passenger cars are higher than for most other tolled crossings in the U.S. The tolls from the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge grossed the MTA $417{{nbsp}}million in 2017, and more than 85% of bridge motorists used a discounted toll rate.<ref name=NYTimes-17Toll-2018/>\n\n===One-way toll===\nAn [[urban legend]] has it that tolls were to be abolished once the bridge's construction bonds were paid off, but this has been debunked by the ''[[Staten Island Advance]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/nyregion/as-verrazano-bridge-turns-50-a-myth-about-its-tolls-persists.html|title=As Verrazano Bridge Turns 50, a Myth About Its Tolls Persists|last1=Yee|first1=Vivian|date=November 21, 2014|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/02/urban_legend_about_verrazano_b.html|title=Urban legend about Verrazano Bridge debunked: You still gotta pay|last1=Calzolari|first1=Anne Marie|date=February 21, 2009|work=Staten Island Advance|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref> Originally, all drivers paid the same toll to cross the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge. Staten Island residents were the only residents of New York City who had to pay a toll in order to enter their home borough, since all four of Staten Island's vehicular crossings collected tolls. This put Staten Island motorists at a financial disadvantage compared with drivers who lived in other boroughs.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201975%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201975%252002571.pdf|title=Arculeo Proposes Toll Reduction At Bridge|date=October 10, 1975|publisher=Brooklyn Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=9|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=NYTimes-17Toll-2018/> A bill to reduce the tolls for Staten Islanders was introduced in the [[New York City Council]] in 1975.<ref name=\":18\" /> Governor [[Mario Cuomo]], the father of future Governor Andrew Cuomo, signed another law to give Staten Island residents discounted tolls in 1983, after years of petitioning and opposition from his two predecessors.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/23/nyregion/new-law-gives-si-drivers-a-25-discount-on-verrazano.html|title=New Law Gives S.I. Drivers a 25\u00a2 Discount on Verrazano|last=Barbanel|first=Josh|date=June 23, 1983|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom its opening until 1986, the toll was collected in both directions.  In 1985, U.S. Representative [[Guy V. Molinari]] co-sponsored a bill that would require the MTA to collect the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge's toll in the Staten Island-bound direction only. This came after Staten Island residents had complained about pollution from idling vehicles.<ref name=\"NYTimes-VerrazanoTolls-1985\">{{cite news | last=Oreskes | first=Michael |work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 | title=Amid The Big Issues Of The Day, Tolls On Verrazano | date=September 13, 1985 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/09/13/nyregion/amid-the-big-issues-of-the-day-tolls-on-verrazano.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> In December of that year, the [[United States House of Representatives]] passed a bill that prohibited the MTA from collecting tolls from Brooklyn-bound vehicles,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/24/nyregion/for-verrazano-one-way-tolls.html|title=For Verrazano, One-Way Tolls|last=Oreskes|first=Michael|date=December 24, 1985|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> under penalty of a loss of highway funding.<ref name=\"Gold 1990\" /> Accordingly, in March 1986, the MTA started a pilot program where it charged a $3.50 toll for Staten Island-bound vehicles rather than charging a $1.75 toll in both directions.<ref name=\"NYTimes-OneWayTolls-1986\">{{cite news | last=Anderson | first=Susan Heller | last2=Dunlap | first2=David W. | title=New York Day by Day; One-Way Tolls In Effect on Verrazano | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 21, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/21/nyregion/new-york-day-by-day-one-way-tolls-in-effect-on-verrazano.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mta-2010-01-16\">{{cite press release |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |date=January 26, 2010 |title=Verrazano\u2013Narrows Toll Plaza Improvement |url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/verrazano-narrows-toll-plaza-improvement|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> The pilot program was extended to six months, but it was controversial due to the dubious benefits involved.<ref name=\"NYTimes-TollExpEndsToday-1986\">{{cite news | last=Boorstin | first=Robert O. | title=One-Way Bridge Toll Experiment Ends Today, but Not Controversy | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=September 20, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/20/nyregion/one-way-bridge-toll-experiment-ends-today-but-not-controversy.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> The new toll plan not only caused a drop in revenues,<ref>{{cite news | last=Brooke | first=James | title=One-Way Verrazano Toll Is Cutting Revenues | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 27, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/27/nyregion/one-way-verrazano-toll-is-cutting-revenues.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> but also caused congestion in Manhattan and Brooklyn<ref>{{cite news | last=Brooke | first=James | title=New Tolls Jam Streets Downtown | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 29, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/29/nyregion/new-tolls-jam-streets-downtown.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> and air pollution in Manhattan. [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal Street]] in Lower Manhattan, which connected to the [[Holland Tunnel]] to New Jersey, saw the most severe congestion, as drivers would go through New Jersey and use the [[Bayonne Bridge]] to pay a cheaper toll to enter Staten Island.<ref>{{cite news | last=Boorstin | first=Robert O. | title=Pollution Rise Tied To One-Way Toll | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 2, 1987 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/02/nyregion/pollution-rise-tied-to-one-way-toll.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> Fatal accidents involving pedestrians in Lower Manhattan also increased greatly as a result.<ref name=\"Lambert 1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/12/nyregion/neighborhood-report-lower-manhattan-around-holland-tunnel-a-deadly-jam.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Lower Manhattan; Around Holland Tunnel, a Deadly Jam|last=Lambert|first=Bruce|date=September 12, 1993|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the MTA supported removing the one-way toll because it reduced MTA revenues by $7{{nbsp}}million a year.<ref>{{cite news| last=French | first=Howard W. | title=M.T.A. Urges End to One-Way Toll on Verrazano | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 21, 1987 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/21/nyregion/mta-urges-end-to-one-way-toll-on-verrazano.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> At that point, Cuomo proposed reinstating an eastbound toll for trucks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/04/nyregion/cuomo-asks-return-of-2-way-toll-for-trucks-on-verrazano-bridge.html|title=Cuomo Asks Return of 2-Way Toll For Trucks on Verrazano Bridge|last=Barron|first=James|date=March 4, 1988|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1990, it was noted that about 455,000 more eastbound vehicles per year were using the bridge's eastbound lanes compared with before the toll reconfiguration, but that this was heavily outweighed by the 1.5{{nbsp}}million fewer westbound vehicles per year.<ref name=\"Gold 1990\">{{cite news | last=Gold | first=Allan R. | title=S.I.'s Relief Called Brooklyn's Headache | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=May 10, 1990 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/10/nyregion/si-s-relief-called-brooklyn-s-headache.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> Residents of Manhattan and Brooklyn wanted the tolls changed so that either eastbound vehicles only, or both directions, would be tolled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/15/nyregion/bridge-toll-divides-city-of-new-york.html|title=Bridge Toll Divides City Of New York|last=Lueck|first=Thomas J.|date=June 15, 1993|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[United States House of Representatives]] voted in favor of a federal appropriations bill, which would repeal the bridge's one-way-toll mandate and allow half of the then-current toll to be applied to both directions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2019/06/27/house-passes-spending-bill-with-2-way-verrazzano-bridge-tolls/|title=House passes spending bill with 2-way Verrazzano Bridge tolls|date=2019-06-27|website=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/3055|title=H.R.3055 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Commerce, Justice, Science, Agriculture, Rural Development, Food and Drug Administration, Interior, Environment, Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, Transportation, and Housing and Urban Development Appropriations Act, 2020|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> At the time, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was the only American bridge with a federal mandate controlling its toll collections. President [[Donald Trump]] signed the bill in December 2019, but the MTA had yet to determine when it would enact two-way tolls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/12/with-legislation-signed-split-tolling-no-longer-banned-on-verrazzano-bridge.html|title=With legislation signed, split tolling no longer banned on Verrazzano Bridge|last=Bascome|first=Erik|date=December 23, 2019|website=silive|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> The implementation of two-way tolls would require approval from the MTA board and would necessitate installation of additional infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2020/01/mta-in-early-stages-of-split-tolling-on-verrazzano-what-you-need-to-know.html|title=MTA in 'early stages' of split tolling on Verrazzano: What you need to know|last=Bascome|first=Erik|date=January 30, 2020|website=silive|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Electronic tolling and tollbooth removals===\n[[File:B&T 9891 (6808498097).jpg|thumb|upright|Demolition of eastbound toll plazas, 2012]]\nE-ZPass was introduced at the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge in late 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/01/nyregion/commuters-work-to-head-off-fare-rise.html|title=Commuters Work to Head Off Fare Rise|last=Rather|first=John|date=September 1, 1995|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24382556/new_ezpass_tags_take_effect/|title=New E-ZPass tags take effect|last=Boylan|first=Kate|date=September 8, 1995|work=[[The Journal News]]|access-date=October 9, 2018|location=White Plains, NY|page=27|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Its introduction helped to reduce traffic congestion at the tollbooths; in March 1997, it was found that drivers with E-ZPass were able to pass through the westbound tollbooths within 30 seconds, compared to 15 minutes for drivers paying with tokens or cash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/25/nyregion/electronic-tolls-are-catching-on-and-commuters-are-catching-up.html|title=Electronic Tolls Are Catching On, And Commuters Are Catching Up|last=Gross|first=Jane|date=March 25, 1997|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> In February 1998, the MTA discontinued the sale of toll tokens on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, except to Staten Island residents purchasing them in bulk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/03/nyregion/the-sale-of-tokens-ends-at-6-tunnels-and-bridges.html|title=The Sale of Tokens Ends At 6 Tunnels and Bridges|last=Chen|first=David W.|date=February 3, 1998|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite not collecting tolls in the eastbound direction since 1986, the MTA did not do anything with the unused booths for a quarter-century.<ref name=\"NYTimes-PhantomTolls-2010\">{{cite news | last=Grynbaum | first=Michael M. | title=Days Numbered for Staten Island's Phantom Tollbooths | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 20, 2010 | url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9C02E4D91E3DF933A15757C0A9669D8B63.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, eight of the eleven Brooklyn-bound toll booths were removed as part of the first phase of a project to improve traffic flow at the toll plaza.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |date=May 28, 2010 |title=New Traffic Pattern at Brooklyn-bound Verrazano Toll Plaza Begins Wed., June 2 \u2013 Removal of Last Two Unused Toll Booths Will Complete This Phase of Construction Work |url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/new-traffic-pattern-brooklyn-bound-verrazano-toll-plaza-begins-wed |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-PhantomTolls-2010\" /> Two years later, the last of the eastbound tollbooths was removed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Sedon |url=http://www.silive.com/eastshore/index.ssf/2012/02/booths_unused_since_1986_final.html |title=Booths unused since 1986 finally removed from Staten Island's Verrazano Bridge toll plaza |work=[[Staten Island Advance]] |date=February 4, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/verrazano-narrows-toll-plaza-improvement-project-moves-next-stage |title=Verrazano-Narrows Toll Plaza Improvement Project Moves To Next Stage Along Narrows Road South |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |date=February 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref> Tolls are still collected in the Staten Island-bound direction only, and congestion within Lower Manhattan persists due to the bridge's one-way westbound toll.<ref name=\"bt-tolls-2017\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-17Toll-2018\">{{cite news | last=Hu | first=Winnie | title='Outrageous' $17 Toll to Cross the Verrazano Vexes Drivers | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 9, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/19/nyregion/verrazano-bridge-toll.html | access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Open road tolling|Open-road cashless tolling]] began on July 8, 2017.<ref name=\"NY1-Cashless-2017\">{{cite news | title=Drivers Have a New Way of Paying Verrazano Bridge Tolls | publisher=[[Spectrum News]] | date=July 8, 2017 | url=http://www.ny1.com//nyc/queens/news/2017/07/8/verrazano-bridge-starts-using-cashless-tolls-staten-island-brooklyn.html | access-date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> The westbound tollbooths were also dismantled, and drivers were no longer able to pay cash at the bridge. Instead, cameras and [[E-ZPass|E&#8209;ZPass]] readers are mounted on new overhead gantries near where the booths were located.<ref name=\"Siff 2016\" /><ref name=\"WABC 2016\" /> A vehicle without E-ZPass has a picture taken of its license plate and a bill for the toll is mailed to its owner.<ref name=\"MTA cashless\">{{cite web | title=What Is Cashless Tolling? | website=MTA Bridges & Tunnels | url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/cashless/ | access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> For E-ZPass users, sensors detect their transponders wirelessly.<ref name=\"Siff 2016\">{{cite web | last=Siff | first=Andrew | title=Automatic Tolls to Replace Gates at 9 NYC Spans: Cuomo | website=NBC New York | date=October 5, 2016 | url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Automatic-Tolls-Coming-to-New-York-City-Bridges-Tunnels-NYC-396050241.html | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WABC 2016\">{{cite web | title=MTA rolls out cashless toll schedule for bridges, tunnels | website=ABC7 New York | date=December 21, 2016 | url=http://abc7ny.com/1666924/ | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA cashless\" />\n\n===Historical tolls===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+History of passenger cash tolls for the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n!scope=\"col\"| Years !!scope=\"col\"| Toll !!scope=\"col\"| Toll equivalent<br />in {{inflation-year|US}}{{Inflation-fn|US}} !!class=unsortable|{{Abbr|Ref.|References cited}} !! class=\"unsortable\"  scope=\"col\"|Direction collected !! class=\"unsortable\"| Method\n|-\n| 1964\u20131972\n|align=right| $0.50\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1972|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1964|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref name=\"NYTimes-NewBridge_Roads-1964\">{{cite news | title=New Bridge and Roads Will Save Time, Trouble and Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | last=Ingraham | first=Joseph C. |date=November 21, 1964 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/21/archives/new-bridge-and-roads-will-save-time-trouble-and-tolls-hour-will-be.html | access-date=November 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Prial 1972\">{{cite news | last=Prial | first=Frank J. | title=Triborough Tolls Cause Snarls Inside and Outside Cars | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 7, 1972 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/01/07/archives/triborough-tolls-cause-snarls-inside-and-outside-cars.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n| rowspan=10|Cash only\n|-\n| 1972\u20131975\n|align=right| $0.75\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.75|1975|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.75|1972|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Prial 1972\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 1975\">{{cite news | title=New Fares and Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=September 2, 1975 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/09/02/archives/new-fares-and-tolls.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| 1975\u20131982\n|align=right| $1.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.00|1982|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.00|1975|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"The New York Times 1975\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 1982\">{{cite news | title=Tolls Rise Tomorrow For Several Crossings | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 18, 1982 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/18/nyregion/tolls-rise-tomorrow-for-several-crossings.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| 1982\u20131984\n|align=right| $1.25\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.25|1984|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.25|1982|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"The New York Times 1982\"/><ref name=\"Daley 1983\">{{cite news | last=Daley | first=Suzanne | title=M.T.A. Raises Fares And Tolls By 20% Across The Board | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=December 17, 1983 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/17/nyregion/mta-raises-fares-and-tolls-by-20-across-the-board.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| 1984\u2013January 1986\n|align=right| $1.50\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.50|1986|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.50|1984|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Daley 1983\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 1986\">{{cite news | title=Motorists - New Tolls on TBTA Bridges and Tunnels 11:59 PM Weds Jan 1, 1986 |page=245 | work=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | via=Newspapers.com | date=December 31, 1985 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24946245/motorists_new_tolls_on_tbta_bridges/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| January\u2013March 1986\n|align=right| $1.75\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.75|1986|r=2}}|2}}}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 1986\"/>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| March 1986 \u2013 1987\n|align=right| $3.50\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|3.50|1987|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|3.50|1986|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"NYTimes-OneWayTolls-1986\"/><ref name=\"Bronstein 1987\">{{cite news | last=Bronstein | first=Scott | title=Drivers Irked By Toll Rise At 5 Bridges And Tunnels | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=February 8, 1987 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/02/08/nyregion/drivers-irked-by-toll-rise-at-5-bridges-and-tunnels.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1987\u20131989\n|align=right| $4.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|4|1989|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|4|1987|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Bronstein 1987\"/><ref name=\"Pitt 1989\">{{cite news | last=Pitt | first=David E. | title=Toll Increase at Bridges Is Described as Smooth | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=July 18, 1989 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/18/nyregion/toll-increase-at-bridges-is-described-as-smooth.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1989\u20131993\n|align=right| $5.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|5|1993|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|5|1989|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Pitt 1989\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 1993\">{{cite news | title=Commuter Alert |page=9 |work=The Journal News |location=White Plains, NY | via=Newspapers.com | date=January 30, 1993 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24946889/commuter_alert/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1993\u20131996\n|align=right| $6.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|6|1996|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|6|1993|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 1993\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 1996\">{{cite news | title=Bridge and Tunnel Traffic Smooth as Tolls Rise | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 26, 1996 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/03/26/nyregion/bridge-and-tunnel-traffic-smooth-as-tolls-rise.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1996\u20132003\n|align=right| $7.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|7|2003|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|7|1996|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"The New York Times 1996\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 2003\">{{cite news | title=Tolls rise on Manhattan bridges and tunnels |page=6A |work=Poughkeepsie Journal | via=Newspapers.com | date=May 19, 2003 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24949406/tolls_rise_on_manhattan_bridges_and/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|rowspan=\"6\"|Cash/E-ZPass\n|-\n| 2003\u20132005\n|align=right| $8.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|8|2005|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|8|2003|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 2003\"/><ref name=\"Lee 2005\">{{cite news | last=Lee | first=Jennifer 8. | title=Bridge-and-Tunnel Blues: Paying More to Cross Over | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 14, 2005 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/14/nyregion/bridgeandtunnel-blues-paying-more-to-cross-over.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2005\u20132008\n|align=right| $9.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|9|2008|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|9|2005|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Lee 2005\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 2008\">{{cite news | title=Toll hikes start on bridges, tunnels |page=12 |work=The Journal News |location=White Plains, NY | via=Newspapers.com | date=March 16, 2008 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24949691/toll_hikes_start_on_bridges_tunnels/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2008\u20132010\n|align=right| $10.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|10|2010|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|10|2008|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 2008\"/><ref name=\"Grynbaum 2010\">{{cite news | last=Grynbaum | first=Michael M. | title=M.T.A. Raises Bridge and Tunnel Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=October 28, 2010 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/28/nyregion/28tolls.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2010\u20132015\n|align=right| $13.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|13|2015|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|13|2010|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref name=\"Grynbaum 2010\"/><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2010\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|title=2010 Toll Information|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=May 14, 2010|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514044013/http://www.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2015\u20132017\n|align=right| $16.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|16|2017|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|16|2015|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref>{{cite news | title=M.T.A. Is Raising Fares and Tolls; One Subway or Bus Ride Will Cost $2.75 | first=Emma G. | last=Fitzsimmons | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 22, 2015 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/23/nyregion/mta-raises-fares-subways-and-buses.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|title=2015 Toll Information|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=April 22, 2015|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422061534/http://web.mta.info:80/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n|align=right| $17.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|17|2019|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|17|2017|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref>{{cite news | title=M.T.A. Votes to Raise Fares and Tolls: What You Need to Know | first=Emma G. | last=Fitzsimmons | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 25, 2017 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/25/nyregion/mta-subway-bus-toll-metrocard-fare-increase.html | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2017\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|title=2017 Toll Information|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=March 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426225055/http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|archivedate=April 26, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Open road tolling|Electronic only]]\n|-\n| Since April 2019\n|align=right| $19.00\n|align=center| $19.00<!-- {{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|19|2019|r=2}}|2}}}} -->\n| <ref>{{cite news | title=Subway Fares Are Rising Again. But That Won't Solve the M.T.A.'s Crisis. | first=Emma G. | last=Fitzsimmons | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=February 27, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/nyregion/mta-fares-hike.html | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2019\">{{cite web | title=New Fares and Tolls Take Effect | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA) | date=February 27, 2019 | url=https://new.mta.info/sites/default/files/2019-03/B%26T_toll_tables_03-01-19.pdf | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|}\n\n==Bridge usage==\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge-NYC.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=United States Coast Guard on patrol in Upper New York Bay. The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge across the Narrows is visible in the background.|[[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] on patrol in Upper New York Bay. In the background, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge spans the Narrows between Brooklyn (left) and Staten Island (right).]]\nIn 2015, an average of 202,523 vehicles used the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge daily in both directions. {{As of|2015}}, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge carries more traffic than the [[Outerbridge Crossing]], the [[Bayonne Bridge]], and the [[Goethals Bridge]]. These three bridges, which connect Staten Island with New Jersey, were used by a combined  168,984 vehicles in both directions.<ref name=\"nycdot16\"/>\n\nIn 2011, advocacy group [[Transportation for America]] rated the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge as New York's most dangerous, because of the combination of deterioration and the number of people who cross it per day.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20110330/REAL_ESTATE/110339991 |publisher=Crain's New York Business |title=Verrazano called NY's most dangerous bridge |date=March 30, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> The MTA responded that the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, which was both the newest large bridge and the longest bridge in the state, was structurally sound, and that the bridge had passed its most recent inspection. The MTA attributed Transportation for America's results to a \"misinterpretation of inspection records\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Cole |first=Marine |title=MTA refutes claim on Verrazano Bridge |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20110331/REAL_ESTATE/110339971/mta-refutes-claim-on-verrazano-bridge |accessdate=September 14, 2014 |publisher=[[Crain Communications]] |date=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSigns at both ends of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge forbid photography and video taping while on the bridge. These signs were installed after the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]], when the MTA started confiscating film from individuals who were caught filming MTA crossings. However, the ban had been in place long before the attacks in order to prevent people from taking close-up pictures of the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/15/weekinreview/ideas-trends-words-of-warning-don-t-shoot.html|title=Ideas & Trends; Words of Warning: Don't Shoot|last=Blair|first=Jayson|date=September 15, 2002|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Public transportation ===\nThree local bus routes operated by [[MTA Regional Bus Operations]] use the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge: the [[S53 (New York City bus)|S53]] local route, the [[S79 SBS (New York City bus)|S79 Select Bus Service]] route, and the [[S93 (New York City bus)|S93]] limited-stop route. The bridge also carries 20 [[express bus]] routes that connect Staten Island with Manhattan and are also operated by [[New York City Transit Authority|New York City Transit]]. They are the [[List of express bus routes in New York City#Manhattan to Staten Island|SIM1, SIM1C, SIM2, SIM3, SIM3C, SIM4, SIM4C, SIM4X, SIM5, SIM6, SIM7, SIM9, SIM10, SIM15, SIM31, SIM32, SIM33, SIM33C, SIM34, and SIM35]].<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|S}}</ref>\n\nSubway tracks were proposed for the bridge early in the planning process,<ref name=\":12\" /> but Moses rejected them, ostensibly over cost concerns.<ref name=\":13\" /> Other bridges proposed and built by Moses, including the [[Triborough Bridge]], [[Henry Hudson Bridge]], [[Bronx-Whitestone Bridge]], and [[Throgs Neck Bridge]], also lack provisions for subway tracks. According to biographer [[Robert Caro]], Moses purposely excluded any provisions for mass transit on his bridges in order to promote private transportation.<ref>{{cite web | last=Nonko | first=Emily | title=New York City's subway crisis started with Robert Moses | publisher=Curbed NY | date=July 1, 2017 | url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/7/27/15985648/nyc-subway-robert-moses-power-broker | access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Pedestrian and bicycle prohibition ===\nThe Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was not built with a pedestrian walkway. At the time, it was seen as too expensive, and planners believed the lack of a walkway would help prevent possible [[suicide]] jumps.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/21/no-pedestrian-walks-provided-for-bridge.html|title=No Pedestrian Walks Provided for Bridge|date=November 21, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Non-motorized transportation is limited to using the bridge during the [[New York City Marathon]] and [[Five Boro Bike Tour]].<ref name=\"Weir 1999\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transalt.org/files/resources/bridges/verrazano.html|title=Verrazano Bridge|publisher=Transportation Alternatives|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref> In 1976, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was designated as the starting point of the New York City Marathon. The 1976 marathon was the first year in the marathon's six-year history that the New York City Marathon course went outside Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/22/archives/city-marathon-oct-24-will-span-5-boroughs.html|title=City Marathon, Oct. 24, Will Span 5 Boroughs|date=June 22, 1976|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Since then, the marathon has started at the Verrazzano Bridge's Staten Island end every year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=trackandfield&id=2648331|title=After 10 NYC Marathons, Bridge Boss is Running Home|date=November 3, 2006|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 27, 2010|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge is not open to pedestrians or bikers outside of the marathon and the bike tour.<ref name=\"Weir 1999\">{{cite news | last=Weir | first=Richard | title=Neighborhood Report: New York On Line; Bike Friendly Bridges | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=May 30, 1999 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/30/nyregion/neighborhood-report-new-york-on-line-bike-friendly-bridges.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe lack of a walkway did not stop suicides completely, since by 1975, four people had died after jumping off the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/10/archives/crash-foils-a-cabby-in-bid-to-halt-suicide-cabby-bid-to-stop.html|title=Crash Foils a Cabby In Bid to Halt Suicide|last=Perlmutter|first=Emanuel|date=February 10, 1975|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The number of suicides has increased over time, despite efforts at deterrence. A sign that says \"Life Is Worth Living\" is located on the Staten Island approach. In 2008, the MTA also installed six suicide hotlines on the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/2013/04/v-n_suicide_bids_a_scourge_tha.html|title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge suicides are a scourge that resists solution|last=Sedon|first=Michael|date=April 22, 2013|website=Staten Island Advance|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In December 2019, the MTA began installing a prototype [[suicide barrier]] after a series of fatal jumps from the bridge.<ref>{{cite web | last=Grunlund | first=Maura | title=MTA begins installing Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge safety fencing as suicide spate continues | website=silive | date=December 23, 2019 | url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/12/mta-begins-installing-verrazzano-narrows-bridge-safety-fencing-as-suicide-spate-continues.html | access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere have been calls for a walkway or bike lane on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge since its opening, when several people protested over the lack of bike lanes at the bridge's opening ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/23/100000-cars-cross-verrazano-bridge-in-first-24-hours.html|title=100,000 Cars Cross Verrazano Bridge In First 24 Hours|first=William |last=Borders|date=November 23, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1977, as a temporary solution, the city modified three buses to fit 12 bikes and 20 passengers each, then operated these buses on a new \"S7 {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge\" route.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201977%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201977%252001802.pdf|title=Begin Bike-Bus Service Across Verazzano Bridge|last=Raphael|first=Kitty|date=June 24, 1977|publisher=Brooklyn Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=5|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> In 1993, the [[New York City Department of City Planning]] called for a footpath across the bridge as part of their Greenway Plan for New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/bike/gpreal.shtml#priorityroute |publisher=New York City Department of City Planning |title=A Greenway Plan for New York City |accessdate=November 27, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001326/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/bike/gpreal.shtml#priorityroute |archivedate=December 3, 2013 }}</ref> The next year, the city sought a $100,000 federal grant to fund a feasibility study into a Verrazzano Bridge pedestrian and bike path.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/01/16/nyregion/neighborhood-report-sourther-brooklyn-bike-lanes-on-the-verrazano.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Southern Brooklyn; Bike Lanes On The Verrazano?|last=Holloway|first=Lynette|date=January 16, 1994|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1997, the DCP released its study, which found that two footpaths running between the suspender ropes along the upper level, separated for pedestrian and cyclist use, would cost a minimum of $26.5{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/nyregion/pedestrian-lane-sought-for-verrazano-narrows-bridge.html|title=Pedestrian Lane Sought for Verrazano-Narrows Bridge|last=Chaban|first=Matt A. V.|date=October 16, 2014|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The MTA at the time expressed concern about the \"safety and liability inherent in any strategy that introduces pedestrian and bicycle access\" to the bridge.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web |url=http://www.transalt.org/files/resources/bridges/verrazano/dcp_rpt.pdf |publisher=New York City Department of City Planning |title=Verrazano \u2013 Pedestrian/Bicycle Access: Planning Design Feasibility |accessdate=November 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLocal residents on both side of the bridge started advocating for the construction of a walkway or bikeway on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge in 2002. Dave Lutz, the director of the Neighborhood Open Space Coalition nonprofit, stated that after the September 11 attacks, Staten Islanders walked home along the bridge's roadway.<ref>{{cite news | last=O'Grady | first=Jim | title=Neighborhood Report: Verrazano-Narrows Bridge; A Crisis Gives Birth To An Inspiration For A Bridge | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=February 24, 2002 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/24/nyregion/neighborhood-report-verrazano-narrows-bridge-crisis-gives-birth-inspiration-for.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] promised to look into the possibility in October 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Long-Denied Verrazano Bridge Walkway Plan Picks Up Steam |first=Sarah |last=Tobol |url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/categories/category.php?category_id=27&id=13787 |newspaper=Brooklyn Eagle |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Harbor Ring Committee was formed in 2011 to advocate for the completion of the Harbor Ring route, which would create a {{Convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} around New York Harbor, including a footpath across the Verrazzano.<ref name=\":17\" /> In spring 2013 the committee began an online petition that generated more than 2,500 signatures, as well as an organizational sign-on letter with the support of 16 regional and local advocacy and planning organizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harborring.org/about/the-harbor-ring-committee/|title=The Harbor Ring Committee|publisher=The Harbor Ring Committee|accessdate=November 27, 2013}}</ref>  That year, the MTA announced that it would include conduct a three-year feasibility study for installing a pathway on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge.<ref name=\":17\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2014/10/17/movement-underway-to-put-pedestrian-walkway-on-verrazano-bridge/|title=Movement Underway To Put Pedestrian Walkway On Verrazano Bridge|date=October 17, 2014|publisher=[[WCBS-TV]]|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The MTA considered plans for a bike lane in 2015, during the reconstruction of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge.<ref name=\"Rivoli 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/bike-lanes-eyed-fixup-verrazano-bridge-article-1.2387891|title=Bike lanes eyed in fixup of Verrazano Bridge|last=Rivoli|first=Dan|date=October 6, 2015|website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The MTA estimated that a dedicated multiple-use pathway would cost $400 million due to the need for a minimum width to accommodate a fire engine and construction of entrance and exit ramps. The plan was ultimately rejected in March 2019 over safety concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-advocates-verrazzano-narrows-bridge-bike-pedestrian-path-20190520-m5u6z6d3lzb2zdjmap2xanw3xy-story.html|title=Put a bike and pedestrian path on Verrazzano Bridge, advocates tell MTA|last=Guse|first=Clayton|date=May 20, 2019|website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York|access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{wide image|Fort Wadsworth.JPG|1800px|alt=Panorama of the Upper New York Bay viewed from Staten Island. The Verrazano-Narrows Bridge is visible in the center of the image and Fort Wadsworth is visible in the foreground.|Panorama of the bay with [[Fort Wadsworth]] (foreground) on the Narrows, under the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |title=Biggest Bridge to Span Busiest Harbor |url={{Google books|biYDAAAAMBAJ|Biggest Bridge to Span Busiest Harbor|page=90|plainurl=yes}} |last=Soule |first=Gardner |journal=Popular Science |date=June 1955 |pages=90\u201393, 264, 268}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge}}\n* {{official website|http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/veraz.html}}\n* [http://www.bridge-info.org/bridge/index.php?ID=87 Verrazano-Narrows Bridge on bridge-info.org]\n* {{Structurae |id=20000085 |title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge}}\n* {{Gnis |968511}}\n* {{HAER |survey=NY-303 |id=ny1803 |title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, Spanning Narrows between Fort Hamilton (Brooklyn) & Staten Island, Brooklyn, Kings County, NY |photos=35 |cap=3}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{NYC Bridge}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure = Crossings\n|place = [[New York Harbor]]\n|bridge = Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n|bridge signs = [[File:I-278.svg|25px]]\n|upstream = [[Bayonne Bridge]]<br />([[Kill Van Kull]])<br />[[File:NY-440.svg|25px]] [[File:Ellipse sign 440.svg|25px]]\n----[[Downtown Hudson Tubes]]<br />([[Hudson River]])<br />[[PATH (rail system)|PATH]]\n----[[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]]<br />([[East River]])<br />[[File:I-478.svg|25px]]\n|upstream signs =\n|downstream = [[Lower New York Bay]]\n|downstream signs =\n}}\n{{LongestBridge\n| type = suspension\n| start = 1964\n| end = 1981\n| previous = Golden Gate Bridge\n| current = Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n| next = Humber Bridge\n}}\n{{Hudson River}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|New York City|Transport|Engineering}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge}}\n[[Category:1964 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Bridges by Othmar Ammann]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Staten Island]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:Double-decker bridges]]\n[[Category:Historic American Engineering Record in New York City]]\n[[Category:Interstate 78]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New York City]]\n[[Category:Robert Moses projects]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Suspension bridges in New York City]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in New York City]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority]]\n[[Category:Roads with a reversible lane]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect2|Verrazzano Narrows|Verrazzano Bridge|the strait over which this bridge crosses|The Narrows|other bridges|Verrazano Bridge (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Suspension bridge crossing the Narrows between Brooklyn and Staten Island, New York}}\n{{good article}}<!-- Sources' titles and image names that already contain \"Verrazano\" should not be changed to \"Verrazzano\", as these would be incorrect. -->\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name= Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n|image= StatenIsland-13 (36416067785).jpg\n|image_upright = 1.1\n|alt=View of one of the bridge's towers\n|image_caption = \n|also_known_as=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge<br />Verrazzano Bridge<br />Narrows Bridge\n|designer= [[Othmar Ammann]]\n|carries= 13 lanes of {{jct|state=NY|I|278}}<br />(7 lanes on upper level: 6 fixed-direction, 1 reversible [[High-occupancy vehicle lane|HOV lane]];<br />6 lanes on lower level)\n|crosses= [[The Narrows]]\n|locale= [[New York City]] ([[Staten Island]]\u2013[[Brooklyn]]), New York\n|maint= [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]]\n|id=\n|mainspan= {{cvt|4260|ft|m|0}}\n|length= {{cvt|13700|ft|m|0}}\n|height= {{cvt|693|ft|m|0}}\n|width= {{cvt|103|ft|m|0}}\n|clearance= {{cvt|15|ft|m|2}} (upper level)<br />{{cvt|14.4|ft|m|2}} (lower level)\n|below= {{cvt|228|ft|m|1}} at mean high water\n|traffic=202,523 (2016)<ref name=\"nycdot16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/nyc-bridge-traffic-report-2016.pdf|title=New York City Bridge Traffic Volumes|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|publisher=New York City Department of Transportation|page=11|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|begin= {{start date and age|1959|8|13}}\n|open={{start date and age|1964|11|21}} (upper level)<br />{{start date and age|1969|06|28}} (lower level)\n|closed=\n|toll= {{As of|2019|3|31|df=US}}:<ref>{{cite web | title=Car Toll Rates | publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (MTA) | url=https://new.mta.info/fares-and-tolls/bridges-and-tunnels/tolls-by-vehicle/cars | access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n{{unbulleted list|$12.24 (New York [[E-ZPass]] users outside Staten Island)|$5.50 (Staten Island residents E-ZPass)|$19.00 (Tolls By Mail and non-New York E-ZPass)|\n$3.40 (Staten Island resident carpool HOV E-ZPass)}}\n|coordinates = {{coord|40|36|23|N|74|02|44|W|region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| map_relief = no \n| map_cue =\n| map_image = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=300|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.60633|-74.04545}}}} \n| map_text =\n| map_width =\n| map_caption = Location within New York City\n}}\nThe '''Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge''' ({{IPAc-en|v|\u0259r|\u0259|\u02c8|z|\u0251\u02d0|n|o\u028a}} {{respell|v\u0259r|\u0259|ZAH|noh}}) (also referred to as the '''Verrazzano Bridge''', locally as the '''Verrazzano''', and formerly as the '''Verrazano-Narrows Bridge''' or '''Narrows Bridge''') is the longest [[suspension bridge]] in the Western Hemisphere, connecting the [[Boroughs of New York City|New York City boroughs]] of [[Staten Island]] and [[Brooklyn]]. It spans [[the Narrows]], a body of water linking the relatively enclosed [[Upper New York Bay]] with [[Lower New York Bay]] and the Atlantic Ocean, and is the only fixed crossing of the Narrows. The [[double-deck bridge]] carries 13 lanes of [[Interstate 278]], with seven lanes on the upper level and six on the lower level. The span is named for [[Giovanni da Verrazzano]], the first documented European explorer to enter [[New York Harbor]] and the [[Hudson River]] in 1524.\n\nEngineer [[David B. Steinman]] proposed a bridge across the Narrows in the late 1920s, and subsequent proposals were deferred over the next 20 years. A 1920s attempt to build a [[Staten Island Tunnel|rail tunnel under the Narrows]] was aborted, as was another 1930s plan for vehicular tubes underneath the Narrows. Discussion of a tunnel resurfaced in the mid-1930s and early 1940s, but the plans were again denied. In the late 1940s, urban planner [[Robert Moses]] championed a bridge across the Narrows as a way to connect Staten Island with the rest of the city. Various issues delayed the start of construction until 1959. The bridge opened on November 21, 1964, and a lower deck was opened in June 1969 to alleviate high levels of traffic. The New York City government began a $1.5{{nbsp}}billion reconstruction of the bridge's two decks in 2014.\n\nThe Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge has a central span of {{convert|4260|ft|km mi|2}}. It was the [[List of longest suspension bridge spans|longest suspension bridge]] in the world until it was surpassed by the [[Humber Bridge]] in the United Kingdom in 1981. The bridge has the 14th-longest main span in the world, as well as the longest in America. When the bridge was officially named in 1960, it was misspelled \"Verrazano-Narrows Bridge\" due to an error in the construction contract, despite the explorer's name having two \"z\"s.<ref name=\"sim\" /> The name was officially corrected to \"Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\" in October 2018.<ref name=\"Campanile 2018\"/>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early plans ===\n\n==== Liberty Bridge ====\n[[File:The Narrows - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|alt=View of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge looking south from Upper New York Bay. The neighborhood of Coney Island in Brooklyn can be seen in the distance.|View of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge from [[Upper New York Bay]], with [[Coney Island]] in the distance]]\nA bridge across the Narrows had been proposed as early as 1926 or 1927, when structural engineer [[David B. Steinman]] brought up the possibility of such a crossing.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|135}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/06/07/archives/asks-suburban-aid-in-regional-plan-committee-urges-cooperation-in.html|title=Asks Suburban Aid In Regional Plan; Committee Urges Cooperation In Furthering Important Public Improvements|date=June 7, 1927|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> At the time, [[Staten Island]] was isolated from the rest of New York City, and its only direct connection to the other four boroughs was by the [[Staten Island Ferry]] to [[South Ferry (Manhattan)|South Ferry]] in [[Manhattan]], or 39th and 69th Streets in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/57555256/|title=The Future Staten Island|last=|first=|date=September 28, 1924|work=[[Brooklyn Eagle|The Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|access-date=September 19, 2017|page=65|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> In 1928, when the chambers of commerce in Brooklyn, [[Queens]], [[Long Island]], and Staten Island announced that the Interboro Bridge Company had proposed the future construction of the \"Liberty Bridge\" to [[United States Department of War]]. The bridge's towers would be {{Convert|800|ft|m}} high and it would cost $60{{nbsp}}million in 1928 dollars.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|136}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/05/02/archives/offer-to-span-narrows-four-ccmmerce-chambers-would-later-give.html|title=Offer To Span Narrows; Four Commerce Chambers Would Later Give Bridge To City.|date=May 2, 1928|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>  In November 1929, engineers released plans for the {{Convert|4500|ft|m|adj=on}} Liberty Bridge spanning the Narrows,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/11/17/archives/span-of-4500-feet-in-narrows-bridge-proposed-60000000-bridge-over.html|title=Span of 4,500 Feet in Narrows Bridge; Proposed $60,000,000 Bridge Over Narrows.|date=November 17, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> with 800-foot-tall towers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/11/14/archives/towers-of-bridge-to-rise-800-feet-db-steinman-engineer-tells-steel.html|title=Towers Of Bridge To Rise 800 Feet; D.B. Steinman, Engineer, Tells Steel Institute Of Huge Harbor Span Planned Here|date=November 14, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>  It was hoped that the new construction would spur development on Staten Island, along with the [[Outerbridge Crossing]] and the [[Bayonne Bridge]], which were under construction at the time.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/01/01/archives/says-bridges-boom-realty-in-richmond-many-industrial-firms-are.html|title=Says Bridges Boom Realty In Richmond|last=|first=|date=January 1, 1928|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberty Bridge would carry vehicles from Bay Ridge to an as-yet-undetermined location on Staten Island.<ref name=\":0\" /> On the Brooklyn side, the city planned to connect the Liberty Bridge to a \"Crosstown Highway\", spanning Brooklyn and Queens and connecting to the proposed [[Triborough Bridge]] in northwestern Queens. The city also envisioned a possible connection to the preexisting [[Manhattan Bridge]], connecting [[Downtown Brooklyn]] to [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59896875|title=Crosstown Highway Brooklyn Hope to Avert Great Industrial Crisis; Key to Traffic Congestion Relief|date=January 20, 1929|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=51|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> However, a vote on the planned Liberty Bridge was never taken, as it was blocked by then-Congressman [[Fiorello H. La Guardia]], who believed that a public necessity should not be provided by private interests.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|136}}\n\n==== 1920s tunnel plan ====\nA prior attempt to link Brooklyn and Staten Island, using the [[Staten Island Tunnel]], had commenced in 1923 but was canceled two years later.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A51VbeqTwogC&pg=PT177|title=Six Bridges: The Legacy of Othmar H. Ammann|last=Rastorfer|first=Darl|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2000|isbn=978-0-300-08047-6|series=Six Bridges: The Legacy of Othmar H. Ammann|chapter=Chapter 7: The Verrazano-Narrows Bridge|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>{{rp|135}}<ref name=\"SIRTImages\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eOSsCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA7&dq=staten+island+rapid+transit|title=Staten Island Rapid Transit Images of Rail|last=Pitanza|first=Marc|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4671-2338-9}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTImes-SITunnel-May1925\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/10/archives/staten-island-waits-for-narrows-tunnel-mayor-hylans-plan-to-build-a.html |title=Staten Island Waits for Narrows Tunnel; Mayor Hylan's Plan to Build a Tube That Can Be Adapted to Freight Traffic Raises Anew the Issue of New York Port Development|last1=Young|first1=James C.|date=May 10, 1925|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>  That tunnel would have extended [[New York City Subway|subway]] service from Brooklyn to Staten Island.<ref name=\"Raskin-RoutesNotTaken-2013\">{{cite Routes Not Taken}}</ref> This proposal was also revived with the announcement of the Liberty Bridge.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/57301690|title=Tube Projects to be Scanned by Chamber of Commerce Body|last=|first=|date=November 27, 1931|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=41|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> One of the alternative proposals had the subway tunnel going from [[St. George, Staten Island]], to [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]], before continuing to [[Governors Island]] and then Lower Manhattan.<ref name=\":1\" /> Simultaneously, engineers proposed a set of vehicular tunnels from [[Fort Wadsworth]], Staten Island, to 97th Street, Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/06/11/archives/narrows-tube-cost-put-at-78000000-engineers-favor-vehicle-tunnel.html|title=Narrows Tube Cost Put At $78,000,000; Engineers Favor Vehicle Tunnel From 97th St., Brooklyn, To Fort Wadsworth|date=June 11, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The tubes were being planned in conjunction with the [[Queens\u2013Midtown Tunnel|Triborough Tunnel]] (the modern-day Queens Midtown Tunnel), which would connect Manhattan, Brooklyn, and Queens.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/07/27/archives/work-is-started-on-plans-for-tubes-board-of-transportation-takes.html|title=Work Is Started On Plans For Tubes; Board Of Transportation Takes Charge And City Will Seek Law To Give It Authority. Bill To Go To Legislature Plant And Structures Bureau Has Jurisdiction, But Already Is Burdened, Walker Believes. Board Experienced With Tunnels. Work Assigned To Engineers.|date=July 27, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The city appropriated $5{{nbsp}}million for the tunnels in July 1929,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/07/26/archives/city-votes-5000000-assuring-midtown-and-narrows-tubes-estimate.html|title=City Votes $5,000,000 Assuring Midtown And Narrows Tubes; Estimate Board Appropriates Funds To Begin Preliminary Work At Once|date=July 26, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] also pledged funding for the vehicular tunnels.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/08/01/archives/bo-will-aid-city-on-narrows-tunnel-willard-offers-cooperation-of.html|title=B.&O. Will Aid City On Narrows Tunnel; Willard Offers Cooperation Of Railroad At Meeting With Delaney|date=August 1, 1929|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Planning for the vehicular tubes started that month.<ref name=\"The New York Times\" />\n\nThe Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce simultaneously considered all three projects\u2014the bridge, the vehicular tunnels, and the subway tunnel. Community groups on both sides of the Narrows disagreed on which projects should be built first, if at all.<ref name=\":1\" /> Residents of Bay Ridge opposed any plans involving a bridge because its construction would almost definitely require the demolition of part of the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/58211924|title=Civic Center Fights Span at Narrows|date=June 22, 1932|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=33|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Boring work for the vehicular tunnels started in November 1930. The {{Convert|11,000|ft|m|adj=on}} twin tunnels, projected to be completed by 1937, were to connect [[Hylan Boulevard]] on Staten Island with 86th Street in Brooklyn once they were completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/11/23/archives/the-narrows-tunnel-is-a-vast-project-engineers-are-making-borings.html|title=The Narrows Tunnel Is A Vast Project; Engineers Are Making Borings For The Tube To Join Staten Island And Brooklyn.|date=November 23, 1930|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> In January 1932, construction of these tunnels was put on hold indefinitely due to a lack of money.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/57286903|title=Economy Plan Hits Bay Ridge Improvements|date=January 22, 1932|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=37|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The construction work did not go beyond an examination of shoreline on the Brooklyn side.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59867305/|title=Private Group Studying Plans for Vehicular and Transit Narrows Tunnel|date=May 11, 1934|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=41|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Cancellation of bridge ====\nIn February 1933, the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] approved a bill authorizing the construction of a suspension bridge across the Narrows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/02/14/archives/approves-bill-for-narrows-span.html|title=Approves Bill for Narrows Span.|date=February 14, 1933|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> With this approval, the Interboro Bridge Company hoped to start constructing the bridge by the end of the year, thereby creating jobs for 80,000 workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/02/15/archives/expect-work-soon-on-narrows-span-backers-of-brooklynstaten-island.html|title=Expect Work Soon On Narrows Span; Backers Of Brooklyn-Staten Island Bridge Encouraged By Congressional Action|date=February 15, 1933|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Structural engineer [[Othmar Ammann|Othmar H. Ammann]], who was building the Triborough Bridge, Midtown Tunnel, and [[Golden Gate Bridge]] at the time, showed interest in designing the proposed Narrows bridge, which would be the world's longest bridge if it were built.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59982748|title=Master Bridge Builder Runs 3 Jobs at Once|last=Keating|first=Isabelle|date=June 10, 1934|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=6|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The city approved the construction of a rapid transit tunnel under the Narrows in December 1933. This tunnel was approved in conjunction with the proposed [[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]] connecting Red Hook with Lower Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1933/12/27/archives/92669000-works-approved-by-city-board-sanctions-narrows-and.html|title=$92,669,000 Works Approved By City; Board Sanctions Narrows And Manhattan-Brooklyn Tubes And Water Tunnel|date=December 27, 1933|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1934, the War Department announced its opposition to the Narrows Bridge's construction. The War Department's opposition to the bridge plan was based on the fact that a bridge could create a blockage during wartime, a rationale it gave for opposing a [[Brooklyn-Battery Bridge]] connecting [[Red Hook, Brooklyn]], with Lower Manhattan.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/07/20/archives/plans-for-tunnel-at-battery-rushed-agencies-move-to-ask-funds-as.html|title=Plans For Tunnel At Battery Rushed; Agencies Move To Ask Funds As Soon As Federal Lending Facilities Are Ready|date=July 20, 1939|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] did not have a public position regarding the Narrows Bridge plan, other than a request that it be allowed to operate the future bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59866160/|title=War Department Opposed to Bridge over Narrows; Port Authority Neutral|date=May 9, 1934|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=33|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref>  Following the War Department's announcement that they would oppose the Narrows bridge, private interests began studying the feasibility of a tunnel under the Narrows.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== 1930s tunnel plan ====\n[[File:VerrazanoBridge.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|View of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge from the Staten Island entrance plaza]]\n\nIn 1936, the plan for a Narrows crossing was brought up again when now-New York City Mayor La Guardia gained authorization to petition the [[U.S. Congress]] for a bridge across the Narrows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/04/18/archives/mayor-will-urge-narrows-bridge-estimate-board-authorizes-reopening.html|title=Mayor Will Urge Narrows Bridge; Estimate Board Authorizes Reopening Of The Project With War Department.|date=April 18, 1936|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Under the new plan, the proposed bridge would charge tolls for motorists, and its $50{{nbsp}}million cost would be paid off using federal bonds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52697541/|title=Mayor Launches Fresh Drive for Toll Bridge Across Narrows|date=January 28, 1936|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=41|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> LaGuardia preferred a tunnel instead, and so the next year he requested the  [[Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority|New York City Tunnel Authority]] to review the feasibility of such a crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/02/09/archives/mayor-urges-tube-to-staten-island-asks-tunnel-authority-to-study.html|title=Mayor Urges Tube To Staten Island; Asks Tunnel Authority To Study Such A Link To City's Arterial Road System|date=February 9, 1937|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> The New York City Planning Commission was amenable to constructing either a bridge or a tunnel across the Narrows, and in 1939, put forth a plan to expand New York City's highway system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/06/20/archives/highway-network-for-city-is-mapped-master-plan-to-supplement-and.html|title=Highway Network For City Is Mapped|date=June 20, 1939|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> In March of the same year, as a bill for the Battery Bridge was being passed, Staten Island state legislators added a last-minute amendment to the bill, providing for a Narrows bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52753796/|title=Battery Span Bill Moves to Vote in Albany|date=March 3, 1939|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=8|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The Narrows crossing was not included in the final version of the Planning Commission's plan, which was approved in 1941.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1941/01/23/archives/master-road-plan-for-city-modified-planning-board-approves-its.html|title=Master Road Plan For City Modified|date=January 23, 1941|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943, the [[New York City Board of Estimate]] allocated $50,000 toward a feasibility study of the tunnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/04/16/archives/50000-plans-approved-fund-for-narrows-tunnel-study-is-authorized-by.html|title=$50,000 Plans Approved; Fund For Narrows Tunnel Study Is Authorized By Board|date=April 16, 1943|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> By this time, Bay Ridge residents now opposed the tunnel plan as well, because they feared that the tunnel's construction would lower the quality of life in that neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52819064/|title=Bay Ridge Aroused by Narrows Tube O.K.|date=March 22, 1943|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 2|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> After the war ended in 1945, the Planning Commission estimated that construction of the Narrows Tunnel would cost $73.5{{nbsp}}million. However, by then, La Guardia had turned against the tunnel, saying that \"it is not my time\" to construct the tunnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/08/01/archives/narrows-tunnel-opposed-by-mayor-he-agrees-it-is-coming-but-not-in.html|title=Narrows Tunnel Opposed By Mayor|date=August 1, 1945|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 1940s and 1950s bridge plan ===\n\n==== Initial proposal ====\nThe cancellation of plans for the Narrows tunnel brought a resurgence of proposals for a bridge across the Narrows. In September 1947, [[Robert Moses]], the chairman of the Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority (TBTA), announced that the city was going to ask the War Department for permission to build a bridge across the Narrows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1947/09/24/archives/city-plans-to-build-span-at-narrows-moses-says-he-expects-early.html|title=City Plans To Build Span At Narrows|last=Pierce|first=Bert|date=September 24, 1947|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses had previously created a feasibility study for a Narrows tunnel, finding that it would be much cheaper to build a bridge.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{rp|137}} Moses and Mayor [[William O'Dwyer]] both supported the Narrows Bridge plan, which was still being referred to as \"Liberty Bridge\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52916051/|title=Mayor, Moses Plead for S.I. Bridge|date=October 26, 1948|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The city submitted its request to the War Department in July 1948,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/07/19/archives/tunnel-authority-asks-army-for-narrows-bridge-permit-proposed.html|title=Tunnel Authority Asks Army For Narrows Bridge Permit|last=Crowell|first=Paul|date=July 19, 1948|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> and a commission composed of three [[United States Armed Forces]] branches was convened to solicit the public's opinions on the proposed span.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/12/08/archives/approval-sought-for-narrows-span-armynavy-air-force-board-to-get.html|title=Approval Sought For Narrows Span; Army-Navy Air Force Board To Get Petition Jan. 12 For Staten Island Bridge|date=December 8, 1948|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Verrazano Bridge 2012-12-23.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=View northwest at the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn during sunset|The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn during sunset]]\n\nU.S. Representative [[Donald Lawrence O'Toole]], whose constituency included Bay Ridge, opposed the proposal for the bridge because he believed it would damage the character of Bay Ridge, and because the bridge might block the Narrows in case of a war.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/01/13/archives/realty-fraud-seen-in-narrows-bridge-otoole-says-proposed-span-would.html|title=Realty Fraud Seen In Narrows Bridge; O'toole Says Proposed Span Would Lead To City's 'Greatest Swindle In History'|date=1949|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52895480/|title=O'Toole Urges U.S. Ban Bridge over Narrows|date=July 19, 1948|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 3|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He cited a poll showing that for every Bay Ridge resident who supported the bridge's construction, 33 more were opposed.<ref name=\":4\" /> The  U.S. military approved the proposal in May 1949, over the vociferous opposition of Bay Ridge residents, on the condition that construction start within five years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/05/25/archives/army-approves-narrows-bridge-worlds-longest-suspension-span-army.html|title=Army Approves Narrows Bridge, World's Longest Suspension Span; Army Backs Span Over The Narrows|agency=Associated Press|date=May 25, 1949|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/59526452/|title=Bay Ridgeites Battle Army Okay on Span|date=May 25, 1949|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 2|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> By that time, plans for the {{Convert|6540|ft|m|adj=on}} span had been finalized, and the project only needed $78{{nbsp}}million in financing in order to proceed. This financing was not set to be awarded until 1950, when the Battery Tunnel was completed. Preliminary plans showed the bridge as being {{Convert|237|ft|m|abbr=on}} above the mean high water level, enough for the {{Convert|215|ft|m|adj=on}} [[RMS Queen Mary|RMS ''Queen Mary'']] to pass under it.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|137}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/05/26/archives/narrows-crossing-seen-4-years-away-financing-of-bridge-to-wait.html|title=Narrows Crossing Seen 4 Years Away|date=May 26, 1949|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMoses and acting Port Authority Chairman Bayard F. Pope were agreeable to letting either of their respective agencies construct and operate the proposed Narrows Bridge, as long as that agency could do so efficiently. In 1954, the two agencies started conducting a joint study on the logistics of building and constructing the bridge. Because of restrictions by the TBTA's bondholders, construction could not begin until at least 1957.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53591292/|title=Narrows Bridge Cited in Traffic Plans|date=February 15, 1954|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|pages=1, 3|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Frederick H. Zurmuhlen, the Commissioner of Public Works, estimated that the Narrows Bridge would cost $200{{nbsp}}million total.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/11/19/archives/for-narrows-bridge-zurmuhlen-sees-construction-within-next-8-years.html|title=For Narrows Bridge; Zurmuhlen Sees Construction Within Next 8 Years|date=November 19, 1954|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> He encouraged the TBTA to start construction on the bridge as soon as possible in order to reduce congestion on [[East River]] crossings to the north.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53590122/|title=Call for Work on Narrows Bridge|last=Noonan|first=Dan|date=February 11, 1954|work=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=4|via=[[Brooklyn Public Library]]; [[newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Staten Islanders viewed the project cautiously, since the Narrows Bridge would provide a connection to the rest of the city, but could also cause traffic congestion through the borough.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/01/18/archives/rural-staten-island-views-span-to-brooklyn-as-a-mixed-blessing.html|title=Rural Staten Island Views Span To Brooklyn as a Mixed Blessing|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses had only a positive view of the bridge's proposed effects on Staten Islanders, saying that it was vital for the borough's future.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/04/14/archives/narrows-bridge-held-a-vital-link-moses-warns-staten-island-its.html|title=Narrows Bridge Held A Vital Link; Moses Warns Staten Island Its Future Depends Greatly On Span To Brooklyn|last=Schumach|first=Murray|date=April 14, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1954, the Army's permit for starting construction on the Narrows Bridge lapsed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/05/01/archives/narrows-bridge-up-to-army-again-triborough-boards-request-for.html|title=Narrows Bridge Up To Army Again; Triborough Board's Request For Two-Year Extension Of Permit May Revive Dispute|date=May 1, 1954|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The Army granted a two-year extension for the start of construction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/07/08/archives/i-bridge-permit-extended-army-sets-may-1956-for-start-of-the.html|title=Bridge Permit Extended; Army Sets May, 1956, For Start Of The Narrows Span|date=July 8, 1954|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In a measure passed in March 1955, the city gained control over the approval process for several tasks related to the Narrows bridge's construction, including land acquisition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/03/30/archives/city-wins-control-of-plan-for-bridge-over-narrows-city-wins-dispute.html|title=City Wins Control Of Plan For Bridge Over Narrows |last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=March 30, 1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> A little more than a month later, New York Governor [[W. Averell Harriman]] signed a $600{{nbsp}}million spending bill authorizing the construction of the Narrows Bridge; the construction of the [[Throgs Neck Bridge]] between Queens and [[the Bronx]]; and the addition of a second level to the [[George Washington Bridge]] between Manhattan and [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/05/01/archives/city-artery-bills-signed-in-albany-package-would-allow-start-of.html|title=City Artery Bills Signed In Albany; 'Package' Would Allow Start Of Work On $600,000,000 Construction Program|date=May 1, 1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Later that year, it was announced that the Narrows Bridge would be part of an expansion to the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/09/29/archives/u-s-bureau-lists-interstate-roads-routes-for-highway-system-in-and.html|title=U. S. Bureau Lists Interstate Roads; Routes For Highway System In And Around 102 Urban Areas Are Approved|date=September 29, 1955|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Although a study on the viability of adding transit service to the Narrows Bridge was commissioned in early 1956,<ref name=\":12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/03/14/archives/engineers-obtained-for-transit-study.html|title=Engineers Obtained for Transit Study|date=March 14, 1956|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses rejected the idea of adding subway tracks onto the new bridge, saying that it would be too costly.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/09/archives/moses-bars-train-on-narrows-span-mocks-idea-of-transit-link-from.html|title=Moses Bars Train On Narrows Span; Mocks Idea Of Transit Link From Kings To Staten Island As Absurdly Expensive |last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=April 9, 1956|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In April of that year, New Jersey Governor [[Robert B. Meyner]] signed a bill that allowed the Port Authority to build the Narrows Bridge and lease it to the TBTA, who would operate the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/04/archives/meyner-signs-bill-on-narrows-bridge.html|title=Meyner Signs Bill on Narrows Bridge|date=April 4, 1956|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The TBTA would buy the bridge from the Port Authority in 1967 as part of the agreement.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/14/archives/bridge-is-started-across-narrows-ground-is-broken-on-staten-island.html|title=Bridge Is Started Across Narrows|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=August 14, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Finalization of plans ====\nOn the Brooklyn side, the Narrows Bridge was originally supposed to connect to the [[Belt Parkway|Circumferential (Belt) Parkway]], but in early 1957, Harriman vetoed a bill that stipulated that the main approach connect to the Belt Parkway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/05/18/archives/delay-is-sought-on-narrows-plan-bay-ridge-residents-call-for.html|title=Delay Is Sought On Narrows Plan; Bay Ridge Residents Call For Putting Off Approval Till All Links Are Proposed|last=Crowell|first=Paul|date=May 18, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> By May 1957, an updated location for the Brooklyn anchorage had been agreed on. The anchorage was now to be located at [[Fort Lafayette]], an island coastal fortification built next to [[Fort Hamilton]] at the southern tip of Bay Ridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/05/01/archives/moses-and-army-agree-on-narrows-span-site.html|title=Moses and Army Agree On Narrows Span Site|date=May 1, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Moses also proposed expanding Brooklyn's [[Gowanus Expressway]] and extending it to the Narrows Bridge by way of Seventh Avenue, which would require cutting through the middle of Bay Ridge. This proposal drew opposition from the community, who wanted the approach to follow the Belt Parkway along the Brooklyn shore.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/06/20/archives/span-approaches-approved-by-city-narrows-and-throgs-neck-routes-are.html|title=Span Approaches Approved By City; Narrows And Throgs Neck Routes Are Advanced By Planning Commission; Moses' Plan Rebuffed; Fourth Ave. Curve Is Deleted In Brooklyn--Alternate Ideas To Be Studied|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=June 20, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> These opponents said that the Seventh Avenue alignment would displace over 1,500 families.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/10/21/archives/city-bars-change-in-narrows-plan-rejects-liberty-bridge-or-tunnel.html|title=City Bars Change In Narrows Plan; Rejects Liberty Bridge Or Tunnel As Substitutes -No Action On Approach|date=October 21, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>  In February 1958, the New York State Legislature approved a bill to change the Brooklyn approaches back to Belt Parkway, which was almost identical to the bill Harriman had vetoed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/02/19/archives/assembly-votes-narrows-change-route-shift-bill-is-same-as-one.html|title=Assembly Votes Narrows Change; Route Shift Bill Is Same As One Vetoed In '57 -- G.O.P. Expects It To Aid Party|last=Egan|first=Leo|date=February 19, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> However, the city approved the Seventh Avenue bridge approach in August 1958.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/08/14/archives/approach-is-fixed-to-narrows-span-plan-board-rejects-urgent-bay.html|title=Approach Is Fixed To Narrows Span; Plan Board Rejects Urgent Bay Ridge Objections To The 7th Ave. Brooklyn Route|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=August 14, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The next month, Mayor [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]] said that the city was committed to building a bridge across the Narrows, but was not committed to the construction of the Seventh Avenue approach. In response, Moses wrote to Wagner that any continuing delays would cause the bridge to be canceled. The bridge's cost had now risen to $320{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/09/23/archives/narrows-bridge-backed-by-mayor-he-supports-moses-on-city-commitment.html|title=Narrows Bridge Backed By Mayor; He Supports Moses On City Commitment -- Suit Seeks To Bar Hearing Friday|date=September 23, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter holding a hearing for concerned Bay Ridge residents, the Board of Estimate affirmed the Narrows Bridge plan in October 1958,<ref name=\":6\" /> without any objections.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\" />{{rp|752}} At the same time, it rejected plans for a tunnel under the Narrows, as well as a bridge or tunnel from Brooklyn directly to [[Jersey City, New Jersey]].<ref name=\":6\" /> The Board was set to vote on the Seventh Avenue approach in mid-December, but the federal government stated that it would only agree to the bridge's construction if the Seventh Avenue approach had 12 lanes, with six on each level.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/12/23/archives/u-s-asks-12-lanes-on-bridge-access-estimate-board-defers-vote-in.html|title=U. S. Asks 12 Lanes On Bridge Access; Estimate Board Defers Vote in Impasse on Brooklyn End of Narrows Span|date=December 23, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The federal government was already paying for two highway improvements on both sides of the proposed bridge: the Clove Lakes Expressway on Staten Island, and the Gowanus Expressway in Brooklyn.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{Rp|137}}<ref name=\":6\" /> On December 31 of that year, the Board of Estimate voted to approve plans for the Seventh Avenue approach, having delayed that vote several times.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/12/31/archives/narrows-bridge-approved-by-city-job-to-be-speeded-estimate-board.html|title=Narrows Bridge Approved by City; Job to be Speeded|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=December 31, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe approval of the Seventh Avenue approach angered Bay Ridge residents since the construction of the approach would displace 7,500 people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/01/01/archives/bay-ridge-seethes-over-bridge-plan-housewife-and-dentist-chafe-over.html|title=Bay Ridge Seethes Over Bridge Plan; Housewife and Dentist Chafe Over Approval by City of Staten Island Span|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=January 1, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> This amount of opposition was not matched in Staten Island, even though more than twice as many people were being displaced there, because the Staten Island Ferry was the only way to get between the island and the rest of the city. On the contrary, the bridge's announcement was welcomed because it sparked a rise in real-estate prices on the island.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|18&ndash;20}} As the controversy progressed, Steinman brought up a competing proposal to build a bridge between Brooklyn and New Jersey directly.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{Rp|138}}<ref>{{cite news | title=Cross-Bay Bridge Urged by Builder | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 4, 1958 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/11/04/archives/crossbay-bridge-urged-by-builder.html | access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Nelson Rockefeller]], the Republican candidate for governor of New York, initially supported Steinman's proposal to build a bridge to New Jersey, but Moses later persuaded Rockefeller to endorse the bridge to Staten Island.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{Rp|138}}\n\nThe State Legislature drafted a bill in an effort to change the Brooklyn approach's location to Belt Parkway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/03/19/archives/bay-ridge-route-for-bridge-upset-narrows-span-approach-on-7th-ave.html|title=Bay Ridge Route for Bridge Upset; Narrows Span Approach on 7th Ave. Is Switched to Parkway by Legislature|date=March 19, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> However, now-Governor Rockefeller vetoed the Belt Parkway bill,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/04/11/archives/governor-backs-7th-avenue-route-to-narrows-span-he-vetoes-shore.html|title=Governor Backs 7th Avenue Route to Narrows Span; He Vetoes Shore Parkway Approach to Bridge as Costly and Long|last=Weaver, Jr.|first=Warren|date=April 11, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> and in March 1959, the Board of Estimate officially condemned land along Seventh Avenue to make way for the Gowanus Expressway extension to the Narrows Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/03/26/archives/7th-ave-affirmed-as-narrows-link-over-angry-protests-of-bay-ridge.html|title=7th Ave. Affirmed As Narrows Link; Over Angry Protests of Bay Ridge Dwellers, City Board Votes to Condemn Land|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=March 26, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The only tasks remaining before the start of construction were to finalize the design of the Narrows Bridge, and to speed up the construction schedule to meet a 1964 deadline.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/04/11/archives/design-is-speeded-on-narrows-span-bridge-to-be-completed-1964.html|title=Design is Speeded on Narrows Plan; Bridge, to Be Completed 1964, Expected to Spur Staten Island Growth|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=April 11, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In April 1959, the bridge was officially renamed after the Italian navigator [[Giovanni da Verrazzano]].<ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/04/18/archives/governor-backs-verrazano-span-favors-naming-of-narrows-bridge-for.html|title=Governor Backs 'Verrazano' Span; Favors Naming of Narrows Bridge for the Explorer -- Italian Honored Here|date=April 18, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> This sparked [[#Naming|a controversy]] because the proposed bridge's name only had one \"z\" while the explorer's name had two \"z\"s.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/14/archives/zs-spell-trouble-for-bridge-name-officials-go-to-staten-island-on.html|title=Z'S Spell Trouble for Bridge Name; Officials Go to Staten Island on Verrazzano Boat for a One-Z Affair|date=August 14, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\n==== Preparation ====\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge circa 1960.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=Construction progress: the towers and cables have been laid, but not the deck.|Tower and cables during construction without risers or roadbed]]\n\nSurveying work for the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge began in January 1959.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|29}} The official construction on the bridge began on August 14, 1959, with a groundbreaking ceremony on the Staten Island anchorage. Those in attendance included New Jersey Governor Meyner, New York City Mayor Wagner, and TBTA Chairman Moses. Although New York Governor Rockefeller had been invited to the event, neither he nor Assembly Speaker [[Joseph F. Carlino]] showed up.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|30}} In December 1959, the TBTA was put in charge of funding and building the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/12/archives/moses-takes-over-narrows-bridge-triborough-agency-regains-financing.html|title=Moses Takes Over Narrows Bridge; Triborough Agency Regains Financing Control From the Port Authority|date=December 12, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>  To raise money for construction, Rockefeller signed a bill that would remove the 4% [[Floor and ceiling functions|ceiling]] on the interest rates for the [[Security (finance)|securities]] that the TBTA was selling to pay for the bridge. This ceiling would be lifted until June 1965. In essence, this meant that the TBTA could sell securities at much higher interest rates to raise the $320{{nbsp}}million that was needed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/04/16/archives/governor-signs-bridge-bond-bill-measure-lifts-4-limit-on-securities.html|title=Governor Signs Bridge Bond Bill; Measure Lifts 4% Limit on Securities Sold to Speed Work on Narrows Span|date=April 16, 1960|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Swiss-born engineer [[Othmar Ammann]] was named as the senior partner for the project.<ref name=\":5\" /> Other notable figures involved chief engineer Milton Brumer;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/10/nyregion/milton-brumer-97-engineer-for-famed-new-york-bridges.html|title=Milton Brumer, 97, Engineer For Famed New York Bridges|last=Ravo|first=Nick|date=August 10, 1999|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Adams1996\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/hudsonriverguide0000adam|url-access=registration|title=The Hudson River Guidebook|last=Adams|first=Arthur G.|date=1996|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-82321-679-6|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hudsonriverguide0000adam/page/45 45]}}</ref> project engineers Herb Rothman and Frank L. Stahl;<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal|last=Kinney|first=John W.|last2=Rothman|first2=Herbert|last3=Stahl|first3=Frank|date=1966|title=Verrazano-Narrow {{sic|nolink=y|expected=Verrazano-Narrows}} Bridge: Fabrication and Construction|url=http://cedb.asce.org/CEDBsearch/record.jsp?dockey=0014164|journal=Journal of the Construction Division|volume=92|issue=2|pages=|via=}}</ref> design engineer [[Leopold Just]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/07/nyregion/leopold-h-just-95-is-dead-designer-of-new-york-bridges.html|title=Leopold H. Just, 95, Is Dead; Designer of New York Bridges|last=Thomas, Jr.|first=Robert McG.|author-link=Robert McG. Thomas Jr.|date=March 7, 1999|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Safety Engineer Alonzo Dickinson,<ref>{{cite book | title=Popular Science | publisher=Bonnier Corporation | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lyADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA74 |date=November 1963 | access-date=March 16, 2018 | page=74}}</ref> and engineer of construction John West Kinney.<ref name=\":10\" /> Meanwhile, John \"Hard Nose\" Murphy supervised the span's and cables' construction.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|52}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/08/25/tough-bridge-builder-nears-end-of-a-tough-job.html|title=Tough Bridge Builder Nears End of a Tough Job|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=August 25, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore starting actual work on the bridge, the TBTA destroyed the structures at the future locations of the anchorages.<ref name=\":5\" /> The agency acquired {{Convert|36|acre|ha}} of the {{Convert|138|acre|ha|abbr=on}} within Fort Hamilton, in return for paying for a $12{{nbsp}}million renovation of the Army installation and giving up {{Convert|10.8|acre|ha|abbr=on}} of land in [[Dyker Beach Park and Golf Course|Dyker Beach Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201963%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201963%2520-%25200579.pdf|title=Fort Hamilton Facelift Is Free To Taxpayer, As TBTA Pays Bill|last=Chatfield|first=James|date=April 1, 1960|work=New York World-Telegram|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=1|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> A 1,000-ton World War I monument on the Brooklyn side, within the path of the future Seventh Avenue approach, was placed atop rolling logs and shifted {{Convert|370|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/01/19/archives/1000ton-obelisk-to-be-moved-370-feet-on-rollers-in-brooklyn.html|title=1,000-Ton Obelisk to Be Moved 370 Feet on Rollers in Brooklyn|last=Maiorana|first=Ronald|date=1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The [[Right of way|right-of-way]] for the Seventh Avenue approach was also being cleared, and despite initial opposition to the clearing work, all of the residents within the approach's path eventually acquiesced to moving elsewhere.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|24}} To prevent contractors from delaying work on the expressways on either side of the bridge, Moses warned them of steep fines if the expressways were not completed by the time the bridge was finished.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/11/10/archives/road-builders-to-face-penalties-for-delays-at-narrows-bridge.html|title=Road Builders to Face Penalties For Delays at Narrows Bridge|date=November 10, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Progress ====\nAn anchorage was built on each side of the Narrows, with each anchorage measuring {{Convert|229|ft|m|abbr=on}} long by {{Convert|129|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide, and containing a combined {{convert|780,000|ST|LT}} of steel and concrete. Each anchorage contained sixty-six large holes for the cables.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{rp|147}}<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/03/16/archives/footing-is-sunk-for-bay-bridge-concrete-foundation-put-in-off-si.html|title=Footing is Sunk for Bay Bridge; Concrete Foundation Put In Off S.I. for One Tower -- Brooklyn Work Pushed|date=March 16, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The bases of each anchorage are built on glacial sands, reaching {{convert|52|ft|m}} below ground level on the Brooklyn side, and {{convert|76|ft|m}} below ground level on the Staten Island side.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\" />{{rp|147}} Foundation work for the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge was well underway by 1960, as visitors were able to see the anchorages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/08/06/archives/work-in-narrows-now-a-city-sight-waterborne-travelers-can-inspect.html|title=Work in Narrows Now a City Sight; Waterborne Travelers Can Inspect Foundation Work for Mammoth Bridge|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=August 6, 1960|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> A concrete workers' strike in mid-1961 threatened the timely completion of the Staten Island anchorage, which had only been partially filled with concrete.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/08/18/archives/washout-feared-at-site-of-bridge-lack-of-concrete-threatens-narrows.html|title=Washout Feared At Site Of Bridge; Lack Of Concrete Threatens Narrows Construction|date=August 18, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> This strike lasted several months and affected many projects under the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/07/11/archives/pact-cuts-tieup-in-construction-800-drivers-end-walkout-1200.html|title=Pact Cuts Tie-Up In Construction; 800 Drivers End Walkout -- 1,200 Continue Strike|last=Katz|first=Ralph|date=July 11, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs construction on the anchorages proceeded, two watertight [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] were sunk into the channel close to either shoreline, so that the bridge's suspension towers could be built atop each caisson. The bases of each caisson consisted of sixty-six circular openings each {{convert|17|ft|m}} in diameter, arranged in a six-by-eleven grid. Shafts of reinforced concrete would be built along the inner rim of each opening, and once each section of shaft reached {{convert|40|ft|m}} above water level, cranes with [[clamshell bucket]]s would dig the sand and mud inside each shaft before sinking the shafts deeper into the water.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|144}} The Staten Island side's caisson was sunk {{Convert|105|ft|m|abbr=on}} into the water, and necessitated the dredging of {{Convert|81000|yd3|m3}} of sand and assorted muck.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|144}} This caisson required {{Convert|47000|yd3|m3|abbr=on}} of concrete, and in March 1961, it became the first of the two caissons to be sunk.<ref name=\":11\" /> The Brooklyn side's caisson required even more work, since it was {{Convert|170|ft|m|abbr=on}} deep, displaced {{Convert|145000|yd3|m3|abbr=on}} of muck, and used {{Convert|83000|yd3|m3|abbr=on}} of concrete.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|144}} Once the caissons were sunk completely, the shafts inside each caisson were filled with water, and the bases of the caissons were covered by a sheet of reinforced concrete.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|146}} The process of constructing the anchorages and caissons took just over two years, and it was complete by the end of 1961.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|54}}\n\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge- The Beginning (15694094466).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Construction of the suspension towers, seen in 1962]]\n\nAfterward, two separate companies constructed the modules that would make up the {{Convert|693|ft|m|-tall|adj=mid|abbr=on}} suspension towers. The Staten Island tower was built  by [[Bethlehem Steel]], and the Brooklyn tower was built by the [[Harris Structural Company]].<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|55}} The first piece of the towers, a 300-foot piece of the tower on the Staten Island side, was lifted into place in October 1961,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/10/11/archives/first-major-steel-section-placed-for-verrazano-narrows-bridge-moses.html|title=First Major Steel Section Placed For Verrazano -- Narrows Bridge; Moses Gives Signal to Put 47-Ton Piece on Pedestal Off Staten Island Shore|date=October 11, 1961|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and this tower was topped out by September 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/09/18/archives/tower-topped-out-on-narrows-bridge.html|title=Tower Topped Out on Narrows Bridge|date=September 18, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The Brooklyn tower started construction in April 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/04/10/archives/tower-in-brooklyn-for-bridge-is-begun.html|title=Tower in Brooklyn for Bridge Is Begun|date=April 10, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> When the towers were fully erected, workers began the process of spinning the bridge's cables. The [[American Bridge Company]] was selected to construct the cables and deck.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|53}} The cable-spinning process began in March 1963, and took six months, since {{Convert|142,520|mi|km|abbr=on}} of bridge cables had to be strung 104,432 times around the bridge.<ref name=\"Cables-Spinning-1963\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/03/08/archives/spinning-of-cables-begins-on-nys-narrows-span.html|title=Spinning of Cables Begins on N.Y.'s Narrows Span|date=March 8, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Moses Says Bridge Ahead Of Marks; Start of 6-Month Cable Spinning Operation|date=March 15, 1963|last=Griffin|first=J. Frank|work=Brooklyn Home-Reporter|pages=[http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201962%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201962%2520Dec-Jan%25201963%252000307_1.pdf 6], [http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2024/Brooklyn%20NY%20Home%20Reporter%20&%20Sunset%20News/Brooklyn%20NY%20Home%20Reporter%20&%20Sunset%20News%201962/Brooklyn%20NY%20Home%20Reporter%20&%20Sunset%20News%201962%20Dec-Jan%201963%2000307_2.pdf 7]|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> The main cables were hung on both sides of the span, and then suspender cables were hung from the bridge's main cables.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|58}} The main cables were fully spun by August.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/08/29/archives/cable-spinning-completed-for-the-verrazano-bridge.html|title=Cable Spinning Completed For the Verrazano Bridge|date=August 29, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1963, builders started receiving the rectangular pieces that would make up the roadway deck. The components for the sixty 40-ton slabs were first created in an assembly line in Jersey City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/09/20/archives/bridge-is-shaped-on-assembly-line-400ton-verrazano-units-fashioned.html|title=Bridge is Shaped on Assembly Line; 400-Ton Verrazano Units Fashioned in Jersey Yard 145 Men in Assembly Line|last=Stengren|first=Bernard|date=September 20, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Then, these components were combined in a Bayonne steelworks {{Convert|5|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} from the bridge site, and after the pieces of each slab were assembled, they were floated to the Narrows via barge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/23/bridge-delights-seaside-supers.html|title=Bridge Delights 'seaside Supers'|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=January 23, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Each piece measured {{Convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} high by approximately {{Convert|115|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide and long. These pieces of the deck were then hung from the suspender cables[[Harris Structural Company|.]]<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|94&ndash;95}} The first piece of the deck was lifted onto the bridge in October 1963.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/10/26/archives/first-overwater-steel-segment-is-hoisted-to-narrows-bridge.html|title=First Overwater Steel Segment Is Hoisted to Narrows Bridge|last=Stengren|first=Bernard|date=October 26, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> By early 1964, the span was nearly finished, and all that remained was to secure the various parts of the bridge.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|133}} By this point, plans for new development on Staten Island were well underway,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/11/20/archives/si-planning-now-for-great-influx-maniscalco-tells-of-efforts-to.html|title=S.I. Planning Now for Great Influx; Maniscalco Tells of Efforts to Keep City From Giving 'Too Much Too Late'|last=Knowles|first=Clayton|author-link=Clayton Knowles|date=November 20, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and tourists had come to observe the construction of the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/04/06/archives/verrazano-bridge-the-citys-newest-landmark-graces-harbor-with-a.html|title=Verrazano Bridge, the City's Newest Landmark|last=Stengren|first=Bernard|date=April 6, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The bridge had been scheduled to open in 1965, but as a result of the faster-than-anticipated rate of progress, the TBTA decided to open the bridge in November 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/03/28/narrows-bridge-is-due-to-open-a-head-of-schedule-in-november.html|title=Narrows Bridge Is Due to Open Ahead of Schedule in November|first=Bernard |last=Stengren|date=March 28, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> In preparation for the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge's opening, the TBTA fully repainted the structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/10/24/verrazano-bridge-getting-coat-of-gray-for-opening.html|title=Verrazano Bridge Getting Coat of Gray for Opening|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=October 24, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The construction process of the bridge had employed an average of 1,200 workers a day for five years, excluding those who had worked on the approaches; around 10,000 individuals had worked on the bridge throughout that five-year period.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\">{{cite Power Broker}}</ref>{{rp|736}}\n\nThree men died during the construction of the bridge.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{rp|91}} The first fatality was 58-year-old Paul Bassett, who fell off the deck and struck a tower in August 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/08/25/archives/man-killed-at-narrows-span.html|title=Man Killed at Narrows Span|date=August 25, 1962|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Irving Rubin, also 58 years old, died in July 1963, when he fell off of the bridge approach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2520May-Nov%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2520May-Nov%252000188_2.pdf|title=Bridge Claims 2nd Victim, Worker Dies In 80-Ft.Fall|date=July 19, 1963|work=Brooklyn Home-Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{rp|91}} The third worker who died was 19-year-old Gerard McKee, who fell into the water in October 1963, after slipping off the catwalk.<ref name=\"Talese Book\">{{cite book|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|title=The Bridge: The Building of the Verrazano\u2013Narrows Bridge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cK-pBAAAQBAJ|isbn=9781620409114|location=New York City|publisher=[[Harper & Row]]|year=1964|lccn=64-7832}}</ref>{{rp|91}}<ref name=\"Rasenberger\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XDSxwPx-yJ4C&pg=PA270|last=Rasenberger|first=Jim|title=High Steel: the Daring Men Who Built the World's Greatest Skyline|page=270|year=2004|location=New York, NY|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=0-06-000434-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/10/10/archives/bridge-worker-falls-to-death.html|title=Bridge Worker Falls to Death|date=October 10, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> After McKee's death, workers participated in a five-day strike in December 1963. The strike resulted in temporary safety nets being installed underneath the deck.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|98}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/12/07/archives/bridge-men-to-get-nets-on-narrows-300-will-return-to-job-on-monday.html|title=Bridge Men To Get Nets On Narrows|last=Arnold|first=Martin|date=December 7, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /> These nets had not been provided during the four years prior to the strike.<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" />\n\n{{Anchor|The Bridge: The Building of the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge|The Bridge}}The construction of the bridge was chronicled by the writer [[Gay Talese]] in his 1964 book ''The Bridge: The Building of the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge''. He also wrote several articles about the bridge's construction for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/02/nyregion/gay-talese-reminisces-about-verrazano-narrows-bridge-construction.html|title=Gay Talese Reminisces About Verrazano Construction|last=Berger|first=Joseph|date=July 1, 2014|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The book also contains several drawings by [[Lili R\u00e9thi]] and photographs by [[Bruce Davidson (photographer)|Bruce Davidson.]]<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|Cover Page}}\n\n=== Opening and early years ===\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge 5c 1964 issue U.S. stamp.jpg|thumb|alt=Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge commemorative stamp, first sold on November 21, 1964, in conjunction with the bridge's opening|{{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge commemorative stamp, first sold on November 21, 1964, in conjunction with the bridge's opening]]\nThe Staten Island approach to the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge was the first part of the new project to be completed, and it opened in January 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/27/verrazano-link-will-open-on-si.html|title=Verrazano Link Will Open on S.I.|last=Ingraham |first=Joseph C.|date=January 27, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The upper deck was opened on November 21, 1964, at a cost of $320&nbsp;million in 1964<!-- equivalent to ${{inflation|US|0.320|1964|fmt=c|r=3}}&nbsp;billion in present dollars -->.<ref name=\":14\"/> Politicians at all levels of the government, from Brooklyn Borough President [[Abe Stark]] to U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], wrote speeches paying tribute to the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201964%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201964%2520b%2520-%25203313.pdf|title=Notables Salute the New Queen|date=November 21, 1964|work=New York World-Telegram|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=2|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> The opening ceremony was attended by over 5,000 people, including 1,500 official guests. Several dignitaries, involving the mayor, the governor, and the borough presidents of Brooklyn and Staten Island, cut the gold ribbon. They then joined a motorcade to mark the official opening of the bridge.<ref name=\"wnyc\">{{cite news |title=Verrazano Bridge Turns 40 |first=Beth |last=Fertig |url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2004/nov/21/verrazano-bridge-turns-40/ |publisher=[[WNYC]] |date=November 21, 2004 |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607022340/http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2004/nov/21/verrazano-bridge-turns-40/ |archivedate=June 7, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/22/verrazano-bridge-opened-to-traffic.html|title=Verrazano Bridge Opened to Traffic|last=Talese|first=Gay|author-link=Gay Talese|date=November 22, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> A 50-cent toll was charged to all motorists crossing the bridge.<ref name=\"NYTimes-NewBridge_Roads-1964\"/> The {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge's opening was celebrated across Staten Island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/22/opening-is-hailed-at-many-parties.html|title=Opening Is Hailed at Many Parties|first=Philip |last=Benjamin|date=November 22, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Moses did not invite any of the 12,000 workers to the opening,<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /> so they boycotted the event and instead attended a mass in memory of the three workers who died during construction.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nThe opening was accompanied by the release of a commemorative postage stamp, which depicted a ship sailing underneath the new span.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/10/23/new-verrazano-bridge-stamp-unveiled-at-a-democratic-rally.html|title=New Verrazano Bridge Stamp Unveiled at a Democratic Rally|date=October 23, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (MTA) created a bus route across the bridge to connect [[Victory Boulevard (Staten Island)|Victory Boulevard]] in Staten Island with the [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]] subway station in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/08/bus-service-set-for-new-bridge.html|title=Bus Service Set for New Bridge|date=November 8, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> This bus service initially saw low patronage, with only 6,000 daily passengers using the route.<ref>{{cite news | title=Transit Authority Cuts Bus Service On Narrows Span | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 7, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/01/07/archives/transit-authority-cuts-bus-service-on-narrows-span.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Five days after the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge opened, the ferry from Staten Island to Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, stopped running, as it was now redundant to the new bridge.<ref>{{cite news | last=Dougherty | first=Philip H. | title=Brooklyn Ferry Enters Oblivion | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 26, 1964 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/26/brooklyn-ferry-enters-oblivion.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWithin the first two months of the bridge's opening, 1.86{{nbsp}}million vehicles had used the new crossing, 10% more than originally projected, and this netted the TBTA almost $1{{nbsp}}million in toll revenue. The [[Goethals Bridge]], which connected New Jersey to the Staten Island Expressway and the {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge, saw its daily average use increase by 75%, or approximately 300,000 trips total, compared to before the Narrows Bridge opened. The [[Holland Tunnel]] from New Jersey to Manhattan, and the Staten Island Ferry from Staten Island to Manhattan, both saw decreased vehicle counts after the bridge opened.<ref>{{cite news | last=Ingraham | first=Joseph C. | title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge Traffic Runs 10% Above Forecasts; 1,860,000 Vehicles Have Paid Nearly $1 Million Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 8, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/01/08/archives/verrazanonarrows-bridge-traffic-runs-10-above-forecasts-1860000.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> In summer 1965, Staten Island saw increased patronage at its beaches, facilitated by the opening of the new bridge.<ref>{{cite news | last=Schanberg | first=Sydney H. | title=Over the Bridge They Go to Staten Island's Beaches | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=July 29, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/07/29/archives/over-the-bridge-they-go-to-staten-islands-beaches.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> By the time of the bridge's first anniversary, 17{{nbsp}}million motorists had crossed the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge, paying $9{{nbsp}}million in tolls.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201965%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520The%2520World%2520Telegram%2520and%2520Sun%25201965%2520a%2520-%25202251.pdf|title=Verrazano Bridge Collects $9 Million in First Year|last=Gerard|first=Patterson|date=November 20, 1965|work=New York World-Telegram|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> The bridge had seen 34% more trips than planners had projected.<ref>{{cite news | last=Ingraham | first=Joseph C. | title=Narrows Bridge a Year Old Today; Traffic Is 34% Higher Than Builders Had Predicted | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 21, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/11/21/archives/narrows-bridge-a-year-old-today-traffic-is-34-higher-than-builders.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Conversely, 5.5{{nbsp}}million fewer passengers and 700,000 fewer vehicles rode the Staten Island Ferry to Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/28/archives/verrazano-bridge-cuts-into-si-ferry-revenue.html|title=Verrazano Bridge Cuts Into S.I. Ferry Revenue|date=April 28, 1966|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge was the last project designed by Ammann, who had designed many of the other major crossings into and within New York City. He died in 1965, the year after the bridge opened.<ref>{{cite news | title=Othmar Ammann, Engineer, Is Dead; Designed Verrazano Bridge and Triborough Span | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=September 24, 1965 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/09/24/archives/othmar-ammann-engineer-is-dead-designed-verrazano-bridge-and.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge was also the last great [[public works]] project in New York City overseen by Moses.<ref>{{cite news | last=Barron | first=Ann Marie | title=Robert Moses: Master planner saw Verrazano-Narrows Bridge as crucial link for commerce | website=Staten Island Advance | date=November 13, 2014 | url=http://www.silive.com/news/2014/11/moses_fingerprints_will_foreve.html | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> The urban planner envisioned that the {{not a typo|Verrazano}} and Throgs Neck Bridges would be the final major bridges in New York City for the time being, since they would complete the city's expressway system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/06/24/archives/moses-sees-close-of-bigbridge-era-narrows-and-throgs-neck-to-be.html|title=Moses Sees Close Of Big-Bridge Era; Narrows And Throgs Neck To Be Last Here, He Says Moses Sees Close Of Big-Bridge Era|date=June 24, 1957|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Additional deck and later years===\nAlthough the bridge was constructed with only one 6-lane roadway, Ammann had provided extra trusses to support a potential second roadway underneath the main deck.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252010%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201963%2520%2520Grayscale%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201963%2520%2520Grayscale%2520-%25201091.pdf|title=Work Rushed On Bridge to Staten Island|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 5, 1963|work=Yonkers Herald Statesman|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> These trusses, which were used to strengthen the bridge, were a design alteration that was added to many bridges in the aftermath of the [[Tacoma Narrows Bridge (1940)|Tacoma Narrows Bridge]] collapse in 1940.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|45}} The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge became so popular among motorists that in March 1969, the TBTA decided to erect the lower deck<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/03/31/archives/narrows-bridge-to-get-2d-deck-in-midjune.html|title=Narrows Bridge to Get 2d Deck in Mid-June|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=March 31, 1969|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> at a cost of $22{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"Caro 1974\"/>{{rp|1130}} The Verrazzano Bridge had not been expected to carry enough traffic to necessitate a second deck until 1978, but traffic patterns over the previous five years had demonstrated the need for extra capacity. By contrast, a lower deck on the [[George Washington Bridge]], connecting New Jersey and Upper Manhattan, had not been built until thirty-one years after the bridge's 1931 opening.<ref name=\"NYT19690629\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/06/29/archives/2d-level-of-verrazano-bridge-opens-11-years-ahead-of-plan.html|title=2d Level of Verrazano Bridge Opens 11 Years Ahead of Plan|last=Schumach|first=Murray|date=June 29, 1969|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The new six-lane deck opened on June 28, 1969.<ref name=\"NYT19690629\" /> Originally, the Verrazzano Bridge's Brooklyn end was also supposed to connect to the planned [[Cross-Brooklyn Expressway]], [[New York State Route 878]], and [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|JFK Airport]], but the Cross-Brooklyn Expressway project was canceled in 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/07/17/archives/mayor-drops-plans-for-express-roads-across-2-boroughs-mayor.html|title=Mayor Drops Plans For Express Roads Across 2 Boroughs; Mayor Abandons Plans for Expressways Across Brooklyn and Lower Manhattan|last=Carroll|first=Maurice|date=July 17, 1969|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 1976, to celebrate the United States' 200th anniversary, workers placed a very large U.S. flag on the side of the Verrazzano Bridge.<ref name=\"NYTimes-BigFlag-1976\"/> The flag, which measured {{convert|193|by|366|ft|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Perez 1980\"/> was described in ''The New York Times'' as being the size of \"a football field and a half\"<ref name=\"NYTimes-BigFlag-1976\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/26/archives/bigflag-story-unfurls-on-verrazano-bridge.html|title=Big\u2010Flag Story Unfurls On Verrazano Bridge|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|date=June 26, 1976|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> and billed as the world's largest flag.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/29/archives/bridge-flag-falls-victim-to-the-wind.html|title=Bridge Flag Falls Victim To the Wind|date=June 29, 1976|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> At the time, it was the largest U.S. flag ever made.<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /> The flag was supposed to withstand wind speeds of {{Convert|30|mph|kph}}, but it ripped apart three days later, when there was a wind speed of {{Convert|16|mph|kph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":15\" /> The flag had been stuck against the bridge's suspender cables, so any slight wind would have caused the cables to make tears in the flag.<ref name=\"Perez 1980\"/> A second flag was created in 1980 for the July 4 celebration that year. This flag was even larger at {{convert|411|by|210|ft|abbr=on}} (an area of {{convert|71,000|ft2|m2|abbr=on}}). The new flag was placed along a steel grid so that the suspender cables would not rip it apart.<ref name=\"Perez 1980\">{{cite news |first=Miguel |last=Perez | work=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | via=Newspapers.com | date=February 3, 1980 |page=334 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24382799/this_time_old_glory_wont_be_seeing/ |title=This time, Old Glory won't be seeing stars | access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Architectural critic [[Ada Louise Huxtable]] derided the new flag as a \"simple-minded, vainglorious proposal\" and asked, \"Does anyone really want to spend $850,000 to upstage the Statue of Liberty?\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Flag flap turns critics red |work=The Star-Gazette |location=Elmira, NY |page=13 | via=Newspapers.com | date=March 18, 1980 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24383069/flag_flap_turns_critics_red/ | access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Huxtable | first=A.L. | title=On Architecture: Collected Reflections on a Century of Change | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8027-7760-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t2nDO99m5-cC&pg=PA423 | access-date=October 9, 2018 | page=423}}</ref>\n\nThe TBTA's successor, [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]], stopped collecting tolls for Brooklyn-bound drivers on the Verrazzano Bridge in 1986, and doubled the toll for Staten Island-bound drivers.<ref name=\"NYTimes-OneWayTolls-1986\"/> This was a result of a bill introduced by [[Guy V. Molinari]], the U.S. Representative for Staten Island, as part of an initiative to reduce traffic that accumulated at the toll booth on Staten Island.<ref name=\"NYTimes-VerrazanoTolls-1985\"/> The one-way toll was initially intended to be part of a six-month pilot program,<ref name=\"NYTimes-TollExpEndsToday-1986\"/> but resulted in permanent changes to traffic flows on the Verrazzano Bridge. The crossing saw more Brooklyn-bound traffic and less Staten Island-bound traffic as a result.<ref name=\"Gold 1990\"/> This unidirectional collection remained in effect through the 21st century<!-- {{as of|March 2017|lc=y}}, the last time the MTA raised tolls on the bridge -->.<ref name=\"bt-tolls-2017\"/>\n\nBeginning in 2008, all 262 of the [[Mercury-vapor lamp|mercury vapor]] fixtures in the bridge's necklace lighting were replaced with energy-efficient [[light-emitting diode]]s. This retrofit was completed in 2009, years before LED street lights were installed in the rest of the city.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=[[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]] |date=October 29, 2009 |title=Verrazano\u2013Narrows Bridge LED Necklace Lights Add \"Green\" Sparkle to New York Harbor Entrance |url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/verrazano-narrows-bridge-led-necklace-lights-add-green-sparkle-new |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe [[#Naming|Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge's name]] was originally spelled with one \"z\". The \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name dates to 1960 when Governor Rockefeller had signed the bill authorizing the bridge's name as such.<ref name=NYTimes-VerrazanoItIs-1960/> A bill to formally change the bridge's name to the variant with two \"z\"s was introduced by college student Robert Nash in 2016,<ref name=CNY-NashPetition-2016/> but stalled the next year,<ref name=\"NYPost-SpellingFix-2018\"/> as did another bill in early 2018.<ref name=AP-AnotherZ-2018/> The New York State Senate voted to change the name of the bridge in June 2018,<ref name=\"AP-AnotherZ-2018\"/> and the name change was officially signed into law that October.<ref name=\"Campanile 2018\"/><ref name=\"AMNewYork-LongLostZ-2018\"/>\n\n===Renovation===\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge Repairs (17509134860).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=Workers rebuilding the bridge's upper deck|Rebuilding the upper deck]]\nIn 2014, the city began a $1.5{{nbsp}}billion reconstruction project on the bridge. At the time, it was expected to take up to 25 years.<ref name=\"Barone 2015\">{{cite news | last=Barone | first=Vincent | title=Decades of construction being planned for Verrazano-Narrows Bridge | website=Staten Island Advance | date=October 15, 2015 | url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2015/10/decades_of_necessary_construct.html | accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> The first phase, which cost $235{{nbsp}}million and lasted until 2017, included replacing the existing upper deck sections with new [[orthotropic deck]] sections, removing the divider on the upper deck, and adding a seventh lane on the upper deck, which was to be used as a [[high-occupancy vehicle lane|high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lane]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Katinas | first=Paula | title=Verrazano Bridge repair work brings lane closure until 2017 | website=Brooklyn Eagle | date=March 26, 2016 | url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2015/3/10/verrazano-bridge-repair-work-brings-lane-closure-until-2017 | accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> The ramps within the [[Belt Parkway]] interchange were also rearranged to allow for a ramp to be constructed for the new HOV lane on the upper deck. The parts for this deck were ordered from [[China]] because the parts that the MTA required were no longer manufactured in the United States.<ref>{{cite news | title=MTA outsources $235M Verrazano revamp |last=Adams Otis |first=Ginger | website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | date=July 1, 2013 | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-outsources-235m-verrazano-revamp-article-1.1387639 | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the upper deck was replaced, parts of the lower deck are to be replaced, but this necessitates the closure of the lower deck during construction. Hence, the MTA opted to replace the upper deck first to add more capacity. The upper level's new HOV lane opened in July 2017.<ref>{{cite news | last=Rizzi | first=Nicholas | title=Cuomo Plan to Speed Up Verrazano Traffic Makes Traffic Worse, Oddo Says | website=DNAinfo New York | date=June 22, 2017 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170622/fort-wadsworth/verrazano-narrows-bridge-traffic-hov-lane | access-date=March 16, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317102232/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170622/fort-wadsworth/verrazano-narrows-bridge-traffic-hov-lane | archive-date=March 17, 2018 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Simultaneously, the MTA dismantled the Staten Island-bound toll booths to speed up westbound traffic.<ref name=NY1-Cashless-2017/> This work was done in advance of the reconstruction of tracks around [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]], which severely limited rail service into that station and created more vehicular traffic at crossings to Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news | last=Goldman | first=Henry | title=New York Speeds Up Road Projects Ahead of Penn Station Work | publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=June 12, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-12/new-york-accelerates-road-projects-ahead-of-penn-station-repairs | access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Long-term plans also call for the installation of a bicycle and pedestrian path on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge.<ref name=\"Rivoli 2015\" />\n\n==Description==\nThe Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge is owned by [[Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority]] bondholders who paid for the bridge at its construction.<ref>{{cite book | title=Journal: Proceedings of the American Society of Civil Engineers | publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers | issue=v. 92\u201395 | year=1966 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N8xVAAAAMAAJ | access-date=March 18, 2018 | page=4}}</ref> It is operated by the TBTA's successor, [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels]], which is an affiliate agency of the MTA.<ref>{{cite web | title=MTA Bridges and Tunnels Introduction | publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] | date=December 31, 2016 | url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/btintro.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> The bridge carries [[Interstate&nbsp;278]], which continues onto the [[Staten Island Expressway]] to the west and the [[Gowanus Expressway]] to the northeast. The Verrazzano, in combination with the [[Goethals Bridge]] and the Staten Island Expressway, created a new way for commuters and travelers to reach Brooklyn, Long Island, and Manhattan by car from [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/15/new-york-bypass.html|title=New York Bypass; Narrows Bridge Adds More New Ways To Avoid City's Traffic Jams|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=November 15, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2011-10-23-queen-mary-2-mast-under-verrazano-narrows-bridge.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=The Queen Mary 2 radar mast passing under the Verrazzano Bridge|''[[Queen Mary&nbsp;2]]'' radar mast passing under the Verrazzano Bridge, showing that there is sufficient clearance for the ship beneath the span]]\n\nEach of the two suspension towers, located offshore, contains around 1&nbsp;million bolts and 3&nbsp;million rivets.<ref name=\"sim\"/> The towers contain a combined {{convert|1,265,000|ST|LT}} of metal, more than three times the {{convert|365,000|ST|LT}} of metal used in the [[Empire State Building]].<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|141}} Because of the height of the towers ({{convert|693|ft|m|0|abbr=on|disp=or}}) and their distance from each other ({{convert|4260|ft|m|0|abbr=on|disp=or}}), the [[Figure of the Earth|curvature of the Earth's surface]] had to be taken into account when designing the bridge. The towers are not [[Parallel (geometry)|parallel]] to each other, but are {{convert|1+5/8|in|mm|3|abbr=on}} farther apart at their tops than at their bases.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}}<ref name=\"Caro 1974\"/>{{rp|752}}<ref name=\"sim\"/><ref name=\"MTA\">{{cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/veraz.html |title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> When built, the bridge's suspension towers were the tallest structures in New York City outside of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"Caplan 2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.amny.com/secrets-of-new-york/secrets-of-the-verrazano-narrows-bridge-its-construction-to-annie-hall-1.11027995|title=Secrets of the Verrazano Bridge|last=Caplan|first=David|date=October 29, 2015|website=[[AM New York]]|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The diameters of each of the four main suspension cables is {{convert|36|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}. Each main cable is composed of 26,108 wires amounting to a total of {{convert|142,520|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name=\"sim\"/><ref name=\"Cables-Spinning-1963\"/> The upper and lower levels are supported by trusses underneath each roadway, which stiffen the bridge against vertical, torsional, and lateral pressure.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|141}} The anchorage on the Staten Island side contains a facility for heating cinders that are used to de-ice the bridge deck during winter.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|148}}\n\nAt the time of opening, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was the [[List of longest suspension bridge spans|longest suspension bridge in the world]]; its 4,260-foot center span, between the two suspension towers, was {{convert|60|ft|m}} longer than the [[Golden Gate Bridge]]'s center span.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{Rp|5}}<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}} Despite being only slightly longer than the Golden Gate Bridge, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge could carry a 75% greater load than the former could.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}} In 1981, the Verrazzano Bridge was surpassed by the [[Humber Bridge]] in England, which has a center span of {{Convert|4626|ft|m|abbr=on}}, as the world's longest suspension bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/26/nyregion/follow-up-on-the-news-bridge-to-nowhere.html|title=Follow-Up on the News; Bridge to Nowhere|last=Haitch|first=Richard|date=December 26, 1982|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBecause of thermal expansion of the steel cables, the height of the upper roadway is {{convert|12|ft|m|2}} lower in summer than in winter.<ref name=\"Six Bridges\"/>{{rp|138}}<ref name=\"sim\"/><ref name=\"Caplan 2015\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Guide to Civil Engineering Projects In and Around New York City |edition=2nd |publisher=Metropolitan Section, American Society of Civil Engineers |year=2009 |pages=36\u201337}}</ref> The Narrows is the only entry point for large cruise ships and container ships that dock in New York City. As a result, they must be built to accommodate the clearance under the bridge. At mean high water, that clearance is {{convert|228|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Adams1996\"/> The [[RMS Queen Mary 2|RMS ''Queen Mary&nbsp;2'']], one such vessel built to Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge specifications, was designed with a flatter funnel to pass under the bridge, and has {{convert|13|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} of clearance under the bridge during high tide.<ref name=\"sim\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/history-verrazano-narrows-bridge-50-years-after-its-construction-180953032/ | title=The History of the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, 50 Years After Its Construction | magazine=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] | date=November 2014 | accessdate=November 21, 2014 | last=Adler |first=Jerry}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Barron | first=James | title=This Ship Is So Big, The Verrazano Cringes | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 18, 2004 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/18/nyregion/this-ship-is-so-big-the-verrazano-cringes.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNumerous birds nest or roost on the bridge, most notably breeding [[peregrine falcon]]s.<ref>{{cite press release |title=10 Peregrine Falcons Are Banded and Doing Well in Their Nesting Boxes|url=http://www.mta.info/news-bridges-tunnels-bridge-and-tunnel-peregrine-falcons-falcons/2016/06/02/10-peregrine-falcons-are|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> The falcons nest at the top of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge's towers, as well as on the Throgs Neck and [[Marine Parkway\u2013Gil Hodges Memorial Bridge|Marine Parkway]] Bridges. As the falcons are endangered, the city places bands on each bird and examines the birds' nesting sites each year. The falcons were discovered on the top of the Verrazzano Bridge in 1983, though they had started breeding there several years prior.<ref>{{cite news | title=Verrazano bridge is home to adorable baby falcons | website=[[New York Post]] | date=May 1, 2016 | url=https://nypost.com/2016/06/01/verrazano-bridge-is-home-to-adorable-baby-falcons/ | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Grynbaum | first=Michael M. | title=City Room; 2 New Tenants Move In Atop The Verrazano Bridge | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=June 8, 2010 | url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9806E1DB1639F93BA35755C0A9669D8B63.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Naming ==\n\n=== Tentative names ===\n[[File:Verrazano Narrows Bridge Triboro monument SI jeh.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=Monument at the Staten Island side of the bridge|The {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge Memorial on [[Lily Pond Avenue]], near the bridge's Staten Island entrance]]\nDuring the planning stages, the bridge was originally named simply the \"Narrows Bridge\".<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/07/archives/hyphen-is-added-as-compromise-in-name-of-span-to-staten-island.html|title=Hyphen Is Added as Compromise In Name of Span to Staten Island|date=August 7, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The co-naming of the bridge for Verrazzano (with two \"z\"s)<!-- PLEASE DON'T CHANGE&nbsp;\u2014 SEE Giovanni da Verrazzano TALK PAGE FOR CONVENTIONAL NAMING --> was controversial. It was first proposed in 1951 by the [[Italian Historical Society of America]], when the bridge was in the planning stage. After Robert Moses turned down the initial proposal, the society undertook a public relations campaign to re-establish Verrazzano's largely forgotten reputation and to promote the idea of naming the bridge for him. The society's director, John N. LaCorte, successfully lobbied several governors of states along the U.S.'s East Coast to proclaim April 17, the anniversary of Verrazzano's arrival in the harbor, as Verrazzano Day. LaCorte then approached the TBTA again, but was turned down a second time. The manager of the authority, backed by Moses, said the name was too long and that he had never heard of Verrazzano.<ref name=\"italian\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italianhistorical.org/page50b.html|title=Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge|work=Italian Historical Society of America|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref> The explorer's name had previously been suggested for the [[George Washington Bridge]], located several miles north, in 1931.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/02/09/archives/would-name-new-span-verrazano-bridge-newark-man-says-navigator-was.html|title=Would Name New Span Verrazano Bridge; Newark Man Says Navigator Was First Man to Cross Bay of New York but Historians Doubt.|date=February 9, 1931|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Italian Historical Society later successfully lobbied to get a bill introduced in the [[New York State Assembly]] to name the bridge for the explorer. After the introduction of the bill, the Staten Island Chamber of Commerce joined the society in promoting the name. In April 1958, Governor W. Averell Harriman announced that he would propose naming the Narrows Bridge after Verrazzano in honor of the explorer's voyage to the New York Harbor in 1524.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/04/17/archives/verrazzano-gets-his-day-and-his-z-harriman-concedes-italian.html|title=Verrazzano Gets His Day And His 'Z'; Harriman Concedes Italian Spelling in Ceremonies Honoring-Explorer|date=April 17, 1958|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> His successor, Nelson Rockefeller, put his support behind the one-\"z\" \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name in April 1959, saying that it was the Americans' standard way of spelling the explorer's name.<ref name=\":7\" /> According to Gay Talese, the one-\"z\" name was bolstered by the fact that it appeared on the bridge's first construction contracts in 1959; this incorrect spelling persisted in all subsequent references to the bridge.<ref name=\"NYPost-SpellingFix-2018\" />\n\nAlthough the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name was not finalized yet, ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted that the Staten Island Ferry boat carrying dignitaries to the bridge's August 1959, groundbreaking ceremony was named the \"Verrazzano\". The ''Times'' further stated that former Governor Harriman and Mayor Wagner had respectively proposed a \"Verrazzano Bridge\" and proclaimed a \"Verrazzano Day\".<ref name=\":8\" /> The Staten Island Chamber of Commerce opposed the Verrazzano name altogether, saying that the proper name of the bridge should be \"Staten Island Bridge\" because there was also a \"[[Brooklyn Bridge]]\", a \"[[Manhattan Bridge]]\", a \"[[Queensboro Bridge|Queens Bridge]]\", and a \"[[Bronx\u2013Whitestone Bridge|Bronx Bridge]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/08/03/archives/name-protested-on-narrows-span-chamber-tells-governor-it-should-not.html|title=Name Protested on Narrows Span; Chamber Tells Governor It Should Not Be Verrazano but Staten Island Bridge|date=August 3, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The Italian Historical Society was reportedly perplexed about the opposition to the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/09/27/archives/name-of-verrazano-pushed-for-bridge.html|title=Name of Verrazano Pushed for Bridge|date=September 27, 1959|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In response to the Staten Island Chamber of Commerce's opposition, the TBTA offered to add a hyphen between \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" and \"Narrows\".<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Official name with one \"z\" ===\nRockefeller signed the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name into law in March 1960, which officially changed the name of the Narrows Bridge to \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge\".<ref name=\"NYTimes-VerrazanoItIs-1960\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/03/10/archives/verrazano-it-is-in-bridges-name-governor-signs-disputed-designation.html|title=Verrazano It Is, in Bridge's Name; Governor Signs Disputed Designation Into Law|date=March 10, 1960|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=February 25, 2010}}</ref> The naming issue did not encounter any more controversy until 1963, after the assassination of President [[John F. Kennedy]]. This prompted a series of suggestions to rename structures, monuments, and agencies across the United States after the late president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/11/28/archives/drives-under-way-for-kennedy-memorials-proposals-are-made-to-rename.html|title=Drives Under Way for Kennedy Memorials; Proposals Are Made to Rename Many Public Works Funds Also Set Up to Help the Widow of Policeman Urges Special Commission School to Honor Memory|last=Benjamin|first=Philip|date=November 28, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> A petition to rename the {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge for Kennedy received thousands of signatures.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201963%2520Dec-May%25201964%252000040_2.pdf|title=Petitions Keep Coming In|date=December 13, 1963|last=Otey|first=Charles F.|work=Brooklyn Home-Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=3|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> In response, LaCorte contacted the president's brother, [[United States Attorney General]] [[Robert Kennedy]], who told LaCorte that he would assure that the bridge would keep the \"{{not a typo|Verrazano}}\" name.<ref name=\"italian\" /> Ultimately, the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge kept its name, while [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|Idlewild Airport]] in Queens was renamed after Kennedy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/12/05/archives/mayor-for-naming-idlewild-kennedy-kennedy-airport-backed-by-mayor-a.html|title=Mayor for Naming Idlewild 'Kennedy'|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=December 5, 1963|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn part due to discrimination against Italian-Americans, the bridge's official name was widely ignored by local news outlets at the time of the dedication. Some radio announcers and newspapers omitted any reference to Verrazzano, referring to the bridge as the Narrows Bridge, or the Brooklyn\u2013Staten Island Bridge. The society continued its lobbying efforts to promote the name in the following years until the name became firmly established. Another ethnic slur for the bridge was its nickname as the \"Guinea Gangplank\", referring to the Italian-Americans who subsequently moved from Brooklyn to Staten Island.<ref name=\"Talese Book\" />{{rp|33}} The Italian Historical Society's published references to the bridge's name all contained two \"z\"s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2016/24/br-spell-verrazano-bridge-right-2016-06-10-bk.html|title=To the letter! Petition to add second Z to Verrazano bridge|last=Lynch|first=Dennis|date=June 10, 2016|work=Brooklyn Daily|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Bills to change bridge's name ===\n[[File:VerraZZano Bridge sign vc.jpg|thumb|Installation of new road signs saying Verrazzano with two \"z\"s in February 2020]]\nIn June 2016, [[St. Francis College]] student Robert Nash started a petition to correctly spell Giovanni da Verrazzano's name on the bridge with two \"z\"s.<ref name=\"CNY-NashPetition-2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20160608/TRANSPORTATION/160609864/robert-nash-a-21-year-old-brooklyn-college-student-has-started-an-online-petition-to-correct-the-spelling-of-the-verrazzano-narrows-bridge-by-adding-the-other-z-to-the-north-americas-longest-suspension-bridge|title=Robert Nash, a 21-year-old Brooklyn college student, has started an online petition to add the other Z to North America's longest suspension bridge|agency=Associated Press|date=June 2016|publisher=[[Crain Communications]]|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pix11.com/2016/06/30/new-yorkers-want-spelling-of-verrazano-narrows-bridge-fixed/|title=New Yorkers want spelling of Verrazano-Narrows Bridge fixed|first=Andrea |last=Cavallier |date=June 2016|publisher=[[WPIX]]|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/New-Petition-Aims-to-Fix-Misspelling-of-New-York-Citys-Verrazano-Bridge-382262961.html|title=New Petition Aims to Fix Misspelling of NYC's Verrazano Bridge|first=Verena |last=Dobnik |date=June 2016|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/06/mama_mia_brooklyn_man_seeks_to.html|title=Mamma mia! Brooklyn man seeks to add second \"Z\" to Verrazano Bridge|first=Diane |last=Lore |date=June 2016|work=[[Staten Island Advance]]|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref> The petition gained support from politicians including New York State Senators [[Martin Golden]] and [[Andrew Lanza]]. The petition was also supported by actors and celebrities of Italian heritage, including [[Robert DeNiro]] and [[Tony Gemignani]].<ref name=\"Shapiro, Rachel\">{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/12/lanza_to_mta_correctly_spell_v.html|title=Lanza to MTA: Correctly spell Verrazzano on future signs|last=Shapiro|first=Rachel|date=December 2016|work=Staten Island Advance|publisher=[[Staten Island Advance]]|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> In December 2016, Senators Golden and Lanza sent letters to the Metropolitan Transportation Authority CEO [[Thomas F. Prendergast (railroad executive)|Thomas F. Prendergast]], in which they recommended that the bridge's name be spelled correctly. An MTA spokesperson said the agency was reviewing the letter.<ref name=\"Shapiro, Rachel\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/39/51/all-mta-fixes-verrazano-bridge-spelling-2016-12-16-bk.html|title=Zed-letter day! Pols back Verrazano-Narrows name fix|first=Max |last=Jaeger |date=December 2016|work=[[The Brooklyn Paper]]|accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA bill to formally change the bridge's name stalled in 2017,<ref name=\"NYPost-SpellingFix-2018\">{{cite news | title=Verrazano Bridge spelling fix could cost taxpayers millions | website=New York Post | date=June 7, 2018 | url=https://nypost.com/2018/06/07/verrazano-bridge-spelling-fix-could-cost-taxpayers-millions/ | access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref> as did another bill in early 2018.<ref name=AP-AnotherZ-2018/> In mid-2018, Golden sponsored a [[New York State Senate]] bill to change the bridge's spelling to \"Verrazzano\" with two \"z\"s. On June 6 of that year, the Senate unanimously passed a bill to change the spelling of the {{not a typo|Verrazano}}-Narrows Bridge, sending the measure to the [[New York State Assembly]] and the office of New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] for approval. If the bill was passed, the MTA would modify nearly a hundred road signs at a cost of $350,000.<ref>{{cite news | title=How Do You Solve a Problem Like the Verrazano? With an Extra Z | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | first=Vivian | last=Wang | date=June 7, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/07/nyregion/bill-would-spell-verrazano-bridge-with-an-extra-z.html | access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AP-AnotherZ-2018\">{{cite news | agency=[[Associated Press]] | title=Bill Would Add Another 'Z' to NYC's Verrazano Bridge | website=[[WNBC]] | date=June 7, 2018 | url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Verrazano-Narrows-Bridge-Spelling-Bill-484815681.html | access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref> The Assembly passed the bill on June 21, sending the measure to Governor Cuomo with a minor modification. As a cost-saving measure, existing signs would retain the one-\"z\" spelling, and only new signs would contain the double-\"z\" spelling.<ref>{{cite news | last=Bascome | first=Erik | title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge spelling fix poised to become law | website=[[Staten Island Advance]] | date=June 21, 2018 | url=https://www.silive.com/news/2018/06/assembly_passes_bill_to_fix_sp.html | access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AMNewYork-LongLostZ-2018\"/> On October 1, 2018, Governor Cuomo signed the bill into law, effectively changing the legal spelling of the bridge to the \"Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\".<ref name=\"Campanile 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Campanile |first1=Carl |title=Cuomo Finally Fixes a 50-Year-Old Typo |url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/01/cuomo-finally-fixes-a-50-year-old-typo/ |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Rivoli | first=Dan | title=Verrazzano Bridge finally gets name corrected, decades later | website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | date=October 1, 2018 | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-metro-verrazano-bridge-name-change-20181001-story.html | access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AMNewYork-LongLostZ-2018\">{{cite news | title=Verrazzano Bridge finally gets its long lost 'z' | website=AM New York | date=September 1, 2018 | url=https://www.amny.com/transit/verrazzano-verrazano-bridge-cuomo-1.21345852 | access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Tolls==\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge @ Night from Brooklyn.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn at night|Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, as seen from Brooklyn at night]]\n{{As of|2019|03|31|df=us}}, drivers traveling westbound into Staten Island pay $19.00 per car or $8.00 per motorcycle for Tolls by Mail, while eastbound drivers do not pay tolls. E-ZPass users with transponders issued by the New York E-ZPass Customer Service Center pay $12.24 per car or $5.32 per motorcycle; a five-axle truck pays $102.82, or $60.38 with NY E-ZPass.<ref name=\"bt-tolls-2019\"/>\n\nThe Staten Island Resident Rebate Program provides a discounted rate of $5.50 to registered residents of Staten Island who use E-ZPass. Staten Island residents can request a special Carpool HOV E-ZPass, which can be used when three or more people are in a passenger vehicle. The Carpool HOV rate is $3.40.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/sicarpol.html|title=Staten Island Carpool HOV E-ZPass| publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> Non-residents do not get the rebated or discounted rates. All E-ZPass users with transponders not issued by the New York E-ZPass Customer Service Center are charged the Toll-by-mail rates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://new.mta.info/fares-and-tolls/bridges-and-tunnels/tolls-by-vehicle/cars |title=Car Toll Rates |at=Footnote 3 | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> A bill that passed in the New York State Senate in May 2019 would give the discounted rate to Brooklyn residents with E-ZPass who cross at least 10 times per month. The discount, not yet approved by the State Assembly, would only apply to non-commercial vehicles.<ref>[https://hamodia.com/2019/06/03/senate-passes-verrazzano-toll-discount-brooklynites/ Senate Passes Verrazzano Toll Discount for Brooklynites]. ''[[Hamodia]]''.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/06/verrazzano-discount-for-brooklynites-passes-state-senate-report-says.html|title=Verrazzano discount for Brooklynites passes state Senate, report says|date=2019-06-02|website=Staten Island Advance|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/42/23/bn-verrazzano-toll-bill-passes-senate-2019-06-07-bk.html|title=Easy rider: Bill to lower Verrazzano Bridge toll for some Brooklyn drivers sails through state Senate|website=Brooklyn Paper|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\nThe undiscounted tolls for passenger cars are higher than for most other tolled crossings in the U.S. The tolls from the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge grossed the MTA $417{{nbsp}}million in 2017, and more than 85% of bridge motorists used a discounted toll rate.<ref name=NYTimes-17Toll-2018/>\n\n===One-way toll===\nAn [[urban legend]] has it that tolls were to be abolished once the bridge's construction bonds were paid off, but this has been debunked by the ''[[Staten Island Advance]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/nyregion/as-verrazano-bridge-turns-50-a-myth-about-its-tolls-persists.html|title=As Verrazano Bridge Turns 50, a Myth About Its Tolls Persists|last1=Yee|first1=Vivian|date=November 21, 2014|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/02/urban_legend_about_verrazano_b.html|title=Urban legend about Verrazano Bridge debunked: You still gotta pay|last1=Calzolari|first1=Anne Marie|date=February 21, 2009|work=Staten Island Advance|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref> Originally, all drivers paid the same toll to cross the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge. Staten Island residents were the only residents of New York City who had to pay a toll in order to enter their home borough, since all four of Staten Island's vehicular crossings collected tolls. This put Staten Island motorists at a financial disadvantage compared with drivers who lived in other boroughs.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201975%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201975%252002571.pdf|title=Arculeo Proposes Toll Reduction At Bridge|date=October 10, 1975|publisher=Brooklyn Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=9|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=NYTimes-17Toll-2018/> A bill to reduce the tolls for Staten Islanders was introduced in the [[New York City Council]] in 1975.<ref name=\":18\" /> Governor [[Mario Cuomo]], the father of future Governor Andrew Cuomo, signed another law to give Staten Island residents discounted tolls in 1983, after years of petitioning and opposition from his two predecessors.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/23/nyregion/new-law-gives-si-drivers-a-25-discount-on-verrazano.html|title=New Law Gives S.I. Drivers a 25\u00a2 Discount on Verrazano|last=Barbanel|first=Josh|date=June 23, 1983|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom its opening until 1986, the toll was collected in both directions.  In 1985, U.S. Representative [[Guy V. Molinari]] co-sponsored a bill that would require the MTA to collect the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge's toll in the Staten Island-bound direction only. This came after Staten Island residents had complained about pollution from idling vehicles.<ref name=\"NYTimes-VerrazanoTolls-1985\">{{cite news | last=Oreskes | first=Michael |work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 | title=Amid The Big Issues Of The Day, Tolls On Verrazano | date=September 13, 1985 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/09/13/nyregion/amid-the-big-issues-of-the-day-tolls-on-verrazano.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> In December of that year, the [[United States House of Representatives]] passed a bill that prohibited the MTA from collecting tolls from Brooklyn-bound vehicles,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/24/nyregion/for-verrazano-one-way-tolls.html|title=For Verrazano, One-Way Tolls|last=Oreskes|first=Michael|date=December 24, 1985|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> under penalty of a loss of highway funding.<ref name=\"Gold 1990\" /> Accordingly, in March 1986, the MTA started a pilot program where it charged a $3.50 toll for Staten Island-bound vehicles rather than charging a $1.75 toll in both directions.<ref name=\"NYTimes-OneWayTolls-1986\">{{cite news | last=Anderson | first=Susan Heller | last2=Dunlap | first2=David W. | title=New York Day by Day; One-Way Tolls In Effect on Verrazano | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 21, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/21/nyregion/new-york-day-by-day-one-way-tolls-in-effect-on-verrazano.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mta-2010-01-16\">{{cite press release |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |date=January 26, 2010 |title=Verrazano\u2013Narrows Toll Plaza Improvement |url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/verrazano-narrows-toll-plaza-improvement|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> The pilot program was extended to six months, but it was controversial due to the dubious benefits involved.<ref name=\"NYTimes-TollExpEndsToday-1986\">{{cite news | last=Boorstin | first=Robert O. | title=One-Way Bridge Toll Experiment Ends Today, but Not Controversy | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=September 20, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/20/nyregion/one-way-bridge-toll-experiment-ends-today-but-not-controversy.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> The new toll plan not only caused a drop in revenues,<ref>{{cite news | last=Brooke | first=James | title=One-Way Verrazano Toll Is Cutting Revenues | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 27, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/27/nyregion/one-way-verrazano-toll-is-cutting-revenues.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> but also caused congestion in Manhattan and Brooklyn<ref>{{cite news | last=Brooke | first=James | title=New Tolls Jam Streets Downtown | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 29, 1986 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/29/nyregion/new-tolls-jam-streets-downtown.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> and air pollution in Manhattan. [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal Street]] in Lower Manhattan, which connected to the [[Holland Tunnel]] to New Jersey, saw the most severe congestion, as drivers would go through New Jersey and use the [[Bayonne Bridge]] to pay a cheaper toll to enter Staten Island.<ref>{{cite news | last=Boorstin | first=Robert O. | title=Pollution Rise Tied To One-Way Toll | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 2, 1987 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/02/nyregion/pollution-rise-tied-to-one-way-toll.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> Fatal accidents involving pedestrians in Lower Manhattan also increased greatly as a result.<ref name=\"Lambert 1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/12/nyregion/neighborhood-report-lower-manhattan-around-holland-tunnel-a-deadly-jam.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Lower Manhattan; Around Holland Tunnel, a Deadly Jam|last=Lambert|first=Bruce|date=September 12, 1993|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the MTA supported removing the one-way toll because it reduced MTA revenues by $7{{nbsp}}million a year.<ref>{{cite news| last=French | first=Howard W. | title=M.T.A. Urges End to One-Way Toll on Verrazano | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=November 21, 1987 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/21/nyregion/mta-urges-end-to-one-way-toll-on-verrazano.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> At that point, Cuomo proposed reinstating an eastbound toll for trucks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/04/nyregion/cuomo-asks-return-of-2-way-toll-for-trucks-on-verrazano-bridge.html|title=Cuomo Asks Return of 2-Way Toll For Trucks on Verrazano Bridge|last=Barron|first=James|date=March 4, 1988|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1990, it was noted that about 455,000 more eastbound vehicles per year were using the bridge's eastbound lanes compared with before the toll reconfiguration, but that this was heavily outweighed by the 1.5{{nbsp}}million fewer westbound vehicles per year.<ref name=\"Gold 1990\">{{cite news | last=Gold | first=Allan R. | title=S.I.'s Relief Called Brooklyn's Headache | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=May 10, 1990 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/10/nyregion/si-s-relief-called-brooklyn-s-headache.html | access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> Residents of Manhattan and Brooklyn wanted the tolls changed so that either eastbound vehicles only, or both directions, would be tolled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/15/nyregion/bridge-toll-divides-city-of-new-york.html|title=Bridge Toll Divides City Of New York|last=Lueck|first=Thomas J.|date=June 15, 1993|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[United States House of Representatives]] voted in favor of a federal appropriations bill, which would repeal the bridge's one-way-toll mandate and allow half of the then-current toll to be applied to both directions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2019/06/27/house-passes-spending-bill-with-2-way-verrazzano-bridge-tolls/|title=House passes spending bill with 2-way Verrazzano Bridge tolls|date=2019-06-27|website=Brooklyn Eagle|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/3055|title=H.R.3055 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Commerce, Justice, Science, Agriculture, Rural Development, Food and Drug Administration, Interior, Environment, Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, Transportation, and Housing and Urban Development Appropriations Act, 2020|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> At the time, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was the only American bridge with a federal mandate controlling its toll collections. President [[Donald Trump]] signed the bill in December 2019, but the MTA had yet to determine when it would enact two-way tolls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/12/with-legislation-signed-split-tolling-no-longer-banned-on-verrazzano-bridge.html|title=With legislation signed, split tolling no longer banned on Verrazzano Bridge|last=Bascome|first=Erik|date=December 23, 2019|website=silive|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> The implementation of two-way tolls would require approval from the MTA board and would necessitate installation of additional infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2020/01/mta-in-early-stages-of-split-tolling-on-verrazzano-what-you-need-to-know.html|title=MTA in 'early stages' of split tolling on Verrazzano: What you need to know|last=Bascome|first=Erik|date=January 30, 2020|website=silive|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Electronic tolling and tollbooth removals===\n[[File:B&T 9891 (6808498097).jpg|thumb|upright|Demolition of eastbound toll plazas, 2012]]\nE-ZPass was introduced at the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge in late 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/01/nyregion/commuters-work-to-head-off-fare-rise.html|title=Commuters Work to Head Off Fare Rise|last=Rather|first=John|date=September 1, 1995|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24382556/new_ezpass_tags_take_effect/|title=New E-ZPass tags take effect|last=Boylan|first=Kate|date=September 8, 1995|work=[[The Journal News]]|access-date=October 9, 2018|location=White Plains, NY|page=27|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Its introduction helped to reduce traffic congestion at the tollbooths; in March 1997, it was found that drivers with E-ZPass were able to pass through the westbound tollbooths within 30 seconds, compared to 15 minutes for drivers paying with tokens or cash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/25/nyregion/electronic-tolls-are-catching-on-and-commuters-are-catching-up.html|title=Electronic Tolls Are Catching On, And Commuters Are Catching Up|last=Gross|first=Jane|date=March 25, 1997|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> In February 1998, the MTA discontinued the sale of toll tokens on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, except to Staten Island residents purchasing them in bulk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/03/nyregion/the-sale-of-tokens-ends-at-6-tunnels-and-bridges.html|title=The Sale of Tokens Ends At 6 Tunnels and Bridges|last=Chen|first=David W.|date=February 3, 1998|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite not collecting tolls in the eastbound direction since 1986, the MTA did not do anything with the unused booths for a quarter-century.<ref name=\"NYTimes-PhantomTolls-2010\">{{cite news | last=Grynbaum | first=Michael M. | title=Days Numbered for Staten Island's Phantom Tollbooths | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 20, 2010 | url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9C02E4D91E3DF933A15757C0A9669D8B63.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, eight of the eleven Brooklyn-bound toll booths were removed as part of the first phase of a project to improve traffic flow at the toll plaza.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |date=May 28, 2010 |title=New Traffic Pattern at Brooklyn-bound Verrazano Toll Plaza Begins Wed., June 2 \u2013 Removal of Last Two Unused Toll Booths Will Complete This Phase of Construction Work |url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/new-traffic-pattern-brooklyn-bound-verrazano-toll-plaza-begins-wed |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-PhantomTolls-2010\" /> Two years later, the last of the eastbound tollbooths was removed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Sedon |url=http://www.silive.com/eastshore/index.ssf/2012/02/booths_unused_since_1986_final.html |title=Booths unused since 1986 finally removed from Staten Island's Verrazano Bridge toll plaza |work=[[Staten Island Advance]] |date=February 4, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/bridges-tunnels/verrazano-narrows-toll-plaza-improvement-project-moves-next-stage |title=Verrazano-Narrows Toll Plaza Improvement Project Moves To Next Stage Along Narrows Road South |publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels |date=February 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref> Tolls are still collected in the Staten Island-bound direction only, and congestion within Lower Manhattan persists due to the bridge's one-way westbound toll.<ref name=\"bt-tolls-2017\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-17Toll-2018\">{{cite news | last=Hu | first=Winnie | title='Outrageous' $17 Toll to Cross the Verrazano Vexes Drivers | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 9, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/19/nyregion/verrazano-bridge-toll.html | access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Open road tolling|Open-road cashless tolling]] began on July 8, 2017.<ref name=\"NY1-Cashless-2017\">{{cite news | title=Drivers Have a New Way of Paying Verrazano Bridge Tolls | publisher=[[Spectrum News]] | date=July 8, 2017 | url=http://www.ny1.com//nyc/queens/news/2017/07/8/verrazano-bridge-starts-using-cashless-tolls-staten-island-brooklyn.html | access-date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> The westbound tollbooths were also dismantled, and drivers were no longer able to pay cash at the bridge. Instead, cameras and [[E-ZPass|E&#8209;ZPass]] readers are mounted on new overhead gantries near where the booths were located.<ref name=\"Siff 2016\" /><ref name=\"WABC 2016\" /> A vehicle without E-ZPass has a picture taken of its license plate and a bill for the toll is mailed to its owner.<ref name=\"MTA cashless\">{{cite web | title=What Is Cashless Tolling? | website=MTA Bridges & Tunnels | url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/cashless/ | access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> For E-ZPass users, sensors detect their transponders wirelessly.<ref name=\"Siff 2016\">{{cite web | last=Siff | first=Andrew | title=Automatic Tolls to Replace Gates at 9 NYC Spans: Cuomo | website=NBC New York | date=October 5, 2016 | url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Automatic-Tolls-Coming-to-New-York-City-Bridges-Tunnels-NYC-396050241.html | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WABC 2016\">{{cite web | title=MTA rolls out cashless toll schedule for bridges, tunnels | website=ABC7 New York | date=December 21, 2016 | url=http://abc7ny.com/1666924/ | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA cashless\" />\n\n===Historical tolls===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+History of passenger cash tolls for the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n!scope=\"col\"| Years !!scope=\"col\"| Toll !!scope=\"col\"| Toll equivalent<br />in {{inflation-year|US}}{{Inflation-fn|US}} !!class=unsortable|{{Abbr|Ref.|References cited}} !! class=\"unsortable\"  scope=\"col\"|Direction collected !! class=\"unsortable\"| Method\n|-\n| 1964\u20131972\n|align=right| $0.50\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1972|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1964|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref name=\"NYTimes-NewBridge_Roads-1964\">{{cite news | title=New Bridge and Roads Will Save Time, Trouble and Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | last=Ingraham | first=Joseph C. |date=November 21, 1964 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/21/archives/new-bridge-and-roads-will-save-time-trouble-and-tolls-hour-will-be.html | access-date=November 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Prial 1972\">{{cite news | last=Prial | first=Frank J. | title=Triborough Tolls Cause Snarls Inside and Outside Cars | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 7, 1972 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/01/07/archives/triborough-tolls-cause-snarls-inside-and-outside-cars.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n| rowspan=10|Cash only\n|-\n| 1972\u20131975\n|align=right| $0.75\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.75|1975|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|0.75|1972|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Prial 1972\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 1975\">{{cite news | title=New Fares and Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=September 2, 1975 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/09/02/archives/new-fares-and-tolls.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| 1975\u20131982\n|align=right| $1.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.00|1982|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.00|1975|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"The New York Times 1975\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 1982\">{{cite news | title=Tolls Rise Tomorrow For Several Crossings | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=April 18, 1982 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/18/nyregion/tolls-rise-tomorrow-for-several-crossings.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| 1982\u20131984\n|align=right| $1.25\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.25|1984|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.25|1982|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"The New York Times 1982\"/><ref name=\"Daley 1983\">{{cite news | last=Daley | first=Suzanne | title=M.T.A. Raises Fares And Tolls By 20% Across The Board | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=December 17, 1983 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/17/nyregion/mta-raises-fares-and-tolls-by-20-across-the-board.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| 1984\u2013January 1986\n|align=right| $1.50\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.50|1986|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.50|1984|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Daley 1983\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 1986\">{{cite news | title=Motorists - New Tolls on TBTA Bridges and Tunnels 11:59 PM Weds Jan 1, 1986 |page=245 | work=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York | via=Newspapers.com | date=December 31, 1985 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24946245/motorists_new_tolls_on_tbta_bridges/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| January\u2013March 1986\n|align=right| $1.75\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|1.75|1986|r=2}}|2}}}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 1986\"/>\n| Both directions\n|-\n| March 1986 \u2013 1987\n|align=right| $3.50\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|3.50|1987|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|3.50|1986|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"NYTimes-OneWayTolls-1986\"/><ref name=\"Bronstein 1987\">{{cite news | last=Bronstein | first=Scott | title=Drivers Irked By Toll Rise At 5 Bridges And Tunnels | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=February 8, 1987 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/02/08/nyregion/drivers-irked-by-toll-rise-at-5-bridges-and-tunnels.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1987\u20131989\n|align=right| $4.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|4|1989|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|4|1987|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Bronstein 1987\"/><ref name=\"Pitt 1989\">{{cite news | last=Pitt | first=David E. | title=Toll Increase at Bridges Is Described as Smooth | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=July 18, 1989 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/18/nyregion/toll-increase-at-bridges-is-described-as-smooth.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1989\u20131993\n|align=right| $5.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|5|1993|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|5|1989|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Pitt 1989\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 1993\">{{cite news | title=Commuter Alert |page=9 |work=The Journal News |location=White Plains, NY | via=Newspapers.com | date=January 30, 1993 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24946889/commuter_alert/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1993\u20131996\n|align=right| $6.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|6|1996|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|6|1993|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 1993\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 1996\">{{cite news | title=Bridge and Tunnel Traffic Smooth as Tolls Rise | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 26, 1996 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/03/26/nyregion/bridge-and-tunnel-traffic-smooth-as-tolls-rise.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 1996\u20132003\n|align=right| $7.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|7|2003|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|7|1996|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"The New York Times 1996\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 2003\">{{cite news | title=Tolls rise on Manhattan bridges and tunnels |page=6A |work=Poughkeepsie Journal | via=Newspapers.com | date=May 19, 2003 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24949406/tolls_rise_on_manhattan_bridges_and/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|rowspan=\"6\"|Cash/E-ZPass\n|-\n| 2003\u20132005\n|align=right| $8.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|8|2005|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|8|2003|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 2003\"/><ref name=\"Lee 2005\">{{cite news | last=Lee | first=Jennifer 8. | title=Bridge-and-Tunnel Blues: Paying More to Cross Over | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=March 14, 2005 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/14/nyregion/bridgeandtunnel-blues-paying-more-to-cross-over.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2005\u20132008\n|align=right| $9.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|9|2008|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|9|2005|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"Lee 2005\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com 2008\">{{cite news | title=Toll hikes start on bridges, tunnels |page=12 |work=The Journal News |location=White Plains, NY | via=Newspapers.com | date=March 16, 2008 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24949691/toll_hikes_start_on_bridges_tunnels/ | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2008\u20132010\n|align=right| $10.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|10|2010|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|10|2008|r=2}}|2}}\n|<ref name=\"newspapers.com 2008\"/><ref name=\"Grynbaum 2010\">{{cite news | last=Grynbaum | first=Michael M. | title=M.T.A. Raises Bridge and Tunnel Tolls | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=October 28, 2010 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/28/nyregion/28tolls.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2010\u20132015\n|align=right| $13.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|13|2015|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|13|2010|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref name=\"Grynbaum 2010\"/><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2010\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|title=2010 Toll Information|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=May 14, 2010|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514044013/http://www.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2015\u20132017\n|align=right| $16.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|16|2017|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|16|2015|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref>{{cite news | title=M.T.A. Is Raising Fares and Tolls; One Subway or Bus Ride Will Cost $2.75 | first=Emma G. | last=Fitzsimmons | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 22, 2015 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/23/nyregion/mta-raises-fares-subways-and-buses.html | access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|title=2015 Toll Information|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=April 22, 2015|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422061534/http://web.mta.info:80/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n|align=right| $17.00\n|align=center| ${{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|17|2019|r=2}}|2}}}}\u2013{{round|{{Inflation|US|17|2017|r=2}}|2}}\n| <ref>{{cite news | title=M.T.A. Votes to Raise Fares and Tolls: What You Need to Know | first=Emma G. | last=Fitzsimmons | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=January 25, 2017 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/25/nyregion/mta-subway-bus-toll-metrocard-fare-increase.html | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2017\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|title=2017 Toll Information|publisher=MTA Bridges and Tunnels|accessdate=March 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426225055/http://web.mta.info/bandt/traffic/btmain.html|archivedate=April 26, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Open road tolling|Electronic only]]\n|-\n| Since April 2019\n|align=right| $19.00\n|align=center| $19.00<!-- {{formatnum:{{round|{{Inflation|US|19|2019|r=2}}|2}}}} -->\n| <ref>{{cite news | title=Subway Fares Are Rising Again. But That Won't Solve the M.T.A.'s Crisis. | first=Emma G. | last=Fitzsimmons | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=February 27, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/nyregion/mta-fares-hike.html | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bt-tolls-2019\">{{cite web | title=New Fares and Tolls Take Effect | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA) | date=February 27, 2019 | url=https://new.mta.info/sites/default/files/2019-03/B%26T_toll_tables_03-01-19.pdf | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Westbound\n|}\n\n==Bridge usage==\n[[File:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge-NYC.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=United States Coast Guard on patrol in Upper New York Bay. The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge across the Narrows is visible in the background.|[[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] on patrol in Upper New York Bay. In the background, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge spans the Narrows between Brooklyn (left) and Staten Island (right).]]\nIn 2015, an average of 202,523 vehicles used the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge daily in both directions. {{As of|2015}}, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge carries more traffic than the [[Outerbridge Crossing]], the [[Bayonne Bridge]], and the [[Goethals Bridge]]. These three bridges, which connect Staten Island with New Jersey, were used by a combined  168,984 vehicles in both directions.<ref name=\"nycdot16\"/>\n\nIn 2011, advocacy group [[Transportation for America]] rated the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge as New York's most dangerous, because of the combination of deterioration and the number of people who cross it per day.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20110330/REAL_ESTATE/110339991 |publisher=Crain's New York Business |title=Verrazano called NY's most dangerous bridge |date=March 30, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> The MTA responded that the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge, which was both the newest large bridge and the longest bridge in the state, was structurally sound, and that the bridge had passed its most recent inspection. The MTA attributed Transportation for America's results to a \"misinterpretation of inspection records\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Cole |first=Marine |title=MTA refutes claim on Verrazano Bridge |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20110331/REAL_ESTATE/110339971/mta-refutes-claim-on-verrazano-bridge |accessdate=September 14, 2014 |publisher=[[Crain Communications]] |date=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSigns at both ends of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge forbid photography and video taping while on the bridge. These signs were installed after the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]], when the MTA started confiscating film from individuals who were caught filming MTA crossings. However, the ban had been in place long before the attacks in order to prevent people from taking close-up pictures of the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/15/weekinreview/ideas-trends-words-of-warning-don-t-shoot.html|title=Ideas & Trends; Words of Warning: Don't Shoot|last=Blair|first=Jayson|date=September 15, 2002|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Public transportation ===\nThree local bus routes operated by [[MTA Regional Bus Operations]] use the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge: the [[S53 (New York City bus)|S53]] local route, the [[S79 SBS (New York City bus)|S79 Select Bus Service]] route, and the [[S93 (New York City bus)|S93]] limited-stop route. The bridge also carries 20 [[express bus]] routes that connect Staten Island with Manhattan and are also operated by [[New York City Transit Authority|New York City Transit]]. They are the [[List of express bus routes in New York City#Manhattan to Staten Island|SIM1, SIM1C, SIM2, SIM3, SIM3C, SIM4, SIM4C, SIM4X, SIM5, SIM6, SIM7, SIM9, SIM10, SIM15, SIM31, SIM32, SIM33, SIM33C, SIM34, and SIM35]].<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|S}}</ref>\n\nSubway tracks were proposed for the bridge early in the planning process,<ref name=\":12\" /> but Moses rejected them, ostensibly over cost concerns.<ref name=\":13\" /> Other bridges proposed and built by Moses, including the [[Triborough Bridge]], [[Henry Hudson Bridge]], [[Bronx-Whitestone Bridge]], and [[Throgs Neck Bridge]], also lack provisions for subway tracks. According to biographer [[Robert Caro]], Moses purposely excluded any provisions for mass transit on his bridges in order to promote private transportation.<ref>{{cite web | last=Nonko | first=Emily | title=New York City's subway crisis started with Robert Moses | publisher=Curbed NY | date=July 1, 2017 | url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/7/27/15985648/nyc-subway-robert-moses-power-broker | access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Pedestrian and bicycle prohibition ===\nThe Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was not built with a pedestrian walkway. At the time, it was seen as too expensive, and planners believed the lack of a walkway would help prevent possible [[suicide]] jumps.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/21/no-pedestrian-walks-provided-for-bridge.html|title=No Pedestrian Walks Provided for Bridge|date=November 21, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Non-motorized transportation is limited to using the bridge during the [[New York City Marathon]] and [[Five Boro Bike Tour]].<ref name=\"Weir 1999\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transalt.org/files/resources/bridges/verrazano.html|title=Verrazano Bridge|publisher=Transportation Alternatives|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref> In 1976, the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge was designated as the starting point of the New York City Marathon. The 1976 marathon was the first year in the marathon's six-year history that the New York City Marathon course went outside Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/22/archives/city-marathon-oct-24-will-span-5-boroughs.html|title=City Marathon, Oct. 24, Will Span 5 Boroughs|date=June 22, 1976|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Since then, the marathon has started at the Verrazzano Bridge's Staten Island end every year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=trackandfield&id=2648331|title=After 10 NYC Marathons, Bridge Boss is Running Home|date=November 3, 2006|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 27, 2010|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge is not open to pedestrians or bikers outside of the marathon and the bike tour.<ref name=\"Weir 1999\">{{cite news | last=Weir | first=Richard | title=Neighborhood Report: New York On Line; Bike Friendly Bridges | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=May 30, 1999 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/30/nyregion/neighborhood-report-new-york-on-line-bike-friendly-bridges.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe lack of a walkway did not stop suicides completely, since by 1975, four people had died after jumping off the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/10/archives/crash-foils-a-cabby-in-bid-to-halt-suicide-cabby-bid-to-stop.html|title=Crash Foils a Cabby In Bid to Halt Suicide|last=Perlmutter|first=Emanuel|date=February 10, 1975|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The number of suicides has increased over time, despite efforts at deterrence. A sign that says \"Life Is Worth Living\" is located on the Staten Island approach. In 2008, the MTA also installed six suicide hotlines on the bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/2013/04/v-n_suicide_bids_a_scourge_tha.html|title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge suicides are a scourge that resists solution|last=Sedon|first=Michael|date=April 22, 2013|website=Staten Island Advance|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In December 2019, the MTA began installing a prototype [[suicide barrier]] after a series of fatal jumps from the bridge.<ref>{{cite web | last=Grunlund | first=Maura | title=MTA begins installing Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge safety fencing as suicide spate continues | website=silive | date=December 23, 2019 | url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/12/mta-begins-installing-verrazzano-narrows-bridge-safety-fencing-as-suicide-spate-continues.html | access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere have been calls for a walkway or bike lane on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge since its opening, when several people protested over the lack of bike lanes at the bridge's opening ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/23/100000-cars-cross-verrazano-bridge-in-first-24-hours.html|title=100,000 Cars Cross Verrazano Bridge In First 24 Hours|first=William |last=Borders|date=November 23, 1964|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1977, as a temporary solution, the city modified three buses to fit 12 bikes and 20 passengers each, then operated these buses on a new \"S7 {{not a typo|Verrazano}} Bridge\" route.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201977%2FBrooklyn%2520NY%2520Home%2520Reporter%2520%26%2520Sunset%2520News%25201977%252001802.pdf|title=Begin Bike-Bus Service Across Verazzano Bridge|last=Raphael|first=Kitty|date=June 24, 1977|publisher=Brooklyn Reporter|access-date=March 14, 2018|page=5|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]}}</ref> In 1993, the [[New York City Department of City Planning]] called for a footpath across the bridge as part of their Greenway Plan for New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/bike/gpreal.shtml#priorityroute |publisher=New York City Department of City Planning |title=A Greenway Plan for New York City |accessdate=November 27, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001326/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/html/bike/gpreal.shtml#priorityroute |archivedate=December 3, 2013 }}</ref> The next year, the city sought a $100,000 federal grant to fund a feasibility study into a Verrazzano Bridge pedestrian and bike path.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/01/16/nyregion/neighborhood-report-sourther-brooklyn-bike-lanes-on-the-verrazano.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Southern Brooklyn; Bike Lanes On The Verrazano?|last=Holloway|first=Lynette|date=January 16, 1994|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1997, the DCP released its study, which found that two footpaths running between the suspender ropes along the upper level, separated for pedestrian and cyclist use, would cost a minimum of $26.5{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/nyregion/pedestrian-lane-sought-for-verrazano-narrows-bridge.html|title=Pedestrian Lane Sought for Verrazano-Narrows Bridge|last=Chaban|first=Matt A. V.|date=October 16, 2014|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The MTA at the time expressed concern about the \"safety and liability inherent in any strategy that introduces pedestrian and bicycle access\" to the bridge.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web |url=http://www.transalt.org/files/resources/bridges/verrazano/dcp_rpt.pdf |publisher=New York City Department of City Planning |title=Verrazano \u2013 Pedestrian/Bicycle Access: Planning Design Feasibility |accessdate=November 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLocal residents on both side of the bridge started advocating for the construction of a walkway or bikeway on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge in 2002. Dave Lutz, the director of the Neighborhood Open Space Coalition nonprofit, stated that after the September 11 attacks, Staten Islanders walked home along the bridge's roadway.<ref>{{cite news | last=O'Grady | first=Jim | title=Neighborhood Report: Verrazano-Narrows Bridge; A Crisis Gives Birth To An Inspiration For A Bridge | work=The New York Times | issn=0362-4331 | date=February 24, 2002 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/24/nyregion/neighborhood-report-verrazano-narrows-bridge-crisis-gives-birth-inspiration-for.html | access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] promised to look into the possibility in October 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Long-Denied Verrazano Bridge Walkway Plan Picks Up Steam |first=Sarah |last=Tobol |url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/categories/category.php?category_id=27&id=13787 |newspaper=Brooklyn Eagle |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Harbor Ring Committee was formed in 2011 to advocate for the completion of the Harbor Ring route, which would create a {{Convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} around New York Harbor, including a footpath across the Verrazzano.<ref name=\":17\" /> In spring 2013 the committee began an online petition that generated more than 2,500 signatures, as well as an organizational sign-on letter with the support of 16 regional and local advocacy and planning organizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harborring.org/about/the-harbor-ring-committee/|title=The Harbor Ring Committee|publisher=The Harbor Ring Committee|accessdate=November 27, 2013}}</ref>  That year, the MTA announced that it would include conduct a three-year feasibility study for installing a pathway on the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge.<ref name=\":17\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2014/10/17/movement-underway-to-put-pedestrian-walkway-on-verrazano-bridge/|title=Movement Underway To Put Pedestrian Walkway On Verrazano Bridge|date=October 17, 2014|publisher=[[WCBS-TV]]|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The MTA considered plans for a bike lane in 2015, during the reconstruction of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge.<ref name=\"Rivoli 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/bike-lanes-eyed-fixup-verrazano-bridge-article-1.2387891|title=Bike lanes eyed in fixup of Verrazano Bridge|last=Rivoli|first=Dan|date=October 6, 2015|website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The MTA estimated that a dedicated multiple-use pathway would cost $400 million due to the need for a minimum width to accommodate a fire engine and construction of entrance and exit ramps. The plan was ultimately rejected in March 2019 over safety concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-advocates-verrazzano-narrows-bridge-bike-pedestrian-path-20190520-m5u6z6d3lzb2zdjmap2xanw3xy-story.html|title=Put a bike and pedestrian path on Verrazzano Bridge, advocates tell MTA|last=Guse|first=Clayton|date=May 20, 2019|website=[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] |location=New York|access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{wide image|Fort Wadsworth.JPG|1800px|alt=Panorama of the Upper New York Bay viewed from Staten Island. The Verrazano-Narrows Bridge is visible in the center of the image and Fort Wadsworth is visible in the foreground.|Panorama of the bay with [[Fort Wadsworth]] (foreground) on the Narrows, under the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |title=Biggest Bridge to Span Busiest Harbor |url={{Google books|biYDAAAAMBAJ|Biggest Bridge to Span Busiest Harbor|page=90|plainurl=yes}} |last=Soule |first=Gardner |journal=Popular Science |date=June 1955 |pages=90\u201393, 264, 268}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge}}\n* {{official website|http://web.mta.info/bandt/html/veraz.html}}\n* [http://www.bridge-info.org/bridge/index.php?ID=87 Verrazano-Narrows Bridge on bridge-info.org]\n* {{Structurae |id=20000085 |title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge}}\n* {{Gnis |968511}}\n* {{HAER |survey=NY-303 |id=ny1803 |title=Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, Spanning Narrows between Fort Hamilton (Brooklyn) & Staten Island, Brooklyn, Kings County, NY |photos=35 |cap=3}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{NYC Bridge}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure = Crossings\n|place = [[New York Harbor]]\n|bridge = Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n|bridge signs = [[File:I-278.svg|25px]]\n|upstream = [[Bayonne Bridge]]<br />([[Kill Van Kull]])<br />[[File:NY-440.svg|25px]] [[File:Ellipse sign 440.svg|25px]]\n----[[Downtown Hudson Tubes]]<br />([[Hudson River]])<br />[[PATH (rail system)|PATH]]\n----[[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]]<br />([[East River]])<br />[[File:I-478.svg|25px]]\n|upstream signs =\n|downstream = [[Lower New York Bay]]\n|downstream signs =\n}}\n{{LongestBridge\n| type = suspension\n| start = 1964\n| end = 1981\n| previous = Golden Gate Bridge\n| current = Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge\n| next = Humber Bridge\n}}\n{{Hudson River}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|New York City|Transport|Engineering}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verrazano-Narrows Bridge}}\n[[Category:1964 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Bridges by Othmar Ammann]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Staten Island]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:Double-decker bridges]]\n[[Category:Historic American Engineering Record in New York City]]\n[[Category:Interstate 78]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New York City]]\n[[Category:Robert Moses projects]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Suspension bridges in New York City]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in New York City]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority]]\n[[Category:Roads with a reversible lane]]\n", "name_user": "Hack1119", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRenovation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verrazzano-Narrows_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Axell Hodges", "text_new": "'''Ben dover''' this kid is a Squid on a Dirtbike, despite the fact of being 69\u20196\u201d tall, as well as being a full blown brace face. He is capable of riding a nose wheelie around the globe. Yes he is that epic. (born August 20, 1996, in [[Encinitas, California]]) is a [[motocross]] and [[X Games]] competitor.<ref name=\"Biography.com\">{{cite web |last1=Editors |title=Axell Hodges Biography |url=https://www.biography.com/athlete/axell-hodges |website=The Biography.com website |publisher=[[A&E Networks|A&E Television Networks]] |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Competition history==\nIn 2012 he won [[Loretta Lynn's Amateur Championship]], known as the world's largest amateur motocross race.<ref name=\"Biography.com\" />\n\nHe received gold in Moto X Quarterpipe High Air and bronze in Moto X Best Whip at [[X Games Minneapolis 2018]].<ref name=\"XGames page\">{{cite web |last1=XGames |title=Axell Hodges |url=http://www.xgames.com/athletes/3993972/axell-hodges |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> He has received a total of six X Games medals.<ref name=\"XGames page\" />\n\n==Media and sponsorships==\nHodges has a large social media following,<ref name=\"Biography.com\" /> with around 800,000 followers on Instagram. He is sponsored by [[Monster Energy]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Monster Energy |title=FREESTYLE MOTOCROSS ATHLETE Axell Hodges |url=https://www.monsterenergy.com/sports/freestyle-motocross/axell-hodges |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has also appeared as a guest on the [[MTV]] show ''[[Ridiculousness (TV series)|Ridiculousness]]''.<ref name=\"Biography.com\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{X Games profile|3993972}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodges, Axell}}\n[[Category:X Games athletes]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Axell Hodges''' this kid is a Squid on a Dirtbike, despite the fact of being 69\u20196\u201d tall, as well as being a full blown brace face. He is capable of riding a nose wheelie around the globe. Yes he is that epic. (born August 20, 1996, in [[Encinitas, California]]) is a [[motocross]] and [[X Games]] competitor.<ref name=\"Biography.com\">{{cite web |last1=Editors |title=Axell Hodges Biography |url=https://www.biography.com/athlete/axell-hodges |website=The Biography.com website |publisher=[[A&E Networks|A&E Television Networks]] |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Competition history==\nIn 2012 he won [[Loretta Lynn's Amateur Championship]], known as the world's largest amateur motocross race.<ref name=\"Biography.com\" />\n\nHe received gold in Moto X Quarterpipe High Air and bronze in Moto X Best Whip at [[X Games Minneapolis 2018]].<ref name=\"XGames page\">{{cite web |last1=XGames |title=Axell Hodges |url=http://www.xgames.com/athletes/3993972/axell-hodges |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> He has received a total of six X Games medals.<ref name=\"XGames page\" />\n\n==Media and sponsorships==\nHodges has a large social media following,<ref name=\"Biography.com\" /> with around 800,000 followers on Instagram. He is sponsored by [[Monster Energy]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Monster Energy |title=FREESTYLE MOTOCROSS ATHLETE Axell Hodges |url=https://www.monsterenergy.com/sports/freestyle-motocross/axell-hodges |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has also appeared as a guest on the [[MTV]] show ''[[Ridiculousness (TV series)|Ridiculousness]]''.<ref name=\"Biography.com\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{X Games profile|3993972}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodges, Axell}}\n[[Category:X Games athletes]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "207.213.183.236", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axell_Hodges"}
