{"title_page": "Diagnostic greed", "text_new": "'''Diagnostic greed''' is a [[Medical terminology|medical term]] coined by physician [[Maurice Henry Pappworth|Maurice Pappworth]] to describe the rigidity of physicians in insisting on every classic [[symptom]] and [[physical sign]] before making a [[diagnosis]]. Papworth explained that \u201coverwhelming evidence is not essential for correct diagnosis, and the absence of some expected symptom or sign often does not invalidate an otherwise reasonable diagnosis.\u201d<ref name=\"Tang\">{{Cite journal|last=Tang|first=Hangwi|date=March 2007|title=Diagnostic greed: using pictures to highlight diagnostic errors|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2599999/|journal=[[Postgraduate Medical Journal]]|volume=83|issue=977|pages=209\u2013210|doi=10.1136/pgmj.2006.053280|issn=0032-5473|pmc=2599999|pmid=17344579|via=}}</ref><ref name=Pappworth1963>{{Cite book|last=Pappworth|first=Maurice Henry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FolrAAAAMAAJ|title=A primer of medicine: being an introduction to clinical neurology, alimentary, respiratory, and cardiovascular diseases|date=1963|publisher=[[Butterworth-Heinemann|Butterworth]]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=251|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Origin and definition==\nThe term \"diagnostic greed\" was coined by physician [[Maurice Henry Pappworth|Maurice Pappworth]] to describe the rigidity of physicians in insisting on every classic symptom and physical sign before making a diagnosis. Papworth explained that \u201coverwhelming evidence is not essential for correct diagnosis, and the absence of some expected symptom or sign often does not invalidate an otherwise reasonable diagnosis.\u201d<ref name=\"Tang\"/><ref name=\"Rajasoorya\">{{Cite journal|last=Rajasoorya|first=C|date=September 2016|title=Prime time to resuscitate clinical medicine and kill diagnostic greed?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5027395/|journal=Singapore Medical Journal|volume=57|issue=9|pages=473\u2013475|doi=10.11622/smedj.2016151|issn=0037-5675|pmc=5027395|pmid=27664173|via=}}</ref><ref name=Winston>{{Cite book|last=Winston|first=Lord Robert|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j71rNbUoG0IC&pg=PA421|title=Bad Ideas?: An arresting history of our inventions|date=2010|publisher=Bantom Books|isbn=978-0-5538-1955-7|location=London|chapter=10. Physician, Heal Thyself|pages=421|language=en}}</ref> He recorded that the correct question was \"wherefore is this disease different from all other disease?\"<ref name=\"Belton\">{{Cite book|last=Belton|first=Neil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pxz637WgTEUC&pg=PT169|title=The Good Listener: Helen Bamber: A Life Against Cruelty|date=2012|publisher=Faber & Faber|year=|isbn=978-0-571-29527-2|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> Coming to a correct diagnosis \"is not like a jury's verdict.\"<ref name=Beck1981>{{Cite book|last=Beck|first=Paul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nWprAAAAMAAJ|title=Case Exercises in Clinical Reasoning|last2=Byyny|first2=Richard Leo|last3=Adams|first3=Kirk S.|date=1981|publisher=Year Book Medical Publishers|year=|isbn=978-0-8151-0597-8|location=|pages=36|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Examples==\nWhere a person presents with a classic history associated with clearly recognisable symptoms and signs of a condition, a diagnosis can be confidently made with ease. However, clinical scenarios of the same disease frequently vary and insisting on an exact match before making the diagnosis may miss the diagnosis and therefore be considered a \"sin of greed\".<ref name=\"Tang\"/> One example is of [[renal cell carcinoma]], which classically presents with [[flank pain]], [[haematuria|blood in urine]] and a [[abdominal mass|mass felt in the abdomen]], a triad of features which present in only less than 10% of cases. In practice, all \"essential\" features are rarely present and a person may reveal merely a few classic features, which is where the request for testing plays a role in confirming or ruling out the suspected diagnosis.<ref name=\"Tang\"/>\n\nIn dermatology, every textbook feature of a lesion need not be present to make the diagnosis.<ref name=pcds>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pcds.org.uk/p/skin-disease-examination|title=Examination {{!}} Primary Care Dermatology Society {{!}} UK|last=|first=|date=|website=www.pcds.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> Likewise, in cardiology, the expectation to explain every change on an [[ECG]] to conclude a diagnosis may represent diagnostic greed.<ref name=Platosnous>{{Cite web|url=http://platosnous.com/main-blog/2015/10/24/sin-of-ecg-interpretation|title=Borkmann's Point and Diagnostic Greed|website=Plato's Nous|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Another example has been of [[lead poisoning]] where toxicology results have failed to support the diagnosis despite other features of heavy metal poisoning being present.<ref name=Ballardie>{{Cite journal|last=Ballardie|first=Francis|last2=Cowley|first2=Richard|last3=Cox|first3=Alan|last4=Curry|first4=Alan|last5=Denley|first5=Helen|last6=Denton|first6=John|last7=Dick|first7=Jeremy|last8=Guerquin-Kern|first8=Jean-Luc|last9=Redmond|first9=Anthony|date=2009-02-14|title=Did he really bring the war home with him? \u2013 Authors' reply|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(09)60197-5/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=373|issue=9663|pages=543|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(09)60197-5|issn=0140-6736}}</ref>\n\nArguments for the need, on occasion, to have diagnostic greed, have also been made.<ref name=King>{{Cite book|last=King|first=Mary D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NGNEJSEiGcC&pg=PA117|title=A Handbook of Neurological Investigations in Children|last2=Stephenson|first2=John B. P.|date=2009|publisher=Mac Keith Press|chapter=2.9. Microscopic examination: Cells and biopsies|isbn=978-1-898683-69-8|location=|pages=117|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical terminology]]\n\n\n{{Med-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Diagnostic greed''' is a [[Medical terminology|medical term]] coined by physician [[Maurice Henry Pappworth|Maurice Pappworth]] to describe the rigidity of physicians in insisting on every classic [[symptom]] and [[physical sign]] before making a [[diagnosis]]. Papworth explained that \u201coverwhelming evidence is not essential for correct diagnosis, and the absence of some expected symptom or sign often does not invalidate an otherwise reasonable diagnosis.\u201d<ref name=\"Tang\">{{Cite journal|last=Tang|first=Hangwi|date=March 2007|title=Diagnostic greed: using pictures to highlight diagnostic errors|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2599999/|journal=[[Postgraduate Medical Journal]]|volume=83|issue=977|pages=209\u2013210|doi=10.1136/pgmj.2006.053280|issn=0032-5473|pmc=2599999|pmid=17344579|via=}}</ref><ref name=Pappworth1963>{{Cite book|last=Pappworth|first=Maurice Henry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FolrAAAAMAAJ|title=A primer of medicine: being an introduction to clinical neurology, alimentary, respiratory, and cardiovascular diseases|date=1963|publisher=[[Butterworth-Heinemann|Butterworth]]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=251|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Origin and definition==\nThe term \"diagnostic greed\" was coined by physician [[Maurice Henry Pappworth|Maurice Pappworth]] to describe the rigidity of physicians in insisting on every classic symptom and physical sign before making a diagnosis. Papworth explained that \u201coverwhelming evidence is not essential for correct diagnosis, and the absence of some expected symptom or sign often does not invalidate an otherwise reasonable diagnosis.\u201d<ref name=\"Tang\"/><ref name=\"Rajasoorya\">{{Cite journal|last=Rajasoorya|first=C|date=September 2016|title=Prime time to resuscitate clinical medicine and kill diagnostic greed?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5027395/|journal=Singapore Medical Journal|volume=57|issu