Gate of Generation | accessdate=September 2, 2013 | work=Dragon Gate | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://iheartdg.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1377856513&template=Default&#disqus_thread | title = 8/30 Gate of Generation | date = August 30, 2013 | accessdate = September 2, 2013 | work = iHeartDG | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131002172404/http://iheartdg.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1377856513&template=Default&#disqus_thread | archive-date = October 2, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref> On September 12, the three were joined by [[Masato Yoshino]], [[Ricochet (wrestler)|Ricochet]] and Shachihoko Boy to form a new stable,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/battle/2013/09/001955.php | title = \u610f\u5730\u3092\u898b\u305b\u305f\u658e\u4e86\u3092\u4e0b\u3057\u305fYamato\u306b\u3001\u571f\u4e95\u304b\u3089\u88cf\u5207\u3089\u308c\u305f\u5409\u91ce\u304c\u6311\u6226\u8868\u660e\uff01\u30b8\u30df\u30fc\u30ba\u3092\u4e0b\u3057\u305f\u30df\u30ec\u30cb\u30a2\u30eb\u30ba\u306f\u30d9\u30c6\u30e9\u30f3\u8ecd\u3092\u6307\u540d\uff01 | date=September 13, 2013 | accessdate=September 13, 2013 | work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> which was on October 6 named Monster Express.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/sports/fight/all/2013/columndtl/201310070010-spnavi | script-title=ja:\u5409\u91ce\u3001\u9df9\u6728\u3001\u6238\u6fa4\u3089\u306e\u65b0\u30e6\u30cb\u30c3\u30c8\u672c\u683c\u59cb\u52d5 \u30c8\u30e9\u30a4\u30a2\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u30b2\u30fc\u30c8\u6226\u306f\uff2d\uff22\u306b\u82e6\u676f | date=October 7, 2013 | accessdate=October 7, 2013 | work=Sports Navi | publisher=[[Yahoo!]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> On January 12, 2014, Uhaa received his first shot at Dragon Gate USA's top title, the [[Open the Freedom Gate Championship]], but was defeated by the defending champion, Johnny Gargano.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_75641.shtml | title = Show results \u2013 1/12 Evolve 27 in Jacksonville, Fla.: Gargano defends DGUSA Title, Young Bucks take out Bravados, two big title matches set for next set of shows, more | last=Gee Schoon Tong | first=Chris | date=January 13, 2014 | accessdate=January 13, 2014 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On March 6, Uhaa also received his first shot at Dragon Gate's top title, the [[Open the Dream Gate Championship]], but was defeated by the defending champion, Monster Express stablemate Ricochet.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2014/0306.html | title = Glorious Gate 2014 | accessdate=March 7, 2014 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> On May 23, it was reported that Uhaa had signed a new contract with Dragon Gate USA.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/article/85838/dgusa-star-signs-new-deal-and-more-news.html?p=1 | title = DGUSA star signs new deal and more news | last=Johnson | first=Mike | date=May 23, 2014 | accessdate=May 24, 2014 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2015, Uhaa made returned to Dragon Gate as Akira Tozawa's surprise partner in a tag team match, where they defeated [[Cyber Kong]] and Don Fujii.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2015/0205.html | title = Truth Gate 2015 | accessdate=February 12, 2015 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> At the end of the event, Uhaa confronted BxB Hulk, challenging him to a match for the Open the Dream Gate Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/?p=5401 | title = \u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3\u30b2\u30fc\u30c82.5\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u5927\u4f1a\u3000\u30cf\u30eb\u30afvs.\u30b9\u30b9\u30e0\u306e\u30c9\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0\u30b2\u30fc\u30c8\u6226\u3001MBvs.\u30df\u30ec\u30cb\u30a2\u30eb\u30bavs.Hearts\u306e6\u4eba\u30bf\u30c3\u30b03Way | date=February 6, 2015 | accessdate=February 12, 2015 | work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> On March 1, Uhaa failed in his title challenge against Hulk, after which he announced he had wrestled his final match for Dragon Gate.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://iheartdg.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1425179589 | title = 03/01 Champion Gate in Osaka | date=March 1, 2015 | accessdate=March 1, 2015 | work=iHeartDG}}</ref> Uhaa worked his final Evolve events later that month during [[WWNLive]]'s [[WrestleMania]] week.<ref name=WWEInterview/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_83116.shtml | title = WWNLive news: Three big matches set for Mania Weekend \u2013 GenNext's opponents, former WWE stars clash, more | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=February 3, 2015 | accessdate=April 7, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\n====NXT (2014\u20132016)====\n[[File:Apollo Crews WrestleMania 32 Axxess.jpg|thumb|upright|Crews in April 2016]]\nIn October 2014, Uhaa took part in a [[WWE]] tryout camp, resulting in him being offered a [[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental]] contract.<ref name=MiamiHeraldInterview/><ref>{{cite magazine| last = Meltzer | first = Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = December 22, 2014 | title = Dec. 22, 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: UFC lawsuit analysis, full reports on 4 consecutive major WWE & UFC shows, and much more! | magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page=34}}</ref> Starting on December 31, 2014, multiple sources reported that Uhaa had come to terms on a contract with WWE.<ref name=WWEContractWON>{{cite magazine| last = Meltzer | first = Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = December 31, 2014 | title = Jan. 5, 2015 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2014 business year in review, Daniel Bryan return, Wrestle Kingdom preview, death of Al Greene, and much more | magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page=51}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_82546.shtml | title = NXT newswire: DGUSA star signs with WWE, Itami & Balor in tag action tonight on NXT | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=January 1, 2015 | accessdate=January 2, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Uhaa reported to the [[WWE Performance Center]], the home of their [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] developmental brand, on April 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/92886/former-dg-star-starts-with-wwe-great-reason-why-celebrity-wrestler-likely-wont-work-summerslam-battleground-nxt-and-more-news.html?p=1 | title = Former DG star starts with WWE, great reason why celebrity wrestler likely won't work SummerSlam, Battleground, NXT and more news | last=Johnson | first=Mike | date=April 6, 2015 | accessdate=April 7, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> WWE officially announced Uhaa as part of a new class of NXT recruits in a press release on April 13.<ref name=WWESigningPR>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits | title = WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits | date=April 13, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> Uhaa made his first televised appearance on the May 6 episode of ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'', signing an NXT contract in a segment with [[William Regal]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/93549/wwe-nxt-report-contract-signing-interview-with-champion-and-challenger-becky-lynch-video-profile-the-nation-is-coming-who-is-number-one.html?p=1 | title = WWE NXT report: contract signing, interview with champion and challenger, Becky Lynch video profile, The Nation is coming, who is number one? | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=May 6, 2015 | accessdate=May 7, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Uhaa started working NXT [[house show]]s the following month, retaining the Uhaa Nation ring name.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=94554 | title = 6/20 NXT results from Lakeland, FL | last=Alston | first=Gary | date=June 21, 2015 | accessdate=July 10, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/article/94695/626-nxt-results-from-cocoa-beach-fl.html?p=1 | title = 6/26 NXT results from Cocoa Beach, FL | last1=Smith | first1=Joseph | last2=Twiss | first2=Andrew | date=June 27, 2015 | accessdate=July 10, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_86313.shtml | title = Show results \u2013 7/18 WWE NXT in Venice, Fla.: Parks's in-person report on Finn Balor vs. Tyler Breeze, Eva Marie, Uhaa Nation, more | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=July 18, 2015 | accessdate=July 19, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, it was announced that Uhaa, now working under the new ring name Apollo Crews, would be making his televised NXT in-ring debut on August 22 at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn]].<ref name=ApolloCrews>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/95676/the-former-uhaa-nations-debut-on-nxt-is-announced-as-well-as-his-nxt-name.html?p=1 | title = The former Uhaa Nation's debut on NXT is announced...as well as his NXT name | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=August 5, 2015 | accessdate=August 5, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Crews made his debut at the August 13 tapings, which would air after ''NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn'', defeating [[Martin Stone (wrestler)|Martin Stone]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_86935.shtml | title =  WWE news: NXT TV spoilers \u2013 results from Full Sail University for 8/19 pre-Takeover show and post-Takeover shows | last=Parry | first=Josh | date=August 13, 2015 | accessdate=August 14, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> At ''NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn'', Crews defeated [[Tye Dillinger]] in his official debut match.<ref name=NXTTakeOverBrooklyn>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/96-wwe-news/44186-wwe-nxt-takeover-live-results-a-main-card-finn-balor-vs-kevin-owens-sasha-banks-vs-bayley-samoa-joe-jushin-qthunderq-liger | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150823140341/http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/96-wwe-news/44186-wwe-nxt-takeover-live-results-a-main-card-finn-balor-vs-kevin-owens-sasha-banks-vs-bayley-samoa-joe-jushin-qthunderq-liger | title = WWE NXT TakeOver live results & main card: Finn Balor vs. Kevin Owens, Sasha Banks vs. Bayley, Samoa Joe, Jushin \"Thunder\" Liger | last=Witner | first=Emerson | archivedate=August 23, 2015 | date=August 22, 2015 | accessdate=August 22, 2015 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> At [[NXT TakeOver: Respect]], Crews defeated [[Tyler Breeze]]. On the October 8 tapings of ''NXT'', Crews won a [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] to become the #1 contender to the [[NXT Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_87926.shtml | title = WWE news: NXT spoilers \u2013 full results from Thursday's TV taping | last=Parry | first=Josh | date=October 8, 2015 | accessdate=October 9, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews received his title shot against [[Finn B\u00e1lor]] on October 22,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-tapings-finn-balor-defends-his-belt-against-apollo-crews-200161 | title = NXT Tapings: Finn Balor defends his belt against Apollo Crews | last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink=Dave Meltzer | date=October 22, 2015 | accessdate=October 23, 2015 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> winning the match, but not the title, by disqualification, when he was attacked by [[Baron Corbin]], who held a grudge against Crews for eliminating him from the #1 contender's battle royal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/2015-11-04/wwe-nxt-results-2015-11-04-28124331 | title = WWE NXT results: Nov. 4, 2015 \u2013 Samoa Joe betrays Finn B\u00e1lor as NXT Championship Match comes to shocking conclusion | last=Melok | first=Bobby | date=November 4, 2015 | accessdate=November 5, 2015 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> The rivalry between Crews and Corbin led to a match at [[NXT TakeOver: London]], which Corbin won.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-takeover-london-live-results-finn-balor-vs-samoa-joe-bayley-vs-nia-jax-203856 | title = NXT TakeOver London live results: Finn Balor vs. Samoa Joe, Bayley vs. Nia Jax | last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink=Dave Meltzer | date=December 16, 2015 | accessdate=December 16, 2015 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Crews had a small feud with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] after he saved Johnny Gargano from Elias' assault on the March 23, 2016, ''NXT''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-nxt-results-asuka-vs-emma-finn-balor-battles-rich-swann-209846 | title = WWE NXT results: Asuka vs Emma; Finn Balor battles Rich Swann | last=Witner | first=Emerson | date=March 23, 2016 | accessdate=April 7, 2016 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The two would subsequently have a match on the April 6 ''NXT'', which was won by Crews.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-nxt-results-takeover-recap-apollo-crews-vs-drifter-210586 | title = WWE NXT results: TakeOver recap; Apollo Crews vs. The Drifter | last=Witner | first=Emerson | date=April 6, 2016 | accessdate=April 7, 2016 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\n====Main roster debut (2016\u20132017)====\nOn April 4, 2016, Crews made his main roster debut on ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', defeating [[Tyler Breeze]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/04/april4rawresults/ | title = 4/4 WWE Raw Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Report on post-WM32 | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=April 4, 2016 | accessdate=April 4, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews then entered a feud with the Social Outcasts ([[Heath Slater]], [[Curtis Axel]], [[Bo Dallas]] and [[Adam Rose]]), defeating each member of the stable, culminating in a match on the April 18 ''Raw''. Prior to the match, Crews agreed to join the Social Outcasts if any member of the stable could defeat him. As part of the agreement, the Social Outcasts also agreed to leave Crews alone if he won the match. Crews defeated Slater to end the feud.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2016-04-18/article/apollo-crews-def-heath-slater | title = Apollo Crews def. Heath Slater | last=Benigno | first=Anthony | date=April 18, 2016 | accessdate=April 20, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> Crews suffered his first loss on the main roster on the May 23 ''Raw'', losing to [[Chris Jericho]] in a [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Money in the Bank]] qualifying match. The loss was blamed on [[Sheamus]]' pre-match attack on Crews, starting a feud between the two.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2016-05-23 | title = Raw results: Five Superstars qualify for Money in the Bank Ladder Match  | date=May 23, 2016 | accessdate=May 24, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> Crews and Sheamus faced off at [[Money in the Bank (2016)|Money in the Bank]], where Crews was victorious.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/06/19/619-wwe-mitb-ppv-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/ | title =  6/19 WWE MITB PPV Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=June 19, 2016 | accessdate=June 20, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, Crews was drafted to the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]] brand in the [[2016 WWE draft]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/19/2016draftresults/ | title = 2016 WWE Draft Picks \u2013 Complete Raw & SD Draftboard | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=July 19, 2016 | accessdate=July 19, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On the July 26 ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'', Crews won a battle royal to earn a spot in a six-pack challenge to determine the #1 contender to [[Dean Ambrose]]'s [[WWE Championship|WWE World Championship]] at [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]]. Later that same episode, Crews was defeated by [[Dolph Ziggler]] in the six-pack challenge, which also included [[A.J. Styles|AJ Styles]], Baron Corbin, [[Bray Wyatt]] and [[John Cena]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/26/july26smackdownfinal/ | title = 7/26 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks\u2019s Complete Live Report | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=July 26, 2016 | accessdate=July 27, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following week, Crews defeated Corbin and [[Kalisto (wrestler)|Kalisto]] to become the #1 contender to the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/02/82-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-complete-live-report/ | title = 8/2 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks\u2019s Complete Live TV Report | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=August 2, 2016 | accessdate=August 3, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews received his title shot on August 21 at [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]], but was defeated by [[The Miz]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/21/summerslam2016results/ | title = 8/21 WWE Summerslam Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=August 21, 2016 | accessdate=August 21, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews defeated The Miz in a non-title match at the [[WWE Tribute to the Troops results#2016|2016 Tribute to the Troops]],<ref name=TttT2016>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/106584/wwe-tribute-to-the-troops-report.html?p=1 | title = WWE Tribute to the Troops report | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=December 15, 2016 | accessdate=December 15, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> which led to a title match on the December 20 ''SmackDown'', where The Miz retained his title.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/20/1220-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-ongoing-real-time-report/ | title = 12/20 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks\u2019s Complete, Real-Time Report | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=December 20, 2016 | accessdate=December 21, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On January 29, 2017, at [[Royal Rumble (2017)|Royal Rumble]], Crews took part in his first [[Royal Rumble match]], entering as number 22 and being eliminated by [[Luke Harper]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/01/29/kellers-wwe-royal-rumble-report-129-ongoing-results-updated-throughout-evening-including-owens-reigns-styles-cena-rumble-match/ | title = Keller's WWE Royal Rumble report 1/29: Ongoing results updated throughout evening including Owens-Reigns, Styles-Cena, Rumble match | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=January 29, 2017 | accessdate=January 30, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> In early 2017, Crews teamed up with Kalisto to feud with Dolph Ziggler after Ziggler attacked Kalisto.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2017/apollo-crews-kalisto-vs-dolph-ziggler | title = Apollo Crews & Kalisto vs. Dolph Ziggler (2-on-1 Handicap Match) | last=Pappolla | first=Ryan | date=February 7, 2017 | accessdate=February 12, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> At [[Elimination Chamber (2017)|Elimination Chamber]], Crews and Kalisto defeated Ziggler in a two-on-one handicap match. Following the match, Ziggler attacked the two, injuring Crews' ankle, which was trapped in a chair.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/02/12/kellers-wwe-elimination-chamber-report-212-ongoing/ | title = Keller's WWE Elimination Chamber report 2/12: Ongoing coverage including Chamber, Bliss vs. Naomi, Tag Team Turmoil, more | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=February 12, 2017 | accessdate=February 12, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> This led to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Chairs match|chairs match]] on the February 28 ''SmackDown'', where Ziggler was victorious.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-smackdown-results/73696-wwe-smackdown-results-22817-no-1-contenders-match/ | title = WWE Smackdown Results \u2013 2/28/17 (WrestleMania main event shake up) | date=February 28, 2017 | accessdate=March 2, 2017 | work=Wrestleview}}</ref>\n\n====Titus Worldwide (2017\u20132018)====\n[[File:Titus Worldwide on Raw April 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Crews (left) along with his fellow Titus Worldwide partners [[Dana Brooke]] and [[Titus O'Neil]] (right) in April 2018]]\nOn April 10, Crews was moved to the ''Raw'' brand as part of the [[Superstar Shake-up]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/apollo-crews-joins-raw-wwe-superstar-shakeup-233451 | title = Apollo Crews joins Raw in WWE Superstar Shakeup | last=Currier | first=Joseph | date=April 10, 2017 | accessdate=April 10, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, a storyline began with [[Titus O'Neil]] offering Crews his managerial services.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/04/17/kellers-wwe-raw-report-417-post-superstar-shake-edition-including-follow-roman-braun-beatdown-angle/ | title = Keller's WWE Raw report 4/17: Post-Superstar Shake-up edition including follow-up on Roman-Braun beatdown angle | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=April 17, 2017 | accessdate=April 25, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> After becoming affiliated with \"The Titus Brand\", Crews started displaying attitude and cockiness, most notably by mocking and attacking [[Enzo Amore]] on the May 15 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2017-05-15 | title =  WWE Raw results, May 15, 2017: It\u2019s every man for himself as Team Red goes Extreme | date=May 15, 2017 | accessdate=May 18, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> The following week, Kalisto confronted Crews about his alliance with \"The Titus Brand\", resulting in a match between the two, which Crews lost.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2017-05-22 | title = WWE Raw, May 22, 2017 results: Which Superstar seized Extreme Rules Fatal 5-Way momentum? | date=May 22, 2017 | accessdate=May 31, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> On the [[Extreme Rules (2017)|Extreme Rules]] kickoff show, Crews was defeated by Kalisto.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/06/04/kellers-wwe-extreme-rules-ppv-report-64-balor-vs-joe-vs-rollins-vs-reigns-vs-wyatt-universal-title-shot/ | title = Keller's WWE Extreme Rules PPV report 6/4: Balor vs. Joe vs. Rollins vs. Reigns vs. Wyatt for Universal Title shot | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=June 4, 2017 | accessdate=June 5, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> During that period, Akira Tozawa joined the Titus Brand, turning it into \"Titus Worldwide\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-brock-lesnar-returns-los-angeles-238041 | title = WWE Raw live results: Brock Lesnar returns to Los Angeles | last=Hamlin | first=Jeff | date=June 26, 2017 | accessdate=July 4, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Crews would then enter a short feud with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]], where Crews lost to Elias at the [[No Mercy (2017)|No Mercy]] kickoff show, the following night and October 9 episodes of ''Raw''. On November 27, [[Dana Brooke]] also joined Titus Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/is-dana-brooke-the-next-member-of-titus-worldwide-wwecom-exclusive-nov-27-2017|title=Is Dana Brooke the next member of Titus Worldwide?: WWE.com Exclusive, Nov. 27, 2017|date=November 27, 2017|website=WWE}}</ref>\n\nBrooke made her first official appearance with the team on the January 1, 2018, episode of ''Raw'' accompanying Crews along with O'Neil in a match against [[Bray Wyatt]], in which he was defeated and at this point Tozawa quietly left the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115617&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: IC TITLE MATCH, NIA'S CHOICE, A CLUB HAS ITS FIRST MEETING OF 2018, BROCK HAS PERFECT ATTENDANCE FOR RAW IN 2018, AND MORE|last=Richard|first=Trionfo|date=January 1, 2018|accessdate=January 31, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On the January 8 and January 15, 2018 episodes of ''Raw'', Crews and O'Neil would defeat [[Cesaro and Sheamus]] in upset victories. At [[Royal Rumble (2018)|Royal Rumble]], Crews entered the Royal Rumble as the thirteenth entrant, being eliminated by Cesaro. On the January 29 episode of ''Raw'', Crews and O'Neil competed in a match against Cesaro and Sheamus for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|Raw Tag Team Championships]], in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115197&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: THREE OF THE SIX IN THE ELIMINATION CHAMBER DETERMINED, THERE IS ANOTHER CHAMBER MATCH, WHAT DID BRAUN DAMAGE TONIGHT?, ASUKA VERSUS SASHA, AND MORE|last=Richard|first=Trionfo|date=January 29, 2018|work=PWInsider|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> On February 19, 2018, his ring name was shortened to '''Apollo'''.<ref name=\"namechange\">{{cite web | url = https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/apollo-crews-loses-his-last-name-wwe-roster-page-251991 | title = APOLLO CREWS LOSES HIS LAST NAME ON WWE ROSTER PAGE | last=Rose | first=Bryan | date=February 19, 2018| accessdate=February 20, 2018 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On the February 19 episode of ''Raw'', Apollo and O'Neil defeated Cesaro and Sheamus in a non-title tag team rematch to earn another shot at the Raw Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115617&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: WAS THE FINAL PERSON IN THE GAUNTLET MATCH THE 'WINNER'?, IS SOMEONE READY FOR ASUKA?, WILL THE ALLIANCES CONTINUE ON SUNDAY?|last=Richard|first=Trionfo|date=February 19, 2018|work=PWInsider|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> On February 25 at [[Elimination Chamber (2018)|Elimination Chamber]], Apollo and O'Neil lost their title match against Cesaro and Sheamus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115732&p=3|title=COMPLETE WWE ELIMINATION CHAMBER PPV COVERAGE INCLUDING RAW TALK COVERAGE|last=Mike|first=Johnson|date=February 25, 2018|accessdate=February 27, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> The following night on the February 26 episode of ''Raw'', Apollo and O\u2019Neil competed in a 2 out of 3 falls match for the championships against Cesaro and Sheamus, losing 2\u20130 to end the feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/98699-wwe-raw-results-february-26-2018/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 2/26/18 (Brock Lesnar confronts Roman Reigns, Ronda Rousey)|date=February 26, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2018|last=Adam|first=Martin|work=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8 at [[WrestleMania 34]], Apollo competed in the 2018 [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant Memorial Battle Royal]] in which he was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=116716&p=1|title=COMPLETE WRESTLEMANIA 34 KICKOFF SHOW COVERAGE|last=Stuart|first=Carapola|date=April 8, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On the April 16 episode of ''Raw'', he reverted to his full ring name '''Apollo Crews''' before he and O'Neil were attacked by [[Dolph Ziggler]] and [[Drew McIntyre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/102206-april-16-2018-wwe-superstar-shake-up-night-one/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 4/16/18 (Night One of the WWE Superstar Shake-Up tonight in Hartford)|date=April 16, 2018|accessdate=May 6, 2018|last=Mike|first=Tedesco|work=WrestleView}}</ref> On the April 23 episode of ''Raw'', Crews and O'Neil were defeated by Ziggler and McIntyre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/102786-april-23-2018-brock-lesnar-returns-greatest-royal-rumble/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 4/23/18 (Brock Lesnar returns, Hype for Greatest Royal Rumble event)|date=April 23, 2018|accessdate=May 6, 2018|last=Mike|first=Tedesco|work=WrestleView}}</ref> On April 27 at the [[WWE Greatest Royal Rumble|Greatest Royal Rumble]], Crews entered at number 33 during the [[Royal Rumble match]], in which he eliminated [[Chad Gable]] before eliminated by [[Randy Orton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-greatest-royal-rumble-results/103117-april-27-2018-50-man-royal-rumble-saudi-arabia/|title=WWE Greatest Royal Rumble Results \u2013 4/27/18 (50-man Royal Rumble, Lesnar vs. Reigns)|date=April 27, 2018|accessdate=May 7, 2018|last=Mike|first=Tedesco|work=WrestleView}}</ref> On September 3, Dana Brooke parted ways with Titus Worldwide after a mid-match coaching backfired, causing Brooke and [[Ember Moon]] to lose to Bayley and Sasha Banks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-09-03/article/sasha-banks-bayley-def-ember-moon-dana-brooke|title=Sasha Banks & Bayley def. Ember Moon & Dana Brooke|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=September 3, 2018|accessdate=September 4, 2018|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref>\n\n====Brand Switches (2018\u2013present)====\nOn the October 15 episode of ''Raw'', Crews returned as a singles competitor when he interrupted Elias during his performance, thus disbanding Titus Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-10-15/article/apollo-crews-confronted-elias|title=Apollo Crews confronted Elias|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=October 15, 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2018|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> The following week, he lost to Elias.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-10-22/article/elias-def-apollo-crews|title=Elias def. Apollo Crews|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=October 22, 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2018|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> On the December 31 episode of ''Raw'', Crews won a battle royal by eliminating eight wrestlers to become the number one contender for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] against [[Dean Ambrose]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-12-31/article/apollo-crews-won-fresh-start-battle-royal|title=Apollo Crews won a Fresh Start Battle Royal to earn an Intercontinental Championship Match against Dean Ambrose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=December 28, 2018|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref> That same night, he was defeated by Ambrose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-12-31/article/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-def-apollo-crews|title=Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose def. Apollo Crews|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=December 31, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> He competed in his third Royal Rumble match at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake pay-per-view]] on January 27, 2019, where he was eliminated by Baron Corbin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=Powell\u2019s WWE Royal Rumble 2019 live review: Men\u2019s and Women\u2019s Royal Rumble matches, Brock Lesnar vs. Finn Balor for the WWE Universal Championship, Daniel Bryan vs. AJ Styles for the WWE Championship, Ronda Rousey vs. Sasha Banks for the Raw Women\u2019s Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/01/27/powells-wwe-royal-rumble-2019-live-review-mens-and-womens-royal-rumble-matches-brock-lesnar-vs-finn-balor-for-the-wwe-universal-championship-daniel-bryan-vs-aj-styles-for-the-wwe-championsh/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> At [[WrestleMania 35]], Crews competed in his third consecutive Andr\u00e9 the Giant Memorial Battle Royal but was eliminated by [[Andrade Cien Almas|Andrade]]. On the April 16th episode of ''SmackDown'', Crews was drafted back to the SmackDown brand during the 2019 Superstar Shake-Up. In June he started feuding with Andrade on ''SmackDown''.<ref name=\"fightful.com\">https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/spoiler-former-nxt-stars-return-brand</ref> Crews was eliminated by Andrade in the 50-Man Battle Royal at [[WWE Super ShowDown]]. At the following NXT tapings, Crews made a surprise appearance to wrestle [[Kushida (wrestler)|Kushida]].<ref name=\"fightful.com\"/>\n\nCrews faced [[Buddy Murphy]] during the [[SummerSlam (2019)|SummerSlam]] Kickoff. The match ended after [[Erick Rowan|Rowan]] attacked Murphy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laboon |first1=Jeff |title=Buddy Murphy def. Apollo Crews by Disqualification after Rowan interrupted |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2019/apollo-crews-buddy-murphy-summerslam-2019 |website=WWE.com |accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> On the April 6, 2020 episode of Raw, Crews was traded to Monday Night Raw where he was defeated by [[Aleister Black]] in his most competitive match to date lasting up to 27 minutes.\n\n==Personal life==\nUhaa is of Nigerian descent.<ref name=WWESigningPR/> His father is originally from the [[Benue State]] in the mid-belt region of Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nigerianscoop.com/2016/05/meet-nigerian-wwe-wrestler-appolo-crews.html | title=Meet Nigerian WWE wrestler Apollo Crews | date=May 9, 2016 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 | work=Nigerian Scoop | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603212836/http://www.nigerianscoop.com/2016/05/meet-nigerian-wwe-wrestler-appolo-crews.html | archive-date=June 3, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Uhaa has a sister, who is in the [[United States Army]] and is stationed in [[San Antonio, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://411mania.com/wrestling/411s-breaking-ground-report-11-09-15-episode-3/ | title = 411's Breaking Ground Report 11.09.15 \u2013 Episode 3 | last=Leighty | first=Robert Jr. | date=November 10, 2015 | accessdate=November 10, 2015 | work=411Mania}}</ref>\n\nUhaa has two children with his wife, Linda Palonen: daughter, Sade (born June 22, 2017)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/apollo-crews-first-child-born | title = Apollo Crews welcomes first child | last=Wortman | first=James | date=June 22, 2017 | accessdate=June 22, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> and son, Kai (born February 9, 2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/article/apollo-crews-welcomes-second-child?sf207510945=1|title=Apollo Crews welcomes second child into the world|work=WWE|date=February 9, 2019|accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nCrews appears as a playable character in the video games ''[[WWE 2K17]]'' (as a [[Downloadable content|downloadable character]]),  ''[[WWE 2K18]]'', ''[[WWE 2K19]]'' and ''[[WWE 2K20]]''. <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k17/article/wwe-2k17-dlc-season-pass-digital-deluxe-edition-update | title = 2K reveals WWE 2K17 DLC, Season Pass and Digital Deluxe Edition details | last=Artus | first=Matthew | date=September 22, 2016 | accessdate=September 8, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/08/30/2k-announces-third-roster-reveal-wwe-2k18-new-entrance-videos-balor-aop-wradicans-analysis/ | title = 2K announces third roster reveal for WWE 2K18, new entrance videos for Balor, AOP (w/Radican's Analysis) | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=August 30, 2017 | accessdate=September 8, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref>https://www.gamesradar.com/wwe-2k19-roster/</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]]'''\n**[[Open the Twin Gate Championship]] ([[Open the Twin Gate Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[BxB Hulk]]<ref name=OWW/><ref name=DGUSA/>\n*'''[[Dragon Gate USA]]'''\n**Best Newcomer (2011)<ref name=DGUSA/>\n*'''[[Full Impact Pro]]'''\n**[[FIP Florida Heritage Championship]] ([[FIP Florida Heritage Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=OWW/><ref name=DGUSA/>\n*'''Great Championship Wrestling'''\n**GCW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=OWW>{{cite web | url = http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/a/uhaa-nation/ | title = Uhaa Nation | accessdate=August 8, 2015 | work=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n*'''[[Preston City Wrestling]]'''\n**PCW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prestoncitywrestling.com/title-history/pcw-heavyweight-championship | title = PCW Heavyweight Championship History | accessdate=November 30, 2014 | work=[[Preston City Wrestling]]}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked No. 72 of the 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 2016<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2016.html | title = Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2016 | accessdate=September 1, 2016 | work=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sesugh Uhaa|Apollo Crews}}\n*{{wwe superstar|apollo-crews|Apollo Crews}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141016135920/http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/prfl/uhaa.html Dragon Gate profile] {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Dragongateusa profile|uhaa-nation|Uhaa Nation}}\n*{{Twitter|id=WWEApollo|name=Apollo}}\n*{{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crews, Apollo}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:African-American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from California]]\n[[Category:Phi Beta Sigma Brothers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the American professional wrestler|crews of U.S. NASA Apollo program missions|List of Apollo missions}}\n{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| image       = Apollo Crews 2017.jpg\n| caption     = Crews in May 2017\n| birthname   = Sesugh Uhaa<ref name=WWEContractWON/>\n| names       = Apollo<ref name=\"namechange\"/><br />'''Apollo Crews'''<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/superstars/apollo-crews Apollo Crews], wwe.com</ref><br />Uhaa Nation\n| height      = {{height|ft=6|in=1}}<ref name=WWE>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/superstars/apollocrews | title = Apollo | accessdate=August 23, 2015 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref>\n| weight      = {{convert|240|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=WWE/>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1987|08|22|mf=y}}<ref name=28Birthday/>\n| birth_place = [[Sacramento, California]], United States<ref name=DG>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/prfl/uhaa.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141016135920/http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/prfl/uhaa.html | script-title=ja:\u30a6\u30fc\u30cf\u30fc\u30fb\u30cd\u30a4\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 | archivedate=October 16, 2014 | accessdate=May 5, 2013 | work=[[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]] | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n| resides     = [[Stone Mountain, Georgia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.thesmackdownhotel.com/roster/wwe2k19/apollo-crews|publisher=Smackdown Hotel|accessdate=25 November 2018|title=Apollo Crews}}</ref>\n| children    = 2\n| billed      = [[Stone Mountain, Georgia]]<ref name=WWE/>\n| trainer     = [[Curtis Hughes|Mr. Hughes]]<ref name=DGUSA/><ref name=WWEArchive>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/superstars/apollo-crews | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160408091058/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/apollo-crews | title = Apollo Crews | archivedate=April 8, 2016 | accessdate=April 12, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref>\n| debut       = August 17, 2009<ref name=OWW/><ref name=911WrestlingInterview>{{cite web | url=http://www.911wrestling.com/viewtopic.php?p=44202 | title=My Interview with the One Man Nation \u2013 Uhaa Nation! | last=Dobson | first=Jamie | date=July 16, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=911 Wrestling | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116023100/http://www.911wrestling.com/viewtopic.php?p=44202 | archive-date=January 16, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Sesugh Uhaa'''<ref name=WWEContractWON/><ref name=WWESigningPR/> (born August 22, 1987)<ref name=28Birthday>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/videos/apollo-crews-reflects-on-his-nxt-debut-wwecom-exclusive-august-22-2015-27851097 | title = Apollo Crews reflects on his NXT debut: WWE.com Exclusive, August 22, 2015 (0:58) | date=August 22, 2015 | accessdate=August 23, 2015 | work=[[WWE]] | quote=Apollo Crews comments on what it was like debuting in NXT, before more than 15,000 NXT fans, on his 28th birthday.}}</ref> is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] currently signed to [[WWE]], where he performs on the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] brand under the [[ring name]] '''Apollo Crews'''.\n\nHe started his career in 2009, originally working under the ring name '''Uhaa Nation''',<ref name=DGUSA>{{cite web | url = http://www.dgusa.tv/bio/uhaa-nation | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150102164019/http://www.dgusa.tv/bio/uhaa-nation | title = Uhaa Nation | archivedate=January 2, 2015 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=[[Dragon Gate USA]]}}</ref> and made his breakthrough in 2011, when he was signed by the [[Dragon Gate USA]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]], which also led to him making his first trip to Japan to work for [[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]]. In 2015, Uhaa signed with WWE and was assigned to its [[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental]] brand [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], where he was given the ring name ''Apollo Crews''. He was promoted to WWE's main roster in April 2016. Standing at {{height|ft=6|in=1}} and weighing {{convert|240|lb|kg|abbr=on}}, Uhaa is known both as a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques|high-flyer]] and a power wrestler.<ref name=MiamiHeraldInterview/><ref name=WWEInterview/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/105-dr-keith/26062-june-12-dr-keith-presents-one-nation-under-uhaa | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120619022413/http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/105-dr-keith/26062-june-12-dr-keith-presents-one-nation-under-uhaa | title = June 12 \u2013 Dr. Keith Presents: One Nation Under Uhaa!!! | last=Counihan | first=Alan | archivedate=June 19, 2012 | date=June 12, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>  He resides in [[Stone Mountain, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.thesmackdownhotel.com/roster/wwe2k19/apollo-crews|publisher=Smackdown Hotel|accessdate=25 November 2018|title=Apollo Crews}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Sacramento, California]], Uhaa was raised in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] and early on fell in love with [[professional wrestling]],<ref name=911WrestlingInterview/> becoming a fan of performers such as [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]], [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] and especially [[Kurt Angle]].<ref name=MiamiHeraldInterview/><ref name=WWEInterview/> He went to a [[military high school]] and began practicing various sports, including [[amateur wrestling]], [[Association football|soccer]], [[American football|football]] and [[track and field]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2015/04/13/atlantan-joins-wwe-training-division.html | title = Atlantan joins WWE training division | last=Hudson | first=Phil W. | date=April 13, 2015 | accessdate=April 13, 2015 | work=Atlanta Business Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sj-r.com/article/20160525/NEWS/160529682 | title = 6 questions with WWE's Apollo Crews, appearing Friday at PCCC | last=Piscia | first=Jason | date=May 25, 2016 | accessdate=May 26, 2016 | work=The State Journal-Register}}</ref> as both an outlet and a way to \"get away from the military life\".<ref name=MiamiHeraldInterview>{{cite web | url = http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388037.html | title = WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Sesugh Uhaa | last=Fishman | first=Scott | date=April 13, 2015 | accessdate=April 13, 2015 | work=[[Miami Herald]]}}</ref> While [[weight training]] in [[high school]], he was given the nickname \"Uhaa Nation\", when his coach noted that he was \"as strong as a single nation\".<ref name=911WrestlingInterview/>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Early career===\nAfter finishing college, Uhaa quickly got a job in order to pay for his professional wrestling training.<ref name=WWEInterview>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/uhaa-nation-interview | title = Exclusive Q&A with Sesugh 'Uhaa Nation' Uhaa: Why he's 'here for the long run' | last=Clapp | first=John | date=April 16, 2015 | accessdate=June 17, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> He began training at the age of 21 under [[Curtis \"Mr.\" Hughes]] at his World Wrestling Alliance 4 (WWA4) promotion's training school in Atlanta.<ref name=DGUSA/><ref name=WWEInterview/> After making his wrestling debut under the [[ring name]] Uhaa Nation on August 17, 2009,<ref name=911WrestlingInterview/> he spent over a year working mainly for small promotions on the Georgian [[independent circuit]], but also made trips to [[Houston|Houston, Texas]]-based [[Reality of Wrestling|Pro Wrestling Alliance]] (PWA) and [[Phenix City, Alabama]]-based Great Championship Wrestling (GCW),<ref name=911WrestlingInterview/><ref name=WWA4>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwa4.com/WWA4-Uhaa-Nation.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141020203649/http://www.wwa4.com/WWA4-Uhaa-Nation.html | title = Uhaa Nation | archivedate=October 20, 2014 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=World Wrestling Alliance 4}}</ref> often working with fellow WWA4 trainee [[AR Fox]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/columns/219353 | title = 411 Interviews: Uhaa Nation of Dragon Gate and Evolve Wrestling | last=Hawke | first=TJ | date=January 14, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=411Mania}}</ref>\n\n===Dragon Gate and affiliates (2011\u20132015)===\nOn September 9, 2011, Uhaa took part in a tryout seminar held by the [[Dragon Gate USA]] promotion.<ref name=DGUSA/> He was immediately signed for appearances for not only Dragon Gate USA, but also its parent promotion, Dragon Gate, and close affiliates [[Evolve (professional wrestling)|Evolve]] and [[Full Impact Pro]] (FIP).<ref name=DGUSA/> He made his wrestling debut for Dragon Gate USA later that same day, defeating Aaron Draven in a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Squash|squash match]].<ref name=DGUSAChasingtheDragon>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/radicanstake/article_59563.shtml | title = Radican's DGUSA DVD Review Series: \"Chasing the Dragon 2011\" \u2013 PAC vs. Ricochet Captain's Six Man Tag, Doi-Callihan, Taylor & Gargano vs. Yamato & Yoshio | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=March 26, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Uhaa made his [[pay-per-view]] debut the following day at [[DGUSA Untouchable#2011|Untouchable 2011]], where he answered [[Luke Harper|Brodie Lee]]'s open challenge and dominated him, before Lee left the ringside area.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/DVDs_-_VGames_-_Books_25/article_61233.shtml | title = Radican's DGUSA DVD Review Series \u2013 \"Untouchable 2011\" 9/11: Yamato vs. Cima, Gargano-Tozawa | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=May 9, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/118-daily-updates/25131-joe-babinsack-reviews-dragon-gate-untouchable | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150416011946/http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/118-daily-updates/25131-joe-babinsack-reviews-dragon-gate-untouchable | title = Joe Babinsack reviews Dragon Gate Untouchable | last=Babinsack | first=Joe | archivedate=April 16, 2015 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The following day at the Way of the Ronin 2011 pay-per-view, Uhaa defeated Facade, Flip Kendrick and Sugar Dunkerton in a four-way match.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_53180.shtml | title = Radican's DGUSA internet PPV report 9/11: Ongoing coverage of DGUSA show from Milwaukee | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=September 11, 2011 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On October 29, Uhaa made his first appearance for Full Impact Pro, when he defeated Jake Manning for FIP Florida Heritage Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/article/62945/2011-jeff-peterson-memorial-cup-report-sixteen-of-the-top-wrestlers-battle-for-the-trophy-and-two-fip-titles-are-on-the-line.html?p=1 | title = 2011 Jeff Peterson Memorial Cup report: Sixteen of the top wrestlers battle for the trophy and two FIP titles are on the line | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=October 31, 2011 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Uhaa then entered a storyline, where different Dragon Gate USA [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Stable|stables]] tried to recruit him to join them.<ref name=DGUSARevolt>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/radicanstake/article_64986.shtml | title = Radican's DGUSA DVD Review Series \u2013 \"Revolt!\" 11/11: Ronin vs. Blood Warriors, Tozawa sings, Yamato-Hulk No Rope match | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=September 10, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On November 30, Uhaa made his Japanese debut for Dragon Gate, during an event produced by the [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] Blood Warriors stable. Uhaa defeated Kotoka in a match that lasted 99 seconds, establishing himself as the newest member of Blood Warriors in the process.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.iheartdg.com/ | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111227080950/http://www.iheartdg.com/ | title = 11/30 Blood Warriors Independent Performance \u2013 1st Blood. \u2013 30 Nov 2011 | archivedate=December 27, 2011 | date=November 30, 2011 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=iHeartDG}}</ref> For the rest of the tour, which lasted until December 25, Uhaa worked alongside the Blood Warriors stable, winning every one of his matches.<ref name=DG120111>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2011/1201.html | title = Fantastic Gate \u958b\u5e55\u6226 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=DG122511>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2011/1225.html | title = The Final Gate 2011 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> At the end of 2011, Dragon Gate USA named Uhaa the Best Newcomer of the year.<ref name=DGUSA/> He also finished second behind [[Daichi Hashimoto]] in ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''s award category for [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]].<ref>{{cite magazine| last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = January 30, 2012 | title = Jan 30 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: Gigantic year-end awards issue, best and worst in all categories plus UFC on FX 1, death of Savannah Jack, ratings, tons and tons of news| magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]| location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page = 18}}</ref>\n\nUpon his return to the United States, Uhaa made his debut for Evolve on January 14, 2012, with a win over Pinkie Sanchez.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_57346.shtml | title = Radican's Evolve 10 iPPV report 1/14: Complete review of final show from ECW Arena | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=January 25, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1326632232 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120118042302/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1326632232 | archivedate=January 18, 2012 | title = Evolve 1/14 ECW Arena results: final event | last=Magee | first=Bob | date=January 15, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Wrestleview}}</ref> When the following March, [[Akira Tozawa]] took over the leadership of Blood Warriors from [[Cima (wrestler)|Cima]] and renamed the group [[Mad Blankey]], Uhaa Nation followed along to the renamed stable.<ref name=DGUSA/> Uhaa made his first appearance representing Mad Blankey at a DGUSA event on March 29, when he and stablemates Akira Tozawa and [[BxB Hulk]] defeated Ronin ([[Chuck Taylor (wrestler)|Chuck Taylor]], [[Johnny Gargano]] and [[Rich Swann]]) and D.U.F. ([[Arik Cannon]], Pinkie Sanchez and [[Sami Callihan]]) in a three-way trios match.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1333311981 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120402184019/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1333311981 | archivedate=April 2, 2012 | title = Viva La Raza! Lucha Weekly | last=Boutwell | first=Josh | date=April 1, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Wrestleview}}</ref> However, during the match Uhaa suffered a knee injury, which sidelined him for a year.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.czwrestling.com/news.php/uhaa_nation_out_of_best_of_the_best.html | title = Uhaa Nation Out of Best of the Best | date = April 3, 2012 | accessdate = November 25, 2012 | work = [[Combat Zone Wrestling]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140113230549/http://www.czwrestling.com/news.php/uhaa_nation_out_of_best_of_the_best.html | archive-date = January 13, 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1333964733 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120411013321/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1333964733 | archivedate=April 11, 2012 | title = As I See It 4/9 | last=Magee | first=Bob | date=April 9, 2012 | accessdate=November 25, 2012 | work=Wrestleview}}</ref> Uhaa returned to the ring on February 1, 2013, at Full Impact Pro's Everything Burns iPPV, where he successfully defended the FIP Florida Heritage Championship against Chasyn Rance.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/article/75148/complete-fip-everything-burns-report-new-fip-world-champion-crowned-tag-titles-and-florida-heritage-title-defended-and-more.html?p=1 | title = Complete FIP Everything Burns report: New FIP World Champion crowned; tag titles and Florida Heritage title defended; and more | last=Trinfo | first=Richard | date=February 1, 2013 | accessdate=February 2, 2013 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> On March 2, Uhaa returned to Japan and Dragon Gate, when he and BxB Hulk defeated [[Don Fujii]] and [[Masaaki Mochizuki]] for the [[Open the Twin Gate Championship]].<ref name=DG030213>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2013/0302.html | title = Champion Gate in Osaka | date=March 2, 2013 | accessdate=March 2, 2013 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> They lost the title to [[Shingo Takagi]] and [[Masato Onodera|Yamato]] on May 5.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2013/0505.html | title = Dead or Alive 2013 | date=May 5, 2013 | accessdate=May 5, 2013 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> On May 11, Uhaa was pinned for the first time in a Dragon Gate ring, when he was eliminated by [[Susumu Mochizuki|Jimmy Susumu]] in the first round of the [[King of Gate#2013|2013 King of Gate]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2013/0511.html | title = King of Gate2013 | date=May 11, 2013 | accessdate=May 12, 2013 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> On July 28 at Enter the Dragon 2013, Dragon Gate USA's fourth anniversary event, Uhaa suffered his first pinfall loss in the promotion, when he was defeated by [[Tony Nese|Anthony Nese]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/otherppvs/article_72312.shtml | title = Radican's DGUSA \"Enter the Dragon 2013\" iPPV Blog 7/28 \u2013 Complete live coverage of DGUSA in NYC, plus Top News from the show featuring three title matches | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=July 28, 2013 | accessdate=July 28, 2013 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On August 9, Uhaa lost the FIP Florida Heritage Championship to [[Gran Akuma]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_72579.shtml | title = Show results \u2013 8/9 FIP Heatstroke iPPV: Baretta wins FIP Title, mixed tag TLC match, more  | last=Gee Schoon Tong | first=Chris | date=August 10, 2013 | accessdate=August 10, 2013 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Back in Dragon Gate, Mad Blankey turned on Uhaa Nation on August 30, after he refused to wrestle Akira Tozawa, who had recently been kicked out of the group. Uhaa then formed a new partnership with Tozawa and Shingo Takagi.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2013/0830.html | title = The Gate of Generation | accessdate=September 2, 2013 | work=Dragon Gate | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://iheartdg.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1377856513&template=Default&#disqus_thread | title = 8/30 Gate of Generation | date = August 30, 2013 | accessdate = September 2, 2013 | work = iHeartDG | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131002172404/http://iheartdg.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1377856513&template=Default&#disqus_thread | archive-date = October 2, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref> On September 12, the three were joined by [[Masato Yoshino]], [[Ricochet (wrestler)|Ricochet]] and Shachihoko Boy to form a new stable,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/battle/2013/09/001955.php | title = \u610f\u5730\u3092\u898b\u305b\u305f\u658e\u4e86\u3092\u4e0b\u3057\u305fYamato\u306b\u3001\u571f\u4e95\u304b\u3089\u88cf\u5207\u3089\u308c\u305f\u5409\u91ce\u304c\u6311\u6226\u8868\u660e\uff01\u30b8\u30df\u30fc\u30ba\u3092\u4e0b\u3057\u305f\u30df\u30ec\u30cb\u30a2\u30eb\u30ba\u306f\u30d9\u30c6\u30e9\u30f3\u8ecd\u3092\u6307\u540d\uff01 | date=September 13, 2013 | accessdate=September 13, 2013 | work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> which was on October 6 named Monster Express.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/sports/fight/all/2013/columndtl/201310070010-spnavi | script-title=ja:\u5409\u91ce\u3001\u9df9\u6728\u3001\u6238\u6fa4\u3089\u306e\u65b0\u30e6\u30cb\u30c3\u30c8\u672c\u683c\u59cb\u52d5 \u30c8\u30e9\u30a4\u30a2\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u30b2\u30fc\u30c8\u6226\u306f\uff2d\uff22\u306b\u82e6\u676f | date=October 7, 2013 | accessdate=October 7, 2013 | work=Sports Navi | publisher=[[Yahoo!]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> On January 12, 2014, Uhaa received his first shot at Dragon Gate USA's top title, the [[Open the Freedom Gate Championship]], but was defeated by the defending champion, Johnny Gargano.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_75641.shtml | title = Show results \u2013 1/12 Evolve 27 in Jacksonville, Fla.: Gargano defends DGUSA Title, Young Bucks take out Bravados, two big title matches set for next set of shows, more | last=Gee Schoon Tong | first=Chris | date=January 13, 2014 | accessdate=January 13, 2014 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On March 6, Uhaa also received his first shot at Dragon Gate's top title, the [[Open the Dream Gate Championship]], but was defeated by the defending champion, Monster Express stablemate Ricochet.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2014/0306.html | title = Glorious Gate 2014 | accessdate=March 7, 2014 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> On May 23, it was reported that Uhaa had signed a new contract with Dragon Gate USA.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/article/85838/dgusa-star-signs-new-deal-and-more-news.html?p=1 | title = DGUSA star signs new deal and more news | last=Johnson | first=Mike | date=May 23, 2014 | accessdate=May 24, 2014 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2015, Uhaa made returned to Dragon Gate as Akira Tozawa's surprise partner in a tag team match, where they defeated [[Cyber Kong]] and Don Fujii.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/result/2015/0205.html | title = Truth Gate 2015 | accessdate=February 12, 2015 | work=Dragon Gate | publisher=Gaora | language=Japanese}}</ref> At the end of the event, Uhaa confronted BxB Hulk, challenging him to a match for the Open the Dream Gate Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/?p=5401 | title = \u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3\u30b2\u30fc\u30c82.5\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u5927\u4f1a\u3000\u30cf\u30eb\u30afvs.\u30b9\u30b9\u30e0\u306e\u30c9\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0\u30b2\u30fc\u30c8\u6226\u3001MBvs.\u30df\u30ec\u30cb\u30a2\u30eb\u30bavs.Hearts\u306e6\u4eba\u30bf\u30c3\u30b03Way | date=February 6, 2015 | accessdate=February 12, 2015 | work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> On March 1, Uhaa failed in his title challenge against Hulk, after which he announced he had wrestled his final match for Dragon Gate.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://iheartdg.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1425179589 | title = 03/01 Champion Gate in Osaka | date=March 1, 2015 | accessdate=March 1, 2015 | work=iHeartDG}}</ref> Uhaa worked his final Evolve events later that month during [[WWNLive]]'s [[WrestleMania]] week.<ref name=WWEInterview/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_83116.shtml | title = WWNLive news: Three big matches set for Mania Weekend \u2013 GenNext's opponents, former WWE stars clash, more | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=February 3, 2015 | accessdate=April 7, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\n====NXT (2014\u20132016)====\n[[File:Apollo Crews WrestleMania 32 Axxess.jpg|thumb|upright|Crews in April 2016]]\nIn October 2014, Uhaa took part in a [[WWE]] tryout camp, resulting in him being offered a [[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental]] contract.<ref name=MiamiHeraldInterview/><ref>{{cite magazine| last = Meltzer | first = Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = December 22, 2014 | title = Dec. 22, 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: UFC lawsuit analysis, full reports on 4 consecutive major WWE & UFC shows, and much more! | magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page=34}}</ref> Starting on December 31, 2014, multiple sources reported that Uhaa had come to terms on a contract with WWE.<ref name=WWEContractWON>{{cite magazine| last = Meltzer | first = Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = December 31, 2014 | title = Jan. 5, 2015 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2014 business year in review, Daniel Bryan return, Wrestle Kingdom preview, death of Al Greene, and much more | magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page=51}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_82546.shtml | title = NXT newswire: DGUSA star signs with WWE, Itami & Balor in tag action tonight on NXT | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=January 1, 2015 | accessdate=January 2, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Uhaa reported to the [[WWE Performance Center]], the home of their [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] developmental brand, on April 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/92886/former-dg-star-starts-with-wwe-great-reason-why-celebrity-wrestler-likely-wont-work-summerslam-battleground-nxt-and-more-news.html?p=1 | title = Former DG star starts with WWE, great reason why celebrity wrestler likely won't work SummerSlam, Battleground, NXT and more news | last=Johnson | first=Mike | date=April 6, 2015 | accessdate=April 7, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> WWE officially announced Uhaa as part of a new class of NXT recruits in a press release on April 13.<ref name=WWESigningPR>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits | title = WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits | date=April 13, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> Uhaa made his first televised appearance on the May 6 episode of ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'', signing an NXT contract in a segment with [[William Regal]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/93549/wwe-nxt-report-contract-signing-interview-with-champion-and-challenger-becky-lynch-video-profile-the-nation-is-coming-who-is-number-one.html?p=1 | title = WWE NXT report: contract signing, interview with champion and challenger, Becky Lynch video profile, The Nation is coming, who is number one? | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=May 6, 2015 | accessdate=May 7, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Uhaa started working NXT [[house show]]s the following month, retaining the Uhaa Nation ring name.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=94554 | title = 6/20 NXT results from Lakeland, FL | last=Alston | first=Gary | date=June 21, 2015 | accessdate=July 10, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwinsider.com/article/94695/626-nxt-results-from-cocoa-beach-fl.html?p=1 | title = 6/26 NXT results from Cocoa Beach, FL | last1=Smith | first1=Joseph | last2=Twiss | first2=Andrew | date=June 27, 2015 | accessdate=July 10, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_86313.shtml | title = Show results \u2013 7/18 WWE NXT in Venice, Fla.: Parks's in-person report on Finn Balor vs. Tyler Breeze, Eva Marie, Uhaa Nation, more | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=July 18, 2015 | accessdate=July 19, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, it was announced that Uhaa, now working under the new ring name Apollo Crews, would be making his televised NXT in-ring debut on August 22 at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn]].<ref name=ApolloCrews>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/95676/the-former-uhaa-nations-debut-on-nxt-is-announced-as-well-as-his-nxt-name.html?p=1 | title = The former Uhaa Nation's debut on NXT is announced...as well as his NXT name | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=August 5, 2015 | accessdate=August 5, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Crews made his debut at the August 13 tapings, which would air after ''NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn'', defeating [[Martin Stone (wrestler)|Martin Stone]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_86935.shtml | title =  WWE news: NXT TV spoilers \u2013 results from Full Sail University for 8/19 pre-Takeover show and post-Takeover shows | last=Parry | first=Josh | date=August 13, 2015 | accessdate=August 14, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> At ''NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn'', Crews defeated [[Tye Dillinger]] in his official debut match.<ref name=NXTTakeOverBrooklyn>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/96-wwe-news/44186-wwe-nxt-takeover-live-results-a-main-card-finn-balor-vs-kevin-owens-sasha-banks-vs-bayley-samoa-joe-jushin-qthunderq-liger | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150823140341/http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/96-wwe-news/44186-wwe-nxt-takeover-live-results-a-main-card-finn-balor-vs-kevin-owens-sasha-banks-vs-bayley-samoa-joe-jushin-qthunderq-liger | title = WWE NXT TakeOver live results & main card: Finn Balor vs. Kevin Owens, Sasha Banks vs. Bayley, Samoa Joe, Jushin \"Thunder\" Liger | last=Witner | first=Emerson | archivedate=August 23, 2015 | date=August 22, 2015 | accessdate=August 22, 2015 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> At [[NXT TakeOver: Respect]], Crews defeated [[Tyler Breeze]]. On the October 8 tapings of ''NXT'', Crews won a [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] to become the #1 contender to the [[NXT Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_87926.shtml | title = WWE news: NXT spoilers \u2013 full results from Thursday's TV taping | last=Parry | first=Josh | date=October 8, 2015 | accessdate=October 9, 2015 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews received his title shot against [[Finn B\u00e1lor]] on October 22,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-tapings-finn-balor-defends-his-belt-against-apollo-crews-200161 | title = NXT Tapings: Finn Balor defends his belt against Apollo Crews | last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink=Dave Meltzer | date=October 22, 2015 | accessdate=October 23, 2015 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> winning the match, but not the title, by disqualification, when he was attacked by [[Baron Corbin]], who held a grudge against Crews for eliminating him from the #1 contender's battle royal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/2015-11-04/wwe-nxt-results-2015-11-04-28124331 | title = WWE NXT results: Nov. 4, 2015 \u2013 Samoa Joe betrays Finn B\u00e1lor as NXT Championship Match comes to shocking conclusion | last=Melok | first=Bobby | date=November 4, 2015 | accessdate=November 5, 2015 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> The rivalry between Crews and Corbin led to a match at [[NXT TakeOver: London]], which Corbin won.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-takeover-london-live-results-finn-balor-vs-samoa-joe-bayley-vs-nia-jax-203856 | title = NXT TakeOver London live results: Finn Balor vs. Samoa Joe, Bayley vs. Nia Jax | last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink=Dave Meltzer | date=December 16, 2015 | accessdate=December 16, 2015 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Crews had a small feud with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] after he saved Johnny Gargano from Elias' assault on the March 23, 2016, ''NXT''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-nxt-results-asuka-vs-emma-finn-balor-battles-rich-swann-209846 | title = WWE NXT results: Asuka vs Emma; Finn Balor battles Rich Swann | last=Witner | first=Emerson | date=March 23, 2016 | accessdate=April 7, 2016 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The two would subsequently have a match on the April 6 ''NXT'', which was won by Crews.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-nxt-results-takeover-recap-apollo-crews-vs-drifter-210586 | title = WWE NXT results: TakeOver recap; Apollo Crews vs. The Drifter | last=Witner | first=Emerson | date=April 6, 2016 | accessdate=April 7, 2016 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\n====Main roster debut (2016\u20132017)====\nOn April 4, 2016, Crews made his main roster debut on ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', defeating [[Tyler Breeze]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/04/april4rawresults/ | title = 4/4 WWE Raw Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Report on post-WM32 | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=April 4, 2016 | accessdate=April 4, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews then entered a feud with the Social Outcasts ([[Heath Slater]], [[Curtis Axel]], [[Bo Dallas]] and [[Adam Rose]]), defeating each member of the stable, culminating in a match on the April 18 ''Raw''. Prior to the match, Crews agreed to join the Social Outcasts if any member of the stable could defeat him. As part of the agreement, the Social Outcasts also agreed to leave Crews alone if he won the match. Crews defeated Slater to end the feud.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2016-04-18/article/apollo-crews-def-heath-slater | title = Apollo Crews def. Heath Slater | last=Benigno | first=Anthony | date=April 18, 2016 | accessdate=April 20, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> Crews suffered his first loss on the main roster on the May 23 ''Raw'', losing to [[Chris Jericho]] in a [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Money in the Bank]] qualifying match. The loss was blamed on [[Sheamus]]' pre-match attack on Crews, starting a feud between the two.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2016-05-23 | title = Raw results: Five Superstars qualify for Money in the Bank Ladder Match  | date=May 23, 2016 | accessdate=May 24, 2016 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> Crews and Sheamus faced off at [[Money in the Bank (2016)|Money in the Bank]], where Crews was victorious.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/06/19/619-wwe-mitb-ppv-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/ | title =  6/19 WWE MITB PPV Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=June 19, 2016 | accessdate=June 20, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, Crews was drafted to the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]] brand in the [[2016 WWE draft]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/19/2016draftresults/ | title = 2016 WWE Draft Picks \u2013 Complete Raw & SD Draftboard | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=July 19, 2016 | accessdate=July 19, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On the July 26 ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'', Crews won a battle royal to earn a spot in a six-pack challenge to determine the #1 contender to [[Dean Ambrose]]'s [[WWE Championship|WWE World Championship]] at [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]]. Later that same episode, Crews was defeated by [[Dolph Ziggler]] in the six-pack challenge, which also included [[A.J. Styles|AJ Styles]], Baron Corbin, [[Bray Wyatt]] and [[John Cena]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/26/july26smackdownfinal/ | title = 7/26 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks\u2019s Complete Live Report | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=July 26, 2016 | accessdate=July 27, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following week, Crews defeated Corbin and [[Kalisto (wrestler)|Kalisto]] to become the #1 contender to the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/02/82-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-complete-live-report/ | title = 8/2 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks\u2019s Complete Live TV Report | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=August 2, 2016 | accessdate=August 3, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews received his title shot on August 21 at [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]], but was defeated by [[The Miz]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/21/summerslam2016results/ | title = 8/21 WWE Summerslam Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=August 21, 2016 | accessdate=August 21, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Crews defeated The Miz in a non-title match at the [[WWE Tribute to the Troops results#2016|2016 Tribute to the Troops]],<ref name=TttT2016>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/106584/wwe-tribute-to-the-troops-report.html?p=1 | title = WWE Tribute to the Troops report | last=Trionfo | first=Richard | date=December 15, 2016 | accessdate=December 15, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> which led to a title match on the December 20 ''SmackDown'', where The Miz retained his title.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/20/1220-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-ongoing-real-time-report/ | title = 12/20 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks\u2019s Complete, Real-Time Report | last=Parks | first=Greg | date=December 20, 2016 | accessdate=December 21, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On January 29, 2017, at [[Royal Rumble (2017)|Royal Rumble]], Crews took part in his first [[Royal Rumble match]], entering as number 22 and being eliminated by [[Luke Harper]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/01/29/kellers-wwe-royal-rumble-report-129-ongoing-results-updated-throughout-evening-including-owens-reigns-styles-cena-rumble-match/ | title = Keller's WWE Royal Rumble report 1/29: Ongoing results updated throughout evening including Owens-Reigns, Styles-Cena, Rumble match | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=January 29, 2017 | accessdate=January 30, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> In early 2017, Crews teamed up with Kalisto to feud with Dolph Ziggler after Ziggler attacked Kalisto.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2017/apollo-crews-kalisto-vs-dolph-ziggler | title = Apollo Crews & Kalisto vs. Dolph Ziggler (2-on-1 Handicap Match) | last=Pappolla | first=Ryan | date=February 7, 2017 | accessdate=February 12, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> At [[Elimination Chamber (2017)|Elimination Chamber]], Crews and Kalisto defeated Ziggler in a two-on-one handicap match. Following the match, Ziggler attacked the two, injuring Crews' ankle, which was trapped in a chair.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/02/12/kellers-wwe-elimination-chamber-report-212-ongoing/ | title = Keller's WWE Elimination Chamber report 2/12: Ongoing coverage including Chamber, Bliss vs. Naomi, Tag Team Turmoil, more | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=February 12, 2017 | accessdate=February 12, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> This led to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Chairs match|chairs match]] on the February 28 ''SmackDown'', where Ziggler was victorious.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-smackdown-results/73696-wwe-smackdown-results-22817-no-1-contenders-match/ | title = WWE Smackdown Results \u2013 2/28/17 (WrestleMania main event shake up) | date=February 28, 2017 | accessdate=March 2, 2017 | work=Wrestleview}}</ref>\n\n====Titus Worldwide (2017\u20132018)====\n[[File:Titus Worldwide on Raw April 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Crews (left) along with his fellow Titus Worldwide partners [[Dana Brooke]] and [[Titus O'Neil]] (right) in April 2018]]\nOn April 10, Crews was moved to the ''Raw'' brand as part of the [[Superstar Shake-up]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/apollo-crews-joins-raw-wwe-superstar-shakeup-233451 | title = Apollo Crews joins Raw in WWE Superstar Shakeup | last=Currier | first=Joseph | date=April 10, 2017 | accessdate=April 10, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, a storyline began with [[Titus O'Neil]] offering Crews his managerial services.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/04/17/kellers-wwe-raw-report-417-post-superstar-shake-edition-including-follow-roman-braun-beatdown-angle/ | title = Keller's WWE Raw report 4/17: Post-Superstar Shake-up edition including follow-up on Roman-Braun beatdown angle | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=April 17, 2017 | accessdate=April 25, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> After becoming affiliated with \"The Titus Brand\", Crews started displaying attitude and cockiness, most notably by mocking and attacking [[Enzo Amore]] on the May 15 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2017-05-15 | title =  WWE Raw results, May 15, 2017: It\u2019s every man for himself as Team Red goes Extreme | date=May 15, 2017 | accessdate=May 18, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> The following week, Kalisto confronted Crews about his alliance with \"The Titus Brand\", resulting in a match between the two, which Crews lost.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2017-05-22 | title = WWE Raw, May 22, 2017 results: Which Superstar seized Extreme Rules Fatal 5-Way momentum? | date=May 22, 2017 | accessdate=May 31, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> On the [[Extreme Rules (2017)|Extreme Rules]] kickoff show, Crews was defeated by Kalisto.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/06/04/kellers-wwe-extreme-rules-ppv-report-64-balor-vs-joe-vs-rollins-vs-reigns-vs-wyatt-universal-title-shot/ | title = Keller's WWE Extreme Rules PPV report 6/4: Balor vs. Joe vs. Rollins vs. Reigns vs. Wyatt for Universal Title shot | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=June 4, 2017 | accessdate=June 5, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> During that period, Akira Tozawa joined the Titus Brand, turning it into \"Titus Worldwide\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-brock-lesnar-returns-los-angeles-238041 | title = WWE Raw live results: Brock Lesnar returns to Los Angeles | last=Hamlin | first=Jeff | date=June 26, 2017 | accessdate=July 4, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Crews would then enter a short feud with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]], where Crews lost to Elias at the [[No Mercy (2017)|No Mercy]] kickoff show, the following night and October 9 episodes of ''Raw''. On November 27, [[Dana Brooke]] also joined Titus Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/is-dana-brooke-the-next-member-of-titus-worldwide-wwecom-exclusive-nov-27-2017|title=Is Dana Brooke the next member of Titus Worldwide?: WWE.com Exclusive, Nov. 27, 2017|date=November 27, 2017|website=WWE}}</ref>\n\nBrooke made her first official appearance with the team on the January 1, 2018, episode of ''Raw'' accompanying Crews along with O'Neil in a match against [[Bray Wyatt]], in which he was defeated and at this point Tozawa quietly left the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115617&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: IC TITLE MATCH, NIA'S CHOICE, A CLUB HAS ITS FIRST MEETING OF 2018, BROCK HAS PERFECT ATTENDANCE FOR RAW IN 2018, AND MORE|last=Richard|first=Trionfo|date=January 1, 2018|accessdate=January 31, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On the January 8 and January 15, 2018 episodes of ''Raw'', Crews and O'Neil would defeat [[Cesaro and Sheamus]] in upset victories. At [[Royal Rumble (2018)|Royal Rumble]], Crews entered the Royal Rumble as the thirteenth entrant, being eliminated by Cesaro. On the January 29 episode of ''Raw'', Crews and O'Neil competed in a match against Cesaro and Sheamus for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|Raw Tag Team Championships]], in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115197&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: THREE OF THE SIX IN THE ELIMINATION CHAMBER DETERMINED, THERE IS ANOTHER CHAMBER MATCH, WHAT DID BRAUN DAMAGE TONIGHT?, ASUKA VERSUS SASHA, AND MORE|last=Richard|first=Trionfo|date=January 29, 2018|work=PWInsider|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> On February 19, 2018, his ring name was shortened to '''Apollo'''.<ref name=\"namechange\">{{cite web | url = https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/apollo-crews-loses-his-last-name-wwe-roster-page-251991 | title = APOLLO CREWS LOSES HIS LAST NAME ON WWE ROSTER PAGE | last=Rose | first=Bryan | date=February 19, 2018| accessdate=February 20, 2018 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On the February 19 episode of ''Raw'', Apollo and O'Neil defeated Cesaro and Sheamus in a non-title tag team rematch to earn another shot at the Raw Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115617&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: WAS THE FINAL PERSON IN THE GAUNTLET MATCH THE 'WINNER'?, IS SOMEONE READY FOR ASUKA?, WILL THE ALLIANCES CONTINUE ON SUNDAY?|last=Richard|first=Trionfo|date=February 19, 2018|work=PWInsider|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> On February 25 at [[Elimination Chamber (2018)|Elimination Chamber]], Apollo and O'Neil lost their title match against Cesaro and Sheamus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115732&p=3|title=COMPLETE WWE ELIMINATION CHAMBER PPV COVERAGE INCLUDING RAW TALK COVERAGE|last=Mike|first=Johnson|date=February 25, 2018|accessdate=February 27, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> The following night on the February 26 episode of ''Raw'', Apollo and O\u2019Neil competed in a 2 out of 3 falls match for the championships against Cesaro and Sheamus, losing 2\u20130 to end the feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/98699-wwe-raw-results-february-26-2018/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 2/26/18 (Brock Lesnar confronts Roman Reigns, Ronda Rousey)|date=February 26, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2018|last=Adam|first=Martin|work=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8 at [[WrestleMania 34]], Apollo competed in the 2018 [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant Memorial Battle Royal]] in which he was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=116716&p=1|title=COMPLETE WRESTLEMANIA 34 KICKOFF SHOW COVERAGE|last=Stuart|first=Carapola|date=April 8, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On the April 16 episode of ''Raw'', he reverted to his full ring name '''Apollo Crews''' before he and O'Neil were attacked by [[Dolph Ziggler]] and [[Drew McIntyre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/102206-april-16-2018-wwe-superstar-shake-up-night-one/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 4/16/18 (Night One of the WWE Superstar Shake-Up tonight in Hartford)|date=April 16, 2018|accessdate=May 6, 2018|last=Mike|first=Tedesco|work=WrestleView}}</ref> On the April 23 episode of ''Raw'', Crews and O'Neil were defeated by Ziggler and McIntyre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/102786-april-23-2018-brock-lesnar-returns-greatest-royal-rumble/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 4/23/18 (Brock Lesnar returns, Hype for Greatest Royal Rumble event)|date=April 23, 2018|accessdate=May 6, 2018|last=Mike|first=Tedesco|work=WrestleView}}</ref> On April 27 at the [[WWE Greatest Royal Rumble|Greatest Royal Rumble]], Crews entered at number 33 during the [[Royal Rumble match]], in which he eliminated [[Chad Gable]] before eliminated by [[Randy Orton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-greatest-royal-rumble-results/103117-april-27-2018-50-man-royal-rumble-saudi-arabia/|title=WWE Greatest Royal Rumble Results \u2013 4/27/18 (50-man Royal Rumble, Lesnar vs. Reigns)|date=April 27, 2018|accessdate=May 7, 2018|last=Mike|first=Tedesco|work=WrestleView}}</ref> On September 3, Dana Brooke parted ways with Titus Worldwide after a mid-match coaching backfired, causing Brooke and [[Ember Moon]] to lose to Bayley and Sasha Banks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-09-03/article/sasha-banks-bayley-def-ember-moon-dana-brooke|title=Sasha Banks & Bayley def. Ember Moon & Dana Brooke|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=September 3, 2018|accessdate=September 4, 2018|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref>\n\n====Brand Switches (2018\u2013present)====\nOn the October 15 episode of ''Raw'', Crews returned as a singles competitor when he interrupted Elias during his performance, thus disbanding Titus Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-10-15/article/apollo-crews-confronted-elias|title=Apollo Crews confronted Elias|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=October 15, 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2018|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> The following week, he lost to Elias.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-10-22/article/elias-def-apollo-crews|title=Elias def. Apollo Crews|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=October 22, 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2018|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> On the December 31 episode of ''Raw'', Crews won a battle royal by eliminating eight wrestlers to become the number one contender for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] against [[Dean Ambrose]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-12-31/article/apollo-crews-won-fresh-start-battle-royal|title=Apollo Crews won a Fresh Start Battle Royal to earn an Intercontinental Championship Match against Dean Ambrose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=December 28, 2018|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref> That same night, he was defeated by Ambrose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-12-31/article/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-def-apollo-crews|title=Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose def. Apollo Crews|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=December 31, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> He competed in his third Royal Rumble match at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake pay-per-view]] on January 27, 2019, where he was eliminated by Baron Corbin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=Powell\u2019s WWE Royal Rumble 2019 live review: Men\u2019s and Women\u2019s Royal Rumble matches, Brock Lesnar vs. Finn Balor for the WWE Universal Championship, Daniel Bryan vs. AJ Styles for the WWE Championship, Ronda Rousey vs. Sasha Banks for the Raw Women\u2019s Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/01/27/powells-wwe-royal-rumble-2019-live-review-mens-and-womens-royal-rumble-matches-brock-lesnar-vs-finn-balor-for-the-wwe-universal-championship-daniel-bryan-vs-aj-styles-for-the-wwe-championsh/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> At [[WrestleMania 35]], Crews competed in his third consecutive Andr\u00e9 the Giant Memorial Battle Royal but was eliminated by [[Andrade Cien Almas|Andrade]]. On the April 16th episode of ''SmackDown'', Crews was drafted back to the SmackDown brand during the 2019 Superstar Shake-Up. In June he started feuding with Andrade on ''SmackDown''.<ref name=\"fightful.com\">https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/spoiler-former-nxt-stars-return-brand</ref> Crews was eliminated by Andrade in the 50-Man Battle Royal at [[WWE Super ShowDown]]. At the following NXT tapings, Crews made a surprise appearance to wrestle [[Kushida (wrestler)|Kushida]].<ref name=\"fightful.com\"/>\n\nCrews faced [[Buddy Murphy]] during the [[SummerSlam (2019)|SummerSlam]] Kickoff. The match ended after [[Erick Rowan|Rowan]] attacked Murphy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laboon |first1=Jeff |title=Buddy Murphy def. Apollo Crews by Disqualification after Rowan interrupted |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2019/apollo-crews-buddy-murphy-summerslam-2019 |website=WWE.com |accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> On the April 6, 2020 episode of Raw, Crews was traded to Monday Night Raw where he was defeated by [[Aleister Black]] in his most competitive match to date lasting up to 27 minutes.\n\n==Personal life==\nUhaa is of Nigerian descent.<ref name=WWESigningPR/> His father is originally from the [[Benue State]] in the mid-belt region of Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nigerianscoop.com/2016/05/meet-nigerian-wwe-wrestler-appolo-crews.html | title=Meet Nigerian WWE wrestler Apollo Crews | date=May 9, 2016 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 | work=Nigerian Scoop | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603212836/http://www.nigerianscoop.com/2016/05/meet-nigerian-wwe-wrestler-appolo-crews.html | archive-date=June 3, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Uhaa has a sister, who is in the [[United States Army]] and is stationed in [[San Antonio, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://411mania.com/wrestling/411s-breaking-ground-report-11-09-15-episode-3/ | title = 411's Breaking Ground Report 11.09.15 \u2013 Episode 3 | last=Leighty | first=Robert Jr. | date=November 10, 2015 | accessdate=November 10, 2015 | work=411Mania}}</ref>\n\nUhaa has two children with his wife, Linda Palonen: daughter, Sade (born June 22, 2017)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/apollo-crews-first-child-born | title = Apollo Crews welcomes first child | last=Wortman | first=James | date=June 22, 2017 | accessdate=June 22, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> and son, Kai (born February 9, 2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/article/apollo-crews-welcomes-second-child?sf207510945=1|title=Apollo Crews welcomes second child into the world|work=WWE|date=February 9, 2019|accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nCrews appears as a playable character in the video games ''[[WWE 2K17]]'' (as a [[Downloadable content|downloadable character]]),  ''[[WWE 2K18]]'', ''[[WWE 2K19]]'' and ''[[WWE 2K20]]''. <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k17/article/wwe-2k17-dlc-season-pass-digital-deluxe-edition-update | title = 2K reveals WWE 2K17 DLC, Season Pass and Digital Deluxe Edition details | last=Artus | first=Matthew | date=September 22, 2016 | accessdate=September 8, 2017 | work=[[WWE]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/08/30/2k-announces-third-roster-reveal-wwe-2k18-new-entrance-videos-balor-aop-wradicans-analysis/ | title = 2K announces third roster reveal for WWE 2K18, new entrance videos for Balor, AOP (w/Radican's Analysis) | last=Radican | first=Sean | date=August 30, 2017 | accessdate=September 8, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref>https://www.gamesradar.com/wwe-2k19-roster/</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]]'''\n**[[Open the Twin Gate Championship]] ([[Open the Twin Gate Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[BxB Hulk]]<ref name=OWW/><ref name=DGUSA/>\n*'''[[Dragon Gate USA]]'''\n**Best Newcomer (2011)<ref name=DGUSA/>\n*'''[[Full Impact Pro]]'''\n**[[FIP Florida Heritage Championship]] ([[FIP Florida Heritage Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=OWW/><ref name=DGUSA/>\n*'''Great Championship Wrestling'''\n**GCW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=OWW>{{cite web | url = http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/a/uhaa-nation/ | title = Uhaa Nation | accessdate=August 8, 2015 | work=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n*'''[[Preston City Wrestling]]'''\n**PCW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prestoncitywrestling.com/title-history/pcw-heavyweight-championship | title = PCW Heavyweight Championship History | accessdate=November 30, 2014 | work=[[Preston City Wrestling]]}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked No. 72 of the 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 2016<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2016.html | title = Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2016 | accessdate=September 1, 2016 | work=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sesugh Uhaa|Apollo Crews}}\n*{{wwe superstar|apollo-crews|Apollo Crews}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141016135920/http://www.gaora.co.jp/dragongate/data/prfl/uhaa.html Dragon Gate profile] {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Dragongateusa profile|uhaa-nation|Uhaa Nation}}\n*{{Twitter|id=WWEApollo|name=Apollo}}\n*{{Professional wrestling profil