{"title_page": "Nwaora Augustine David", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Nwaora Augustine David\n| image       = \n| caption     = Nwaora Augustine David\n| birth_place = [[Kano, Nigeria]]\n| occupation  = Realtor, Philanthropist\n}}\n\n'''Nwaora Augustine David''' is a [[Nigerian]] Realtor and philanthropist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ng/who-is-augustine-austyn-david-nwaora-%EF%BB%BF/|title=who is augustine austyn david nwaora|website=independent.ng}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nNwaora Augustine  Born on the 2nd of November 1989 to Chief and Chief Mrs Ben Nwaora, is a native of Anambra State, Nigeria. He was born and bred in Kano State, in the Northern part of Nigeria. Augustine, in 2008 at the age of 19, joined his father's company Bentell Properties Limited where he started off as a contractor and then rose to the position of director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/meet-business-paladin-and-entrepreneur-nwaora-austyn-david/|title=meet business paladin and entrepreneur nwaora austyn david|website=vanguardngr.com}}</ref> In 2012 he attained a Bachelor of Arts degree in Philosophy from the University of Ibadan and a Masters in International Relations and Diplomacy in 2017 from [[Nile University of Nigeria]], in 2012 he started his own real estate company named Suave Properties Limited of which he is the CEO.  \nAs a philanthropist, while currently pursuing his doctorate degree, Augustine set up the Audisep Foundation, that caters for the less privileged, particularly people in IDP([[Internally Displaced Person]]) camp and hospitals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/04/12/nwaora-augustine-hunger-will-kill-faster-than-corona-virus/|title=hunger will kill faster than corona virus, by nwaora-augustine|website=thisdaylive.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/04/why-im-in-love-with-real-estate-business-austin-nwaora/|title=why I'm in love with real estate business|website=vanguardngr.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.sunnewsonline.com/hunger-will-kill-faster-than-coronavirus-in-nigeria-nwaora-augustine-bentell-properties-limited/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribuneonlineng.com/why-i-am-in-love-with-real-estate-business-\u2015-austin-nwaora/|title=why i am in love with real estate business, Austin Nwaora|website=tribuneonlineng.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.independent.ng/covid-19-hunger-will-kill-faster-than-the-pandemic-nwaora-augustine/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Nwaora Augustine David\n| image       = \n| caption     = Nwaora Augustine David\n| birth_place = [[Kano, Nigeria]]\n| occupation  = Realtor, Philanthropist\n}}\n\n'''Nwaora Augustine David''' is a [[Nigerian]] Realtor and philanthropist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ng/who-is-augustine-austyn-david-nwaora-%EF%BB%BF/|title=who is augustine austyn david nwaora|website=independent.ng}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nNwaora Augustine  Born on the 2nd of November 1989 to Chief and Chief Mrs Ben Nwaora, is a native of Anambra State, Nigeria. He was born and bred in Kano State, in the Northern part of Nigeria. Augustine, in 2008 at the age of 19, joined his father\u2019s company Bentell Properties Limited where he started off as a contractor and then rose to the position of director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/meet-business-paladin-and-entrepreneur-nwaora-austyn-david/|title=meet business paladin and entrepreneur nwaora austyn david|website=vanguardngr.com}}</ref> In 2012 he attained a Bachelor of Arts degree in Philosophy from the University of Ibadan and a Masters in International Relations and Diplomacy in 2017 from [[Nile University of Nigeria]], in 2012 he started his own real estate company named Suave Properties Limited of which he is the CEO.  \nAs a philanthropist, while currently pursuing his doctorate degree, Augustine set up the Audisep Foundation , that caters for the less privileged, particularly people in IDP([[Internally Displaced Person]]) camp and hospitals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/04/12/nwaora-augustine-hunger-will-kill-faster-than-corona-virus/|title=hunger will kill faster than corona virus, by nwaora-augustine|website=thisdaylive.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/04/why-im-in-love-with-real-estate-business-austin-nwaora/|title=why I'm in love with real estate business|website=vanguardngr.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.sunnewsonline.com/hunger-will-kill-faster-than-coronavirus-in-nigeria-nwaora-augustine-bentell-properties-limited/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribuneonlineng.com/why-i-am-in-love-with-real-estate-business-\u2015-austin-nwaora/|title=why i am in love with real estate business, Austin Nwaora|website=tribuneonlineng.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.independent.ng/covid-19-hunger-will-kill-faster-than-the-pandemic-nwaora-augustine/</ref>  \n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtags,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 , , \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nwaora_Augustine_David"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg\n| width           = \n| caption         = Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown\n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 16 April)\n{{legend|#a50f15|100+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#de2d26|50\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fc9272|10\u201349 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fee5d9|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n<!-- The confirmed, active, recovery and deaths cases are fetched from the Wikidata; Kindly don't delete the codes below.-->\n| confirmed_cases = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1603|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| active_cases    = {{formatnum: {{#expr: {{formatnum: {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1603|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}-{{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P8010|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}-{{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1120|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}} |R}} }} }}\n| recovery_cases  = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P8010|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| deaths          = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1120|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#Cases by districts|34 districts]]\n| total_ili       = 5<ref name=\"SARI-10Apr\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=10 April 2020|title=Severe acute respiratory illness surveillance for coronavirus disease 2019, India, 2020|url=http://www.ijmr.org.in/temp/IndianJMedRes000-2175279_060232.pdf|journal=Indian Journal of Medical Research|volume=|pages=5|via=}}</ref>\n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}<br/>[https://nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/095ad0a1c0254b058fa36b32d1ab1977 COVID-19 Public dashboard]\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was reported on 7 March 2020. The [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] has confirmed a total of 1,323 cases, including 15 deaths and 283 recoveries, as of 17 April 2020.<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|access-date=2020-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331222637/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Among the reported cases, 1113 ({{Percentage|1113|1323}}) cases were from one cluster linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious congregation event that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref name=\"MB-17Apr\"/> \n\nTamil Nadu is the third worst-affected in the country after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maharashtra|Maharashtra]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delhi|Delhi]]. 34 of the [[List of districts of Tamil Nadu|37 districts]] are affected, with [[Chennai district|Chennai]] and [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]] being the worst-hit districts. As of 15 April, the state has the most number of coronavirus hotspots in India with 22 districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/major-metros-in-hotspots-list-tamil-nadu-tops-with-most-11586979604010.html|title=Major metros in hotspots list, Tamil Nadu tops with most|date=2020-04-16|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> However, the mortality rate of 0.94% is among the lowest in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/covid-19-body-count-indias-low-mortality-rate-and-the-contrasting-pictures-of-two-states-2578653.html|title=Covid-19 Body Count: India's Low Mortality Rate and the Contrasting Pictures of Two States|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> As per the Health Department, 80% of the patients are asymptomatic while most deaths are among elderly and those with comorbidities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/health/tamil-nadu-is-containing-covid-19-well-and-it-is-not-following-bhilwara-model/403663/|title=Tamil Nadu is containing Covid-19 well, and it is not following Bhilwara model|last=Ch|first=Himani|last2=na|date=2020-04-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe state is under a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]] since 25 March. The [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] has responded to the outbreak by following a contact-tracing, testing and surveillance model.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329134259/https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> However, it was initially criticised for low amount of tests.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{See also|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319193205/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161417/https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184127/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328044912/https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328125841/https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329142751/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"MB-Mar30\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Corona helmet of Chennai cop.jpg|alt=Chennai cop corona helmet|thumb|A police official in Chennai wearing a unique 'Corona' helmet to dissuade commuters from venturing out during the lockdown.]]\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331163219/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day ''[[Tablighi Jamaat]]'' congregation in [[Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz mosque]], [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401020556/https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211819/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, the Nizamuddin Markaz emerged as a new virus hotspot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|title=How Nizamuddin markaz became Covid-19 hotspot; more than 8,000 attendees identified|date=2020-04-02|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162727/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|archive-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234. <ref name=\"MB-Apr1\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TNM-TJ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402005422/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210601/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\"TNM-TJ\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\"TOI-TJcontainment\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, 75 new cases were reported, of which 74 of them attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB_april02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_02_04_20_COVID_19_6_PM.pdf|title=Media Bulletin April 02|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 102 new cases were reported, of which 100 were Delhi event participants. Two others were from Chennai, one with [[Comorbidity|co-morbid]] condition and one US-returnee.<ref name=\"MB-Apr3\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404185030/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=4 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, 74 new cases were reported, of which 69 were Delhi event participants, 4 were contacts of the event participants. One was from Chennai.<ref name=\"MB-Apr4\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-04-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-04-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"TheHinduApr04\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} 74 new cases take Tamil Nadu's total to 485|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405032029/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|archive-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Two more deaths were reported, a 51 years old male who attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' at Villupuram and a female at Theni Government hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece#|title=Two dead of Covid-19 in Tamil Nadu|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055948/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece|archive-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, 86 new cases were reported of which 85 are related to Delhi event directly or indirectly. A 71 year old from Ramanathapuram who died on Thursday was tested positive. A 60 year old also died in the same hospital as previous patient.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sujatha|first=R.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Tamil Nadu reports 86 new cases, two more patients die|date=2020-04-05|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406035038/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health department revealed that 1246 contacts of Tablighi Jamaat participants have been traced and isolated so far.<ref name=\"MB-Apr5\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405215542/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=5 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, 50 new cases were reported bringing the total cases to 621. 48 of them were returnees of Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-Apr6\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406132432/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|archive-date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> 101 people who attended a COVID-19 victim's burial were home-quarantined in [[Ramanathapuram district|Ramanathapuram]]. They were not aware of his condition as the test result returned positive after only two days his burial.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|title=Over 100 quarantined after COVID-19 victim buried without precautions in Tamil Nadu|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123052/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, 69 new cases were reported, of which 63 were related to Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-Apr7\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407141921/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 48 new cases were reported bringing total to 738. 42 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB-8Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408133536/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=8 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> One among the 42 is a Malaysian national. Government had revealed that 1480 attendees of the Delhi event were traced and isolated. 1716 samples from them and their contacts were tested, of which 679 had returned positive.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/09/tamil-nadu-reports-48-new-covid19-cases-tally-climbs-to-738-2127606.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 48 new COVID19 cases, tally climbs to 738|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the state reported 96 new cases which brought the total cases to 834.<ref name=\"MB-9Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409140149/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|archive-date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, 77 new cases were reported bringing total to 911. 70 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi. 17 cases were clinically recovered, bringing the total recovered to 44.<ref name=\"MB-10Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-10-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-10-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, 58 new cases were reported bringing the total to 969 of which, 47 belonged to the Delhi cluster.<ref name=\"MB-11Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-11.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-11.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> One more died in IRT Government Hospital at Perundurai in Erode, taking the death toll to 10. The state government revealed that it will decide on the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]] extension based on Centre's announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-awaits-pms-announcement-on-lockdown-extension-reports-58-more-covid-19-cases-and-one-more-death/articleshow/75098435.cms|title=Tamil Nadu awaits PM\u2019s announcement on lockdown extension, reports 58 more Covid-19 cases and one more death {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, 106 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1075.<ref name=\"MB-12Apr\" >{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-12.04.2020-5-pages-English-178-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-12.04.2020-5-pages-English-178-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> One death was reported, a 45-year-old women died on previous day evening, she was undergoing treatment at a Government Hospital in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/13/covid-19-tamil-nadu-scales-1000-mark-93560-people-quarantined-for-28-days-2129281.html|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu scales 1000-mark, 93,560 people quarantined for 28 days|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The new infections were found in clusters in Chennai - where four were primary sources and Coimbatore - where two primary sources were identified. According to the health department, of the 106 new cases, 90 contracted the infection from them 16 people who had travel history.<ref name=\"Hindu-106cases\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-one-more-death-106-fresh-cases-in-tamil-nadu/article31325855.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} One more death, 106 fresh cases in Tamil Nadu|date=2020-04-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, 98 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1173.<ref name=\"MB-13Apr\" >{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-13.04.2020-5pages-English-181-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-13.04.2020-5pages-English-181-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, 31 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1204. It was the lowest daily rise since 31 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-lowest-daily-rise-in-covid-19-cases-since-march-31-missing-patient-secured/articleshow/75145246.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports lowest daily rise in Covid-19 cases since March 31; missing patient secured {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Marx|first2=Karal|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> A 96-year-old died, making the total of 12 deaths in the state.<ref name=\"MB-14Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-14.04.2020-4-Pages-English-175-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-14.04.2020-4-Pages-English-175-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, 38 new cases were reported in the state of which, 34 were related to Delhi cluster.<ref name=\"MB-15Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-15.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-15.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Deaths of two men were reported, a 47-year-old man with [[Influenza-like illness|SARI]] in [[Stanley Medical College|Stanley Government hospital]], Chennai and a 59-year-old man in a private hospital, making the total of 14 deaths in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/15/two-men-die-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-toll-now-14-1242-people-infected-2130568.html|title=Two men die of COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu, toll now 14; 1242 people infected|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, 25 new cases were reported bringing total to 1267. One death was reported making total of 15 deaths in the state<ref name=\"MB-16Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin16.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin16.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, 56 new cases were reported which brought the total to 1323.<ref name=\"MB-17Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-17.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-17.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cases ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n=== Cases by districts ===\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\">{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases by district}}</div>\n\n==== Districts without confirmed cases ====\nThe following districts have not reported any cases and are classified as 'Green' zones.<ref name=\"TOI-zones\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Tamil Nadu wants lockdown extended by two weeks, but will await PM Modi\u2019s call {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n* [[Dharmapuri district|Dharmapuri]]\n* [[Krishnagiri district|Krishnagiri]]\n* [[Mayiladuthurai district|Mayiladuthurai]]\n* [[Pudukkottai district|Pudukkotai]]\n\n== Testing and treatment ==\nThe government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April. As of 16 April, More than 1 lakh passengers have been placed under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNIE-0case\" />\n\nBy 16 March, following [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]]'s guidelines to test for community transmission, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with influenza and severe acute respiratory infection (SARI) for coronavirus. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328121533/https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> By 10 April, of 577 SARI patients tested, five were positive.<ref name=\"SARI-10Apr\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Second ICMR report on random sampling test results shows possible community transmission|last=DelhiApril 10|first=Milan Sharma New|last2=April 10|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:17}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing rates ===\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for the low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighbouring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321071302/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31|agency=TNN}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests by saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /> The Public Health department had also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" /> Following the Delhi Nizamuddin event, the families of all identified participants were tested regardless of whether they showed symptoms or not.<ref name=\"TOI-TJcontainment\" />\n\nTamil Nadu has the highest the percentage of positive samples among total samples tested in the country at 13% as of 7 April. This has been attributed to detection of cases related to the Tablighi Jamaat gathering in Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiaspend.com/13-of-samples-in-tamil-nadu-are-testing-positive-4-in-india/|title=13% of samples in Tamil Nadu are testing positive, 4% in India {{!}}|last=Raman|first=Shreya|date=2020-04-08|website=www.indiaspend.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, the health officials of the state said that they have changed the testing strategy to \u201caggressive testing\u201d, also including asymptomatic individuals.<ref name=\"DNext-12Apr2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/12183523/1224770/Tamil-Nadu-crosses-1000mark-in-coronavirus-cases.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu COVID-19 cases cross 1000, eight doctors contract virus|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-12|website=dtNext.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The Health Secretary also said the state is looking to employ the 24,000 real time [[Polymerase chain reaction|PCR]] (RT-PCR) test kits that it has in possession for more stringent testing. \u201cOur strategy is to ramp up testing using RT-PCR kits. These testing kits are of the gold standard and their results are completely reliable. We will use the RT-PCR test kits to aggressively test primary and secondary contacts.\" the official said.<ref name=\"DH-13Apr2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/coronavirus-with-over-1000-cases-tn-changes-testing-strategy-825043.html|title=Coronavirus: With over 1,000 cases, TN changes testing strategy|date=2020-04-13|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The move was welcomed health professionals. [[Sumanth C. Raman|Sumanth C Raman]], a doctor and a popular TV critic said \"The only way is to test, test and test. Hope they translate their words of aggressive testing into action,\u201d.<ref name=\"DH-13Apr2\" />\n\n=== Rapid test kits ===\nOn 6 April after ICMR's approval, the state government placed an independent order to purchase around one lakh serology-based [[Rapid diagnostic test|rapid test kits]] from China, that was expected to be delivered by 9 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/06155451/1223661/1-lakh-rapid-test-kits-to-speed-up-COVID19-screening-.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu to deploy 1 lakh rapid test kits to speed up COVID-19 screening|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-06|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407044426/https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/06155451/1223661/1-lakh-rapid-test-kits-to-speed-up-COVID19-screening-.vpf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>  On 11 April, the Chief Secretary K Shanmugam said that the consignment meant for India was reportedly diverted to the [[United States]], causing delay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rapid-testing-not-arrived-yet-consignment-diverted-us-tamil-nadu-chief-secy-1665964-2020-04-11|title=Rapid testing haven't arrived yet, consignment diverted to US: Tamil Nadu chief secy|last=ChennaiApril 11|first=Akshaya Nath|last2=April 11|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|last3=Ist|first3=2020 21:09}}</ref> The delay affected the testing rate of the state. The director of public health K Kolandaswamy said \"It is admittedly one of our biggest weakness, but we decided there is no point in waiting for the kits. We have to use every minute in this period resourcefully.\" Instead of waiting, the health department has decided to use the existing RT-PCR kits for mass screening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/why-tamil-nadu-has-to-do-more-with-less/articleshow/75114082.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Why Tamil Nadu has to do more with less {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> After several delays, 24,000 rapid test kits reached Chennai on 17 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-gets-24000-rapid-testing-kits-from-china/articleshow/75194586.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Corona News: Tamil Nadu gets 24,000 rapid testing kits from China {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe serology-based antibody test kits ordered from China can return quick results and are expected to be used for mass testing in smaller towns and rural areas.<ref name=\"HT-response\" /><ref name=\"DH-13Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/coronavirus-with-over-1000-cases-tn-changes-testing-strategy-825043.html|title=Coronavirus: With over 1,000 cases, TN changes testing strategy|date=2020-04-13|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The state aims to use it to test the family members of COVID-19 positives, their contacts and the areas around the containment zones.<ref name=\"HT-rapid\" /> The state had also ordered an additional 5 lakh rapid test kits and 1 lakh RT-PCR kits.<ref name=\"HT-rapid\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/with-400-000-kits-tn-to-ramp-up-testing/story-GyQ1gZbOr9oVumdeagzK3M.html|title=Coronavirus update: With 400,000 kits, Tamil Nadu to ramp up Covid-19 testing|date=2020-04-11|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\"TNIE-0case\" />\n\nChief Minister E Palaniswami had urged Prime Minister Narendra Modi to provide COVID-19 rapid test kits and {{INRConvert|1000|c}} immediately to procure medical supplies in a video-conference chaired by Modi and attended by the Chief Ministers of other states on 11 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramakrishnan|first=T.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-chief-minister-urges-prime-minister-modi-to-provide-covid-19-rapid-test-kits-1000-crore-immediately/article31317569.ece|title=Tamil Nadu Chief Minister urges Prime Minister Modi to provide COVID-19 rapid test kits, \u20b91,000 crore immediately|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing facilities ===\nInitially, the state only had four government labs for conducting tests for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /> As of 16 April, the state has 27 laboratories (17 government and 10 private) approved by ICMR to testing.<ref name=\"MB-16Apr\" /> According to reports, private labs has fixed a rate of Rs 4,500 for testing a COVID-19 sample. The state government had announced that it will bear all the expenses.<ref name=\"DNext-12Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/12183523/1224770/Tamil-Nadu-crosses-1000mark-in-coronavirus-cases.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu COVID-19 cases cross 1000, eight doctors contract virus|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-12|website=dtNext.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==== Operational testing facilities ====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===== Public =====\n* [[King Institute of Preventive Medicine and Research|King Institute of Preventive Medicine & Research, Chennai]]\n* [[Madras Medical College|Madras Medical College, Chennai]]\n* [[Theni Medical College|Govt. Theni Medical College, Theni]]\n* [[Tirunelveli Medical College|Tirunelveli Medical College, Tirunelveli]]\n* [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]] VDRL\n* Govt. Medical College, Thiruvarur\n* Kumar Mangalam Govt. Medical College, Salem\n* [[Coimbatore Medical College|Coimbatore Medical College, Coimbatore]]\n* Govt. Medical College, Villupuram\n* [[Madurai Medical College|Madurai Medical College, Madurai]]\n* [[K.A.P. Viswanatham Government Medical College|Govt. Medical College, Trichy]]\n* [[Stanley Medical College|Stanley Medical College, Chennai]] <sup>\u00a7</sup>\n* [[Government Erode Medical College|Perundurai Medical College, Perundurai]]\n* [[Government Dharmapuri Medical College]], [[Dharmapuri]]\n* [[Government Vellore Medical College]], [[Vellore]]\n* State Public Health Laboratory, Chennai\n* [[Thanjavur Medical College]], Thanjavur\n* Kanyakumari Government Mediacal college, Nagercoil\n\n{{col-2}}\n===== Private =====\n* [[Christian Medical College & Hospital, Vellore|Dept. of Clinical Virology, CMC, Vellore.]]\n* Department of Laboratory Services, Apollo Hospitals Enterprise Ltd, Chennai \n* Neuberg  Ehrlich  Lab  Pvt  Ltd,  46-48  Masilamani  Road,  Balaji Nagar, Chennai \n* [[Sri Ramachandra Institute of Higher Education and Research|Sri Ramachandra Medical College & Research Institute, Porur, Chennai]]\n* Microbiology Lab, Veerakeralam Road, Coimbatore \n* [[YRG Care]], Taramani, Chennai\n* Hitech Diagnostic Centre, Dr.Ganesan's Hitech Diagnostic Centre Pvt Ltd, Poonamallee High Road, Chennai\n* MIOT Hospitals \u2013 Dept of   Lab   Medicine, Manapakkam, Chennai\n* Madras Medical Mission Clinical Lab Services, Mogappair East, Chennai\n* PSG Hospitals Diagnostic Centre, Peelamedu, Coimbatore\n\n<small>'''Sources:''' <ref name=\"ICMR Private 16Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/List-of-Private-Laboratories-for-COVID-19-Testing-16.04.2020-4-Pages-English-460-KB.pdf|title=List-of-Private-Laboratories-for-COVID-19-Testing-16.04.2020-4-Pages-English-460-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref name=\"ICMR Govt 16Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/List-of-operational-initiated-independent-testing-Government-Laboratories-16.04.2020-5-Pages-English-594-KB.pdf|title=List-of-operational-initiated-independent-testing-Government-Laboratories-16.04.2020-5-Pages-English-594-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> </small>\n<br/><small>'''Note:''' \u00a7 Approved, but not supported by ICMR</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Treatment ===\nThe state has 3,371 ventilators and 29,074 beds in isolation wards according to the [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] as of April 2.<ref name=\"TNHFW\" /> The number of hospital beds available is 1.1 per 1000 population and 7.8 per 1000 for elderly population according a [[Brookings Institution|Brookings]] reports.<ref name=\"Brookings\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2020/03/24/is-indias-health-infrastructure-equipped-to-handle-an-epidemic/|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Is India\u2019s health infrastructure equipped to handle an epidemic?|last=Chakraborty|first=Prachi Singh, Shamika Ravi, and Sikim|date=2020-03-24|website=Brookings|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> As of 2 April, 21 government facilities are designated for treating COVID-19 illness cost free. As of 3 April, 25 private colleges and 110 private hospitals in the state are designated for treating COVID-19 illness.<ref name=\"private hosp apr3\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Private-Hospital-List.pdf|title=Private-Hospital-List.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407063519/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Private-Hospital-List.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"public Hospitals apr2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Government-Hopital-treating-COVID-19.pdf|title=Government-Hopital-treating-COVID-19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407063630/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Government-Hopital-treating-COVID-19.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from [[China]] under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The state government had announced a {{INRConvert|3280|c|year=2020}} relief package on 24 March. It included financial support of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} to all ration card holders, free rice and other essential commodities in the wake of [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]]. It also provided registered [[Hawker (trade)|street vendors]], autorickshaw drivers, migrant labourers and construction workers in the state with similar provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|title=TN announces \u20b93,280-crore relief package|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143624/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It had also announced extension periods of three months to make loan and tax payments for all citizens, and one month to pay house rent for workers including migrants across the state.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-govt-announces-one-month-rent-freeze-action-can-be-taken-if-house-owners-disobey-121552|title=TN govt announces one month rent freeze for workers, including migrants|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Loans-BS\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-tamil-nadu-gives-3-month-extension-for-payment-of-taxes-loans-120033101318_1.html|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu gives 3-month extension for payment of taxes, loans|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently, the government operates 178 relief camps and shelters for migrant workers.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-files-report-on-migrant-workers/article31283896.ece|title=Centre files report on migrant workers|date=2020-04-07|work=The Hindu|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-IN|issn=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408015424/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-files-report-on-migrant-workers/article31283896.ece|archive-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, it had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. It had also taken steps to provide medicines for the next two months to patients with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, HIV and TB while also monitoring pregnant women who are due within that time.<ref name=\"Hindu-CM\">{{Cite news|last=Palaniswami|first=Edappadi K.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|title=Tamil Nadu CM writes on how the State is stopping the pandemic in its tracks|date=2020-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401124254/https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|title=Pregnant women to be monitored|date=2020-03-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326171940/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March in the wake of the nationwide lockdown, the government announced a one-month rent freeze for students and workers, including migrant labourers.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\" /> It also extended the time to make payments including loans and taxes by three months.<ref name=\"Loans-BS\" />\n[[File:Covid-19 in India- Market in TN\u2019s Tiruppur sets up disinfection tunnel for customers.webm|thumb|Disinfection tunnel set up in a market in [[Tiruppur district|Tiruppur]] before ban on its usage.]]\nOn 2 April, the government announced care package of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} and monthly allowed ration of food supply for each household.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/8496PDIPR-P.R.No.249-TNPDS-PressRelease-Date02.04.2020.pdf|title=TNPDS-PressRelease-Date02.04.2020|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTo avoid overcrowding in markets, the state has converted bus stations in towns and cities into vegetable markets. They were also installed with disinfectant tunnels. Later, the government ordered a ban on such tunnels since it created a \"false sense of security in people\" and was also not effective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-top-health-official-in-tamil-nadu-issues-orders-banning-use-of-disinfection-tunnels-1666070-2020-04-12|title=Covid-19: Top health official in Tamil Nadu issues orders banning use of disinfection tunnels|last=Nath|first=Akshaya|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-says-no-to-new-disinfection-tunnels-823888.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu says no to new disinfection tunnels|date=2020-04-10|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In Chennai, the horticulture department has started door delivery service of vegetables that makes 1000 deliveries a day with 3700 mobile vegetable units.<ref name=\"HT-response\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-lessons-from-tamil-nadu-s-book-how-the-state-is-fighting-covid-19/story-Sl4kD5HZksOIuOTRDm2OeM.html|title=5 lessons from Tamil Nadu\u2019s book: How the state is fighting Covid-19|date=2020-04-07|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407165126/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-lessons-from-tamil-nadu-s-book-how-the-state-is-fighting-covid-19/story-Sl4kD5HZksOIuOTRDm2OeM.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials to monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, Coimbatore district administration made usage of face masks compulsory for all.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/mask-made-compulsory-in-coimbatore/article31333781.ece|title=Mask made compulsory in Coimbatore|date=2020-04-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-14|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspensions and closedowns ===\nOn 15 March, Chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres, commercial complexes and malls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316010520/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Hindu-CM\" /> He had also ordered to close state borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, it announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|Section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323102039/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan|author2=Esha Mitra|author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325053856/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the nationwide lockdown, Chennai suspended delivery of cooked food from services like [[Swiggy]] and [[Zomato]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327081146/https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The services were allowed by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Sundaram|first=Ram|date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329135126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the state government reduced the operating hours of essential stores during lock-down to 6 am to 1 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/05/tamil-nadu-people-can-buy-essentials-only-between-6-am-to-1-pm-now-2125875.html|title=Tamil Nadu people can buy essentials only between 6 am to 1 pm now|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406200806/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/05/tamil-nadu-people-can-buy-essentials-only-between-6-am-to-1-pm-now-2125875.html|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the state's chief secretary K Shanmugam said that it favoured a two-week extension of the lockdown, but would wait for PM's announcement. When questioned about other states extending the lockdown, Shanmugam said that \u201cIt is not a decision to be taken by a single state. Ours will be in tune with the PM\u2019s announcement\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Tamil Nadu wants lockdown extended by two weeks, but will await PM Modi\u2019s call {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, the state government extended the lock-down till 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/coronavirus-lockdown-tamil-nadu-extends-restrictions-till-april-30-day-before-pm-modis-address-to-nation/1927168/|title=Coronavirus lockdown: Tamil Nadu extends restrictions till April 30 day before PM Modi\u2019s address to nation|date=2020-04-13|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Containment measures ===\nStickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees to warn the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|title=54,000 people who landed from overseas to be home quarantined|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401214313/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326175649/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 200\n | image1 = COVID19 Containment measure in Kanchipuram, Tamil Nadu - 1.png\n | caption1 = A street is closed-off by municipality in Kanchipuram as a containment measure.\n | image2 = COVID19 Containment measure in Kanchipuram, Tamil Nadu.png\n | caption2 = Same street from inside the containment.\n}}\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread. The containment zones of 5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> radius around the residences of infected across 16 districts were set up. It is ringed by an additional 3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> buffer zone.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-screens-households-in-vulnerable-areas-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread-819999.html|title=Tamil Nadu screens households in vulnerable areas to prevent coronavirus spread|date=2020-04-01|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /> Active surveillance inside these zones along with passive surveillance outside of it to trace the contacts of the infected has been initiated. People found infected are quarantined and the area where they lived is added into the containment plan.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/over-2-lakh-passengers-screened-43000-in-home-quarantine-tamil-nadu-cm-assures-state-ready-to-battle-covid-19-2559869.html|title='Over 2 Lakh Passengers Screened, 43,000 in Home Quarantine': Tamil Nadu CM Assures State Ready to Battle Covid-19|date=2020-04-01|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Houses inside the containment zones are surveyed and disinfected every day.<ref name=\"HT-response\" />\n\nFrom 29 March, as part of its containment plan, the government had screened 3,96,147 people in their houses inside containment zones of 16 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\" /> It was in process of screening up to 7 lakh persons.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, 74,533 passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. 79 are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"Daily30Mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|title=Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070449/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the state deployed 12 'Special Task Teams' each comprising a [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]/[[Indian Police Service|IPS]] officers to coordinate with the respective district collectors to manage the pandemic-affected districts. The teams monitor contact tracing and ensures quick sampling, testing and release of results.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kumar|first=S. Vijay|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-deploys-senior-bureaucrats-to-manage-pandemic-in-districts/article31317820.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Tamil Nadu deploys senior bureaucrats to manage pandemic in districts|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nThe state has categorised affected districts into three zones based on the number of cases. Districts with less than ten cases fall under yellow zone, while the ones with 10\u201325 cases are classified as orange zones. Districts with more than 25 cases are classified as red zones.<ref name=\"TOI-zones\" />\n\n=== Medical supplies ===\nThe newly built [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital|Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital]] in Chennai was converted with 500 beds to exclusively treat COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328230331/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|archive-date=28 March 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\"Hindu-CM\" /> The government had also issued appointment order to recruit 530 doctors, 1,000 nurses and 1,508 lab technicians with immediate effect due to the situation. Orders for 200 new ambulances in the state have also been placed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami|date=2020-03-27|website=Zee News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327100522/https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nOn 3 April, in order to ease the strain on the state's healthcare system, the government announced an incentive package of 30% capital investment with a cap of {{INRConvert|20|c}} for new manufacturers of medical equipment such as [[ventilator]]s, [[Personal protective equipment|PPE kits]], [[N95 mask|N-95 masks]], multi para monitors and drugs such as [[hydroxychloroquine]], [[azithromycin]] and [[Vitamin C|vitamin C tablets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investindia.gov.in/team-india-blogs/tamil-nadu-fights-covid-19-business-way|title=Tamil Nadu fights COVID-19 the business way|website=www.investindia.gov.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"HT-response\" /> After the announcement, eight small and medium-scale companies approached the government to manufacture the required medical equipment. [[Tamil Nadu Medical Services|Tamil Nadu Medical Services Corporation]] said that it would purchase at least 50% of the equipment manufactured by these companies between May and June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/8-firms-offer-to-supply-ppe-kits-to-tamil-nadu/articleshow/75089933.cms|title=8 firms offer to supply PPE kits to Tamil Nadu {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal action ===\nAs of 16 April, 1,94,995 cases have been registered, 2,08,139 persons have been arrested, and 1,79,827 vehicles have been seized in the state for defying lockdown.<ref name=\"TNIE-0case\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/17/is-tamil-nadu-nearing-0-cases-scenario-2131220.html|title=Is Tamil Nadu nearing 0-cases scenario?|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n=== Education ===\nPrimary schools were closed in the state as early as 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316010520/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the Class 10 SSLC board exams were postponed to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322145203/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|archive-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325135110/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 April, the [[Department of Higher Education (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Higher Education]] postponed the summer semester exams for academic year 2019-20 to the beginning of next academic year for all colleges and universities in Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Press-Release-Higher-Education-Department-16.04.2020-1-Page-Tamil-26-KB.pdf|title=Press-Release-Higher-Education-Department-16.04.2020-1-Page-Tamil-26-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Social ===\nOn 10 April in [[Ariyalur district|Ariyalur]], a 60-year-old man in the COVID-19 isolation ward of Ariyalur Government Hospital committed suicide while awaiting his test results. However his results returned negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-man-hangs-self-in-isolation-ward-later-tests-negative-for-covid-19-823884.html|title=Tamil Nadu man hangs self in isolation ward; later tests negative for COVID-19|date=2020-04-10|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Reports of thefts from liquor shops, which were shut by the state government, have emerged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/|title=Business News Today, Stock Market News, Sensex & Finance News|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation and discrimination ==\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nFalse information regarding the coronavirus started circulating in the social media platform Whatsapp<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/covid-19-tamil-nadu-teachers-use-whatsapp-to-spread-awareness-815828.html|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu teachers use WhatsApp to spread awareness|date=2020-03-20|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320222741/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/covid-19-tamil-nadu-teachers-use-whatsapp-to-spread-awareness-815828.html|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which led to several arrests in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/03/cops-book-case-against-tamil-nadu-man-for-spreading-rumours-about-coronavirus-on-whatsapp-2125267.html|title=Cops book case against Tamil Nadu man for spreading rumours about coronavirus on WhatsApp|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406122637/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/03/cops-book-case-against-tamil-nadu-man-for-spreading-rumours-about-coronavirus-on-whatsapp-2125267.html|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-three-tn-youths-arrested-for-spreading-misinformation/articleshow/74675707.cms|title=Covid-19: Three TN youths arrested for spreading misinformation {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|first=Karal|last=Marx|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321075014/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-three-tn-youths-arrested-for-spreading-misinformation/articleshow/74675707.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/india-news/law-and-order/school-teacher-held-for-fake-information-on-covid-19|title=Tamil Nadu school teacher held for fake information on COVID-19|last=World|first=Republic|website=Republic World|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> A 33-year-old [[Quackery|quack]] was detained for deceiving the local people with a vaccine for COVID-19 in Ranipet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/31/quack-held-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-vaccine-in-tamil-nadu-2124054.html|title=Quack held for selling fake coronavirus vaccine in Tamil Nadu|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406122541/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/31/quack-held-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-vaccine-in-tamil-nadu-2124054.html|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government had warned of legal action against people spreading misinformation on COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-warns-of-action-against-people-spreading-false-info-on-covid-19/articleshow/74552383.cms|title=Coronavirus in Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu warns of action against people spreading false info on Covid-19 {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311022741/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-warns-of-action-against-people-spreading-false-info-on-covid-19/articleshow/74552383.cms|archive-date=11 March 2020|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Twitter removed actor [[Rajinikanth]]'s video citing as misinformation after he claimed a 14-hour stay at home during the Janata Curfew can stop the disease going from \"stage-2\" to \"stage-3\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21|title=Twitter takes down Rajinikanth's Janata Curfew video for spreading misinformation|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2020|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329165753/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi Palaniswami]] had asked people not to communalise the coronavirus infection. He also asked people to avoid discrimination saying, \"people should avoid looking at the infected people and families with disgust\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/dont-communalise-coronavirus-infection-tamil-nadu-cm-says/articleshow/74984047.cms|title=Don\u2019t communalise coronavirus infection, Tamil Nadu CM says {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407112036/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/dont-communalise-coronavirus-infection-tamil-nadu-cm-says/articleshow/74984047.cms|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:40%; float:left; text-align:right;\"\n|+Latest statistics\n!Samples collected\n!style=\" text-align:right\"|29,673{{refn|including 4,699 repeat samples of the same individuals|group=lower-alpha}}\n|-\n|Positive\n|1,323\n|-\n|Negative\n|21,628\n|-\n|Pending\n|2,023\n|-\n!Under quarantine\n!style=\" text-align:right\"|23,968\n|-\n|Government facilities\n|34\n|-\n|Home quarantine\n|23,934\n|-\n|Completed 28-day quarantine\n|75,421\n|-\n!In hospital isolation\n! style=\" text-align:right\" |1,891\n|-\n!Recovered/discharged\n!style=\" text-align:right\"|283\n|-\n!Passengers screened\n!style=\" text-align:right\"|2,10,538\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{small|Data provided by the [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Health and Family Welfare Department]] as of 17 April 2020.<ref name=\"MB-17Apr\"/>}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left\"|{{small|'''Notes'''<br/>{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}}}\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Graphs ===\n==== Overview ====\n{{Graph:Chart\n |